<PRE>
<H2>THE INTERNATIONAL CENTRE for CRIMINAL LAW REFORM and CRIMINAL JUSTICE POLICY</H2>

<H1>INTERNET RESOURCES IN CRIMINAL LAW AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE</H1>

TABLE OF CONTENTS  

CATALOGUE OF RESOURCES	
Networking Resources			
Mailing Lists				
USENET Groups		          
Information Resources		          
Internet Sites with Criminal Justice Resources (Gopher, WWW, Telnet, FTP)
Information Resources Listed Individually

GUIDES TO THE INTERNET		
Law Resource Guides			
Subject-Oriented Guides		
Internet Guides for New Users

____________________________________________________________________
		
			CATALOGUE OF RESOURCES
____________________________________________________________________

There are an increasing number of specific documents and resources 
available on the Internet related to law and criminal justice.  

This section is divided into two parts, the first describing resources 
for networking, and the second describing particular information 
resources.  In the second part, resources are described by site, and by 
the type of resource.   This is because some resources on the Internet 
are available by more than one Internet service.  For example you may be 
able to access the same database via either Telnet, Gopher or WWW.  

Criminal justice is a broad field and there are many related subjects 
that will be of interest.  The resources listed here include both well-
known resources and some lesser-known ones.

_________________________

NETWORKING RESOURCES
_________________________

MAILING LISTS
Subscribing to a mailing list is an excellent way to exchange ideas, 
consult with specialists, or just to keep up with the latest news in a 
particular field.  Most new users subscribing to mailing lists will 
experience a great deal of pleasure in the realization that others in 
locations far-flung have similar interests and concerns.  The sense of 
community found in participating in discussions on a particular subject 
in your field is one of the most rewarding aspects of using Internet 
mailing lists.  

This compilation is not exhaustive, as the field of criminal justice is 
far-reaching, but several of the principal lists are given, and by 
subscribing to lists that relate to your field you will soon learn of 
other lists or resources you may be interested in.

ACTIV-L
Activists mailing list; peace, human rights, justice
	Subscribe to: LISTSERV@MIZZOU1.MISSOURI.EDU or
		      LISTSERV@MIZZOU1.BITNET
	Text of message: Subscribe activ-l Your Name


CALL-L
Canadian Academic Law Libraries
	Subscribe to: LISTSERV@unb.ca  or
		      LISTSERV@unbvm1.bitnet
	Text of message: subscribe CALL-L  Your Name

CELLO-L
List for discussion of the World Wide Web client program Cello
	Subscribe to: LISTSERV@listserv.law.cornell.edu
	Text of message: subscribe CELLO-L Your Name

CJMOVIES 
Journal of Criminal Justice and Popular Culture; film reviews and 
original essays
	Subscribe to: LISTSERV@albany.edu  or
		      LISTSERV@albnyvm1.bitnet   or
		      LISTSERV@albany.bitnet
	Text of message: subscribe cjmovies Your Name

CJUST-L
Criminal Justice List
CJUST-L is meant to serve as a forum for free and open discussion of 
Criminal Justice issues and problems, whether they be theoretical or 
real, from your own experience or the newspapers front page.  It is 
meant primarily to be an academic discussion list, although all 
subscribers are encouraged to participate regardless of their 
backgrounds.

New subscribers are likewise encouraged to post to the list when they 
first join CJUST-L to introduce themselves. CJUST-L list members come 
from a variety of walks of life and who you are is of great interest 
to the list.

	Subscribe to: LISTSERV@iubvm.ucs.indiana.edu
	Text of message: Subscribe CJUST-L First name Last name

CRIM-L@sulaw.law.su.oz.au
Australian Criminal Justice and Criminology Mailing List
	Subscribe to: LISTSERV@sulaw.law.su.oz.au
	Text of message: subscribe  crim-l Your Name


CSPPLIST
List for critical discussion of crime, society, and the politics of 
punishment
	Subscribe to: LISTPROC@weber.ucsd.edu
	Text of message: subscribe cspplist Your Name
Before you can post or receive mail you must send a brief letter of 
introduction with your name, your interests in crime and punishment, and 
related work or projects to: triley@weber.ucsd.edu.

EURO-LEX
All-European Legal Information Exchange
Includes discussion of European Community/European union & European 
country legal information sources.
	Subscribe to: LISTSERV@vm.gmd.de 
		or    LISTSERV@dearn.bitnet
	Text of message: subscribe euro-lex Your Name

INFO-LAW
Computers in Law
	Subscribe to: INFO-LAW-REQUEST@BRL.MIL
	Text of message: (That you want to subscribe.)

INT-LAW  
International and Comparative Law
This is a list for librarians and others interested in exchanging 
information related to foreign, comparative and international legal 
materials and issues.
	Subscribe to: LISTSERV@VM1.SPCS.UMN.EDU
	Text of message: subscribe INT-LAW your_name

INTVIO-L
All aspects of family violence
The INTVIO-L list serves as a networking system devoted to all aspects 
of family violence.  While various other lists may explore the topics of 
child abuse or violence within the family, the intimate violence list is 
unique in that it serves the full range of topics that are included 
within the definition of intimate violence.  The list is designed to 
encompass all areas of interest regarding family violence rather than 
limiting discussion to one interest.

While welcoming responses generated from research as well as 
intervention perspectives, the intimate violence list will consist of 
discussion and debate concerning the following topics: physical child 
abuse, child sexual abuse, child 
neglect, spousal physical violence, spousal sexual violence, 
psycological abuse and dating violence as well as any other areas of 
intimate violence that subscribers may wish to explore.

The intimate violence list was developed by the Family Violence Research 
Team at the University of Rhode Island.  They are interested in all 
aspects of the research and intervention of intimate violence.
Subscribe to: LISTSERV@uriacc.uri.edu ,     or 
	      LISTSERV@URIACC.BITNET
Text of message: subscribe INTVIO-L Yourfirstname Yourlastname

LAWAND
Law and Society list.  Interdisciplinary communication between scholars 
researching related issues
Subscribe to: LISTPROC@polecat.law.indiana.edu
Text of message: subscribe lawand Your Name

LAWSOC-L
Canadian Law And Society Discussion List
The lawsoc-l list has been set up as a forum for sharing information and 
discussing issues relevant to the study of law and society in the 
Canadian context. It is meant to serve primarily as an interdisciplinary 
academic discussion list of interest to law and society researchers 
representing a wide spectrum of social science disciplines and 
specialized research fields including law, economics, history, 
sociology, psychology, political science, criminology, feminist studies, 
native studies, geography, education, and social work.  However, the 
list will also be of interest to practitioners involved in government 
policy-making, law reform, and the provision of legal services.
Subscribe to: lawsoc-l-request@cc.umanitoba.ca
Text of message: subscribe lawsoc-l Firstname Lastname

LAWSRC-L
Internet law sources list.   This list is good for keeping up to date 
with new resources on the internet
Subscribe to: LISTSERV@fatty.law.cornell.edu
Text of message: subscribe LAWSRC-L your_name

NCS-L
Discussion of the design and use of the U.S. National Crime Survey
Subscribe to: LISTSERV@umdd.bitnet    or
	      LISTSERV@umdd.umd.edu
Text of message: subscribe NCS-L Your Name

PSYLAW-L.  Psychology and Law
International discussion list.
Subscribe to: LISTSERV@UTEPA.bitnet    or
	      LISTSERV@utepvm.ep.utexas.edu
Text of message: subscribe PSYLAW-L your_name

RIGHTS-L
Rights and Responsibilities 
Subscribe to: LISTSERV@AMERICAN.EDU
Text of message: subscribe RIGHTS-L Your Name

UNCJIN-L  
United Nations Criminal Justice Information Network List
UNCJIN-L is devoted to enhancing exchange of information on criminal 
justice in the international arena.  The definition of criminal justice 
is a broad one.  This is a key electronic conference in the field and is 
used by participants from many countries.  In addition to the exchanging 
of information on criminal justice there are also conference calls, job 
postings, reviews of current books, descriptions of new resources 
available on the Internet at other sites, and tables of contents of some 
journals, i.e. Current Issues in Criminal Justice.  

[Note that there is both a mailing list and a Gopher site with similar 
names:  UNCJIN-L for the mailing list and UNCJIN for the Gopher site 
(see page 17)].

Subscribe to: listserv@albnyvm1.bitnet
	or    listserv@uacsc2.albany.edu

Text of message: Subscribe UNCJIN-L Your first name Your last name

___________________________

USENET GROUPS

USENET groups can be less academic in approach than mailing lists, 
however very good use can be made of the groups related to Internet 
topics.  They can provide quick answers through their periodic postings 
of Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ's).

These are the groups to ask those seemingly obvious questions that you 
just don't know the answers to, such as what is an FAQ?


Internet-related Topics
These are some of the Internet related topics that have Newsgroups:  
news.answers	Repository for periodic USENET articles
news.announce.newuser	Explanatory postings for new users
news.newusers.questions	Questions and answers for new USENET users
comp.infosystems.Gopher	The Internet Gopher
comp.infosystems.wais	About WAIS full-text search
comp.infosystems.www	World Wide Web topics
bit.listserv.help-net	Help on Bitnet and the Internet
bit.listserv.new-list	Announcements about new mailing lists

General Legal Topics
misc.legal		Legalities and the ethics of law.
misc.legal.computing	Discusses the legal aspects of computing.

The ClariNet hierarchy  
This is a little different from other newsgroups in that it is a read-
only group.  Its is like a newswire service that has pre-selected 
articles relating to one subject area.  Not all Internet sites have 
ClariNet as there is a charge at the institution level for receiving it.   
These are some of the groups related specifically to crime and the law.  
There are many other ClariNet groups on a great variety of topics, 
including politics, social issues, and particular countries.

clari.news.law		General group for law related issues.
clari.news.law.civil	Civil trials & litigation
clari.news.crime.misc	Major crimes
clari.news.crime.sex	Sex crimes and trials
clari.news.crime.trial	Trials for criminal actions
clari.news.crime.abuse	Child and spousal abuse
clari.news.crime.juvenile Crime by children and teenagers
clari.news.crime.issue	Social issues related to crime, new laws and how 
			people live with crime
clari.news.crime.top	Well-known crimes
clari.news.crime.white_collar	Business crime, fraud, embezzlement
clari.news.drugs	Drug related crime & drug stories
clari.news.law.police	Police & law enforcement
clari.news.law.prison	Prisons, prisoners & escapes
clari.news.law.profession	Lawyers, Judges etc.
clari.news.law.supreme	U.S. Supreme court rulings & news


_________________________

INFORMATION RESOURCES
_________________________

After Networking Resources (e-mail, mailing lists, and Usenet), the 
second most popular group of Internet services (in terms of use) is 
Information Resources.  These are the services that provide access to 
data stored in in various formats that users can avail themselves of 
according to their needs.  

This section is in two parts: the first is grouped by Internet site, and 
the second by the individual resource.

The first section is grouped by Internet site because some sites give 
access by more than one Internet service (such as Gopher or WWW).  As 
well, many sites have links to other Internet locations. There has been, 
and will continue to be, a tremendous expansion of the number of 
information resources placed on the Internet.  

Internet Sites with Criminal Justice Resources (Gopher, WWW, Telnet, 
FTP)
These information resources are listed in alphabetical order by site 
because many of them are accessible through more than one Internet 
service.  These sites contain a wide variety of information, such as 
primary source documents, archives of mailing list groups, and links to 
other Internet sources.  Many of these Internet sites maintain links to 
other sites with law-related information, which makes it easier to keep 
up to date on new resources as they become available. 

Indiana University School of Law
The Indiana University School of Law maintains a WWW server as a means 
of accessing both information about the School and various online 
research tools and information.  Subjects currently listed include:

- Information about the IU School of Law
- Global Legal Studies Journal  (online version)
- Federal Communications Law Journal (online version)
- Library information and services
- LawTalk
- Links to other law-related Internet sources


The WWW is accessible by using a WWW client such as Cello or Mosaic or 
by connecting to the WWW through the Gopher.

Instructions:	WWW:	http://www.law.indiana.edu
		Gopher: polecat.law.indiana.edu

International Centre for Criminal Law Reform and Criminal Justice Policy 
The International Centre for Criminal Law Reform and Criminal Justice 
Policy was established in 1992 in Vancouver, British Columbia as a joint 
initiative of the Society for the Reform of  the Criminal Law, Simon 
Fraser University and the University of British Columbia.

The International Centre is the newest of the United Nations-affiliated 
institutes for Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice.  The Centre seeks 
to improve the administration of justice locally and internationally 
through reform of criminal law and justice policy.  The programs of the 
Centre focus on:  1) International criminal law and procedure reform, 2) 
International human rights and administration of criminal justice, 3) 
Criminal justice research and policy development, 4) Education, 
communications and the provision of information in criminal law and 
justice.

In addition to this Guide, Information about the Centre's programs and 
other publications are available at this site.

Instructions:	Gopher:	view.ubc.ca
		WWW: http://view.ubc.ca
		Subdirectory: /Academic Units and Information / Guide to 
Internet Resources 


Law Technology Centre of the University of Warwick
The Law Technology Centre of the University of Warwick operates as a 
resource in the field of information technology and computer-based 
learning for all United Kingdom law schools.  In addition to its 
extensive network of contacts within the UK, the Law Technology Centre 
has established an international reputation including contacts in the 
US, Canada, and Australia.

Instructions:	Gopher:	Gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk


Legal Information Institute of the Cornell Law School 
This is a key site for law-related information on the Internet.  There 
is a great variety of resources and documents available, including links 
to other law-related sites.  

The Legal Information Institute is also responsible for the development 
of Cello, a fully-featured client program for using World Wide Web 
resources.  Cello is available for downloading from this site.  Some of 
the resources which are available at the Legal Information Institute 
(LII) include the archives of  some mailing lists related to law.

Instructions:	Gopher:	fatty.law.cornell.edu  
		ftp: fatty.law.cornell.edu
		WWW: fatty.law.cornell.edu


Library of Congress MARVEL
LC MARVEL  offers access to a wealth informational files about the 
Library of Congress as well as links to many other United States sources 
of government information available on the Internet.

There is access to the Library of Congress Information System (LOCIS), 
which contains over 26 million records located in a variety of databases 
or files, many of them of interest to the fields of law and criminal 
justice.  As well as the catalogue itself, there are special files for 
the following:


	U.S. Federal Legislation:
Several files contain summaries, abstracts, chronologies, and detailed 
status information for legislation (bills and resolutions) introduced in 
the U.S. Congress since 1973. Searchable by subject (use Legislative 
Indexing Vocabulary terms), member's name, key words, bill number, 
public law number, committee name.  Information for the current Congress 
is up-to-date within 48 hours.

	Non-U.S. Law:
Two files contain records that abstract and cite foreign laws and 
regulations as well as journal articles on legal topics.  Currently, 
most countries represented are Hispanic-speaking, though a few are 
French and English.  More countries and languages will be included 
eventually.

	Hispanic Legal Serials (HISS)
Abstracts of articles from selected legal periodicals; presently,
those related to Latin American, Hispanic, and Central American legal 
systems.   HISS has been available since 1989.

-  Browse searching by author, article title, country of publication, 
and thesaurus term (HLVT).
-  Word searching by title, author, subject.

	Legal Database (LAWL)
The INTERNATIONAL LEGAL DATABASE contains abstracts of andreferences to 
legislation as reported in legal gazettes of all Spanish-and Portuguese-
speaking countries worldwide since 1976.  Some French and one English 
speaking countries are also available.  Updated weekly. 

	Books (LOCI)
BOOKS in English cataloged by LC since 1968, in European languages since 
the mid-1970s, and in all languages since 1980; some microforms 
cataloged since 1984.  Updated daily.

-  Browse searching by author, title, subject (Library of Congress   
Subject Headings), series, partial LC call #, Dewey #.
-  Word searching by title, author, subject, series, notes.
-  Number searching by ISBN, LC record #.

Instructions:	Gopher:	marvel.loc.gov or
		telnet:	marvel.loc.gov

Saint Louis University School of Law
This site has a well-developed Gopher in the field of law and an obvious 
commitment to keep the Gopher site up-to-date and useful as a tool for 
professionals.   The menu choices are clear and there are many useful 
resources on this site including law-related Internet guides and 
archives of some key law-related mailing lists.  There are pointers to 
most of the other law-related Gopher and WWW sites.

Instructions:	Gopher:	sluava.slu.edu
		Subdirectory: /Library Services/SLU Law Library 
Services/
		WWW: http://lawlib.slu.edu/home.htm

United Nations Criminal Justice Information Network (UNCJIN)
This is probably the most comprehensive Gopher site devoted to criminal 
justice.  It is well-maintained, easy to follow, and new resources are 
added regularly.  At the first level the menu choices include:  a 
descriptive document about UNCJIN, available information from UNCJIN, UN 
Rules (and other instruments), connections to the United Nations 
Development Program and other UN Gophers, Bureau of Justice Statistics 
documents, UN Criminal Justice Country Profiles, the World Criminal 
Justice Library Network (which has a sub directory with Telnet 
connections to several important Criminal Justice and Law Libraries), a 
Telnet connection to U.S. Supreme Court Decisions, the CIA World 
Factbook 1992, the Centre for the Study of Constitutionalism in Eastern 
Europe, Primary Documents in foreign and International Law, and 
Information on New York State Criminal Justice Agencies.

There is also a mailing list, UNCJIN-L, for discussion of topics related 
to criminal justice and for posting of current news (see "MAILING LISTS" 
in previous section).

Instructions:	Gopher:	uacsc2.albny.edu


University of Massachusetts Legal Studies Department
The Legal Studies Department at the University is part of the Campus 
Wide Information Network.  There is complete departmental information 
posted on the gopher site.  

There are two special areas of interest relating to criminal justice 
here: Law and Society and the Conflict Resolution.  Files on each topic 
have been placed on the Gopher.

Instructions:	Gopher:	gopher.ucs.umass.edu


University of Montreal Law Gopher
This site has the full text of recent Canada Supreme Court decisions 
(see p. 19).
Instructions:	Gopher:	gopher.droit.umontreal.ca


University of  the Saarland, Saarbrueken, Germany
Law-related internet sources in Germany.  Full text of German laws. Most 
documents are in German.

Instructions:	Gopher:	pfsparc02.phil15.uni-sb.de

Villanova University Archives
Villanova Center for Information Law and Policy.
Instructions:	Gopher:	ming.law.vill.edu
		Login: 	Gopher

Washburn University School of Law
The Washburn University School of Law maintains a telnet site called 
"Washlaw" for access to legal information on the Internet.  It is a 
combination of online services and resources of potential interest to 
the legal research community.  There are pointers to all the main law 
related resources from here.  A particular strength of this site are the 
many directories.  These are very wide ranging and include law 
librarians, USA law schools and staff, West's Legal Directory, legal 
publishers, law library resource directories, and government e-mail 
addresses.

Instructions:	Telnet:	acc.wuacc.edu
	Login:	washlaw


Washington and Lee University
A large Gopher and Telnet site with many law-related items available, as 
well as links to other law-related sites.  In addition to the law-
related items, there are a great many additional resources about general 
use of the Internet, and many pointers to other sites on the Internet.  
This site is well-maintained and up to date.

Instructions:	Gopher:	liberty.uc.wlu.edu
		Telnet:	liberty.uc.wlu.edu
		Login:	lawlib
		Subdirectory: /Libraries and Information Access/Law/Law 
			       Related Sources


Wiretap Gopher
Internet Wiretap is a site not connected with an academic institution, 
however it has an eclectic mixture of documents related to the law and 
links to other sites.  In the Government and Civics Archives there is a 
large collection of laws, treaties, and other assorted legal and 
historical documents.

Instructions:	Gopher:	Gopher.wiretap.spies.com

Information Resources Listed Individually
This list includes resources by name rather than by the site.  Several 
of them, such as the U.S. Supreme Court Decisions are accessible at more 
than one site, and by using more than one Internet service.


Canada Supreme Court Decisions
The text of the decisions of the Canada Supreme Court are now available 
in French and English on the Internet.  The Gopher has access by recent 
decisions, a complete decisions index (1993 to present) searchable by 
keyword, and Supreme Court Bulletins (starting with 1994).

Instructions:	Gopher:	gopher.droit.umontreal.ca


Law and Society Association
The Law and Society Association has placed several files on the Gopher 
at the University of Massachusetts, Department of Legal Studies.


The Law and Society Association is a group of scholars from many fields 
and countries who are, interested in the place of law in social, 
political, economic and cultural life.  Members have academic training 
or interests in law, sociology, criminology, political science, 
psychology, anthropology, economics, history and other related fields.


The Law and Society Association works with the scholarly community 
toward the interdisciplinary development of the field of sociolegal 
studies and exists to overcome these barriers and to enable the growth 
and integration of the social study of law.

Instructions:	Gopher:	gopher.ucs.umass.edu
		Subdirectory:	/academic department information/legal 
				 studies/law and society association

Law Reform Database
Law Reform Database v3.0.   This MS-DOS database provides legal 
researchers with a convenient computerized index to 5100 reports and 
related documents of the permanent  law reform agencies and similar 
bodies which have been established throughout the Commonwealth and of 
selected American agencies.   The database, which is a self-running 
program, may be downloaded from the site.

Instructions:	ftp:	bbs.qp.gov.bc.ca
	Login:	Anonymous
	Subdirectory:	/govtinfo/lrc/reform3.exe
	telnet:	bbs.qp.gov.bc.ca


Law Reform Commission of British Columbia
Publications from the Law Reform Commission of British Columbia are 
available on the Queen's Printer BBS.

Instructions:	telnet:	bbs.qp.gov.bc.ca
	ftp:	bbs.qp.gov.bc.ca 
	Login:	Anonymous
	Subdirectory:	/govtinfo/lrc


Peacenet World News Service
The PeaceNet World News Service (PWN) is an e-mail news publication 
sponsored by the Institute for Global Change (ICG).  Subscribers 
receive, each day, a single e-mail news digest with a table of contents 
and articles on events in parts of the world, or on issues, that may not 
get coverage in the mainstream media.  Subscribers choose from several 
issue- and region-oriented digests.  There is a monthly subscription 
fee, depending on how many digests you receive.

Instructions:	telnet:	igc.org, or
			cdp.igc.org


Tufts University Multilaterals Project
The Multilaterals Project is an experimental program begun at the 
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy in Medford, Mass. to make available 
to the Internet community the text of a wide variety of multilateral 
conventions. This FTP site is the home location for these materials.  
They are also carried by Gopher at the Cornell Law School.

Instructions:	Gopher:	Gopher:  fatty.law.cornell.edu
		Subdirectory:	/Foreign and International 
Law/Multilateral Treaties
		ftp:	jade.tufts.edu
				cd pub/diplomacy 
			(The home location for these materials).
				get INDEX
			(New users should consult this file).
				cd pub/diplomacy/new 
			(Copies of the most recent postings).
				cd pub/diplomacy/historical 
			(A small number of older documents).


Unesco's Dare Social Sciences Institutes Database
The UNESCO DARE database has global, world wide information on 
Institutions working in the field of the humanities, social sciences and 
covering research and policy making in several disciplines.  Information 
on the Institutes covers addresses, phone numbers, staffing, main 
disciplines, geographical area, issues of journals and bulletins, 
(current, published) research and other activities by the Institute.  
The language of description is English.  A search of the term "Criminal 
Justice" brings up a list of about 40 institutes or organizations. 

Instructions:	Gopher:	liberty.uc.wlu.edu
		Subdirectory:	/netcom/wais/wais sources/UNESCO 	DARE 
Database 

U.S. Bureau of Justice Statistics Documents
The United States Bureau of Justice Statistics publishes documents which 
are available on the Internet.  As of March 1994 there were over 70 full 
text documents available on the UNCJIN Gopher.  These documents may be 
examined online or you may request they be sent to your electronic mail 
address.  New documents are being added on a regular basis.

Some sample titles are given below:
1.  U.S. Bureau of Justice Statistics Telephone Contacts.
....
56. Prisoners in 1992.
57. Pretrial Release of Felony Defendants, 1990.
58. Capital Punishment, 1991.
59. Bulletin Board List.
60. Highlights of 20 Years of Surveys.
61. Criminal Victimization, 1992.
62. Prisoners at Midyear, 1993.
63. Census of Law Enforcement, 1992.
64. Household Crimes, 1992.
65. Jail Inmates, 1992.
66. HIV in Prisons and Jails.
67. Firearms and Crimes of Violence.
68. Prosecuting Criminal Enterprises.
69. Capital Punishment, 1992.
70. Criminal Victimizations, 1992.
71. Violence Against Women.


U.S. Supreme Court Decisions (Project Hermes)
U.S. Supreme Court decisions are available online as part of "Project 
Hermes." You can electronically receive the full text of the Court's 
opinions within minutes of their release.

The decisions have been made available online at many law-related sites 
in the United States.  Most of the sites maintained by Law Schools 
either have the decisions on their own site, or have pointers to other 
locations where they are mounted.  The Cornell Law School is one of the 
sites that has the decisions.
Instructions:	Gopher:	Gopher.law.cornell.edu
		WWW:	http://www.law.cornell.edu/
		telnet:	Gopher.law.cornell.edu
		Login:	Gopher
	
	FTP  sites.  
The following are two of the anonymous FTP sites that maintain Supreme 
Court rulings:

	ftp:		ftp.cwru.edu	login:  anonymous
	password:	your e-mail address
			cd /hermes

	ftp:		ftp.uu.net	login:  anonymous
			password:  your e-mail address
			cd /archive/opinions/supreme-court/get index

	E-mail Mailing List
E-mail mailing list subscribers will receive the syllabi of decisions of 
the Supreme Court as they are placed on the Internet.  
Subscribe to:   LISTSERV@fatty.law.cornell.edu
Text of message:   subscribe liibulletin Name, Address, Telephone Number 
(all on one line)


West's Legal Directory Via Wais
West's Legal Directory (WLD) contains over 675,000 profiles of law firms 
and branch offices, and biographical records of lawyers.  The bulk are 
from the U.S. but there are many Canadian firms represented.   This 
database is now freely available on the Internet since April 1994.

Instructions:	Gopher:	wld.westlaw.com


_______________________________________________________________________

			GUIDES TO THE INTERNET
_______________________________________________________________________

LAW RESOURCE GUIDES

There are several subject guides to legal resources on the Internet that 
are frequently updated and are easily obtained from various sites.  
Three are described here:

The Legal List, by Erik J. Heels
This is the most comprehensive of the legal guides and is currently in 
its third revision.  It is organized by method of access.  An extremely 
helpful feature is the great number of resources in the guide that have 
annotated descriptions.  At the start of each Internet tool such as 
Gopher or World Wide Web there is a brief introduction to the basics of 
using that tool.  The document is very long, and therefore much easier 
to use when downloaded and printed.  The author requests a fee of $9.17 
to be paid if the document is printed.

Availability:  This list is available through several Internet methods.  
The Gopher and FTP addresses are as follows:

	Gopher:	Gopher.usmacs.maine.edu
	FTP:	ftp.midnight.com

Law Lists, by Lyonette Louis-Jacques
This is an excellent guide to mailing lists that are related to the 
field of law.  The criteria for inclusion is fairly broad and includes a 
number of very good lists related to law librarianship that are 
excellent for keeping up to date with new resources.  

Availability:
	Gopher:	Gopher.law.cornell.edu
	telnet:	fatty.law.cornell.edu, login:  Gopher
	Subdirectory:	/Discussions and Listserv Archives/Internet Law 
			Source (LAWSRC-L) Archive/Law Lists 

St. Louis University Introduction to Using the Internet as a Legal 
Research Tool, by James Milles
This guide is written for users of the St. Louis University VAX computer 
system and contains some information specific to that site, however, as 
the subtitle suggests, it is an excellent introduction to using the 
Internet as a legal research tool.  It is particularly strong in 
detailed instructions in using the various types of Internet resources.  
It is intended for an audience of law librarians, law faculty, and law 
students.

Availability:  
	Gopher:	sluava.slu.edu
	Subdirectory:	/Library Services/SLU Law Library 
			Services/Internet Training and Access Info).

	ftp:		sluaxa.slu.edu
	Login:		anonymous
	Subdirectory:	/pub/millesjg/interlaw.wp
			(for Wordperfect format)
	Subdirectory:	/pub/millesjg/interlaw.txt
			(for ASCII version)


SUBJECT-ORIENTED INTERNET GUIDES

This section describes some guides which focus on locating subject 
guides to resources on the Internet.  As in the General Guides to Using 
the Internet, they are separated into two groups--print form, and those 
available on the Internet.

Books

Along with the proliferation of books on the Internet in general, there 
have been several published that focus only on the resources available 
on the Internet.  These books assume a basic general familiarity with 
Internet services such as Gopher, ftp, WWW, and 
e-mail.

Newby, Gregory B.  Directory of Directories on the Internet: A Guide to 
Information Sources.  Westport: Meckler, 1994.  153 pp.  ISBN 0-88736-
768-2.  (This is a well organized and presented book focusing on 
resources rather than connectivity.)
________________

Internet Accessible Guides

The Clearinghouse for Subject-Oriented Internet Resource Guides
The Clearinghouse for Subject-Oriented Internet Resource Guides is a 
joint effort of the University of Michigan's University Library and the 
School of Information and Library Studies.  Its goal is to collect and 
make widely available guides to Internet resources which are subject-
oriented.  The guides made available by the Clearinghouse have been 
created by various individuals in the Internet community.   More guides 
are being continually added.  The guides are available by Gopher or FTP.

	Gopher:	una.hh.lib.umich.edu
	Subdirectory:	/inetdirs
	ftp:		una.hh.lib.umich.edu
	Login:		anonymous
	Subdirectory: 	/inetdirsstacks

Yanoff's List of "Special Internet Connections"
Scott Yanoff frequently publishes a list he calls "Special Internet 
Connections."  These describe resources of note on various subjects 
including law.   The list is available on many sites on the Internet.

	Gopher:	sluava.slu.edu
	Subdirectories:	/Library Services/SLU Law Library/Internet 
			Training and Access Info

Gopher Jewels
Gopher jewels is catalogue of Gopher sites by category (subject tree).  
When you select this Gopher you are given a choice of subjects areas to 
choose from, including legal or law-related.  After selecting a choice 
you can then make a direct link to Gopher sites displayed on the menu.

	Gopher:	cwis.usc.edu
	Subdirectories: /Other Gophers and Information Resources/Gophers 
			by Subject/Gopher Jewels


INTERNET GUIDES FOR NEW USERS

For the new user, we recommend purchasing a print copy of a general 
guide to the Internet.  Having an actual book at your side by the 
computer as you encounter new features of the Internet is extremely 
helpful.  Even after you have familiarized yourself with the basic 
features of the Internet, there will be frequent occasions to refer to a 
print guide for explanation of new, unfamiliar, or forgotten aspects.   
These are some recommended books for new users of the Internet:

Carroll, Jim and Rick Broadhead. The Canadian Internet Handbook.  
Scarborough, Ont : Prentice Hall Canada, 1994. 413 pp.  ISBN 0-13-
304395-9,  Cdn$16.95.  A newly published and very well-received handbook 
written especially for the Canadian market.  The explanations of 
Internet resources will be useful for users in other countries as well.  
All the basics are explained fully and clearly.

LaQuey, Tracy. The Internet Companion Plus: A Beginner's Start-up Kit 
for Global Networking. Reading, MA : AddisonWesley, 1993. 196pp.  ISBN 
0-201-62719-1,  US$10.95.   A good guide for the beginner that has 
detailed information but not presented  in an overly technical manner.

Gilster, Paul.  The Internet Navigator.  New York: John Wiley, 1993.  
470 pp.  ISPN 0-471-59782-1, US$24.95. 

Hahn, Harley & Rick Stout.  The Internet Complete Reference.  Berkeley: 
Osborne McGraw-Hill, 1993.  818 pp.  ISBN 0-07-881980-6, US$29.95.    A 
very hefty volume.  Good for detailed coverage of the fine points.  

Krol, Ed. The Whole Internet: User's Guide and Catalog.  Sebastapol, CA: 
O'Reilly & Associates, 1994.  376 pp.  ISBN 1-56592-063-5, US$24.95.  
The 1994 edition of this very successful guide to the Internet.  Very 
readable and helpful to all levels of users.

Levine/Baroudi.  Internet for Dummies.  San Mateo, CA:  IDG Books 
Worldwide 1993.  ISBN 1-56884-024-1 U.S.$19.95; Cdn$26.95.  A good, 
basic overview of the uses and tools of the Internet by the same people 
who did the series that includes DOS for Dummies and Windows for 
Dummies.


INTERNET ACCESSIBLE RESOURCES ABOUT THE INTERNET

There are many excellent guides to the Internet available on the 
Internet itself.  These range from electronic versions of published 
books, to guides available only on the Internet, to guides written for a 
specific aspect of the internet such as FTP.  

For the new user there is an obvious problem:  not having the experience 
to access and retrieve these documents, let alone being aware of their 
existence.  This is why it is so useful to purchase a copy of a 
published book to help you get started and on your way to retrieve these 
guides.

"WHERE TO START" FOR NEW INTERNET USERS
This is an excellent bibliography of published material on using the 
Internet.  Most of the items are printed books, however some of them are 
available both in print form and in electronic form on the Internet.  
The list is maintained by Jim Milles, of the Saint Louis University Law 
School.

The latest version of "Where to Start" for New Internet Users version 
4.3 (15 May 1994), is available by anonymous ftp and e-mail request.  
There are two anonymous ftp sites:

	Gopher:	sluava.slu.edu
	Subdirectory:	/Library Services/SLU Law Library Services/ 
			Internet Training and Access Info

	FTP:		sluva.slu.edu
			cd pub/millesjg
			get newusers.faq

	E-Mail:	To:	LISTSERV @ubvm.cc.bufffalo.edu
	Text of message: get newusers.faq mettrain F=mail

	WWW:	http:	//lawlib.slu.edu


Saint Louis University Law Library Gopher
The St. Louis University Law Library Gopher has a particularly strong 
collection of files on using the Internet.  The "Introduction to Using  
the Internet at Saint Louis University School of Law" has good 
instructions in using the basic Internet tools, especially as they apply 
to legal research.  As well as this document there are other Internet 
training materials and pointers to Internet material available on other 
sites.  All the main Internet sources of material on the Internet are 
included  here.

	Gopher:	sluava.slu.edu
	Subdirectory:	Library Services/SLU Law Library Services 
			/Internet Training and Access Info/

_______________________

We hope you have found this guide useful.  If you have any comments, 
questions, suggested additions, or revisions, please contact:

   John Evans
   Senior Associate
   International Centre for Criminal Law Reform and Criminal Justice Policy
   1822 East Mall
   Vancouver, V6T 1Z1
   Canada
   e-mail:  evans@law.ubc.ca
   Tel: (604) 822-9322

