</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Edward Helgeson">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="wall.jpg">

<UL>
<H1><IMG SRC="Nic3.gif" HSPACE=5 HEIGHT=115 WIDTH=76 ALIGN=ABSCENTER>Nicholas
Sinclair-Brown</H1>
</UL>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1 >
<TR>
<TD>
<H3>Position</H3>
</TD>

<TD>
<UL>
<P>Fellow</P>
</UL>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>
<H3>Address </H3>
</TD>

<TD>
<UL>
<P>Research Centre for International Law <BR>
5 Cranmer Road<BR>
Cambridge CB3 9BL<BR>
United Kingdom</P>
</UL>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>
<H3>Telephone</H3>
</TD>

<TD>
<UL>
<P>+44 1223 335 358 (ext. 212)</P>
</UL>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>
<H3>Fax</H3>
</TD>

<TD>
<UL>
<P>+44 1223 300 406</P>
</UL>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>
<H3>Email</H3>
</TD>

<TD>
<UL>
<P><A HREF="mailto:npms100@cus.cam.ac.uk">npms100@cus.cam.ac.uk</A></P>
</UL>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT> arrived in Cambridge in 1992 as a Visiting Fellow
and became a full time Fellow of the Research Centre for International
Law, and a Fellow in Law at the graduate college Hughes Hall, in 1996.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he main projects on which I am working are the completion
of a book on the International Law of Shipwrecks, and preparation of various
biographies of international lawyers. I have also been lecturing on aspects
of international law concerning the Sea, Antarctica, Global Environmental
Problems, and Trade, to M.Phil. students of International Relations. <BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>O</FONT>utside of law, I have previously spent time as a
jazz and cabaret pianist and I am currently a Director of Caledonian Opera
Company which over the past few years has toured with Rossini's La Cenerentola,
and Donnizetti's Mary Stuart and Lucia di Lammermoor.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Prior Career.<BR>
<BR>
</B><FONT SIZE=+2>I </FONT>qualified as a solicitor in 1975 and was subsequently
based in Bergen [1976-78] as part of the project management team for Mobil's
development of the first major offshore oil field in Norway 'Statfjord
A' [1976-1978]. I then moved to London [1978-1980] to join the legal department
of the multinational construction and engineering company Brown &amp; Root
where I specialised in joint ventures, project management, vessel charters,
and proprietary technology. <BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT> moved to Aberdeen [1980-83] to take up an appointment
as Legal advisor to Wharton Williams which was quickly becoming one of
the leading international diving and subsea engineering companies. Here
I developed ancillary responsibilities for sub sea salvage which led to
participation in the management team responsible for the successful gold
recovery from HMS Edinburgh, which was undertaken at a record depth of
800 feet for the Russian and British Governments. I moved back to London
[1984-88] to become a director of a specialist international deepwater
salvage project management team. During this time I was also a founding
director of a conservation laboratory in Dundee which had been established
to continue the development of 'freeze drying' technology pioneered by
the Mary Rose project in relation to items recovered from shipwrecks and
also to expand its application to such fields as archival restoration on
which a collaborative research project was undertaken with the British
Library.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>I </FONT>moved back to Aberdeen [1988 - 1991] to establish
a company to exploit development of proprietary underwater excavation technology.
The Company was winner of the Scottish Offshore Technology Award for 1989
(having been commended the previous year), a finalist in the Norwegian
Offshore Technology Awards 1990, a runner up in the Castrol R&amp;D award
1991, commended in the 1991 Aberdeen Enterprise &quot;Business Achievements
Award&quot; and selected into the finals of the 1992 Scottish Innovation
awards. I left the Company in 1994 to move full time to Cambridge and shortly
after the Company received the Queens award for Industry in recognition
of its innovative technical achievements.</P>

<CENTER><P>
