<BODY BACKGROUND="wall.jpg">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/RCIL/UCam.gif" HEIGHT=63 WIDTH=298 ALIGN=ABSCENTER></H1>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Research Centre for International Law</H1>

<H3>
<HR WIDTH="100%"><A NAME="anchor26604"></A><B>INDEX</B> </H3>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#anchor357115">Introduction</A> </LI>

<LI><A HREF="#anchor281143">Foundation &amp; Development</A> </LI>

<LI><A HREF="#anchor374175">Funding &amp; Donations</A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="#Application & Eligibility">Application &amp; Eligibility</A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="#anchor378564">Contact Information </A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="directory.htm">RCIL Directory</A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="lectures.htm">Friday Lecture Series</A><A HREF="lectures.htm"><IMG SRC="updated2.gif" HSPACE=3 BORDER=0 HEIGHT=14 WIDTH=51 ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM></A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="publications.htm">Publications</A> </LI>

<LI><A HREF="news.htm">RCIL News</A> </LI>

<LI><A HREF="alumni.htm">Alumni News</A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="trivia.htm">Trivia Quiz</A> <IMG SRC="new2.gif" HSPACE=3 HEIGHT=12 WIDTH=31 ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM></LI>

<LI><A HREF="links.htm">International Law WebLinks</A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="#camlinks">University of Cambridge WebLinks</A></LI>
</UL>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<H3><A NAME="anchor357115"></A>INTRODUCTION </H3>

<UL>
<P><A HREF="picture.htm"><IMG SRC="Rcil2.gif" HSPACE=10 BORDER=0 HEIGHT=257 WIDTH=375 ALIGN=ABSCENTER></A></P>
</UL>

<UL>
<P><FONT SIZE=+2>S</FONT>ince its foundation in 1983, the Research Centre
for International Law has become an important forum for the exchange of
information and ideas for international lawyers from around the world.
It fosters critical and constructive research on the role, content and
methods of the operation of law in the international community by:</P>
</UL>

<UL>
<UL>
<LI><B><I>organising collective research and publication</I></B> to provide
fundamental research materials to scholars and practitioners; </LI>

<LI><I><B>welcoming scholars and practitioners</B> </I>from around the
world to Cambridge and offering the best possible facilities and environment
for the pursuit of individual research projects; </LI>

<LI><I><B>providing a forum</B> </I>for the development of knowledge of
and solutions to current problems in the field; and </LI>

<LI><B><I>participating on an interdisciplinary basis</I></B> in the advancement
of legal regulation of matters of international concern. </LI>
</UL>
</UL>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he Centre's interests cover the whole of the law
governing the peaceful relations between states including: systems of international
dispute settlement, limitations on the use of force and the regulation
of hostilities, international human rights, the development and operation
of international organisations and the emergence of new legal regimes in
such fields as international economic, maritime and environmental law.</P>

<H4>Visiting Fellows and Scholars</H4>

<P>Providing a home in Cambridge for visitors from many parts of the world
is an important aspect of the Centre's activity. Visitors are welcomed
for periods varying from a few weeks to a year to pursue their own research
projects. While in Cambridge, they meet with other scholars in their fields
and gain encouragement and direction from the many distinguished international
lawyers associated with the Centre and the University. Visitors are encouraged
to participate fully in the activities of the Centre and to attend lectures
and seminars on international law and related subjects in the Faculty of
Law and elsewhere in the University.</P>

<CENTER><P><A HREF="#anchor26604">Return to Index</A> </P></CENTER>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<H3><A NAME="anchor281143"></A>FOUNDATION AND DEVELOPMENT </H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he Research Centre for International Law was established
in 1983 within the faculty of law of the University of Cambridge by its
founding director <IMG SRC="lauterpacht1.gif" HSPACE=5 HEIGHT=200 WIDTH=180 ALIGN=LEFT>(now
Emeritus Director), <B>Professor Elihu Lauterpacht, CBE, QC</B>. Over the
decade of his leadership, the Centre gained wide recognition for the significant
contribution it made to the development of international law. In 1985,
the Centre moved to its present home at 5 Cranmer Road, a short walk from
the new <A HREF="http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/">University Law Faculty</A><B>
</B>at the Sidgwick Site. A spacious Edwardian house situated in pleasant
gardens, the Centre enjoys a congenial and friendly atmosphere.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he Centre houses a basic international law library
which supplements the extensive holdings of the University Library and
Squire Law Library (to both of which its fellows and scholars have access).
It also maintains a unique collection of pleadings and other documents
from international litigation and arbitrations of interest to scholars
and practioners alike. It is hoped that the Centre's collection will soon
be part of the&nbsp;online <A HREF="telnet://ul.cam.ac.uk">Cambridge University
Libraries Catalogue</A> system. The Centre has recently improved its computing
facilities, networking PCs and providing direct internet and email access
to individual offices. The telephone system has been upgraded to include
voicemail services. The completion of a sizeable extension to the building
in November 1996 will provide much needed additional office, library and
conference space for the Centre.</P>

<DT><FONT SIZE=+2>S</FONT>ince 1995, two new directors have continued the
work of Professor Lauterpacht:</DT>

<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH="85%" >
<TR>
<TD>
<CENTER><DT><IMG SRC="dugard1.gif" HEIGHT=180 WIDTH=150><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1><I>John Dugard<BR>
</I><B>Director<BR>
</B>Visiting Professor (1995-1997) on secondment from the University of
Witwatersrand in South Africa and Member of the International Law Commission</FONT></DT></CENTER>
</TD>

<TD>
<CENTER><DT><IMG SRC="wall.jpg" HEIGHT=80 WIDTH=160><BR>
<IMG SRC="crawford1.gif" HEIGHT=180 WIDTH=135><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1><I>James Crawford<BR>
</I><B>Co-Director<BR>
</B>Whewell Professor of International Law and Member of the International
Law Commission</FONT></DT></CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>ith a careful regard for established tradition,
the new directors intend to build upon the Centre's international reputation,
to develop further its work and resource base, and reinforce the Centre's
links with the Faculty of Law and other academic institutions.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><P><A HREF="#anchor26604">Return to Index</A> </P></CENTER>

<H3>
<HR WIDTH="100%"><BR>
<A NAME="anchor374175"></A>FUNDING &amp; DONATIONS </H3>

<UL>
<P><A HREF="extension.gif"><IMG SRC="extension" BORDER=0 HEIGHT=257 WIDTH=375></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>The generous support of donors has made possible the construction
of <BR>
a substantial extension to the Centre which will provide much needed <BR>
additional office, library and conference space.</FONT></P>
</UL>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he Research Centre for International Law is partially
funded by the University of Cambridge, and in addition has been generously
supported on a project basis by the Ford Foundation, the John D. and Catherine
T. MacArthur Foundation and the Commission of the European Union among
others. The Centre has also been the beneficiary of many individual acts
of philanthropy, especially towards the expansion and improvement of facilities.
In particular, the Centre would like to acknowledge Earl Snyer of Indiana
for the establishment of the Snyder Scholarship, and his general support
of the Centre over many years. Donations are gratefully received and are
subject to tax relief. </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><P><A HREF="#anchor26604">Return to Index</A> </P></CENTER>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<H3><A NAME="Application & Eligibility"></A>APPLICATION &amp; ELIGIBILITY</H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>pplicants are required to have an established
academic, professional or governmental position in their home country.
While in Cambridge, they generally pursue self-directed research projects.
The titles 'fellow' and 'scholar' are accorded at the discretion of the
Management Committee by reference to the applicant's seniority and intended
length of stay in Cambridge, and are not associated with colleges within
the University. </P>

<P><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>he Research Centre does not accept persons enrolled
in University degree courses at Cambridge. It does not itself offer courses
or award degrees, and cannot provide financial support to visiting scholars.
For information about law courses, degree programmes and scholarships offered
by the University, please contact the <A HREF="http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/">Faculty
of Law</A>.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3><A NAME="anchor378564"></A>CONTACT INFORMATION </H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT SIZE=+2>F</FONT>or further information about the Centre, please
contact: </P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Mrs Glen Howard, Administrative Secretary<BR>
Research Centre for International Law<BR>
5 Cranmer Road<BR>
Cambridge CB3 9BL<BR>
United Kingdom</P>

<P>Telephone: (+44) 1223 335 358<BR>
Facsimile: (+44) 1223 300 406<BR>
Email: <A HREF="mailto:gh10008@hermes.cam.ac.uk">gh10008@hermes.cam.ac.uk</A></P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
