<HEAD><TITLE>The Legal List - Introduction</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>Chapter 0.  Introduction to <i>The Legal List</i></H1>
<PRE>
This chapter gives an overview of <i>The Legal List</i> and of the Internet.

<H2>0.1.  About This Book - What is <i>The Legal List</i>?</H2>

<i>The Legal List</i> is the short, historical, name of this book, <i>The 
Legal List, Fall 95 Internet Desk Reference</i>.  The purpose of <i>The Legal 
List</i> is to provide a consolidated list of all of the law-related resources 
available on the Internet and elsewhere.

<i>The Legal List</i> was originally created in the summer of 1992 as I was 
preparing to enter the University of Maine School of Law.  Before I started 
law school, I wanted to compile a list of law-related resources that I could 
use as a legal research guide.  I've been on the Internet since 1984, when I 
was was a freshman at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), and, 
through the years, I have made a habit of jotting down noteworthy Internet-
accessible resources.  In the summer of 1992, there were few law-related 
resources on the Internet, and there was no comprehensive listing of these 
resources.  With my personal list of noteworthy Internet-accessible resources 
as a starting point, I started to compile a separate list of law-related 
Internet-accessible resources.  I called this list my legal list.  As I 
discussed with others what I had been doing, they began to request copies of 
my list.  In August, 1992, I sent the first version of <i>The Legal List</i> 
via electronic mail (e-mail) to those who had requested it.  Since then, 
<i>The Legal List</i> has been updated approximately every six months.  What 
started as a relatively short list for my own use has grown into the 
relatively large book you are now reading.

Today, <i>The Legal List</i>--or often TLL for short--is available as a 
paperback book, and as an ASCII text-only file, and as a compilations of 
hypertext files on the World-Wide Web (WWW).  As the print-and-pay portion of 
the copyright notice indicates, <i>The Legal List</i> ASCII is free on the 
Internet, but it costs if you print it.  I believe that this arrangement is 
consistent with the spirit of providing free information on the Internet, 
while at the same time allowing for a reasonable compensation from those who 
want the value-added benefit of having a paper copy of <i>The Legal List</i>.  
I use both the paperback version, the ASCII text-only version, and the WWW 
version  of <i>The Legal List</i>.  If I want to find something in the ASCII 
text-only version, I open the file with my word-processing software and do a 
key-word search.  With the paperback version, I look in the index.  With the 
WWW version, I use the search capabilities on LCP's server and on my WWW 
browser.

Since the last edition of <i>The Legal List</i>, the number of law-related 
organizations on the Internet has continued to increase.  <i>The Legal 
List</i> contains information about the following organizations.

- All Federal Government organizations authorized to publish in the <i>Federal 
Register</i> (based on the 1994/95 <i>The United States Government 
Manual</i>).  For Federal Government organizations with no Internet presence, 
I have included USPS addresses and phone numbers.

- All State Governments.  For state governments that do not have their own WWW 
home page, I have listed the page for that state from the W3 Consortium 
(http://www.w3.org).

- All 176 ABA-approved law schools (from the ABA's 01/95 <i>A Review of Legal 
Education in the United States</i>) plus non-ABA approved law schools with an 
Internet presence.  For law schools that do not have a WWW home page, I have 
listed the page of that school's parent educational institution.

- All major legal vendors (most of whom are members of the National 
Association of Legal Vendors) with a WWW presence.

- All <i>Fortune 500</i> publishers with a WWW presence.

- All of the 1st-100th largest US law firms with an Internet presence (from 
the 08/95 <i>The American Lawyer</i>).

- All of the 101st-250th largest US law firms with an Internet presence (from 
the 10/94 <i>The National Law Journal</i>).

- E-mail, WWW, Gopher, listserv list, FTP, BBS, and telnet resources made 
available by the above.

All <i>Fortune 500</i. publishers, <i>American Lawyer 100</i> law firms, and 
<i>National Law Journal 250</i> law firms are identified as such.  For the WWW 
version of <i>The Legal List</i>, additional information is included for many 
organizations.  Also, each organization has its own WWW page.  Organizations 
with an e-mail address (and with access to the submission form at 
http://www.lcp.com/The-Legal-List/submission.html) can use <i>The Legal 
List</i> as their home on the WWW.

<i>The Legal List</i> continues to focus on the sponsor of the law-related 
resources, in part to encourage the reader to consider the source of the 
material.  (For example, listserv lists with an identifiable law-related 
sponsor are now listed with the sponsor.)  For Internet users who want 
reliable information, it is important to know whether material is being 
published by a government organization based on a statute or regulation, by a 
corporation for profit, or by an individual as a hobby, for fun, or for 
profit.  If Internet users, as taxpayers, want more from their government, 
then they should demand more.  If Internet users, as customers, want more from 
companies, then they should demand more.  If Internet users, as Net citizens, 
want more from the Internet, then they can contribute to the Internet 
community themselves by publishing material on the Internet.  The 
Legal/Internet community is strong and growing.  The following table indicates 
that it will soon be the rule, rather than the exception, that a law-related 
organization is on the Internet.

Type of Organization          WWW Presence (%)      Registered Domain (%)
--------------------          ----------------      ---------------------
State Governments                     95                     85
Law Schools                           85                     95
Legal Corporations/Vendors            80                     70
Fortune 500 Publishers                40                     80
Federal Government Agencies           25                     40
American Lawyer 100 Law Firms         20                     60
National Law Journal 250 Law Firms    10                     40

The above numbers require some explanation.  Because alternate WWW pages are 
listed in <i>The Legal List</i> for law schools and state government 
organizations, the actual percentage of these organizations with a WWW 
presence is slightly lower than reported above.  I have organized <i>The Legal 
List</i> in this fashion in order to make it easier for the user to find a 
particular organization.

The only requirements for a resource to be listed in <i>The Legal List</i> are 
that 1) it must be law-related, and 2) it must be on the Internet.  In order 
to manage the large number or requests to be listed, entries can only be 
accepted from the submission form (http://www.lcp.com/The-Legal-
List/submission.html).  I have endeavored to improve <i>The Legal List</i> 
based on suggestions from the Internet community.  As always, the best way to 
keep abreast of changes with <i>The Legal List</i> is to subscribe to one of 
the listserv lists (legal-list or TLL-announce) dedicated to <i>The Legal 
List</i>.

Thank you for your interest in <i>The Legal List</i>, and I hope you find this 
edition useful!

0.1.1.  Disclaimer.

I am committed to providing high-quality information, and as such, I have 
tried to verify all of the information in <i>The Legal List</i>.  The 
appearance of any resource in <i>The Legal List</i> does not constitute 
endorsement of approval of the resource by the author, editors, and publisher 
of <i>The Legal List</i>.  The author, editor, and publisher of <i>The Legal 
List</i> have made reasonable efforts to provide correct information, but the 
author, editor, and publisher cannot guarantee the accuracy of the information 
in <i>The Legal List</i>.  Updates, additions, and corrections to <i>The Legal 
List</i> should be submitted via http://www.lcp.com/The-Legal-
List/submission.html.

0.1.2.  Organization of <i>The Legal List</i>.

The Legal List is primarily organized by the sponsoring organization of the 
law-related resource.  Resources that are sponsored primarily by an 
individual, and not by the organization for which the individual works, are 
included in Chapter 6, because it is often difficult to distinguish the sole 
proprietor from the hobbyist.

Certain typographical conventions should also be pointed out.  Items that 
should be interpreted are listed in italics.  For example, If I were 
instructed to type <i>your name</i>, I would type <i>Erik J.  Heels</i>.  
Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) are listed for each Internet resource.  I 
have followed the conventions outlined in RFC (Request for Comments) 1738 
(12/94) and 1808 (06/95).  The URLs for these standards are

URL:  http://ds.internic.net/rfc/rfc1738.txt
URL:  http://ds.internic.net/rfc/rfc1808.txt

In general, the URL will be in the format of connection-
method://machine/path/file.  In the above example, the connection-method is 
http, the machine is ds.internic.net, and  path is /rfc, and the files are 
rfc1738.txt and rfc1808.txt.  In this example, the final part of the path name 
contains the file name, but not all URLs contain file names.  WWW servers can 
be configured to serve a default file (usually called home.html, index.html, 
or default.html) to the client computer.  For example, the following URLs are 
equivalent.

URL:  http://www.lcp.com/The-Legal-List
URL:  http://www.lcp.com/The-Legal-List/
URL:  http://www.lcp.com/The-Legal-List/home.html 

The following is a chapter summary of The Legal List:

Chapter 0.  Introduction to <i>The Legal List</i>.  This chapter gives an 
overview of <i>The Legal List</i> and of the Internet.

Chapter 1.  Talk, Talk, Talk.  This chapter contains information about law-
related listserv lists, BBSs, and Usenet newsgroups.  Listserv lists are like 
magazines in that one can subscribe and unsubscribe.  There are lists for a 
wide range of law-related interests such as intellectual property, civil 
rights, and issues of interest to law students.  Usenet is the news network 
that is intertwined with, but independent from, the Internet.

Chapter 2.  Federal Government.  This chapter contains information about US 
Federal Government organizations.  All Federal Government organizations 
authorized to publish in the <i>Federal Register</i> (based on the 1994/95 
<i>The United States Government Manual</i>) are listed.  For Federal 
Government organizations with no Internet presence, I have included USPS 
addresses and phone numbers.  An organization in this chapter would most 
likely have a domain name ending in .gov (government).

Chapter 3.  State Governments.  This chapter contains information about all US 
State Governments.  For state governments that do not have their own WWW home 
page, I have listed the page for that state from the W3 Consortium 
(http://www.w3.org).  An organization in this chapter would most likely have a 
domain name ending in .gov (government) or .us (United States).

Chapter 4.  Law Schools.  This chapter contains information about US law 
schools.  All 176 ABA-approved law schools (from the ABA's 01/94 <i>A Review 
of Legal Education in the United States</i>) plus non-ABA approved law schools 
with an Internet presence are listed.  For law schools that do not have a WWW 
home page, I have listed the page of that school's parent educational 
institution.  An organization in this chapter would most likely have a domain 
name ending in .edu (education).

Chapter 5.  Other Educational Institutions.  This chapter contains information 
about other US educational institutions.  An organization in this chapter 
would most likely have a domain name ending in .edu (education).

Chapter 6.  Corporations Et Cetera.  This chapter contains information about 
for-profit, nonprofit, and not-for-profit corporations and organizations.  All 
<i>Fortune 500</i> publishers with a WWW presence are listed.  All major legal 
vendors (most of whom are members of the National Association of Legal 
Vendors) with a WWW presence are listed.  This chapter also includes resources 
primarily made available by individuals rather than by an organizations, 
governments, or educational institutions.  An organization in this chapter 
would most likely have a domain name ending in .com (commercial) or .org 
(organization).

Chapter 7.  Law Firms.  This chapter contains information about law firms.  
All of the 1st-100th largest US law firms with an Internet presence (from the 
08/95 <i>The American Lawyer</i>) are listed and identified as such.  All of 
the 101st-250th largest US law firms with an Internet presence (from the 10/94 
<i>The National Law Journal</i>) are listed and identified as such.  The state 
or country of the primary office (or of the largest office if there is no 
primary office) is listed in parentheses following the name of the firm.  An 
organization in this chapter would most likely have a domain name ending in 
.com (commercial).

Chapter 8.  Non-US Resources.  This chapter contains information about non-US 
organizations, governments, and educational institutions including the United 
Nations.

Appendix.  More About the Internet.  This appendix contains, for example, 
information about Internet access providers.

0.1.3.  How to Get Paperback and Electronic Copies of <i>The Legal List</i>.

0.1.3.1.  Listserv Lists.

There are two listserv lists available:

1) Full text delivery of <i>The Legal List</i> - <b>legal-list</b>.

<i>The Legal List</i> is available via e-mail via the listserv list legal-
list@listserv.lcp.com.

To subscribe to legal-list, send a message with "subscribe legal-list <i>your 
name</i>" in the body of the message to the following address.

URL: mailto:listserv@listserv.lcp.com

The next version of <i>The Legal List</i> (as well as other announcements) 
will be mailed to those who subscribe.  I always like to hear where you 
learned about <i>The Legal List</i>, so if you also include this information 
in the body of the message, I would greatly appreciate it!

To cancel your subscription to legal-list, send a message with "unsubscribe 
legal-list" in the body of the message to the following address.

URL: mailto:listserv@listserv.lcp.com

2) Announcements only - <b>TLL-announce</b>.

If you wish receive only announcements about the next version of <i>The Legal 
List</i>, send a message with "subscribe TLL-announce <i>your name</i>" in the 
body of the message to the following address.

URL: mailto:listserv@listserv.lcp.com

TLL-announce subscribes will receive all of the announcements that legal-list 
subscribers receive, but TLL-announce subscribers will not receive the next 
version of <i>The Legal List</i> via e-mail.  I always like to hear where you 
learned about <i>The Legal List</i>, so if you also include this information 
in the body of the message, I would greatly appreciate it!

To cancel your subscription to TLL-announce, send a message with "unsubscribe 
TLL-announce" in the body of the message to the following address.

URL: mailto:listserv@listserv.lcp.com

0.1.3.2.  Updates, Additions, and Corrections.

Updates, additions, and corrections to <i>The Legal List</i> should be 
submitted via http://www.lcp.com/The-Legal-List/submission.html.

0.1.3.3.  Internet Servers (FTP, and WWW).

<i>The Legal List</i> is available via anonymous FTP and WWW.

Domain:  lcp.com
WWW:  http://www.lcp.com
FTP:  ftp://ftp.lcp.com/pub/LegalList/legallist.txt

