<H1>Chapter 1.  Talk, Talk, Talk</H1>
<PRE>
SHORT DESCRIPTION:
This chapter contains information about law-related listserv lists, BBSs, and 
Usenet newsgroups.  Listserv lists are like magazines in that one can 
subscribe and unsubscribe.  There are lists for a wide range of law-related 
interests such as intellectual property, civil rights, and issues of interest 
to law students.  BBSs, or Bulletin Board Systems, are essentially computers 
with one or more dial-in modem lines. Usenet is the news network that is 
intertwined with, but independent from, the Internet.

One of the best ways to find the e-mail address for a particular individual is 
to call that individual.  If you choose to contact the individuals in this 
chapter via e-mail, please keep your e-mail message short and to-the-point.

1.1.  Listserv Lists.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
Many law-related listserv lists exist on the Internet.  The most comprehensive 
listing of listserv lists is <i>Law Lists</i> by Lyonette Louis-Jacques.  
Lyonette's <i>Law Lists</i> is updated frequently and contains hundreds of 
law, government, and political-related lists.  See "Law Lists" in Chapter 6.

In this edition of <i>The Legal List</i> I've decided to put listservs 
sponsored by a particular group or organization in the listing for the 
organization. Because all lists which are sponsored by a law-related 
organization are now included in the listing of the organization, you will 
find entries for listservs scattered throughout the following chapters on  
government organizations, law schools, other educational institutions, 
corporations, and law firms, if any of those organizations sponsors a 
listserv. The list servers included in this chapter are here because the 
sponsoring organization is <i>not</i> necessarily law-related, and I had to 
put them somewhere!  Note that several lists may be included under a single 
'List Server" entry.

For how to subscribe, post, and unsubscribe to listserv lists, see Section 
0.2.4.6.  Note that some lists are based outside of the US, and, as such, they 
concentrate on the law of the host country.  For example, the lists ending in 
".uk" are based in the United Kingdom.  See  the Appendix for a complete 
listing of the two-letter country codes.

1.1.01.  List Server - Listproc@israel.nysernet.ORG.

