<BODY>

<H1>Chapter 2.  Federal Government</H1>
<PRE>
SHORT DESCRIPTION:
This chapter contains information about US Federal Government organizations.  
All Federal Government organizations authorized to publish in the <i>Federal 
Register</i> (based on the 1994/95 <i>The United States Government Manual</i>) 
are listed.  For Federal Government organizations with no Internet presence, I 
have included USPS addresses and phone numbers.  An organization in this 
chapter would most likely have a domain name ending in .gov (government).

In addition to information about how to contact each of these organizations, I 
have included information about the history of and statutory authority for 
each organization (also based on the 1994/95 <i>The United States Government 
Manual</i>).

One of the best ways to find the e-mail address for a particular individual is 
to call that individual.  If you choose to contact the individuals in this 
chapter via e-mail, please keep your e-mail message short and to-the-point.

2.1.  Executive Branch.

2.1.1.  White House Offices.

2.1.1.1.  The President of the United States.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
Article II, Section 1, of the Constitution provides that "the executive Power 
shall be vested in a President of the United States of America.  He shall hold 
his Office during the Term of four Years, ... together with the Vice 
President, chosen for the same Term ...."

2.1.1.2.  Executive Office of the President.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
Under authority of the Reorganization Act of 1939 (5 USCS 133-133r, 133t 
note), various agencies were transferred to the Executive Office of the 
President.  The heads of these agencies are traditionally afforded Cabinet-
level rank.  The Cabinet, a creation of custom dating back to George 
Washington's administration, functions at the pleasure of the President.  Its 
purpose is to advise the President on any subject.  Its members include the 
heads of the fourteen executive departments and any others whom the President 
may designate.

Domain:  eop.gov

2.1.1.2.1.  Council of Economic Advisors.

NAME AND ADDRESS:
Council of Economic Advisors
Old Executive Office Building
Washington, DC  20500
Phone:  202-395-5084

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Council of Economic Advisors primary performs an analysis and appraisal of 
the national economy for the purpose of providing policy recommendations to 
the President.  Established in 1946 (15 USCS 1023) (1946), it now functions 
according to Reorganization Plan No. 9 of 1953 (5 USCS app.) (1953).

Domain:  None.

2.1.1.2.2.  Council on Environmental Quality.

NAME AND ADDRESS:
Council on Environmental Quality
722 Jackson Place NW
Washington, DC  20503
Phone:  202-395-5754

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
Established by the National Environmental Policy Act of 1969 (42 USCS 4341 et 
seq.) (1969) to formulate and recommend national policies to promote the 
improvement and the quality of the environment.

Domain:  None.

2.1.1.2.3.  National Security Council.

NAME AND ADDRESS:
National Security Council
Old Executive Office Building
Washington, DC  20506
Phone:  202-456-7430

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Council advises and assists the President in integrating all aspects of 
national security policy.  Established by the National Security Act of 1947, 
as amended (50 USCS 402) (1947) and placed in the Executive Office of the 
President by Reorganization Plan No. 4 of 1949 (5 USCS app.).

Domain:  None.

2.1.1.2.4.  Office of Administration.

NAME AND ADDRESS:
Office of Administration
Old Executive Office Building
725 Seventeenth Street NW
Washington, DC  20503
Phone:  202-395-6963

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Office of Administration provides administrative support services to all 
units within the Executive Office of the President.  Established by 
Reorganization Plan No. 1 of 1977 (5 USCS app.) and activated by Executive 
Order 12028 of Dec. 12, 1977.

Domain:  None.

2.1.1.2.5.  Office of Management and Budget.

NAME AND ADDRESS:
Office of Management and Budget
Executive Office Building
Washington, DC  20503
Phone:  202-395-3080

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Office of Management and Budget evaluates, formulates, and coordinates 
management procedures and program objectives within and among Federal 
departments and agencies.  It also controls the administration of the Federal 
budget, while routinely providing the President with recommendations regarding 
budget proposals and relevant legislative enactments.  Established by 
Reorganization Plan No. 1 of 1939 (5 USCS app.).

Domain:  omb.gov

2.1.1.2.6.  Office of National Drug Control Policy.

NAME AND ADDRESS:
Office of National Drug Control Policy
Executive Office of the President
Washington, DC  20500
Phone:  202-395-6700

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Office of National Drug Control Policy coordinates Federal, State, and 
local efforts to control illegal drug abuse.  Established by the National 
Narcotics Leadership Act of 1988 (21 USCS 1501 et seq.) (1988).

Domain:  None.

2.1.1.2.7.  Office of Science and Technology Policy.

NAME AND ADDRESS:
Office of Science and Technology Policy
Old Executive Office Building
Washington, DC  20500
Phone:  202-456-6021

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Office serves as a source of scientific, engineering, and technical 
analysis and judgment for the President with respect to major policies, plans, 
and programs of the Federal Government.  Established by the National Science 
and Technology Policy, Organization, and Priorities Act of 1976 (42 USCS 6611) 
(1976).

Domain:  None.

2.1.1.2.8.  Office of the United States Trade Representative.

NAME AND ADDRESS:
Office of the United States Trade Representative
600 Seventeenth Street NW
Washington, DC  20506
Phone:  202-395-3230

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The United States Trade Representative is responsible for directing all trade 
negotiations of and formulating trade policy for the United States.  
Established by Executive Order 11075 of January 15, 1963.  Reorganized into 
the Executive Office of the President under the Trade Act of 1974 (19 USCS 
2171) (1974).

Domain:  None.

2.1.1.2.9.  White House Office, The.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The White House Office serves the President in the performance of the many 
detailed activities incident to his immediate office.

This site provides press releases, briefings, speeches, and more.

Domain:  whitehouse.gov
E-mail:  mailto:Publications@Research.AI.MIT.EDU (with "help" as the subject)
WWW:  http://www.whitehouse.gov

2.1.1.3.  Office of the Vice President.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
In addition to his role as President of the Senate, the Vice President is 
empowered to succeed to the Presidency, pursuant to Article II and the 20th 
and 25th Amendments to the Constitution.  The executive functions of the Vice 
President include participation in Cabinet meetings and, by statute, 
membership on the National Security Council and the Board of Regents of the 
Smithsonian Institution.

Domain:  None.

2.1.1.3.1.  FinanceNet.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
FinanceNet's mission is to innovate and optimize the way governments manage 
and account for taxpayer resources.  FinanceNet is staffed by dedicated 
volunteers and is associated with the NetResults network of people and 
reinvention teams at   Vice President Gore's office of the National 
Performance Review in Washington, D.C.

Domain:  financenet.gov
WWW:  http://www.financenet.gov

2.1.1.3.2.  National Peformance Review.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore charged the National Performance 
Review with creating a new customer service contract with the American people, 
a guarantee of effective, efficient, and responsive government. Our goal is to 
make government work better and cost less.

Domain:  npr.gov
WWW:  http://www.npr.gov

2.1.1.3.3.  US Business Advisor.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
Service and information that government offers to businesses.

Domain:  business.gov
WWW:  http://www.business.gov

2.1.2.  Departments.

2.1.2.01.  Department of Agriculture.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Department of Agriculture works to improve and maintain farm income and to 
develop and expand markets abroad for agricultural products.  Established by 
the act of May 15, 1862 (7 USCS 2201) (1862).  Duties enlarged by the act of 
Feb. 9, 1889 (7 USCS 2202, 2208, 2212) (1889).  Department of Agriculture 
agencies include the Forest Service and the Farmers Home Administration.

Domain:  usda.gov
WWW:  http://www.usda.gov
Gopher:  gopher://gopher.usda.gov

2.1.2.02.  Department of Commerce.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Department of Commerce encourages, serves, and promotes the Nation's 
international trade, economic growth, and technological advancement.  
Established by the act of Feb. 14, 1903 (15 USCS 1501) (1903).  Department of 
Commerce agencies include the Bureau of Economic Analysis, Bureau of Export 
Administration, Bureau of the Census, Economic Development Administration, 
International Trade Administration, Minority Business Development Agency, 
National Institute of Standards and Technology, National Oceanic and 
Atmospheric Administration, National Technical Information Service, National 
Telecommunications and Information Administration, United States Patent and 
Trademark Office, and the United States Travel and Tourism Administration.

Domain:  doc.gov
WWW:  http://www.doc.gov

2.1.2.02.1.  National Technical Information Service.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
FedWorld provides access to detailed information from over 50 agencies and 
includes access to online ordering services, federal jobs opportunities, and 
dial-up access to other Government information systems (Gateway).

Domain:  fedworld.gov
WWW:  http://www.fedworld.gov
FTP:  ftp://ftp.fedworld.gov
Telnet:  telnet://fedworld.gov
BBS Phone:  (703) 321-3339

2.1.2.03.  Department of Defense.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Department of Defense is responsible for providing the military forces 
needed to deter war and protect the security of the United States.  The DOD is 
the successor to the National Military Establishment created by the National 
Security Act of 1947 (50 USCS 401) (1947).  Established as an executive 
department by the National Security Act Amendments of 1949 (5 USCS 101) 
(1949).

Domain:  dla.mil
WWW:  http://www.dtic.dla.mil/defenselink
Gopher:  gopher://gopher.dtic.dla.mil
Telnet:  
BBS Phone:  (703) 321-3339

2.1.2.04.  Department of Education.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Department of Education's mission is to ensure access to education and to 
promote educational excellence throughout the Nation.  Established by the 
Department of Education Organization Act (20 USCS 3411) (1979).

Domain:  ed.gov
WWW:  http://www.ed.gov
Gopher:  gopher://gopher.ed.gov

2.1.2.05.  Department of Energy.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Department of Energy is responsible for long-term, high-risk research and 
development of energy technology; the marketing of Federal power; energy 
conservation; the nuclear weapons program; energy regulatory programs; and 
central energy data collection and analysis program.  Established by the 
Department of Energy Organization Act (42 USCS 7131) (1977) pursuant to 
Executive Order 12009 of Sep. 13, 1977.

Domain:  doe.gov
WWW:  http://www.doe.gov

2.1.2.06.  Department of Health and Human Services.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Department of Health and Human Services touches the lives of more 
Americans than any other Federal agency.  Established on Apr. 11, 1953.  
Renamed by the Department of Education Reorganization Act (20 USCS 3508) 
(1980).  HHS agencies include the Administration for Children and Families, 
Administration on Aging, Agency for Health Care Policy and Research, Agency 
for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry, Centers for Disease Control and 
Prevention, Food and Drug Administration, Health Care Financing 
Administration, Health Resources and Services Administration, Indian Health 
Service, National Institutes of Health, Public Health Service, and the 
Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration.

Domain:  dhhs.gov
WWW:  http://www.os.dhhs.gov
Gopher:  gopher://gopher.os.dhhs.gov
LISTSERV LISTS:
LISTSERV@LIST.NIH.GOV

GILS-L (DHHS Government Information Locator Service)

2.1.2.07.  Department of Housing and Urban Development.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Department of Housing and Urban Development is the principal Federal 
agency responsible for programs concerned with the Nation's housing needs, 
fair housing opportunities, and improvement and development of the Nation's 
communities.  Established by the Department of Housing and Urban Development 
Act (42 USCS 3532-3537) (1965).  HUD agencies include the Federal Housing 
Finance Board, Government National Mortgage Association, and the Interagency 
Council on the Homeless.

Domain:  hud.gov
WWW:  http://www.hud.gov
Gopher:  gopher://gopher.hud.gov

2.1.2.08.  Department of Justice.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
As the largest law firm in the Nation, the Department of Justice serves as 
counsel for its citizens.  It represents them in enforcing the law in the 
public interest.  Established by the act of Jun. 22 1870 (28 USCS 501, 503) 
with the Attorney General as its head.  The Office of Attorney General was 
created by the act of Sep. 24, 1789, as amended (28 USCS 503) (1789).  DOJ 
agencies include the Bureau of Prisons, Drug Enforcement Administration, 
Federal Bureau of Investigation, Immigration and Naturalization Service, 
Office of the Solicitor General, United States Attorneys, United States 
Marshall Service, United States National Central Bureau (INTERPOL), and the 
United States Parole Commission.

Domain:  usdoj.gov
WWW:  http://www.usdoj.gov
Gopher:  gopher://gopher.usdoj.gov

2.1.2.09.  Department of Labor.

NAME AND ADDRESS:
Department of Labor
200 Constitution Avenue NW
Washington, DC  20210
Phone:  202-219-5000

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The purpose of the Department of Labor is to foster, promote, and develop the 
welfare of the wage earners of the United States, to improve their working 
conditions, and to advance their opportunities for profitable employment.  
Established by the act of Mar. 4, 1913 (29 USCS 551) (1913).  Department of 
Labor agencies include the Bureau of Labor Statistics, Employment and Training 
Administration, Employment Standards Administration, Mine Safety and Health 
Administration, Occupational Safety and Health Administration, Pension and 
Welfare Benefits Administration, and the Veterans' Employment and Training 
Service.

Domain:  doleta.gov

