<H1>2.2.  Judicial Branch</H1>
<PRE>
2.2.1.  The Supreme Court of the United States.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
Article III, Section 1, of the Constitution of the United States provides that 
"[t]he judicial Power of the United States, shall be vested in one supreme 
Court, and in such inferior Courts as the Congress may from time to time 
ordain and establish."  The Supreme Court of the United States was created in 
accordance with this provision and by the authority of the Judiciary Act of 
Sep. 24, 1789 (1 Stat. 73) (1789).  The Supreme Court comprises the Chief 
Justice and eight Associate Justices (28 USCS 1) (1948).

Domain:  None.
WWW:  http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/supct.table.html
FTP:  ftp://ftp.cwru.edu/hermes

2.2.2.  Lower Courts.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The courts of appeal are intermediate appellate courts created by the act of 
Mar. 3, 1891 (28 USCS ch. 3) (1891).  They are empowers to review all final 
decisions and certain interlocutory decisions (18 USCS 3731, 3734; 28 USCS 
1291, 1292) of district courts.  The United States is divided geographically 
into 12 judicial circuits, including the District of Columbia.  Each circuit 
court has a court of appeals (28 USCS 41, 1294).  Each of the 50 States is 
assigned to one of the circuits.

The United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit was established 
under Article III of the Constitution pursuant to the Federal Courts 
Improvement Act of 1982 (28 USCS 1) as successor to the United States Court of 
Customs and Patent Appeals and the United States Court of Claims.  The 
jurisdiction of the court includes appeals from the district courts in patent 
cases, appeals from the district court in contract, and certain other civil 
actions.

The United States District Courts are the trial courts of general Federal 
jurisdiction.  Each State has at least one district court.  Larger states have 
as many as four.  There are 89 district courts in the 50 States, one in the 
District of Columbia, one in the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, one in Guam, and 
one in the Virgin Islands.

Other lower courts include the United States Court of International Trade (28 
USCS 251) (1980) and the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation (28 USCS 
1407) (1968).

2.2.3.  Special Courts.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
Special courts include the United States Court of Federal Claims (28 USCS 171) 
(1982), (28 USCS 1, note, 106 Stat. 4516) (1992); the United States Court of 
Military Appeals (10 USCS 867) (1950); the United States Tax Court (83 Stat. 
730) (1969); and the United States Court of Veterans Appeals (38 USCS 4051) 
(1988).

2.2.4.  Administrative Office of the United States Courts.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The Administrative Office of the United States is charged with the 
nonjudicial, administrative business of the United States Courts, including 
the maintenance of workload statistics and the disbursement of funds 
appropriated for the maintenance of the US judicial system.  Created by the 
act of Aug. 7, 1939 (28 USCS 601) (1939).

This site serves as a clearinghouse for information from and about the 
Judicial Branch of the U.S. courts. Current offerings include (1) 
"Understanding the Courts", hypertext document describing the U.S. Federal 
Courts, (2) "The Third Branch", selected articles published in the monthly 
newsletter, (3) Recent Press Releases from the U.S. Judicial Conference and 
A.O., and (4) official "Directory of Electronic Public Access Services", 
updated monthly.

All federal circuit courts offer access via BBSs to appellate court decisions 
(slip opinions) and other court information (e.g. case dockets, local court 
rules, and press releases).  User fees have been approved by the Judicial 
Conference and will be instituted during 1995 on a circuit-by-circuit basis. 

In addition, district and bankruptcy courts are beginning to offer electronic 
access to court orders, opinions, and rules.  User fees for this service have 
been or will be instituted in most courts. Persons desiring to use this 
service must first register with the registration center (800-676-6856).

The PACER Service Center BBS has been established by the federal court's 
centralized registration and billing service in San Antonio, Texas.  This new 
BBS (800-214-0847) is available at no charge to existing registrants (24 hours 
a day, 7 days a week).  This BBS 1) provides an updated listing of courts 
serviced by the service center; 2) allows users to automatically register for 
additional courts and change passwords; 3) reviews user's billing history for 
all courts nationwide; 4) provides user manuals and status of each court's 
PACER system (e.g., courts with computer disruptions or other technical 
problems); and 5) allows users to leave messages and comments for service 
center personnel.

For the BBSs listed in the following sections, all modem setting are N/8/1 (no 
parity, 8 bits, 1 stop bit) unless indicated otherwise (i.e. E/7/1 = even 
parity, 7 bits, 1 stop bit).

Domain:  uscourts.gov
WWW:  http://www.uscourts.gov

