<H1>  Chapter 7.  Law Firms</H1>
<PRE>
SHORT DESCRIPTION:
This chapter contains information about law firms.  All of the 1st-100th 
largest US law firms with an Internet presence (from the 08/95 <i>The American 
Lawyer</i>) are listed and identified as such.  All of the 101st-250th largest 
US law firms with an Internet presence (from the 10/94 <i>The National Law 
Journal</i>) are listed and identified as such.  The state or country of the 
primary office (or of the largest office if there is no primary office) is 
listed in parentheses following the name of the firm.  An organization in this 
chapter would most likely have a domain name ending in .com (commercial).

Communication with a lawyer or law firm by e-mail, including use of 
information resources provided by a law firm via a WWW server or other 
Internet resource, <i>does not</i> necessarily, without an explicit mutual 
agreement, create an attorney-client relationship.  A lawyer-client 
relationship can be created by e-mail only by a direct and explicit agreement, 
confirmed by the lawyer or law firm and the client.  No implicit agreement can 
be asserted.  Accordingly, great care should be taken not to communicate 
information deemed confidential absent such explicit confirmation.  Contact 
your local bar association if you are in doubt about the law in your 
jurisdiction.

The law firms listed here are under no obligation to keep any information you 
send them confidential until after they agree to form a lawyer-client 
relationship with you.  You should use e-mail or any information services 
lawyers or firms provide via the Internet only as a means of learning more 
about a lawyer or firm.  If a lawyer or firm does agree to represent you, you 
should then discuss how best to exchange confidential information.

The firms listed below are on the Internet.  Nearly all of them subscribe to 
<i>The Legal List</i>.  All of the firms below are accessible via e-mail, some 
have gone the extra step of establishing their own domain name, and some have 
gone even further, providing a WWW server.  Note that the information below, 
except where it was already available on the Internet, was provided by the 
individual law firms.

One of the best ways to find the e-mail address for a particular individual is 
to call that individual.  If you choose to contact the individuals in this 
chapter via e-mail, please keep your e-mail message short and to-the-point.

