<H1>  Appendix.  More About the Internet</H1>
<PRE>
SHORT DESCRIPTION:
This appendix contains, for example, information about Internet access 
providers.

A.1.  Internet Service Providers.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
Over the last several years, there has been an exponential increase in the 
number of companies providing Internet access services.  There are so many, in 
fact, that they cannot all be listed here.  But until Internet access 
providers figure out that they should be advertising under "Internet" in the 
telephone yellow pages, the catch-22 remains a frustrating reality for those 
who want to get on the Internet:  that the best way to find an Internet 
service provider is get on the Internet and review your options.  For example, 
one of the best places to find an Internet service provider is The List 
(http://www.thelist.com), which lists and reviews companies by area code.  
Here is a short list of some of the major players in this field.  UUNET and 
Microsoft; BBN and AT&T

Nationwide Internet Access Providers

Bolt, Beranek & Newman Inc. (BBN) (http://www.bbn.com)
NETCOM On-Line Communications, Inc. (http://www.netcom.com)
Performance Systems International, Inc. (PSI) (http://www.psi.com)
UUNET Technologies (http://www.uu.net)

Telecommunications Companies

Ameritech (http://www.ameritech.com)
AT&T Corp. (http://www.att.com)
Bell Atlantic (http://www.bell-atl.com)
Bellcore (http://www.bellcore.com)
BellSouth (http://www.bst.bls.com)
MCI Telecommunications, Inc. (http://www.mci.com)
NYNEX (http://www.niyp.com)
Pacific Bell (http://www.pacbell.com)
Southwestern Bell (http://www.sbc.com)
Sprint, Inc. (http://www.sprint.com)
US West (http://www.uswest.com)

On-Line Service Providers

America Online, Inc. (http://www.aol.com)
CompuServe.(a division of H&R Block) (http://www.compuserve.com)
GEnie.(a division of GE Information Services) (http://www.genie.com)
Microsoft (http://www.msn.com)
Prodigy.(a joint venture of IBM and Sears) (http://www.prodigy.com)

A.2.  Two-Letter Country Codes.

SHORT DESCRIPTION:
The International Standards Organization standard ISO 3166 defines two-letter, 
three-letter, and numeric codes for countries.  With a few exceptions (most 
notably "UK" for the United Kingdom), the ISO 3166 two-letter codes are being 
used by the Internet mail system and in Internet domain name addresses.  

Country  A2 A3 Number

