<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Business Organisation
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Business Organisation
 </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/bloom.htm">Bankruptcy's Fresh Start vs. Enviromental Cleanup: Statutory Schizophrenia</A> by Micheal A.  <STRONG>Bloom</STRONG><I> Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1.</I> This article takes a hard look at the exacerbating conflict between bankruptcy and environmental law, especially after the Third Circuit's recent decision in In re Torwico Electronics, Inc. 1 First, this Article outlines the two-step analysis required in administering environmental obligations in bankruptcy. Next, it examines the pertinent case law for each step of the analysis. Finally, this Article attempts to craft a synthesized approach to resolving environmental obligations in bankruptcy, taking into account judicial economies, public policy and the objectives of both bankruptcy and environmental laws. In so doing, the author hopes to simplify and clarify one of the most controversial and confusing areas in bankruptcy and environmental law today.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/dine1.html">Corporate Governance, Cadbury and Friendly Societies</A> by Professor Janet <STRONG>Dine</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1.</I> The Cadbury Report upon corporate governance has inspired both the Friendly Societies Act 1992 and also a recently published Code of Practice by the Friendly Societies Commission.  Janet Dine sets out details of this Code and comments upon the significance of the new Cadbury-inspired regime for Friendly Societies. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/simmonds.txt">Curbing Self-Dealing in Corporations: Australia's New Approach</A> by Ralph <STRONG>Simmonds</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993.</I> The traditional approach in countries like Australia has been to rely on the common law fiduciary duties, augmented by specific statutory requirements for particular sorts of transactions perceived to carry a high risk of abuse.  The latest in the line of these requirements is contained in _Corporations Law_, Part 3.2A.  It is distinguished by the breadth of its application, particularly in relation to transactions in corporate groups.   Its greatest novelty lies in its basic rule prohibiting the giving of financial benefits to related parties unless approval by a majority of disinterested shareholders is secured. <I> Legislation Note </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/larson.html">Florida's new partnership law: the revised uniform partnership act and limited liability partnerships</A> by John  <STRONG>W. Larson </STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2).</I> After eighty years of nearly uniform and virtually unchanged partnership law, the recent passage of these two laws has ushered in a truly new era of partnership jurisprudence, both in the United States and in Florida. This Article will explain the major changes in partnership law wrought by the Revised Florida Act, identify the Florida nonuniform provisions, and consider the meaning and significance of Florida's limited liability partnership legislation.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/lower1.html">Going Dutch? Who foots the bill in section 459 petitions</A> by Michael <STRONG>Lower</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1.</I> Whether or not the company can play, and fund out of corporate assets, an active role in section 459 proceedings was considered in Re a Company (No 001126 of 1992) and Re Milgate Developments Limited. The latter decision also considers whether a petitioner can obtain an injunction to prevent a company from playing an active part in section 459 proceedings. <I> (casenote) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/lo.html">Improving Corporate Governance: Lessons from the European Community</A> by Benjamin T. <STRONG>Lo</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993.</I>  <I> (note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/bradley.html">In Defense of Abolishing Chapter 11</A> by Michael Rosenzweig and Michael <STRONG>Bradley</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> In this paper we have responded to those who have criticized our call for repeal of Chapter 11. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/mckenzie.txt">Jumping the gun : an examination of the law relating to Securities Issues in Australia</A> by Robert <STRONG>McKenzie</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993.</I> The author argues that the Corporations Law fails to provide an adequate foundation for the effective regulation of "image" advertising, during the period prior to the registration of a prospectus, by corporations intending to issue securities. <I> (work in progress) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/levmore.html">Love It or Leave It: Property Rules, Liability Rules, and Exclusivity of Remedies in Partnership and Marriage</A> by Saul <STRONG>Levmore</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> The traditional rule in partnership law, and the continuing rule in domestic relations law, is that a claim for dissolution (or divorce) is a partner's exclusive remedy. On its face this mandatory "love-it-or-leave-it" rule seems strange, anachronistic, unfair, and inefficient, because where there is going concern value there is room for exploitation. In contrast, corporate law offers a kind of reverse "exclusivity" rule, in that a shareholder can bring a suit for damages but can not force dissolution of the enterprise. These rules offer a window to general questions about remedies. The Calabresi-Melamed property-liability rules framework is expanded with the incorporation not only of rules explored by Polinsky and by Krier and Schwab but also with several seemingly novel rules that draw attention to the possibility of remedies that are only forward-looking or only backward-looking. The critical connection is that the power to "stop" a partnership or a marriage is akin to the power to stop a nuisance, so that love-it-or-leave-it rules can have the character of a "property rule" with no liability component. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/carney.html">Political Economy of Competition for Corporate Charters</A> by William J. <STRONG>Carney</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> This paper explains the differences between American and European corporate laws using interest group theory. Interest groups are described as seeking to extract rents through corporate laws. Their ability to do so is constrained by the mobility of corporations to seek competing corporate laws. A common market provides the optimal competitive setting, and has been present in the U.S. but not in Europe until recently. Evidence of interest group legislation appears far greater in Europe than in the U.S. Further, European nations adopted anticompetitive conflicts of law rules that U.S. states could not adopt, given their competitive setting. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/hicks.html">Protection of Individual Investors Under U.S. Securities Laws :  The Impact of International Regulatory Competition</A> by J. William <STRONG>Hicks</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/michalos.html">Review of "A Pragmatic Approach to Business Ethics" by Alex Michalos</A> reviewed by Richard  <STRONG>Hansen</STRONG><I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1  No. 3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/fukuyama.html">Review of "Trust: The Social Virtues and Creation of Prosperity" by Francis Fukuyama</A> reviewed by Daryl  <STRONG>Koehn</STRONG><I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1  No. 3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/lomnicka2.html">Review of Janet Dine, "Criminal Law in the Company Context".</A> Reviewed by Eva  <STRONG>Lomnicka</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/horwitz.html">Swaps Ahoy! Should Regulators Voyage into Unknown Waters?</A> by Marc A. <STRONG>Horwitz</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/gerde.html">Teaching Business Ethics Through Literature</A> by Jon M. Shepard, Michael G. Goldsby and Virginia W.  <STRONG>Gerde</STRONG><I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1  No. 3.</I> America's economic ideology lacks a vocabulary of ethics. If, as we assume, an economic system requires a moral component for long-term survival, students in business schools must be exposed to a vocabulary of ethics that is consistent with the ideology of capitalism. We present a vocabulary of ethics and describe an approach to teaching business ethics based on business-related classic literature and moral philosophy.    <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/adler.html">Theory of Corporate Insolvency</A> by Barry E <STRONG>Adler</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Modern scholarship on corporate bankruptcy proceeds from the premise that investors are willing to expend resources identifying and saving insolvent firms that can continue efficiently. In this paper, I argue that this premise may be faulty, at least for publicly held firms. Viewed properly, from an ex ante perspective, investors may wish to design initial capital structures that will produce few insolvent but viable firms. Consequently, in a world of unimpeded contractual choice, investors might forgo any collective insolvency process and permit a firm's dismemberment by individual creditors. I argue, accordingly, that corporate bankruptcy law is illegitimate for large firms, not because these firms face no collective action problem among creditors, but because it may be appropriate for these firms to suffer the consequences of any such problem. In the process of making this argument, I offer new explanations for three puzzling phenomena: the apparent investor acquiescience in the expensive American bankruptcy reorganization process; common equity's residual interest in a firm that fails to pay dividends on preferred stock; and asset-based finance. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/peterson.html">Theory Versus Fact in the Choice of Organizational Form: A Study of Body and Frame Production in the Automobile Industry</A> by Laura Bennett Peterson and Thomas G. <STRONG>Marx</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Klein, Crawford and Alchian (hereinafter  "Klein") argue that relationship-specific assets raise problems of opportunism, escalate the cost of market  contracting, and explain General Motors' vertical integration into body manufacturing. We set forth in our paper the theoretical debate between Coase and Klein. Coase understates, we believe, the extent to which the cost of contracts rises with the risk of opportunism. We study the General Motors-Fisher Body relationship after GM's acquisition of its body supplier. A relationship is seen between asset specificity and internal, as well as external, transactions costs. We examine the historical relationships between other automobile companies and their body suppliers. We find a range of customer-supplier relationships -- from total integration, to tapered integration, to no integration and from long-term contracts, to short-term contracts, to no contracts. Such a range of relationships undermines any deterministic conclusion that asset specificity dictates vertical  integration. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/colaw.txt">Understanding Company Law: Computer Tutorials"</A> reviewed by Pei Teing <STRONG>Kee</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994.</I> Student review of a computerised tutorial package for use in teaching Australian company law. <I> (review) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/wood.html">United States Antitrust Law in the Global Market</A> by Diane P. <STRONG>Wood</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
