<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Civil Procedure and Evidence
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Civil Procedure and Evidence
</H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/hoey1.html">Analysis of The Police and Criminal Evidence Act, s.69 - Computer Generated Evidence</A> by Amanda  <STRONG>Hoey </STRONG><I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1.</I> At present there are special rules governing the admissibility of computer-generated evidence in criminal proceedings. In this article the issues of when computer output will be considered direct evidence or hearsay and the reliability of computer-generated evidence are discussed. In conclusion the article attempts to ascertain whether these special rules for computer output are necessary and, if so, whether the conditions established by the statutory provisions are appropriate.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part3.htm">December 1993 amendments to the Federal rules of civil procedure </A> by Leslie M.  <STRONG>Kelleher</STRONG><I> Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/ranson.txt">Expert Evidence"  by Freckleton and Selby</A> reviewed by David L <STRONG>Ranson</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I>  <I> (book review) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/quest.txt">QUEST Evidence Computer Tutorials - A Review</A> by Jeffrey <STRONG>Rosales-Castaneda</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994.</I> A student review of a computer based tutorial for use in teaching Australian evidence law <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/chung.html">Settlement of Litigation under Rule 68: An Economic Analysis</A> by Tai-Yeong <STRONG>Chung</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Rule 68 of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure provides that a plaintiff who refuses a defendant's formal settlement offer and then obtains a judgment not more favorable than the offer must pay the defendant's post-offer costs. An economic analysis is provided (i) to argue that the standard definition of settlement range is not adequate for analyzing Rule 68, because it contains unreasonable, dominated offers, (ii) to present a new definition of the refined settlement range that is adequate for analyzing the effects of Rule 68, and (iii) to propose a revision of Rule 68 to encourage settlements of litigation. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/ogus1.html">Some Reflections on the Woolf Interim Report</A> by Anthony  <STRONG>Ogus</STRONG><I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1.</I> Drawing on law and economics literature, the author critically examines some of the key features of the Woolf Interim Report. The need to constrain lawyers' incentives to escalate costs is paramount and some shift away from the adversarial culture to judicial management is desirable. But care must be exercised in designing new procedures if the changes are not to be self-defeating. There is also a danger of over- optimism regarding proposals for encouraging alternative dispute resolution (ADR). More generally, legal costs will remain a problem so long as professional self-regulation is allowed to imposes fetters on competition.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/ehrhardt.html">Using leading questions during direct examination</A> by Stephanie J. Young and Charles W.  <STRONG>Ehrhardt </STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2).</I> Historically, limitations upon a party's impeaching its own witness and upon using leading questions during direct examination have been intertwined. Clarification of this area began in 1990, when the Florida Legislature amended section 90.608, Florida Statutes, to permit impeachment of a party's own witness. In 1995, the Florida Legislature amended section 90.612(3), Florida Statutes, to provide for the use of leading questions during direct examination. This Article traces the development of the Florida Rules of Civil Procedure and the Florida Statutes from before the adoption of the Florida Evidence Code to the present.  <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
