<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Computers and Law
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Computers and Law
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/caden_lucas.html">Accidents on the Information Superhighway: On-line Liability and Regulation</A> by Stephanie E. Lucas and Marc L.  <STRONG>Caden</STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Informatica/Post-1996/Post~1.htm">Anarchy, State, and the Internet: an Essay on Law-Making in Cyberspace</A> by D.G.  <STRONG>Post</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/post.html">Anarchy, State, and the Internet: An Essay on Law-Making in Cyberspace</A> by David G.  <STRONG>Post</STRONG><I> Journal of Online Law  .</I> The legal rules that will govern cyberspace are yet to be clarified. Important as those rules will be, a prior question is "who will make and enforce those rules?" Professor Post examines various "controllers," or points from which rules can issue, ranging from technical network protocols, to private organizations like universities, to Congressional statutes. These controllers vary in their ability to enforce whatever rules they choose to adopt, depending on the existence of conflicting higher-level controllers, and on the possibility that those who are subject to the rules can change jurisdictions to seek a more favorable rule set.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/froomkin.htm">Anonymity and Its Enmities</A> by A. Michael  <STRONG>Froomkin</STRONG><I> Journal of Online Law .</I> Professor Froomkin analyzes the legal status of attempts to ban anonymity. Through a combination of public-key encryption and special "anonymous remailer" computers, messages can be sent over the net with a high degree of certainty that they cannot be traced to their originator. These techniques also make possible the creation of "pseudonymous" personalities. The Supreme Court in the McIntyre case recently struck down state prohibitions on the use of anonymity in the context of political leaflets. But such state laws have generally been very broadly drawn, and have been applied to political speech. The possibility remains that a narrowly drawn statute banning anonymous political speech, or one directed to non-political speech, might nevertheless be upheld.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/myers.html">Apple v. Microsoft: Virtual Identity in the GUI Wars (Note)</A> by Joseph  <STRONG>Myers </STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/stinger.html">Arizona v. Evans: Adapting the Exclusionary Rule to Advancing Computer Technology</A> by C. Maureen  <STRONG>Stinger</STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2f.html">Automating Design Packages for Law</A> by E. <STRONG>Wilson</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1m.html">Building Intelligent Legal Information Systems" by John Zeleznikow & Dan Hunter  </A> reviewed by A.  <STRONG>Terrett</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1g.html">CD-roms - A Law Librarian's Perspective </A> by C.  <STRONG>Cope</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/bookrev/1scott/default.htm">Colin D Long (Ed), "Telecommunications Law and Practise"  2nd Edition </A> Reviewed by Colin  <STRONG>Scott</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1sweden/default.htm">Comments on the EC Data Protection Directive : The View from Sweden</A> by Peter  <STRONG>Seipel</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/halbert.txt">Computer technology and legal discourse : the potential for modern communication technology to challenge legal discourses of authorship and property</A> by Debora <STRONG>Halbert</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/hardy.html">Contracts, Copyright and Preemption in a Digital World </A> by I. Trotter  <STRONG>Hardy </STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1k.html">Cyberspace and the Law: Your Rights and Duties in the On-line World" by Gavino Morin & Edward A. Cavazos </A> reviewed by A.  <STRONG>Charlesworth </STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/katsh.htm">Cybertime, Cyberspace and Cyberlaw</A> by M. Ethan  <STRONG>Katsh </STRONG><I> Journal of Online Law  .</I> Professor Katsh pursues the relationship between time in cyberspace, or "cybertime" as he calls it, and legal doctrines. He speculates that many such doctrines are based explicitly or implicitly on time or our conception of time. He then asks whether the concept of "cybertime", with its accelerated pace, may not cause substantial disruption in these legal doctrines, a disruption not before noted or appreciated.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1eire/default.htm">Data Protection in the Republic of Ireland</A> by Robert  <STRONG>Clark</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/loundy.txt">E-Law 2.0 :  Computer Information Systems Law and System Operator Liability Revisited</A> by David J <STRONG>Loundy</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I> The article examines the current regulatory structure of Cyberspace in the United States.  The article also discusses the liability of the operators/administrators of these systems  ("Sysops") in this context, and includes an examination of the relevant legislation.  The author outlines the difficulties involved in applying current regulatory standards to Cyberspace in general, and contends that the creators of the law need to have an adequate understanding of the technology relevant to computer systems if the laws are to effectively regulate such a rapidly changing area as this <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://sulaw.law.su.OZ.AU:70/00/Law%20Documents/Collection%20of%20various%20Laws%20%28mainly%20from%20U.S.%29/tempest.law">Eavesdropping On the Electromagnetic Emanations of Digital Equipment:  The Laws of Canada, England and the United States</A> by Christopher <STRONG>Seline</STRONG><I>  .</I> This note explores the legal status of a surveillance technology ruefully known as TEMPEST. Using TEMPEST technology the information in any digital device may be intercepted and reconstructed into useful intelligence without the operative ever having to come near his target. The technology is especially useful in the interception of information stored in digital computers or displayed on computer terminals. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/kosten2">EC Data Protection Directive 1995: An Analysis</A> by Chris Pounder and Freddy  <STRONG>Kosten</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2d.htm">Electric Lawyer: From Quill to Computer</A> by D. Wall and K. <STRONG>Reid</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1j.html">Electronic Banking and the Law" (2nd Ed.) By Anu Anora</A> reviewed by A.  <STRONG>Charlesworth </STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/belohlav.html">Ethical Issues of Expert Systems</A> by David Drehmer, Louis Raho, and Jim  <STRONG>Belohlav</STRONG><I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1 * No. 2 *.</I> This study examines ethical considerations related to one of the more recent information technologies, the expert system. Specifically, the study examines the perceptions of 499 computer professionals with respect to contribution and ownership issues arising from expert system usage within organizations. The results indicate that no uniform ethical perspective yet dominates the perceptions of the respondents in assessing expert system applications. Unless ethical differences are resolved, the eventual repercussion will be increasing individual and organizational conflict as greater numbers of expert systems are developed and become a part of organizational operations.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1e.html">Executive Training </A> by N. <STRONG>McDonnell</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I> With all the hype about the information age, it is not surprising that lawyers and other professionals feel that they should learn about computers. But how? This article presents one successful approach at the University of Waikato, NZ.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/issue1/1abdul/">From Academic Tombstones to Living Bazaars - The Changing Shape of Law Reviews</A> by Adbul  <STRONG>Paliwala</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I> Electronic law journals are likely to be successful because they meet a need, the resolution of a crisis in academic journal publishing which cannot fulfill the needs of a fast changing legal information environment. This requires electronic law journals and reviews which promote living intellectual discourse through uptodate and interactive information. However, this requires the overcoming of a number of obstacles, and in particular it is necessary to promote changes in academic legal culture which make writing and reading electronic journals an acceptable activity.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/hein3.html">Harmonised Global Interchange - UNCITRAL's Draft Model Law for Electronic Data Interchange</A> by Gregor <STRONG>Heinrich</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> Traditionally, companies have always conducted and documented a large part of their business on paper. Paper transactions went along with well-developed mechanisms and legal concepts for proving origin, preventing repudiation and maintaining confidentiality. Now, this paper-based tradition is increasingly being abandoned in favour of 'electronic data interchange' (EDI). However, it is generally accepted that electronic exchange of trade data between companies, across business branches and even across borders is ultimately inconceivable without a high degree of standardisation.  A recent initiative by the United Nations Commission on International Trade Law (UNCITRAL) is now trying to fill this gap by creating a set of rules that aim at establishing a global legal framework for EDI. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1dutch/default.htm">Impact of the EC Data Protection Directive on Dutch Data Protection Law</A> by J P  <STRONG>Bergfeld</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1danish/default.htm">Implementation of the European Data Protection Directive : The View from Denmark</A> by Peter  <STRONG>Blume</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/sergienko.html">Incrimination and Cryptographic Keys</A> by Greg S.  <STRONG>Sergienko</STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1b.html">Information Systems and Regulatory Management</A> by J. <STRONG>Bing</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/abbey5.html">Information Technology and the Legal Practice Course</A> by Robert M  <STRONG>Abbey</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5.</I> This article considers four topics. First, it considers the nature of the legal practice course ("LPC") in the context of its stated aims and information technology ("IT"). Secondly, it seeks to review that context in the light of the forms of IT currently used in the legal profession. Thirdly, it reports the results of a survey of the provision of IT within existing legal practice courses. Finally the article concludes with an analysis of the use of IT within one specific LPC and makes some general recommendations.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/issue1/1demuldr/">Is a computer capable of interpreting case law?</A> by R.V. De Mulder and C.J.M.  <STRONG>Combrink-Kuiters</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I> In the near future the complete texts of all the verdicts of the Supreme Court and a selection of lower courts verdicts will be electronically accessible. This will give a new stimulus to jurimetrical research because some techniques can be applied only on digitised material. Particular attention is paid to the question of whether a conceptual technique is capable of deciding whether cases could be classified as 'positive' or 'negative' in the light of a specific legal item. In other words, whether a computer could interpret legal cases with respect to their outcome.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/widdis4.html">Law Courseware: Big Bang or Damp Squib?</A> by Robin  <STRONG>Widdison</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/maher.html">Lawfutures, or Will You Still Need Me, Will You Still Feed Me, When I'm Sixty-Four? (Note)</A> by Stephen T.  <STRONG>Maher</STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1d.html">Lawyering on the Infobahn </A> by V.  <STRONG>Mayer-Schoenberger</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I> This paper presents three models of information processing, three models of legal practice in Europe and four very practical conclusions for lawyering in a digital age.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1 /widdis1.html">Lawyering on the Internet</A> by Robin <STRONG>Widdison</STRONG><I> [1995] No. 1 Web JCLI.</I> This article attempts to show why the Internet is not just a passing fad but also a major step forward in information technology that will have enduring significance both in the workplace and the place of study. Secondly, it seeks to explain the Internet by reference to what it enables users to do rather than in terms of its underlying technologies. Finally, the article examines how the development of the Internet is likely to impact on legal practice and on legal education. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/greinke.txt">Legal Expert Systems: A Humanistic Critique of Mechanical Legal Inference</A> by Andrew <STRONG>Greinke</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994.</I> The author surveys a wide range of computerised expert systems and shows that they invariably rely on pattern-matching and rule application strategies which have been embodied in their inference mechanisms and knowledge representations.  This computational approach is argued to be unsuitable for use with law which presents a domain of intractable complexity arising out of the need to refer to social context and human purpose in resolving legal issues. The author concludes that a better use for computation in legal applications is in the form of decision- support systems that leave legal inference to human agents. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/aiken2.html">Legal knowledge based systems: some observations on the future</A> by Michael <STRONG>Aikenhead</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I> The adoption by AI researchers specialising in law of new AI techniques, such as case based reasoning, neural networks, fuzzy logic, deontic logics and non-monotonic logics, may move closer to achieving an automation of legal reasoning.   Even if these new techniques do not achieve an automation of legal reasoning however, they will still be valuable in better automating office tasks and in providing insights about the nature of law. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3i.html">LINK - The Legal Information Network: Users views</A> by R. Susskind, M. Young, and A. <STRONG>Katz</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/bookrev/1terrett/default.htm">M Ethan Katsch, "Law In A Digital World"</A> Reviewed by Andrew  <STRONG>Terrett</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/lyford.txt">Ministry of Truth Redefined: A Consideration of Privacy and Data Protection Law ...</A> by Jamie H. <STRONG>Lyford</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I> This paper looks at the issue of privacy in light of the information age.  Particular emphasis is made in the Australian context.  National and international laws are also examined. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part5.htm">Multimedia computing:  copyright law's &quot;last stand&quot; </A> by Steven  <STRONG>Pepe</STRONG><I> Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/greguras.txt">Multimedia Content and the Super Highway: Rapid Acceleration or Foot on the Brake?</A> by Sandy Wong, Michael R Egger and Fred <STRONG>Greguras</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2.</I> This article discusses emerging legal issues concerning copyright/patent protection of material used in multimedia applications. Describes existing processes for the administration of copyright/patent material in the US and the deficencies of traditional rights agreements where material is used in multimedia products.  Cites recent reports from Japan concerning the advantages of streamlining copyright/patent administration, and proposes the establishment of a US based copyright/patent clearinghouse for multimedia materials. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3c.html">New Frontiers in Instructional Software</A> by B. <STRONG>Boyd</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>An <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/intros/default.htm">Outline of the European Data Protection Directive</A> by Ian  <STRONG>Lloyd</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3b.html">Place of Computers in Legal Education</A> by H. <STRONG>Collins</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mcgregor.txt">Practical Strategies for Using Computers in Legal Education</A> by Myles McGregor-Lowndes and Alan <STRONG>Davidson</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2.</I> The paper chronicles the past experience and future plans of the School of Accounting Legal Studies Computer Based Education Project at the Queensland University of Technology.  The first part of the paper describes the computer based learning products that have been produced and tested.  The second part of the paper outlines products that are currently under production. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1c.html">Purchasing Decision Support System </A> by A. Hoey and J.  <STRONG>Garvan </STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I> Public procurement law is a complex subject which is continually evolving. As a result of the formation of the single market public procurement has become high profile and all those involved in purchasing are now required to be familiar with legislation operating in the fields of public supplies, works, services and utilities. This paper reports on the development of a computerised decision support tool in public procurement by a team of staff from the University of Ulster.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/wolfson.html">Review of <i>Federal Broadband Law</i> by John Thorne, Peter W. Huber, and Michael K. Kellog</A> Reviewed by Jeffrey A.  <STRONG>Wolfson</STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/aiken2.html">Review of John Zeleznikow and Dan Hunter, Building Intelligent Legal Information Systems: Representation and Reasoning in Law</A> Reviewed by Michael  <STRONG>Aikenhead</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> y <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/lemley.html">Rights of Attribution and Integrity in Online Communications</A> by Mark A.  <STRONG>Lemley</STRONG><I> Journal of Online Law  .</I> Is there a right of attribution in cyberspace? Professor Lemley explores the interrelated rights of attribution, integrity of identity, and anonymity as they apply to electronic communications. A related issue involves net users' rights to integrity of their electronic identities, whether real or pseudonymous. For a reliable online community to develop, users must be able to trust the integrity of the electronic personalities created by themselves and others. Finally, the desire of many Internet users to remain anonymous complicates the exercise of their other rights. Lemley concludes that net users may be able to protect their rights to attribution and the integrity of their electronic personalities only at the risk of losing their right to anonymity.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/burk.html">Trademarks Along the Infobahn: A First Look at the Emerging Law of Cybermarks </A> by Dan L.  <STRONG>Burk </STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/auburn1.html">Usenet News And The Law</A> by Francis <STRONG>Auburn</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1.</I> In Rindos v Hardwick (1994) the Western Australia Supreme Court awarded damages for defamation arising out of an item in a newsgroup published on the Internet. This comment examines the decision and considers its wider implications both for users of the Internet and service providers on the Internet. <I> (casenote) </I><HR>
