<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Conflict of Laws
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Conflict of Laws
 </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/mayss2.html">Statutory Reform of Choice of Law in Tort and Delict: A Bitter Pill or a Cure for the Ill?</A> by Abla  <STRONG>Mayss</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> The common law rules on choice of law in tort in the field of Private International Law have long been criticised. The double-actionability rule in Phillips v Eyre (1868) tended to operate in favour of defendants. The exception, established in Boys v Chaplin (1971) and expanded in the Red Sea Case (1994), had created much uncertainty. This article examines the new provisions in Part III of the Private International Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1995 , and asks whether it is likely to be a cure <I>  </I><HR>
