<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Constitutional and Administrative Law
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Constitutional and Administrative Law
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/thomas1.html">Aldermen, Reasons and Judicial Review</A> by Robert  <STRONG>Thomas</STRONG><I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1.</I> At present there is no general duty upon public authorities to provide reasons for their decisions. The courts have recently increased the situations in which reasons must be given. R v The Mayor and Commonalty and Citizens of the City of London ex parte Matson (transcript, 18th August 1995) is the latest in a line of cases where fairness has been employed to require reasons to be given. However, there is an inherent contradiction within the reasoning employed in such cases, which, if explicated, demonstrates the need for a general duty to give reasons.  <I> (casenote) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/adams.pag">Amicus Brief in Opposition to Florida's Anti-Gay Constitutional Amendment</A> by William E.  <STRONG>Adams, Jr.</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996).</I> This brief was filed in response to a proposed state constitutional amendment in Florida similar to those proposed in Colorado and Oregon prohibiting protection on the basis of sexual orientation, by specifying bases on which protection <I>could</I> be provided.  This brief successfully argued to the court that the amendment violated Florida statutory requirements requiring that its language and its title be clear and unambiguous in that "the only place where it is not made abundantly clear that this initiative is about the rights or lesbians and gay men is in the amendment itself and its ballot title and summary." (Decision reported at  632 So.2d 1018 (Florida 1994)).  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/froomkin.htm">Anonymity and Its Enmities</A> by A. Michael  <STRONG>Froomkin</STRONG><I> Journal of Online Law .</I> Professor Froomkin analyzes the legal status of attempts to ban anonymity. Through a combination of public-key encryption and special "anonymous remailer" computers, messages can be sent over the net with a high degree of certainty that they cannot be traced to their originator. These techniques also make possible the creation of "pseudonymous" personalities. The Supreme Court in the McIntyre case recently struck down state prohibitions on the use of anonymity in the context of political leaflets. But such state laws have generally been very broadly drawn, and have been applied to political speech. The possibility remains that a narrowly drawn statute banning anonymous political speech, or one directed to non-political speech, might nevertheless be upheld.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/onions2.html">Blackstone's Guide to the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994, by Martin Wasik and Richard Taylor</A> reviewed by Helen <STRONG>O'Nions</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I>  <I> (book review) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/jameson.html">Citizen initiative in Florida: an analysis of Florida's constitutional initiative process, issues, and statutory intitiative alternatives </A> by P. K. Jameson and Marsha  <STRONG>Hosack </STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2).</I> This Article examines Florida's constitutional initiative process and describes the constitutional and statutory initiative processes in other states. It then discusses issues about Florida's current constitutional initiative process and addresses several bills introduced during the 1995 Regular Session to revise the current process. The Article concludes that Florida should develop and adopt an indirect statutory initiative procedure. It further concludes that in tandem with insituting a statutory process, Florida should revise the current constitutional initiative process to make it more difficult toamend the constitution.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/profwms.html">European and U.S. Perspectives on Civic Republicanism</A> by David <STRONG>Williams</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/lafferty.html">Florida's capital sentencing jury override: whom should we trust to make the ultimate ethical judgment?</A> by Latour Rey  <STRONG>Lafferty</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2).</I> This article examines Florida's trifurcated capital sentencing scheme, specifically the jury override provision, from its origin to the present. It identifies and analyzes several criticisms of Florida's jury override provision, and examines the potential impact of Florida Committee Substitute for House Bill 1319, which Governor Chiles vetoed on June 14, 1995. Finally, this Article concludes that the Governor's veto was appropriate because Florida's jury override provision represents a valuable balance between the judge and the jury.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/lazos.html">Florida's property rights act: a political quick fix results in a mixed bag of tricks</A> by Sylvia R. Lazos  <STRONG>Vargas </STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2).</I> This Article reviews the political climate that made passage of the 1995 Florida Property Rights Act possible. It articulates an interpretive framework for the Act, briefly describes the law, and applies that framework to key issues posed by the Act. It explains how the settlement order mechanism is a type of decentralized decisionmaking and explores why decentralized decisionmaking is becoming a trend in regulatory reform. It also examines how information asymmetry, transaction costs, perceived risks, and other factors could affect the strategic behavior of property owners and agencies, thereby skewing incentives in the settlement order process. Finally, it suggests reforms that need to be considered in order to avoid results not intended by the Act.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/shelton.html">In search of the lost amendment: challenging federal firearms regulation through the state's right interpretation of the second amendment</A> by Gregory L.  <STRONG>Shelton</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1.</I> This Comment embraces the individual rights interpretation of the Second Amendment which holds that the Second Amendment grants to the citizen the right to keep and bear arms, a right that now flounders between the Scylla of state police and militia powers and the Charybdis of federal regulation. This Comment argues, however, that federal firearms regulation is unconstitutional whether Second Amendment rights are interpreted as belonging to the individual or to the states. The heart of this Comment, thus, proposes and explores constitutional challenges to federal firearms regulation. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/ama.htm">Jury participation as political participation akin to voting</A> by Vikram David <STRONG>Amar</STRONG><I> Cornell LR January 1995.</I> The argument of this Article is that the link between jury service and other rights of political participation is an important part of our overall constitutional structure.  The voting-jury service linkage was recognized by the Framers in the 1780s, by those responsible for drafting the reconstruction amendments and implementing legislation, and still later.   Moreover, each of the groups the Supreme Court has already determined should be protected against discrimination in jury service is also protected by one of the voting discrimination amendments. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/sirwms.html">Law and Administrative Discretion</A> by Sir David <STRONG>Williams Q.C.</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I> Williams proceeds to analyze administrative law development in England. Williams also stresses the relationship between democratic ideals and judicial deference to the decisions of local authorities. He concludes by describing the ever-evolving nature of administrative law in England today, arguing that just as in the 1920s, the underlying approach of the courts to questions in administrative law can only be interpreted by taking into account the multitude of circumstances from which such questions arise. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/rofes.html">Law school and the constitution</A> by Peter K.  <STRONG>Rofes</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1.</I> This essay is a satirical look at constitutional law course descriptions in law school bulletins. The author suggests alternative descriptions that would make bulletins as "fresh and original" as the typical curriculum in the classroom. This essay is part of a larger project in which the author examines different aspects of the American law school. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/kandeva.html">Legal System and American Constitutional Democracy" Edited by Maria Frankowska & Albert P. Melone </A> by Emilia  <STRONG>Kandeva-Spiridonova </STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.qub.ac.uk/1legal.htm">Legal System of Nortern Ireland</A> by Brice <STRONG>Dickson</STRONG><I> Book Chapter .</I> The history and adminstration of the Legal System of Northern Ireland. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/mcc.htm">Mistakes, precedent, and the rise of the administrative state:  toward a constitutional theory of the second best</A> by Peter <STRONG>McCutchen</STRONG><I> Cornell LR November 1994.</I> This Article proposes a form of constitutional damage control.   Under this theory, the Court should adhere to constitutional structures whenever possible.  Nonetheless, the Court should tolerate structures or practices that are conceded to be unconstitutional when such structures or practices have become institutionalized.. Where unconstitutional institutions are allowed to stand based on a theory of precedent, the Court should allow (or even require) the creation of compensating institutions that seek to move governmental structures closer to the constitutional equilibrium. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Constitutional/Mattei2.html">New Ethiopian Constitution: First Thoughts on Ethnical Federalism and the Reception of Western Institutions</A> by U.  <STRONG>Mattei</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/leigh3.html">Prerogative, Legislative Power, and the Democratic Deficit: The Fire Brigades Union Case</A> by Ian <STRONG>Leigh</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> The recent decision of the House of Lords in R v Secretary of State for the Home Department, ex parte Fire Brigades Union [1995] 2 WLR 464 raises important constitutional questions about the extent to which the government is required to seek Parliamentary approval for its policies or may rely instead on prerogative powers. This note considers the implications of the ruling.  It is argued that the House of Lords reached the right decision, but for the wrong reasons. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/birk.html">Protecting truthful advertising by attorney-cpasIbanez v. Florida Department of Business & Professional Regulation, Board of Accountancy, 114 S. Ct. 2084 (1994)</A> by Edward L.  <STRONG>Birk</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1.</I> Sylvia Ibanez advertised her qualifications as a member of the Florida Bar, a certified financial planner, and a certified public accountant. She was reprimanded by the Florida Board of Accountancy. Ibanez challenged the Board decision, and the United States Supreme Court ruled in her favour. This Note examines <i>Ibanez</I> and considers the substantial government interests states must demonstrate before they may regulate truthful commercial speech. It concludes that the <i>Ibanez</I> Court failed in its reasoning and holding to extend - under its own precedent - the maximum possible protection to consumers who may be misled, or at least left uninformed. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1c.html">Purchasing Decision Support System </A> by A. Hoey and J.  <STRONG>Garvan</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I> Public procurement law is a complex subject which is continually evolving. As a result of the formation of the single market public procurement has become high profile and all those involved in purchasing are now required to be familiar with legislation operating in the fields of public supplies, works, services and utilities. This paper reports on the development of a computerised decision support tool in public procurement by a team of staff from the University of Ulster.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/shi.htm">Racist speech, outsider jurisprudence, and the meaning of America</A> by Steven <STRONG>Shiffrin</STRONG><I> Cornell LR November 1994.</I> The argument that first amendment values (such as truth, autonomy, self-expression, and liberty) dictate that racist speech cannot be regulated is ultimately indefensible.  The victims of racist speech should have the primary voice in determining whether sanctions should be imposed in this area.  My argument, therefore, seeks to close a discussion about the first amendment (of course, it will not) and open a discussion about the effectiveness of hate speech regulations in a racist society. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/leigh2.html">Reforming Public Interest Immunity</A> by Ian <STRONG>Leigh</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I> This article makes recommendations for the reform of Public Interest Immunity (PII) against the background of the Matrix Churchill case and of evidence to the Scott Inquiry. Three issues are critically evaluated: the distinction between class and contents claims of immunity, whether ministers should continue to sign PII certificates, and the role of the judiciary in dealing with inspection and disclosure of documents in criminal proceedings. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/berlin.html">Revealing the constitutional infirmities of the "crime victims protection act", Florida's new privacy statute for sexual assault victims </A> by Brett Jarad  <STRONG>Berlin</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2).</I> This Comment attempts to organize the relevant issues surrounding Florida's new privacy statute for sexual assault victims. It reviews Florida's original legislative answer to the identity-disclosure debate and identifies victim privacy statutes from other jurisdictions. It then summarizes the facts surrounding the publication of the name of William Kennedy Smith's alleged victim. It then analyzes the Florida court opinions in </B>Globe Communications</B> that unanimously held the original ban unconsitutional. Finally, it describes and critiques the replacement statute passed by the Florida Legislature six months after the <B>Globe</B> decision. This Comment concludes that Florida's new Crime Victims Protection Act is no more constitutional than the original statute.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mhills.txt">Rule of law and democracy in Hong Kong : comparative analysis of British Liberalism and Chinese Socialism</A> by Mason <STRONG>Hills</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994.</I> This paper seeks to explore the concept of Rule of Law in Hong Kong, at the present and in its future as part of the People's Republic of China. Democracy is seen as not essential but complementary to Rule of Law providing checks on its implementation. Some of the main political, ethnic and cultural influences is explored. It concludes with the assertion that Rule of Law is one of the elements required for the maintenance of a stable Hong Kong society. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/webster.html">Selection and retention of judges: is there one "best" method?</A> by Peter D.  <STRONG>Webster</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1.</I> This Article first discusses the relationship between judicial theory and choice of a method of judicial selection and retention. It then addresses what each of the principal alternative methods of judicial selection and retention now in use does, and does not, accomplish. Finally, it proposes a compromise method which might prove more likely to satisfy all participants in the debate than does any of the current alternatives. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/cripps.html">Some Effects of European Law on English Administrative Law</A> by Yvonne <STRONG>Cripps</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I> Dr. Cripps discusses how European law has affected English law in recent decades, particularly with regard to the constitutional supremacy enjoyed by the English legislative branch.  Dr. Cripps predicts that the English bench will be increasingly willing to take European law into account in their decisionmaking. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/wyeth.html">Takings as the Failure of the Regulatory Market</A> by George <STRONG>Wyeth</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> This paper suggests addressing the stubborn "takings" problem by using a hypothetical perfectly competitive "regulatory market" as a normative reference point. The paper contends that this approach allows us to resolve apparent tensions between past takings analyses, and reconcile apparently conflicting views about the desirability of compensation. It also examines the light that such an approach sheds on the generally discredited notion of a "harm-benefit" distinction -- arguing that the hypothetical market provides the "baseline" that allows such a distinction to be drawn.. This approach is seen to explain some hitherto difficult rulings, and to suggest changes in other areas. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/thomps1.html">Whitehall's Cultural Revolution</A> by Brian <STRONG>Thompson</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1.</I> The Government has issued a White Paper on the Civil Service which is, in part, a response to a report of the Sub-Committee of the House of Commons Treasury and Civil Service Select Committee. The White Paper is significant in that the Government has abandoned its opposition to some of the Sub-Committee's recommendations, in particular a new Code of Conduct for the Civil Service which includes an independent appeal procedure. <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
