<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Contract and Commercial Law
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Contract and Commercial Law
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz1a.html">Bargaining at a Distance: the Mailbox Rule and Related Contract Formation Games</A> by Avery  <STRONG>Katz</STRONG><I>  .</I> This essay applies economic analysis to the so-called "mailbox rule". An economic analysis reveals some broad functional implications of the rule. It turns out that the legal rule governing contracts by correspondence does make an allocative difference -- though not for the reliance reason that has been offered in the legal commentary. The difference between the rules lies in their ability to encourage the offeror to keep to the bargain when bad news arrives only after reliance has taken place. On this dimension of efficiency, the mailbox rule performs better than its alternatives.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>" <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/cal/1maharg/">Contracts": An Introduction to the Skills of Legal Writing and Analysis</A> by Paul  <STRONG>Maharg</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I>  <I>Contracts</I> is a computer program designed for first year undergraduates. The program addresses undergraduates' legal writing and problem-solving skills. <I>Contracts</I> calls on learning theories which support the view that such skills can be learned via computer-based learning. Despite the general opinion that legal practitioners will more and more be using computers to communicate, there have been few other attempts to date to help students learn basic legal writing skills on computer.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Musy-1995/musy1.htm">Disclosure of Information in the Pre-contractual Bargaining</A> by A.M.  <STRONG>Musy</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Pardolesi-1995/pardo.html">Economic Analysis of Contract Law: Some Insights</A> by R.  <STRONG>Pardolesi</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506002.abs">Economics of Agency Law and Contract Formation</A>  <STRONG>Rasmusen</STRONG><I>  .</I> This article addresses issues that arise in agency law when agents make contracts on behalf of principals. The main issue is whether the principal should be bound when the agent makes a contract with some third party on his behalf which the principal would immediately wish to disavow. The resulting tradeoffs resemble those in tort law, so the least-cost-avoider principle is useful for deciding when contracts are valid and may be the underlying logic behind a number of different legal doctrines applied to agency cases. In particular, an efficiency explanation can be found for the undisclosed principal rule.   <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1j.html">Electronic Banking and the Law" (2nd Ed.) By Anu Anora</A> reviewed by A.  <STRONG>Charlesworth </STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/kaye3.html">Implementing An EC Directive on Unfair Terms</A> by Tim  <STRONG>Kaye</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> This article considers the substantive effect of the Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1994, and argues that despite their apparent commencement date of 1st July 1995 consumers have been able to claim the benefit of the protection afforded by the Regulations on the grounds that the Minister's specification of 1st July 1995 as the effective date of implementation is ultra vires. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/hartley.txt">Introduction to the Law of Contract: Computorials"</A> by Angela <STRONG>Hartley</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2.</I>  <I> (book review) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Alpa-1995/alpa.html">Law and Economics and Method Analysis: the Contractual Damages Issue</A> by G. Giampieri and A.  <STRONG>Alpa</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/clements3.html">Lending on the Security of Co-Owned Homes, Suretyship and Undue Influence</A> by L.M. <STRONG>Clements</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> The purpose of this Article is to examine how the law relating to lending on the security of co-owned homes, suretyship and undue influence has recently been developed, what are the real underlying policy issues and whether a balance is being struck between the competing economic interests and protection of the vulnerable. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A "<A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/clarke.txt">Near" Contract Experience</A> by Kirsty <STRONG>Clarke</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I> The author focusses especially on the unwillingness of the court to intervene in and enforce 'domestic' agreements, in which women are often the weaker party.   It is propounded that contractual rules and terminology may be manipulated so as to perpetuate and legitimate an unequal status quo.  The concepts of the 'reasonable person' and 'freedom of contract' are criticised, and it is proposed that these concepts should be expanded to apply wider principles of fairness which will remedy  basic inequalities of bargaining power. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/clay.html">Trade without Law: Private-Order Institutions in Mexican California</A> by Karen <STRONG>Clay</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> This paper examines the role played by a private-order institution in California in the growth of a complex system of trade in the absence of law. This institution, a coalition, governed agency relations among the merchants in California. A reputation mechanism supported by an information network, behavioral norms, and expectations regarding who was a member mitigated the commitment problem inherent in having individuals handle goods that they did not own by linking a merchant's past behavior and his future payoff. A game-theoretic model of the agent's commitment problem motivated by primary evidence from the merchants' correspondence on individual transactions is presented. Predictions that follow from the model explain patterns of social and economic behavior, the organization of trade, and the coalition's response to exogenous shocks. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/collins3.html">Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1994</A> by Brian St.J <STRONG>Collins</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> This article examines the substantive provisions of the Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1994 and compares the protection which these Regulations will afford to consumers with that which is currently available under common law and statutory provisions, in particular the Unfair Contract Terms Act 1977. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz3a.html">When Should an Offer Stick? The Economics of Promissory Estoppel in Preliminary Negotiations (forthcoming, Yale Law Journal, 1996) </A> by Avery  <STRONG>Katz </STRONG><I>  .</I> Under the modern doctrine of promissory estoppel, a person making an offer is bound when the offeree relies, even in the absence of an acceptance or any explicit negotiation for a binding option. But courts have generally declined to construe the offeree's reliance as an acceptance or as a promise to accept. This paper considers the incentive effects of this rule for the optimal timing of contract formation and reliance. In preliminary negotiations both parties have some control over the timing of reliance, but the rule of law affects their relative incentives to exercise this control. I argue that the efficiency of promissory estoppel in preliminary negotiations depends in large part on which party holds the bulk of the bargaining power ex post.  <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
