<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Criminal Law
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Criminal Law
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/onions2.html">Blackstone's Guide to the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994, by Martin Wasik and Richard Taylor</A> reviewed by Helen <STRONG>O'Nions</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I>  <I> (book review) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/ormerod1.html">Criminal Liability for the Transmission of HIV</A> by D.C. Ormerod and M.J.  <STRONG>Gunn</STRONG><I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1.</I> This article explores the issues arising when a person, knowing that he or she is anti-HIV positive, proceeds to engage in intimate sexual behaviour, and asks whether he or she is liable to criminal prosecution.  In the light of the Government's refusal to legislate in this area, the article considers the possible sanctions under existing criminal law, providing analysis of sections 23 and 24 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861. It reviews possible problems with the use of these sections, and concludes that they could be used successfully to prosecute this type of behaviour. Finally, consideration is given to proposed law reform.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/swensen.txt">Drug Problems in Western Australia:  a review of non-criminal mechanisms ...</A> by Greg <STRONG>Swensen</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I> Discussion of the shortcomings in the Western Australian system of notifying drug addicts. There is an examination of the practical considerations as well as the natural justice implications. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/boland4.html">Involuntary Intoxication Is Not A Defence</A> by Faye  <STRONG>Boland</STRONG><I> Web JCLI [1995] no. 4.</I> In R v Kingston [1994] 3 All ER 353, HL, it was held that involuntary intoxication is no defence to a criminal charge and is only relevant insofar as it disproves or proves mens rea. An intent produced by the surreptitious administration of drink or drugs is still a criminal intent. <I> (Casenote) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/lomnicka2.html">Review of Janet Dine, "Criminal Law in the Company Context".</A> Reviewed by Eva  <STRONG>Lomnicka</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part4.htm">Use" and the irresistible impulse to legislate </A> by Robert C.  <STRONG>Dorf</STRONG><I> Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995).</I> The purpose of this article is to discuss the loss of the possession-use distinction. It is possible that both Congress and the New York legislature will amend the statutes in question to punish both "use" and "possession" of firearms at the same level. It is impossible to applaud judicial hammering of statutory "possession" into "use" which is contrary to legislative intent.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/lauw3.txt">Victimless Crimes :  Decriminalisation of Homosexual Sexual Activity</A> by Inge <STRONG>Lauw</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I> Explores the arguments for and against decriminalisation of sexual acts between consenting adult males.  Also discusses the recent statement by the United Nations Human Rights Committee declaring Tasmania's anti-sodomy laws to be unlawful. <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
