<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Criminal Procedure and Evidence
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Criminal Procedure and Evidence
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/hoey1.html">Analysis of The Police and Criminal Evidence Act, s.69 - Computer Generated Evidence</A> by Amanda  <STRONG>Hoey </STRONG><I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1.</I> At present there are special rules governing the admissibility of computer-generated evidence in criminal proceedings. In this article the issues of when computer output will be considered direct evidence or hearsay and the reliability of computer-generated evidence are discussed. In conclusion the article attempts to ascertain whether these special rules for computer output are necessary and, if so, whether the conditions established by the statutory provisions are appropriate.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/stinger.html">Arizona v. Evans: Adapting the Exclusionary Rule to Advancing Computer Technology</A> by C. Maureen  <STRONG>Stinger</STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/schwartz.html">Challenge of Peremptory Challenges</A> by Warren F and Edward P <STRONG>Schwartz</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/stone3.html">Exclusion of Evidence under Section 78 of the Police and Criminal Evidence Act: Practice and Principles</A> by Richard <STRONG>Stone</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> Section 78 of PACE gives the courts a discretion to exclude from a criminal trial evidence which has been obtained unfairly.   This article is an attempt to analyse the principles which the courts use.  It trying to identify the factors which the judges regard as relevant to this discretion.  Secondly, it examines the possible policies which might underlie a discretion to exclude.  It then attempts to match the practice to the policies, and concludes that fairness as fair play is the dominant policy. The conclusion considers how the changes in the rights of the suspect (in particular the right to remain silent) introduced by the Criminal Justice Act 1994 are likely to impact on the operation of s 78. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/ranson.txt">Expert Evidence"  by Freckleton and Selby</A> reviewed by David L <STRONG>Ranson</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I>  <I> (book review) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/lafferty.html">Florida's capital sentencing jury override: whom should we trust to make the ultimate ethical judgment?</A> by Latour Rey  <STRONG>Lafferty</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2).</I> This article examines Florida's trifurcated capital sentencing scheme, specifically the jury override provision, from its origin to the present. It identifies and analyzes several criticisms of Florida's jury override provision, and examines the potential impact of Florida Committee Substitute for House Bill 1319, which Governor Chiles vetoed on June 14, 1995. Finally, this Article concludes that the Governor's veto was appropriate because Florida's jury override provision represents a valuable balance between the judge and the jury.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/james2.html">Good Character Directions and Blemished Defendants</A> by Jennifer  <STRONG>James</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> Since thedecision which clarified the direction to be given to a jury in respect of an accused with a good character, the issue of who possesses such a character has become highly relevant. This article provides a brief introduction to good character evidence before concentrating on the blemished defendant whose record is not above reproach. Three categories of blemished defendants are considered and the cases analyzed with some suggestions for rationalization of the principles applicable.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/sergienko.html">Incrimination and Cryptographic Keys</A> by Greg S.  <STRONG>Sergienko</STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/cooper4.html">Jury Warnings: The Exercise of Judicial Discretion</A> by Simon  <STRONG>Cooper</STRONG><I> Web JCLI [1995] 4.</I> The Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994 abrogated the need for a trial judge to warn the jury of the dangers of acting on the uncorroborated evidence of an alleged accomplice or victim of a sexual offence. This casenote evaluates R v Makanjuola [1995] 145 NLJ 959, the first Court of Appeal case to address these provisions, and considers the future of jury warnings where the evidence has been provided by a witness whose testimony is in some way suspect. <I> (Casenote) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/laing1.html">Police Surgeon and Mentally Disordered Suspects: An Adequate Safeguard?</A> by Judith M  <STRONG>Laing</STRONG><I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1.</I> This article examines the role of the police surgeon in identifying and assessing mentally disordered suspects in police custody. It suggests that police surgeons lack the relevant knowledge and expertise to deal with these people, and concludes that duty-psychiatrist schemes currently operating at magistrates' courts should be extended to police stations to ensure that mentally disordered suspects are assessed by medical professionals who possess the relevant psychiatric expertise.    <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/quest.txt">QUEST Evidence Computer Tutorials - A Review</A> by Jeffrey <STRONG>Rosales-Castaneda</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994.</I> A student review of a computer based tutorial for use in teaching Australian evidence law <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/conferen/papers/schwartz.html">Simple Majority Rule for Criminal Jury Trials: The Verdict is Now In</A> by Edward P. Schwartz and Warren F.  <STRONG>Schwartz</STRONG><I>  .</I> The paper proposes that the current two way unanimity rule governing jury verdicts in criminal cases be replaced by a rule of simple majority.  Neither the history of the use of the unanimity rule nor the reasons advanced to justify its use provide persuasive grounds for retaining the rule rather than employing the rule of simple majority which is used in virtually all other democratic institutions.   <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/choo2.html">Undercover Police Operations and What the Suspect said (or didn't say)</A> by Manda Mellors and Andrew L-T <STRONG>Choo</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I> This paper is about the legal regulation of undercover police operations. A number of recent cases, notably the celebrated cases of Keith Hall and Colin Stagg in 1994, provide instances of undercover operations which apparently have as an aim the extraction of confessions from suspects. This paper examines the adequacy of the relevant executive and judicial pronouncements on undercover police operations. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/kar.htm">Unlucky Thirteenth: a constitutional amendment in search of a doctrine</A> by Lauren <STRONG>Kares</STRONG><I> Cornell LR January 1995.</I> *Steirer* is not anomalous; in fact, the Thirteenth Amendment is notable for its lack of a coherent jurisprudence.  This Note argues that a balancing test like the one used by the *Steirer* trial court is more useful and truer to the Thirteenth Amendment's vision of liberty than the criminal standard used by the appellate court.  Consistent application of a balancing test would afford the Thirteenth Amendment a degree of elasticity and relevance that it now lacks. <I> (note) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/scott2.html">Use of Public Interest Immunity Claims in Criminal Cases</A> by The Right Hon. Sir Richard  <STRONG>Scott</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> Sir Richard Scott suggests that the application to criminal trials of Public Interest Immunity principles derived from civil cases and designed for application in civil cases has been a mistake and has acted as an impediment to the evolution of satisfactory principles for dealing with PII claims in criminal trials. Sir Richard goes on to suggest what should be the correct approach to PII claims in criminal trials.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/gilb2.html">Who has Jurisdiction for Cross-Frontier Financial Crimes?</A> by Geoff <STRONG>Gilbert</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I> This article has been prompted by the Nick Leeson case, where a trader in the Japanese derivatives market was working in Singapore, but whose activities had the effect of bringing down Barings, the oldest merchant bank in the City of London. It considers which State should have jurisdiction in these circumstances, particularly since the alleged criminal may now be in a third State. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/lei.htm">Why grand juries do not (and cannot) protect the accused</A> by Andrew D <STRONG>Leipold</STRONG><I> Cornell LR January 1995.</I> The weakness in the system lies less with the procedures employed than with the characteristics of the decisionmakers.   Rather than being asked to find facts and apply those facts to the law, the jurors are presented with a single set of facts, instructed on the law by the prosecutor, and asked to decide whether those undisputed facts are sufficient to satisfy a specific legal test - the probable cause standard.  Even reasonable, independent-minded jurors will defer to the prosecutor's judgment that an indictment should issue. <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
