<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Family Law
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Family Law
 </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/cox3.pag">Amicus brief: In re H.S.H-K, 193 Wis. 2d 649, 533 N.W.2d 419(1995) with introduction.</A> by Barbara  <STRONG>Cox</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996).</I> This brief, with an introduction by Prof. Barbara Cox, was written by her and filed with the Wisconsin Supreme Court on behalf of the National Center for Lesbian Rights.  That case involved a custody and visitation claim filed by a non-biological parent of H.S.H-K, who had participated in the decision to have and raise the child with the child's biological parent.  The court granted the petition and in doing so, became the first state supreme court to recognize the visitation rights of a non-biological lesbian parent.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/thomas.pag">Amicus brief: In re Ry R.-Y.</A> by  <STRONG>National Center for Lesbian Rights, et al.</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996).</I> This amicus brief, filed by the National Center for Lesbian Rights on behalf of the defendant argues that the decision of a New York trial court, <B>Thomas S. v. Robin Y.</B>, 599 N.Y.S.2d 377 (Fam. Ct. 1993) to deny the paternity petition of Thomas S., a known sperm donor and the biological father of Ry, a child born into a household of a lesbian couple, should be affirmed.  The appellate court held that, despite an oral agreement to the contrary, Thomas S.'s paternity petition should be granted. <B>Thomas S. v. Robin Y.</B>, 618 N.Y.S.2d 356 (App. Div. 1994).  The Court of Appeals, New York's highest court, stayed the appellate court's decision and granted certiorari.  The appeal was ultimately dismissed, however, when Thomas S. withdrew his paternity petition.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecipa/archive/UT-ECIPA-REAS-95-01.html">Breaking Up is Hard to Do: The Economics of Spousal Support </A> by Samuel A. <STRONG>Rea, Jr.</STRONG><I>  .</I> The introduction of "no-fault" divorce has eliminated the traditional basis for spousal support without providing a satisfactory alternative. In a recent case, Elliot v. Elliot, an Ontario court awarded the woman half of the difference between her earnings had she not married and her earnings after the divorce. The model developed in this paper highlights the changes in earnings that result from specialization in housework or market work, investment in children, and investment in the spouse's human capital. The incentive effects on human capital, marriage, and divorce are considered. Although no measure is perfect, the paper concludes that the approach taken in Elliot, adjusted for additional leisure enjoyed during marriage, offers a reasonable compromise between competing objectives.  <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/allen1.html">Children with Special Educational Needs in a Consumer-Driven Education System</A> by Tom <STRONG>Allen</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1.</I> This article looks at recent changes in the English educational provision which make it more difficult for parents to obtain a satisfactory education for children who have special needs, while at the same time expanding their legal right to the question the provision their children do receive. It examines the general trend to consumerism as the underlying philosophy of educational 'planning' and the statutory framework for protecting the position of special needs children. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/sclater4.html">Critical Approach to the White Paper on Divorce Reform</A> by Shelley Day  <STRONG>Sclater</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 .</I> This paper discusses some of the issues raised by recent Government proposals for reform of the divorce law. It begins by considering the responses of professional bodies (the Law Society, the Solicitors' Family Law Association, and National Family Mediation) to the green consultation paper of December 1993. It is argued that the concerns voiced by lawyers have, in the main, not been addressed. It is suggested that a broader range of issues, including questions of justice and fairness, should be introduced into the debate, and that social scientific commentary has a valuable contribution to make in this regard.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A (Personal) <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/cox.pag">Essay on Same-Sex Marriage</A> by Barbara J.  <STRONG>Cox</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995).</I> In this article Barbara Cox examines the institution of marriage in the gay and lesbian community from a personal perspective.  Prof. Cox reviews recent articles in the gay and lesbian literature arguing both for and against marriage as a political goal for homosexuals.  She then relates experiences arising out of her marriage to her partner, Peg.  The author advocates same-sex unions as a way to radically restructure the institution of marriage while challenging heterosexual assumptions about gay and lesbian love.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/gerencse.html">Family mediation: screening for domestic abuse</A> by Alison E.  <STRONG>Gerencser</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1.</I> This Article proposes that all legislatures mandating family mediation allow exemption from mediation when participant screeners determine that, because of the level of domestic abuse, mediation is inappropriate. Next, this Article argues that legislatures also must mandate that all participants screen for domestic violence. The Article concludes by discussing the multi-tiered screening process and the roles of the various participants in screening for domestic abuse. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/lind2.html">Family Redefinition under Part III of the Family Law Bill 1996</A> by Craig Lind and Anne  <STRONG>Barlow</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> We assess the effects of Part III of the Family Law Bill 1996 on unmarried couples in domestic violence law, and on the jurisprudential scope of family law itself. We begin by noting the erosion of the dominance of the traditional married family. Then we consider the equivocal and, consequently, incohesive legal response to this social diversification. We examine the adequacy of the new remedies available to expanded categories of victims of family violence. We conclude that the Bill significantly improves current law, but that by creating three tiers of legal regulation, it inappropriately complicates the resolution of comparable disputes. The ideological importance of the married state has prevented pragmatic and coherent reform.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/wolfson.pag">Fighting to Win and Keep the Freedom to Marry: The Legal, Political, and Cultural Challenges Ahead </A> by Evan  <STRONG>Wolfson</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995).</I> In this series of documents Mr. Wolfson describes Lambda's work in the area of marriage rights and provides information necessary for anyone to help promote equal marriage rights for gays and lesbians including a briefing on the legal status of the case and the tasks ahead, a series of questions and answers about marrage and gay people and finally a series of documents designed to help gays and lesbians in all states gain legal recognition of Hawaii marriages, assuming a victorious conclusion of the litigation there.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/burton.html">Gay Marriage - A Modern Proposal:  Applying Baehr v.  Lewin to the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights</A> by Anne M.  <STRONG>Burton</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I>  <I> (Note) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/todd.html">Hague Convention on the Civil Aspects of International Child Abduction: Are the Convention's Goals Being Achieved? </A> by Julia A.  <STRONG>Todd </STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I>  <I> (note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/todd4.html">Inferring share of interest in home: Midland Bank v Cooke (Casenote)</A> by Paul Todd and Nicola  <STRONG>Glover</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 .</I> In Midland Bank v Cooke, CA, 7 July 1995, the Court of Appeal held that Mrs Cooke was entitled to a half share in the matrimonial home, binding on a third party mortgagee, although this was not justified by her direct contribution to the purchase price, and there had been no express discussions between the parties. In Springette v Defoe (1992) 24 HLR 552, [1992] 2 FCR 561, the Court of Appeal had held that the absence of express discussions precluded any claim to apportion shares otherwise than in proportion to contributions to the purchase price, but Waite LJ in Midland Bank v Cooke took the view that the lack of discussions or express agreement did not preclude the court from inferring an agreement on general equitable principles.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/levmore.html">Love It or Leave It: Property Rules, Liability Rules, and Exclusivity of Remedies in Partnership and Marriage</A> by Saul <STRONG>Levmore</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> The traditional rule in partnership law, and the continuing rule in domestic relations law, is that a claim for dissolution (or divorce) is a partner's exclusive remedy. On its face this mandatory "love-it-or-leave-it" rule seems strange, anachronistic, unfair, and inefficient, because where there is going concern value there is room for exploitation. In contrast, corporate law offers a kind of reverse "exclusivity" rule, in that a shareholder can bring a suit for damages but can not force dissolution of the enterprise. These rules offer a window to general questions about remedies. The Calabresi-Melamed property-liability rules framework is expanded with the incorporation not only of rules explored by Polinsky and by Krier and Schwab but also with several seemingly novel rules that draw attention to the possibility of remedies that are only forward-looking or only backward-looking. The critical connection is that the power to "stop" a partnership or a marriage is akin to the power to stop a nuisance, so that love-it-or-leave-it rules can have the character of a "property rule" with no liability component. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk:70/00/ltc/publications/conferences/oxford/walsum.txt">Mixed Metaphors: The Nation and the Family</A> by S. van <STRONG>Walsum</STRONG><I> Oxford Critical Legal Conference 1993.</I> The concept of nationality is a contingent one, and must be placed in its historical and geographical context. Equally important for the meaning of this concept is the legal field in which it is employed: immigration law, law of conflicts or social policies directed at migrants. The equally contingent concept of family is intimately linked to that of nationality, and this relationship too varies according to time, place and specific legal context. This paper attempts to analyse the relationship between the nation and the family in the specific context of present-day Dutch immigration law. Inspired by writings of the geographer David Harvey, the author considers the consequences for control over mobility, identity and family loyalty. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A "<A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/clarke.txt">Near" Contract Experience</A> by Kirsty <STRONG>Clarke</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I> The author focusses especially on the unwillingness of the court to intervene in and enforce 'domestic' agreements, in which women are often the weaker party.   It is propounded that contractual rules and terminology may be manipulated so as to perpetuate and legitimate an unequal status quo.  The concepts of the 'reasonable person' and 'freedom of contract' are criticised, and it is proposed that these concepts should be expanded to apply wider principles of fairness which will remedy  basic inequalities of bargaining power. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/becker.pag">Recognition of Domestic Partnerships by Governmental Entities and Private Employers</A> by Lewis  <STRONG>Becker</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995).</I> In this piece, Lewis Becker discusses the creation and benefits of domestic partnerships.  Prof. Becker explains and examines arguments advanced by opponents of the recognition of domestic partners concluding that these arguments are not supported by the evidence.  Finally Prof. Becker points out questions about the legal effects of domestic partner registration which remain unanswered.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/lauw2.txt">Recognition of Same-Sex Marriage :  Time for Change ?</A> by Inge <STRONG>Lauw</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I> Discusses the case Baehr v Lewin, relating to legal recognition of same-sex marriages.  Also examines policy arguments for and against granting marriage licences to same-sex couples.  Briefly examines the situation in Australia <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/edge3.html">Reforming Termination of Pregnancy : Two Models within the British Islands</A> by Peter W <STRONG>Edge</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> This note considers current proposals for reform of the law governing termination of pregnancy in the Isle of Man and Jersey, and suggests the possible value of these developments for the English jurisdiction. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/rodgers2.html">Standard of Proof in Care Order Applications under the Children Act 1989</A> by M E  <STRONG>Rodgers</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> In re H and Others (Minors) [1995] 2 WLR 8, HL is the culmination of a series of appeals by the Nottingham County Council against the judgment of His Honour Judge Davidson on 23rd November 1994. The application for care orders under Children Act 1989, s 31, in respect of 3 children was refused. A subsequent appeal to the Court of Appeal was dismissed on 14th December 1994. The Local Authority appealed to the House of Lords, the matter being heard on 17 & 18th July 1995, with judgement reserved, and opinions being delivered on 14th December 1995.   <I> (casenote) </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
