<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Immigration
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Immigration
 </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/conway.htm">Are There New Complexities in Global Migration Systems of Consequence for the United States "Nation-State"?</A> by Dennis <STRONG>Conway</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/tessrtr2.html">Challenge of Immigration Policy in the New South Africa</A> by Kevin  <STRONG>Tessier</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk:70/00/ltc/publications/conferences/oxford/akobay.txt">Challenging the National Dream: Gender Persecution and Canadian Imigration Law</A> by Audrey <STRONG>Kobayashi</STRONG><I> Oxford Critical Legal Conference 1993.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/zolberg.html">Changing Sovereignty Games and International Migration</A> by Aristide R. <STRONG>Zolberg</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I> In this article, Professor Zolberg argues that today's immigration issues should be analyzed within their historical bases.  The author concludes that despite the recent development of borderless markets and communication infrastructures, much remains to be done to build a truly global community. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/hart.html">Comments on "Changing Sovereignty Games and International Migration"</A> by Jeffrey A. <STRONG>Hart</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/delbruck.html">Global Migration -- Immigration -- Multiethnicity: Challenges to the Concept of the Nation-State</A> by Jost <STRONG>Delbrck</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/delusign.html">Global Migration and European Integration</A> by Guy <STRONG>De Lusignan</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/tessrnot.html">Immigration Crisis in Federalism: A Comparison of the United States and Canada</A> by Kevin  <STRONG>Tessier</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/tessrtr1.html">Immigration Law in the Russian Federation</A> by Kevin  <STRONG>Tessier</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/goldamm.html">International Reaction to Hong Kong's Countdown to 1997: Doors Open to Hong Kong's Emigrants</A> by Susan  <STRONG>Goldammer</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/aman.html">Migration and Globalization</A> by Alfred C. <STRONG>Aman, Jr.</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I> (symposium introduction) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk:70/00/ltc/publications/conferences/oxford/walsum.txt">Mixed Metaphors: The Nation and the Family</A> by S. van <STRONG>Walsum</STRONG><I> Oxford Critical Legal Conference 1993.</I> The concept of nationality is a contingent one, and must be placed in its historical and geographical context. Equally important for the meaning of this concept is the legal field in which it is employed: immigration law, law of conflicts or social policies directed at migrants. The equally contingent concept of family is intimately linked to that of nationality, and this relationship too varies according to time, place and specific legal context. This paper attempts to analyse the relationship between the nation and the family in the specific context of present-day Dutch immigration law. Inspired by writings of the geographer David Harvey, the author considers the consequences for control over mobility, identity and family loyalty. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/tessrtr3.html">New Slave Trade:  The International crisis of Immigrant Smuggling</A> by Kevin  <STRONG>Tessier</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/karst.html">Out of Many, One?</A> by Kenneth L. <STRONG>Karst</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I> The Governor of California has called for an amendment to the U.S. Constitution that would deny citizenship to a child born in the United States if the child's parents entered the country illegally. Although this appalling proposal seems unlikely to be taken seriously in Congress, undoubtedly it is well received by a constituency the Governor needs to reassure. Similar constituencies were vocal during the colonial era, and their successors have made nativism a recurring political theme. In sum, this experience makes clear that the ideal of the "Open Republic," so ably defended by Professor Jost Delbrck, confronts powerful opposition. In this paper I comment briefly on the problems of maintaining political community and political legitimacy in the face of ethnic difference. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/scheetr1.html">Politics of Western Immigration</A> by Stephen E.  <STRONG>Scheele</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/schenk.html">Proposal to Improve the Treatment of Women in Asylum Law :  Adding a "Gender" Category to the International Definition of "Refugee"</A> by Todd Stewart <STRONG>Schenk</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I> (Note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/gaebler.html">Review of Yael Tamir, "Liberal Nationalism"</A> by Ralph  <STRONG>Gaebler</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/katart5.html">Rights of Foreigners and Immigrants in Europe: Recent Trends</A> by George  <STRONG>Katrougalos</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5.</I> Immigration policies which have been traditionally conceived and implemented at the national level can not cope with the new situation of globalization and European unification. Within the European Union, the easing of "internal" frontier controls contrasts with an intensification of controls at the "external frontiers". The Schengen Treaty is the culmination of this trend. Moreover, there is a universal tightening of the policies and procedures in granting asylum, that resulted in constitutional revision in France and Germany. Most other European countries have enacted new, more restrictive legislation toward foreigners, adapted in the context of European Integration and the Schengen criteria. The article reviews the present status of national and international legislation related to foreigners' rights, in order to analyze the relationship between nationality and citizenship rights. It concludes with the proposal of a concept of rights based on residence.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/passel.html">U.S. Immigration in a Global Context: Past, Present, and Future</A> by Jeffrey S. Passel and Michael <STRONG>Fix</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I> Through the use of their own empirical studies, the authors address three themes: (1) immigration in the global context; (2) the scale and characteristics of immigration to the United States; and (3) the expected future impact of immigration to the United States. The authors conclude that the situation is not dire; rather, they believe that the ties created by immigrants may become increasingly important to the United States in an interrelated world economy. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/calavita.html">U.S. Immigration Policy: Contradictions and Projections for the Future</A> by Kitty <STRONG>Calavita</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I> What will become of immigration barriers in the future, particularly given the globalization of capital and the increasing free trade of goods?  And second, is democratic rule antithetical to or destructive of such barriers. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/scanlan.html">View from the United States -- Social, Economic, and Legal Change, the Persistence of the State, and Immigration Policy in the Coming Century</A> by John A. <STRONG>Scanlan</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I> In this article, Professor Scanlan argues that in spite of recent trends toward globalism, traditionally composed nation-states, especially the United States, will continue to exercise localized control over immigration and receiving nations may pursue increasingly restrictive policies. <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
