<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Indigenous Peoples
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Indigenous Peoples
</H1>

<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/french.txt">Applying the Native Title Act 1993</A> by Justice Robert <STRONG>French</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> Outlines the common law of concepts of native title contained within the High Courts Mabo decision, the scope of the _Native Title Act_ and provides details of the operations and directions of the Native Title Tribunal. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns1.txt">Australian Ratification of International Labour Organisation Convention No. 169</A> by Catherine J. <STRONG>Iorns</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993.</I> The Convention accords little status to indigenous laws and values, and it is generally paternalistic.  However, adopting it will expand upon the rights of Australian Aborigines and may foster wider recognition of the rights of Indigenous Peoples worldwide <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/pritchar.txt">Constitutional Validity of the Commonwealth's Native Title Regime Confirmed</A> by Sarah <STRONG>Pritchard</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> Case comment on the recent Australian cases of The State of Western Australia v the Commonwealth; The Wororra Peoples v The Commonwealth; Teddy Biljabu v The Commonwealth   decided by the High Court of Australia <I> (case comment) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mccallum.txt">Dispute Resolution Mechanisms in the Resolution of Comprehensive Aboriginal Claims:  Power Imbalance Between Aboriginal Claimants and Governments -- Negotiation</A> by Andrea Gaye <STRONG>McCallum</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> This article focuses on the manner in which negotiation has been, or may be, employed to resolve Aboriginal claims.  The process of negotiation is analysed and assessed in terms of the extent to which it facilitates cultural domination, and reinforces power imbalance between the parties. The author concludes by suggesting various means by which the negotiation process may be improved to redress elements of the power imbalance between the parties. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns2.txt">Draft Declaration of the Rights of Indigneous Peoples</A> by Catherine J. <STRONG>Iorns</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993.</I> This article discusses the important provisions therein.  Suggestions are made for improvements that might be incorporated before it is adopted by the UN General Assembly <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/garkawe.txt">Impact of the Doctrine of Cultural Relativism on the Australian Legal System, The</A> by Sam <STRONG>Garkawe</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> This article commences with a discussion of the doctrine of cultural relativism and its validity. In relation to immigrant practices and customs, the doctrine does not deny the incorporation of international human rights standards into Australian law, but calls for a sensitive and culturally aware approach to the question of prohibition of these practices. However, the author concludes that the doctrine does make out a case for denying the applicability of international human rights standards to aboriginal practices and customs. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/kamien.txt">Implementing Self-Government- An Examination of the Aboriginal Communities Act (Western Australia)</A> by T. <STRONG>Kamien</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> This report examines the Aboriginal Communities Act in the context of the right to self-government given by article 31 of the Draft Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples.  The report criticises the Act in that although it has found some acceptance with Aboriginal people, it has an assimilationist focus, in some cases increasing powerlessness felt by Aboriginal people. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/devarenn.txt">Indigenous Peoples and Language</A> by Fernand <STRONG>De Varennes</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> This article explores the entitlement of indigenous peoples to preferential treatment in linguistic affairs.  This is due not to their position as a minority, but to the acknowledgement in international law, as well as in some national jurisdictions, that indigenous peoples occupy a unique political and legal niche, with corresponding privileges not necessarily available to others. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/begg.txt">Justice at Last or Just More of the Past - An Evaluation of the British Columbia Treaty Commission</A> by Michael <STRONG>Begg</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> This paper discusses a new agency intended to help create new equitable treaties between the indigenous peoples of British Columbia and the governments of that Province and of Canada. It evaluates the British Columbia Treaty Commission in the hope that readers can draw ideas from the Canadian experience.  The Treaty Commission has no power to investigate, make conclusions, or submit recommendations but is a facilitative agency whose duty is to keep negotiations organised and whose power is primarily persuasive. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/ross.txt">Learning About Survival From Survivors: Mohawk Environmental Communicative Action</A> by Susan <STRONG>Ross</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> This report examines two case-studies in order to illustrate the argument that environmental justice requires that indigenous people, who may have a different world-view, be involved in environmental decision-making. The author stresses the danger of using purely "statistical and quantitative" methods and excluding human, ethical value-judgements in formulating environmental policy <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/shanahan.txt">Legislative Responses to *Mabo*- Rendering the Law Unconscious?</A> by Christopher <STRONG>Shanahan</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> The common law precedents cited in *Mabo* reveal the common law's long established capacity to recognise pluralism.  This is contrasted with the effects of the *Native Title Act 1993* (Cth) and the *Land (Titles and Traditional Usage) Act 1993* (WA), which seek to overcome the plurality implicit in the legal recognition of indigenous interests in land, thereby denying this tradition of plurality within Anglo-Australian legal culture. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/blakeney.txt">Milpurrurru & Ors v Indofurn Pty Ltd & Ors - Protecting Expressions of Aboriginal Folklore Under Copyright Law</A> by Michael <STRONG>Blakeney</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> The author traces the development of the law through two cases.  The author points out that the Copyright Act's requirement that the creator of a work be able to assert copyright ownership creates a problem where the design which is the subject of a claim dates back more than 50 years before the infringing act. The author concludes by emphasising the importance of comprehensive legislation to protect expressions of Aboriginal folklore. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mah.txt">National Native Title Tribunal - Compensation Issues -  A Discussion Paper</A> by Daniel C. H. <STRONG>Mah</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> Although the Tribunal was largely set up as a mediating body, with the reaching of compensation agreements to be a consensual process between parties, certain boundaries have been set within that process. This paper considers those processes and boundaries, with emphasis on determining liability for compensation, measurement and forms that compensation may take, and the application procedure <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/netwatch/netw1.txt">Netwatch April 1995</A> by Anne <STRONG>Greenshields</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> This issue of Netwatch focuses on indigenous resources.  While this listing is not a comprehensive list of indigenous peoples resources it is a list of sites which the library has been able to connect to and have determined that they are resources which would interest a researcher in this area.  New sites and new discussion lists follow the special subject section. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/humphry.txt">Opportunity Lost for Aboriginal Self-Determination: Australia's compliance with ILO 169</A> by Alison <STRONG>Humphry</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> The paper addresses the requirements of articles 8 and 9 of ILO 169 and whether WA complies with these. It examines primarily the interplay between the customary law of Australian Aboriginal people and the criminal justice system of Western Australia. The author concludes that compliance is limited to taking into account customary law when applying non-Aboriginal law and not so much compliance with the requirements of respect for Aboriginal law and institutions. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/howe.txt">Poststructuralist Consideration of Property as Thin Air- Mabo, A Case Study</A> by Adrian <STRONG>Howe</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> This report examines the decision in _Mabo (no 2)_ from the point of view of property as a power relation rather than a tangible resource. The actual nature of the rights recognised has resulted in uncertainty. The result of the case is to "propertise" Aboriginal interests in land, rendering them a "real", though second rate, interest. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/seaman.txt">Providing a Sustainable Economic Land Base for Aboriginal Populations</A> by Paul <STRONG>Seaman QC</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> Provides general background to the substance and implications of the High Court's Mabo decision, the workings of the _Native Title Act_, the Native Title Tribunal and an outline of statutary requirements and current policy for processing native title applications <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns4.txt">Report of the 11th Session of the Working Group of Indigenous Peoples, 19-30 July 1993</A> by Catherine J. <STRONG>Iorns</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 1.</I> The major items were the debate on the draft Declaration of Rights of Indigenous Peoples and the Review of Developments, where Indigenous Peoples worldwide present statements to the session describing their current circumstances.  There were also reports on studies conducted by Working Group members and by a Maori group. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns95.txt">Report on Aboriginal Women and Bias in the Western Australian Justice System</A> by Catherine J. <STRONG>Iorns</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> This is an account of the Sub-Committee on Aboriginal Women and the Law in the Taskforce which drafted a report into gender bias in the law and administration of justice in Western Australia in 1994.  It looks into some of the recommendations for reform that could significantly reduce the many difficulties faced by Aboriginal women due to bias in the Western Australian legal system <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/ryser.txt">Resuming Self-Government in Indian Country: From Imposed Government to Self-Rule Inside and Outside the United States of America</A> by Rudolph C. <STRONG>Ryser</STRONG><I> E-Law .</I> This paper examines the right of self-determination with particular focus upon the native Americans of the United States of America. <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
