<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Intellectual Property
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Intellectual Property
</H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/myers.html">Apple v. Microsoft: Virtual Identity in the GUI Wars (Note)</A> by Joseph  <STRONG>Myers </STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Bioethics/Ricolfi-1995/Bioethics.html">Bioethics Market and Morals: the Case of Biotechnological Patents</A> by M.  <STRONG>Ricolfi</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2a.html">Bringing Law into the Information Age</A> by P. <STRONG>Pearce</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/halbert.txt">Computer technology and legal discourse : the potential for modern communication technology to challenge legal discourses of authorship and property</A> by Debora <STRONG>Halbert</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/hardy.html">Contracts, Copyright and Preemption in a Digital World </A> by I. Trotter  <STRONG>Hardy </STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Students/Marino1.html">Database Protection in the European Union</A> by F.  <STRONG>Marino</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/t.htm">Dressing up software interface protection: the application of *Two Pesos* to look-and-feel</A> by Steven <STRONG>Shortgen</STRONG><I> Cornell LR November 1994.</I> This note presents the Supreme Court's *Two Pesos* decision and discusses that decision's implications for intellectual property lawyers. Finally, it provides closing comments on asserting trade dress protection for GUIs, and includes a model application based loosely upon the litigation between Apple, Inc. and Microsoft, Inc. Ultimately, this Note argues that GUIs as well as future creative interfaces deserve protection under trade dress doctrine in certain cases. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/cate.html">Global Information Policymaking and Domestic Law</A> by Fred <STRONG>Cate</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/downing4.html">Magill and the Software Directive: are they interoperable?</A> by Robbie <STRONG>Downing</STRONG><I> Web JCLI [1995] no. 4.</I> In Magill, the ECJ held that a refusal to license copyright protected materials could be an abuse of a dominant position under Article 86 of the EC Treaty. The ECJ's analysis could be applied to certain cases where copyright protection of computer programs is relied on to control the creation of a third party product or service, although much depends on how we interpret the ECJ's notion of abuse. Courts would be better advised sensitively to circumscribe the scope of copyright protection under the Software Directive taking into account the experience of US courts.  Article 86 is arguably not the proper instrument to strike the balance inherent in the grant of an intellectual property right. Moreover, in applying Magill, a realistic approach to market power in secondary markets is required. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/blakeney.txt">Milpurrurru & Ors v Indofurn Pty Ltd & Ors - Protecting Expressions of Aboriginal Folklore Under Copyright Law</A> by Michael <STRONG>Blakeney</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995.</I> The author traces the development of the law through two cases.  The author points out that the Copyright Act's requirement that the creator of a work be able to assert copyright ownership creates a problem where the design which is the subject of a claim dates back more than 50 years before the infringing act. The author concludes by emphasising the importance of comprehensive legislation to protect expressions of Aboriginal folklore. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part5.htm">Multimedia computing:  copyright law's &quot;last stand&quot; </A> by Steven  <STRONG>Pepe</STRONG><I> Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/greguras.txt">Multimedia Content and the Super Highway: Rapid Acceleration or Foot on the Brake?</A> by Sandy Wong, Fred Greguras and Michael R <STRONG>Egger</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2.</I> This article discusses emerging legal issues concerning copyright/patent protection of material used in multimedia applications. Describes existing processes for the administration of copyright/patent material in the US and the deficencies of traditional rights agreements where material is used in multimedia products.  Cites recent reports from Japan concerning the advantages of streamlining copyright/patent administration, and proposes the establishment of a US based copyright/patent clearinghouse for multimedia materials. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/meyer.html">National and International Copyright Liability for Electronic System Operators </A> by Charles J.  <STRONG>Meyer </STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I>  <I> (note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/booton2.html">Novelty of Inventions under the Patents Act 1977 and the European Patent Convention</A> by D. L.  <STRONG>Booton</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> In Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals Inc and Another v H N Norton & Co Ltd, the House of Lords considered the circumstances under which an invention shall be taken to be new under the Patents Act 1977 s 2. Their Lordships questioned whether a patent may be granted for an old product used in an old way but for a new purpose. This aspect of the decision created problems in respect of infringement. Nevertheless, it was acknowledged that while the question of whether a person is working an invention is objective in the case of a claim for a product per se, this may be different where the claim is for the use of a product.   <I> (casenote) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/liberman.html">Overreaching Provisions in Software License Agreements (Note)</A> by Michael  <STRONG>Liberman </STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/carroll.html">Priority of Invention in United States Patents: From the Paris Convention to GATT (Note)</A> by John F.  <STRONG>Carroll, IV </STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/davies1.html">Privacy and Human Rights" by James Michael</A> reviewed by Simon <STRONG>Davies</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1.</I>  <I> (book review) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1f.html">Privacy and Telecommunications</A> by R. <STRONG>Bradgate</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/llewel2.html">Proposals for the Introduction of a Community Utility Model System: A UK Perspective</A> by Margaret <STRONG>Llewelyn</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I> The European Commission is currently looking at proposals to introduce a new Community intellectual property right (IPR), the Utility Model (UM) which will serve to protect those inventions which are not regarded as capable of fulfilling the strict granting requirements of the patent system. The Commission wishes to harmonise existing practices and to broadened the scope of UM protection. One of the EU member states which has been the most vocal in voicing its concerns over the proposals is the UK. The reason for the extent of concern is that UK does not at present operate a UM system. There is, therefore, considerable concern and doubt about: a) the need to introduce UM protection and b) the scope and type of protection to be granted. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1l.html">Publishing and Multimedia Law" by Michael Henry</A> reviewed by A.  <STRONG>Charlesworth</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/lemley.html">Rights of Attribution and Integrity in Online Communications</A> by Mark A.  <STRONG>Lemley</STRONG><I> Journal of Online Law  .</I> Is there a right of attribution in cyberspace? Professor Lemley explores the interrelated rights of attribution, integrity of identity, and anonymity as they apply to electronic communications. A related issue involves net users' rights to integrity of their electronic identities, whether real or pseudonymous. For a reliable online community to develop, users must be able to trust the integrity of the electronic personalities created by themselves and others. Finally, the desire of many Internet users to remain anonymous complicates the exercise of their other rights. Lemley concludes that net users may be able to protect their rights to attribution and the integrity of their electronic personalities only at the risk of losing their right to anonymity.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/burk.html">Trademarks Along the Infobahn: A First Look at the Emerging Law of Cybermarks </A> by Dan L.  <STRONG>Burk </STRONG><I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
