<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   International Law
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : International Law
  </H1>

<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/padgett.html">African Elephant, Africa, and CITES: The Next Step </A> by Bill  <STRONG>Padgett </STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I>  <I> (note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/bland.html">Analysis of the United Nations International Tribunal to Adjudicate War Crimes Committed in the Former Yugoslavia:  Parallels, Problems, Prospects</A> by Mark A. <STRONG>Bland</STRONG><I>  Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>   <I> (Note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/buchanan.html">Border Crossings: NAFTA, Regulatory Restructuring, and the Politics of Place </A> by Ruth  <STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I> Professor Buchanan begins her paper by questioning whether recent economic and political shifts towards notions of "globalization" (e.g., the NAFTA) have failed to consider the politics or economics of change in particular places. Her prime example of a "place" where integration is illogically forced against a background of differentiation is the U.S.-Mexico border region. Through the scope of a "regulatory complex" (a complex of legal, institutional, regulatory, and social orderings), she departs from the common view of the NAFTA as a productive tool of North American integration, and instead views the NAFTA as exacerbating "differences between localities, industries, and labor markets." She argues that the debate over the NAFTA underemphasized its different local, sectoral, and regional impacts.. The author focuses primarily on the social and economic aspects of the maquiladora industry, including labor migration into the United States and the potential for increased migration because of the NAFTA. She concludes by arguing for a shift in perspective from the outdated, territorial concept of "borders" to the richer, more complex concept of "borderlands." <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/nash.html">Challenge of Trade Liberalization to Cultural Survival on the Southern Frontier of Mexico</A> by June <STRONG>Nash</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/maslen3.html">Child Soldiers, The Role of Children in Armed Conflicts", by G S Goodwin-Gill and I Cohn</A> by Stuart <STRONG>Maslen</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I>  <I> (book review) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/bodansky.html">Customary (and not so Customary) International Environmental Law</A> by Daniel  <STRONG>Bodansky</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I> This article reevaluates the concept of customary international environmental law. Claims that these norms have the status of customary law reflect a conception of "customary law" that focuses on what states say, rather than what they do. The purported norms of customary environmental law represent community standards - they set the general terms of the debate about what actions are appropriate. Since this functions do not depend on a norm's legal status, debates about whether a norm is part of customary international law tend to be sterile. The author concludes that international lawyers should spend less time debating the legal status of environmental norms and more time working to make them more precise and effective.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/greenhouse.html">Democracy and Demography</A> by Carol J. <STRONG>Greenhouse</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/marasi.txt">Development ideology perspective</A> by Lakshman <STRONG>Marasinghe</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994.</I> The article traces the legal history of Sri Lanka -- highlighting the assumptions relating to individual rights to property made in colonial law. The author then discusses the move away from adjudication by means of an adversarial system towards the establishment of conciliation boards for dispute resolution. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/oconnell.html">Enforcement and the Success of International Environmental Law</A> by Mary Ellen  <STRONG>O'Connell</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I> Professor O'Connell argues that international law is generally obeyed. Its enforcement is based primarily on compliance, not enforcement. Accordingly, the author argues against using international enforcement mechanisms to enforce international environmental law. Instead, she posits that domestic courts should be used; however, certain obstacles, such as sovereign immunity, the doctrine of standing, and the principle of forum non conveniens, must be overcome. She argues that it may be possible to overcome many of these court-made obstacles to enforcing international law through domestic courts.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/drennen.html">Environmental Diplomacy: Negotiating More Effective Global Agreements" by Lawrence E. Susskind</A> reviewed by Thomas E. <STRONG>Drennen</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I> (book review) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/atik.html">Environmental Standards Within NAFTA: Difference by Design and the Retreat from Harmonization</A> by Jeffery  <STRONG>Atik</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I> Professor Atik argues that NAFTA, in legitimating regulatory differences among the NAFTA parties, represents a repudiation of standard harmonization. Both high- standard and low-standard parties may prefer the maintenance of differentials. While there may be efficiency gains, other interests, including environmental quality, may well be compromised. However, despite NAFTA's maintenance of divergent standards, the agreement does allow for the joint determination of environmental standards, and institutions established by NAFTA are available to both monitor and adjust standards (especially Mexico's) to appropriate levels.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/lazer.html">Flow of International Water Law: The International Law Commission's Law of the Non-Navigational Uses of International Watercourses</A> by David J. <STRONG>Lazerwitz</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993.</I>  <I> (Note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/barber.html">Global Democracy or Global Law: Which Comes First?</A> by Benjamin R. <STRONG>Barber</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/aman.html">Global Perspective on Current Regulatory Reform: Rejection, Relocation, or Reinvention</A> by Alfred C <STRONG>Aman, Jr</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I> This article addresses recent U.S. administrations' attempts at regulatory reform and notes that as far as the actual reforms are concerned, there are more similarities over time than differences. The globalization of politics and markets and manufacturing, in particular, has helped create global political economic forces that militate in favor of various forms of deregulation and privatization not only in the United States, but in other western democracies as well. Firms are increasingly free to choose where to locate plants and employ labor. He considers the Reagan, Bush, and Clinton administrations' market-oriented regulatory reforms. He notes some important differences among these administrations, however, and argues that reformers who advocate market approaches as a means to collective ends, rather than as ends in themselves, are likely to be more receptive to the development of new global legal regimes. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/shapiro.html">Globalization of Law</A> by Martin <STRONG>Shapiro</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/delbruck.html">Globalization of Law, Politics, and Markets Implications for Domestic Law: A European Perspective</A> by Jost <STRONG>Delbrck</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993.</I> Professor Delbrck argues that the modern form of the State should be based on the concept of the "Open Republic" -- a constitutional government involving the democratic participation of all citizens and a "marketplace of ideas."   He focuses on a republic geared in nature and character toward an "openness" to accepting and assimilating citizens of different ethnic, religious, or cultural backgrounds, with equal rights for those diverse citizens. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/cav.html">Globalization of Markets and Its Impact on Domestic Institutions</A> by S. Tamer <STRONG>Cavusgil</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/gallaghe.html">Great Lakes Water Quality Initiative: National Standards Governing a Binational Resource; A Call for International Rulemaking </A> by Sean P.  <STRONG>Gallagher </STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I>  <I> (note) </I><HR>
<LI>The "<A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/sands.html">Greening" of International Law Emerging Principles and Rules</A> by Philippe <STRONG>Sands</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994.</I> The article is outlines some of the more controversial (from a U.S. perspective) international legal issues which have arisen in recent years, including in particular the global instruments adopted at the United Nations Conference on Environment and Development  (UNCED), held at Rio de Janeiro in June 1992, as well as the regional developments reflecting the efforts of the EC Member States in their attempt to "green" the EEC Treaty. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/todd.html">Hague Convention on the Civil Aspects of International Child Abduction: Are the Convention's Goals Being Achieved? </A> by Julia A.  <STRONG>Todd </STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I>  <I> (note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/zoller.html">Institutional Aspects of International Governance</A> by Elisabeth  <STRONG>Zoller</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I> Professor Zoller argues that the international community is not really a community at all, but several "intertangled communities" with common interests. Common interests among nation states and priority setting are the two prerequisites necessary for international governance. Although power is decentralized in international governance, it can still be exercised collectively. She concludes by suggesting that the shortcomings of global regulation, especially with respect to environmental issues, can be addressed most effectively by the institutional aspects of international governance. To that end, the success of international governance, in terms of international environmental protection, depends upon the leadership exerted by the "great powers," specifically the United States.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/danish.html">International Environmental Law and the &quot;Bottom-Up&quot; Approach:  A Review of the Desertification Convention</A> by Kyle W.  <STRONG>Danish</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I> Mr. Danish analyzes the Desertification Convention of 1995, discussing both the Convention's efforts to address the environmental degradation and the Convention's impact on international notions of the state. This Convention employs a "bottom-up" approach; it focuses on local developmental issues and the marginalized peoples living in the threatened areas. It provides increased international recognition for non-governmental organizations and local land users. The article presents an overview of the Convention and analysis based on international environmental legal norms.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/chapman.html">International Law, Industrial Location, and Pollution</A> by Duane Chapman, Vivek Suri and Jean  <STRONG>Agras</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I> The dominant position of economists on trade and environment is that increasing trade raises living standards, which provide the economic basis for reduced pollution. The paper presents a very different perspective. In summary, on a global basis, the international economy is characterized by increasing trade and world economic product, stagnation in gross economic product per capita, accelerating energy use, and exponential growth in emissions of major pollutants.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/maurer.html">Law Writing, Immigration, and Globalization in the British Virgin Islands </A> by Bill  <STRONG>Maurer </STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I> While British Virgin Islanders (BVIslanders) proudly term themselves a "law and order" people and seek to distinguish themselves from other Caribbean peoples, the territory remains as wedded as ever to its British rulers and the West. BVIslanders consider their ties to Britain a critical element of their uniqueness and thus self-rule is never seriously discussed.The author illustrates this paradox by describing the passage and effects of the BVI's International Business Companies Ordinance, a law that established the BVI as a tax haven. He argues that while BVIslanders are proud to call the law their first truly local one, in fact the local legislature was forced as a result of this law to submit to increased foreign regulatory scrutiny and to enact recommendations set out in a Coopers and Lybrand study commissioned by the British. Mr. Maurer concludes that as long as Britain remains the reference point for the BVI's claims to autonomy, BVI self-rule will remain out of reach. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/moran.html">Law, Politics, and Economics of Amazonian Deforestation</A> by Emilio F. <STRONG>Moran</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/griffin.html">MARPOL 73/78 and Vessel Pollution: A Glass Half Full or Half Empty?</A> by Andrew <STRONG>Griffin</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/gilbert4.html">Problems and Process: International Law and How We Use It", by Rosalyn Higgins</A> reviewed by Geoff  <STRONG>Gilbert</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/porras.html">Puzzling Relationship Between Trade and Environment:  NAFTA, Competitiveness, and the Pursuit of Environmental Welfare Objectives</A> by Ileana M.  <STRONG>Porras</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I> Harmonization of standards to facilitate the free flow of trade is a familiar trade goal. NAFTA's provisions regarding environmental standards, however, are not a straightforward requirement to harmonize standards. Rather, NAFTA recognizes state autonomy in standard setting, on the one hand, while requiring a form of upward harmonization, on the other. The result of such an arrangement is the perpetuation of economic and political inequality among states. NAFTA fails to give equal attention to the demands of "sustainable development" in poorer countries.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/abbott.html">Regional Integration Mechanisms in the Law of the United States: Starting Over</A> by Frederick M. <STRONG>Abbott</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/steer.html">Role of Multilateral Finance and the Environment: A View from the World Bank</A> Andrew Steer and Jocelyn  <STRONG>Mason  </STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I> Since funding for the Rio Earth Summit agreements has not been forthcoming, multilateral financial institutions (MFIs) have taken responsibility for advancing the environmental agenda set forth at the Summit. MFIs furnish three crucial functions in implementing the global environmental agenda. First, MFIs are able to target investments in developing countries that involve important environmental issues. Second, MFIs are able to support policy reforms within developing countries to ensure environmental standards and issues are properly addressed. Finally, MFIs can multiply a small amount of funding into a significant amount.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/acaintro.html">Symposium: Introduction</A> by Alfred C.  <STRONG>Aman, Jr.</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995.</I> There is strong evidence to suggest that increasing world trade and production has dramatically increased global pollution and that the legal regimes currently in place can be made more effective. If these treaties and organizations are but the first steps towards achieving an international approach to environmental quality, what should the next generation of international environmental laws, agencies, and approaches look like? Do we have the necessary legal framework in place to protect the global environment, or are new approaches and reforms necessary?  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/chan.html">Taiwan's Application to the GATT: A New Urgency With the Conclusion of the Uruguay Round</A> by Susanna <STRONG>Chan</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I> (Note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/christop.html">U.S. Policy toward the New Independent States: A Pragmatic Strategy Grounded in America's Fundamental Interests </A> by Warren  <STRONG>Christopher</STRONG><I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/rose.html">U.S.-Japan Trading Relationship and Its Effects</A> by Richard <STRONG>Rosecrance</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/gilb2.html">Who has Jurisdiction for Cross-Frontier Financial Crimes?</A> by Geoff <STRONG>Gilbert</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I> This article has been prompted by the Nick Leeson case, where a trader in the Japanese derivatives market was working in Singapore, but whose activities had the effect of bringing down Barings, the oldest merchant bank in the City of London. It considers which State should have jurisdiction in these circumstances, particularly since the alleged criminal may now be in a third State. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/katz.html">World of Regions:   America, Europe, and East Asia</A> by Peter J. <STRONG>Katzenstein</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993.</I> Recent events in world politics are creating a substantial break in the history of international politics comparable in this century only to the years 1917-22 and 1947-53. With specific reference to Germany and Europe as well as to Japan and East Asia, this essay argues that these changes in world politics tend to reinforce a new political regionalism that expresses different norms, which, in the foreseeable future, are unlikely to be assimilated fully into one normative global order. <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
