<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Law and Economics
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Law and Economics
  </H1>

<LI>An <A HREF="http://www-leland.stanford.edu/~tstanley/tjspaper/tstanley.paper.html">Analysis of the Rules of Contribution and No Contribution for Joint and Several Liability in Conspiracy Cases </A> by Timothy James  <STRONG>Stanley </STRONG><I>  .</I> This paper examines deterrence and settlement effects of three rules that have been applied in joint and several liability conspiracy cases. These rules are the no contribution rule, the contribution with claim reduction rule and the contribution with settlement reduction rule.  It is shown that where conspirators have asymmetric information that the no contribution rule could lead to less deterrence than the contribution rules for all conspirators. The paper concludes that the contribution with claim reduction rule with liability allocated per capita or the no contribution rule should be applied to joint and several liability in conspiracy situations. The one rule that is disfavored is the contribution with settlement reduction rule. More importantly this paper encourages greater focus on whether the joint harm is caused by defendants acting in concert or independently.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz1a.html">Bargaining at a Distance: the Mailbox Rule and Related Contract Formation Games</A> by Avery  <STRONG>Katz</STRONG><I>  .</I> This essay applies economic analysis to the so-called "mailbox rule". An economic analysis reveals some broad functional implications of the rule. It turns out that the legal rule governing contracts by correspondence does make an allocative difference -- though not for the reliance reason that has been offered in the legal commentary. The difference between the rules lies in their ability to encourage the offeror to keep to the bargain when bad news arrives only after reliance has taken place. On this dimension of efficiency, the mailbox rule performs better than its alternatives.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecipa/archive/UT-ECIPA-REAS-95-01.html">Breaking Up is Hard to Do: The Economics of Spousal Support </A> by Samuel A. <STRONG>Rea, Jr.</STRONG><I>  .</I> The introduction of "no-fault" divorce has eliminated the traditional basis for spousal support without providing a satisfactory alternative. In a recent case, Elliot v. Elliot, an Ontario court awarded the woman half of the difference between her earnings had she not married and her earnings after the divorce. The model developed in this paper highlights the changes in earnings that result from specialization in housework or market work, investment in children, and investment in the spouse's human capital. The incentive effects on human capital, marriage, and divorce are considered. Although no measure is perfect, the paper concludes that the approach taken in Elliot, adjusted for additional leisure enjoyed during marriage, offers a reasonable compromise between competing objectives.  <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/schwartz.html">Challenge of Peremptory Challenges</A> by Warren F and Edward P <STRONG>Schwartz</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/hansmann.html">Comparative Law and Economics of Private Trusts</A> by Ugo Mattei and Henry <STRONG>Hansmann</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I>  <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/thompson.html">Determining Appropriate Surface Water Quality Policies through a Law and Economics Theory of a Sanctionable Act</A> by Dale B. <STRONG>Thompson</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> In this paper, I examine surface water quality policies using a new pragmatic policy-analysis framework. This framework emphasizes institutional-transaction-costs which are normally forgotten or misanalyzed in typical cost-benefit analyses. These costs include the costs of initially enacting a policy,implementing it, and enforcing it. A performance-based policy instrument, nontradeable effluent limit permits, has much lower institutional- transaction-costs associated with it than does an incentive based instrument, effluent taxes. My framework allows these transaction costs to be properly considered in relation with other costs and benefits. I conclude that we should address policies to reduce nonpoint pollution at regional bodies like irrigation districts. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/ayres.html">Distinguishing Between Consensual and Nonconsensual Advantages of Liability Rules</A> by Eric Talley and Ian <STRONG>Ayres</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I>  <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/edlin.html">Do Guaranteed-Low-Price Policies Guarantee High Prices?  How Price Matching Challenges Antitrust</A> by Aaron S. <STRONG>Edlin</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Price-matching policies can allow firms to break a competitive equilibrium by discriminating in price between informed and uninformed customers. The resulting high prices can persist even when there is entry to the industry, which implies that welfare losses may be much larger than under ordinary monopoly. This article suggests that price-matching policies may violate the price-discrimination laws and examines whether price matchers should be able to protect themselves with a "meeting competition" defense. The article concludes they should not have such a defense; studying price-matching policies forces one to acknowledge that meeting competition is not inherently competitive. The article also explores whether the vertical agreements between buyer and seller violate the Sherman Act. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Pardolesi-1995/pardo.html">Economic Analysis of Contract Law: Some Insights</A> by R.  <STRONG>Pardolesi</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>An <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Students/neg.html">Economic Analysis of Liability Rules</A> by A.  <STRONG>Rossato</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/posner.html">Economic Psychology of the Old</A> by Richard A. <STRONG>Posner</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Economists usually take values, preferences and attitudes as givens and  consider how a rational actor can maximize his utility by the choices he makes based on those givens. This paper takes a different tack and considers  the extent to which the psychology of the old might fruitfully be modelled as a consequence rather than foundation of rational choice. The paper does  not argue that old people always or even often make conscious choices; only  that certain choices, conscious or unconscious, appear to be rational in the  sense of utility-maximizing once the fundamental attributes of being old are  understood. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506002.abs">Economics of Agency Law and Contract Formation</A>  <STRONG>Rasmusen</STRONG><I>  .</I> This article addresses issues that arise in agency law when agents make contracts on behalf of principals. The main issue is whether the principal should be bound when the agent makes a contract with some third party on his behalf which the principal would immediately wish to disavow. The resulting tradeoffs resemble those in tort law, so the least-cost-avoider principle is useful for deciding when contracts are valid and may be the underlying logic behind a number of different legal doctrines applied to agency cases. In particular, an efficiency explanation can be found for the undisclosed principal rule.   <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecipa/archive/UT-ECIPA-MTURNER-95-02.html">Economics without Free-disposal: Quota-induced Discarding in Heterogenous Fisheries </A> by Matthew A.  <STRONG>Turner </STRONG><I>  .</I> Individual quota (IQ) programs are a promising and increasingly common means of regulating fisheries. The responses of profit maximizing fishers to different IQ programs are analysed. This analysis shows first that the most common types of individual quota program can induce discarding, and second that of all possible individual quota programs, only those that regulate the value of harvest never induce discarding. Since discarded fish have a high mortality rate, "value-based" individual quota programs are superior to their more conventional counterparts in that they waste fewer fish. These results are driven by the fact that the fishing technology examined here does not satisfy a "free-disposal" assumption. Since this free disposal assumption is ubiquitous in production theory, and not obviously true, the framework developed herein is useful for analyzing a broad class of problems involving joint production.   <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/kaplow2.html">Fundamental Objection to Tax Equity Norms: A Call for Utilitarianism Taxation</A> by Louis <STRONG>Kaplow</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Anti-utilitarian norms often are used in assessing tax systems. Two motivations support this practice. First, many believe utilitarianism to be insufficiently egalitarian. Second, utilitarianism does not give independent weight to other equitable principles, notably concerns that reforms may violate horizontal equity or result in rank reversals in the income distribution. This investigation suggests that a policy maker who believes in the Pareto principle -- that any reform preferred by everyone should be adopted -- cannot consistently adhere to any of these anti-utilitarian sentiments. Moreover, the affirmative case for utilitarian tax policy assessment is stronger than is generally appreciated. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/lott.html">Have Changing Liability Rules Compensated Workers Twice for Occupational Hazards?: Earnings Premiums and Cancer Risks</A> by Richard L. Manning and John R. <STRONG>Lott</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> During the last couple of decades, courts have intervened in employment relationships by allowing employees to circumvent workers' compensation liability restrictions, and gain compensation for long term illnesses  through tort cases. Recent papers point to firms divesting themselves of  operations whose employees handled dangerous substances as firms protecting themselves from these new liabilities. Supposedly, these actions prevent their workers from being justly compensated. We show that the central legal  premise behind this argument is wrong. Firms cannot expose workers to  hazards and then eliminate this liability by divesting or shutting down the hazardous operation. This paper also shows that workers were already being well compensated for carcinogenic exposures even before the courts started allowing workers to collect large damages for occupational illnesses.  Instituting the new liability rules also coincided with a large drop in earnings premiums. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/stout.html">Heterogeneous Expectations Model of Speculation and Speculative Bubbles</A> by Lynn A. <STRONG>Stout</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Economists disagree over the proper definition of the word "speculation" as well as over its effects on the welfare of speculators and society as a whole. Although conventional theories of risk-hedging, information arbitrage, and liquidity dealing certainly explain some apparently speculative transactions, this paper examines a fourth, and relatively neglected, approach that focuses on heterogeneous expectations and uncertainty as a cause of speculative trading. The paper explores the value of the HE approach by examining the implications of the HE model for three issues that have troubled economic theory: the proper definition of "speculation", the causes and nature of asset price bubbles, and the normative significance of speculative trading. In each case, the HE model proves of value in understanding speculative phenomena. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9503/9503001.abs">Identifying Participants in a Price-fixing Conspiracy: Output and Market Share Tests Reexamined </A> by Mehmet E.  <STRONG>Karaaslan</STRONG><I>  .</I> If there is a cartel agreement among a subset of firms in an industry, it should be predicted that all firms in that industry will increase prices. According to the output test and its market share variant if the output or the market share of the firm that claims to be innocent in the collusive activity rises in response to the price increase, that firm's claim should be accepted as true. Using a collusive variant of the dominant firm model, this paper shows that these are not robust tests to reveal innocence or guilt. This paper also shows that a market share test can not be used to prove a dominant firm's intent for predatory pricing   <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/bradley.html">In Defense of Abolishing Chapter 11</A> by Michael Rosenzweig and Michael <STRONG>Bradley</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> In this paper we have responded to those who have criticized our call for repeal of Chapter 11. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/kantor.html">Insurance Rationing and the Origins of Workers' Compensation</A> by Shawn Everett Kantor and Price V <STRONG>Fishback</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> A central question concerning the economic motivation for the adoption of workers' compensation is the extent to which workers had access to their desired levels of private accident insurance around the turn of the century. We develop a theoretical model that suggests that workers' compensation should have caused a reduction in households' precautionary saving. Our empirical test is based on a sample of over 7000 households surveyed for the 1917-1919 Bureau of Labor Statistics Cost-of-Living study. Regression analysis suggests that households tended to save less, holding all else constant, if their states had workers' compensation in force. This finding, in concert with qualitative information about the insurance industry, provide some evidence that insurance companies were unable to effectively offer workplace accident insurance to a wide range of workers. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/thiel.html">Is There A Demand for Pain and Suffering Coverage ?</A> by Stuart E. <STRONG>Thiel</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> There is a large literature on this question, almost all of which avers that economic theory rules out the possibility of demand for insurance coverage of nonpecuniary losses on a priori grounds. This paper argues that the existence or nonexistence of demand for pain and suffering coverage is a purely empirical issue and policy recommendations should view it as such. The underlying economic theory is too weak to support such a recommendation without, at least, some supporting evidence. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/rubin.html">Judicial Hierarchies and the Rule-Individual Tradeoff</A> by. Joel L. Schrag and Paul H <STRONG>Rubin</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> In the United States laws are interpreted by a hierarchy of judges. In this paper we identify a conflict between the different levels of the hierarchy. When deciding how to rule in a case, a judge balances the interests of the litigants against the interests of the people who will be affected by the precedent that the ruling establishes. But higher level judges' decisions affect more people than lower level judges' decisions. Therefore, higher level judges should produce decisions that are less sensitive to the litigants' interests and more sensitive to the interests of the rest of society. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Alpa-1995/alpa.html">Law and Economics and Method Analysis: the Contractual Damages Issue</A> by G. Giampieri and A.  <STRONG>Alpa</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/waterman.html">Local Monopsony, Free Riding, and Antitrust Policy</A> by David <STRONG>Waterman</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> This paper models the development of market structure in industries which are characterized by upstream economies of scale in the distribution of differentiated products to retail firms having local monopoly power within separate geographic areas. Examples are cable television and other mass media. Antitrust applications to the cable television, motion picture, and newspaper industries are discussed. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/eastman.html">Logic of the Two-Person Coase Theorem in Game-Theoretic Terms</A> by Wayne <STRONG>Eastman</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> The logic of the Coase Theorem translates into the game-theoretic point that a 2 x 1 matrix in which only one player apparently has a choice is actually a 2 x 2 matrix in which the other player can offer the first player a payoff. Given this point, it follows that there is a close connection between the Coase Theorem and the Prisoner's Dilemma. It further follows that a Coasean analysis of a payoff matrix will often show opportunities for threat bargaining that a standard analysis does not show. The game-theoretic interpretation of Coasean logic has implications for law, some of which differ from those associated with other interpretations of the Coase Theorem. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/levmore.html">Love It or Leave It: Property Rules, Liability Rules, and Exclusivity of Remedies in Partnership and Marriage</A> by Saul <STRONG>Levmore</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> The traditional rule in partnership law, and the continuing rule in domestic relations law, is that a claim for dissolution (or divorce) is a partner's exclusive remedy. On its face this mandatory "love-it-or-leave-it" rule seems strange, anachronistic, unfair, and inefficient, because where there is going concern value there is room for exploitation. In contrast, corporate law offers a kind of reverse "exclusivity" rule, in that a shareholder can bring a suit for damages but can not force dissolution of the enterprise. These rules offer a window to general questions about remedies. The Calabresi-Melamed property-liability rules framework is expanded with the incorporation not only of rules explored by Polinsky and by Krier and Schwab but also with several seemingly novel rules that draw attention to the possibility of remedies that are only forward-looking or only backward-looking. The critical connection is that the power to "stop" a partnership or a marriage is akin to the power to stop a nuisance, so that love-it-or-leave-it rules can have the character of a "property rule" with no liability component. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Torts/Mattei1.html">Making the Other Path Efficient :Economic Analysis and Tort Law in Less Developed Countries</A> by U. Mattei and M.  <STRONG>Bussani</STRONG><I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/dfriedman.html">More Justice for Less Money: A Step Beyond Cimino</A> by David <STRONG>Friedman</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> In Cimino v. Raymark, a federal court resolved 2298 asbestos cases with 160 trials by grouping the cases, trying a random sample of each group, and awarding to all members of each group the average verdict. I propose an improved procedure designed to allocate damages correctly among plaintiffs. Plaintiffs' attorney submits a list of claims; defense selects cases for trial. Plaintiffs in untried cases receive their claim times the average ratio of award to claim for tried cases. Some potential problems are examined through a formal model. Modifications are suggested to adapt the procedure to situations involving a very large number of very small cases. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/carney.html">Political Economy of Competition for Corporate Charters</A> by William J. <STRONG>Carney</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> This paper explains the differences between American and European corporate laws using interest group theory. Interest groups are described as seeking to extract rents through corporate laws. Their ability to do so is constrained by the mobility of corporations to seek competing corporate laws. A common market provides the optimal competitive setting, and has been present in the U.S. but not in Europe until recently. Evidence of interest group legislation appears far greater in Europe than in the U.S. Further, European nations adopted anticompetitive conflicts of law rules that U.S. states could not adopt, given their competitive setting. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz2a.html">Positivism and the Separation of Law and Economics </A> by Avery  <STRONG>Katz </STRONG><I>  .</I> The economic analysis of law has since its beginnings in the early 1960s provoked substantial opposition and antagonism in the legal academy and, to a lesser extent, in the profession at large. In this essay, I argue (1) that economists as a matter of official professional methodology subscribe to a strong form of positivism; and that law and economics is particularly influenced by this approach; (2) that this methodological position places law and economics firmly on one side of the controversy over legal positivism, and (3) that the pragmatic justifications for taking this methodological position within the field of economics do not necessarily carry over to the field of law.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506003.abs">Predictable and Unpredictable Error in Tort Awards: The Effect of Plaintiff Self Selection and Signalling</A> by Eric  <STRONG>Rasmusen </STRONG><I>  .</I> If a potential tort plaintiff can predict that the court will overestimate damages he is more likely to bring suit, but if the court is aware of this, it will adjust its awards accordingly. In general, court error implies that the court should moderate extreme awards whether they are high or low, because of regression towards the mean. Predictable error, however, tends to push the optimal adjustment downwards and unpredictable error pushes it upwards, because of plaintiff selection and signalling, respectively. The expectation of either kind of error leads plaintiffs to bring meritless suits.   <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/game/papers/9403/9403007.abs">Product Safety: Liability, R&D and Signaling </A> by Jennifer F. Reinganum and Andrew F.  <STRONG>Daughety </STRONG><I>  .</I> This paper develops a two-stage model of product design and safety signaling incorporating a parametric liability specification in a monopoly context. In the first stage, the firm engages in research and development in order to determine the safety of its product. We model the research and development process as sequential sampling from a fixed distribution of potential safety levels. Since the outcome of research and development trials is unobservable to consumers, in the second stage of the model the firm must choose its price with the understanding that consumers may attempt to draw inferences about the product's safety.  <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/shavell.html">Property Rules vs Liability Rules</A> by Steven Shavell and Louis <STRONG>Kaplow</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> A fundamental legal problem is whether property rights should be protected by property rules or by liability rules. In this Article, we provide a systematic economic analysis of the choice between property and liability rules. We answer a basic question: why is it that liability rules are commonly used in the context of harmful externalities (such as pollution and automobile accidents), whereas property rules are generally employed toprotect possessors of things against potential takers? In the course of our analysis, we demonstrate that many commonly held beliefs about property and liability rules are mistaken. Our analysis is also relevant to policy; for example, we show that in important contexts liability rules (and pollution taxes) are more efficient than property rules (including much regulation) even when damages must be set using only limited information about harm. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9507/9507002.abs">Radar Detectors, Fixed and Variable Costs of Crime </A> by Tim  <STRONG>Stanley</STRONG><I>  .</I> Raising the sanction will not always lead to less crime, and may lead to more crime. If a criminal has the opportunity to commit multiple criminal acts and has fixed and variable costs of committing these acts, then an increase in the criminal sanction, over a certain range of sanctions, may actually lead the criminal to commit more crime. Once the criminal pays his fixed costs, they will be sunk costs, and thus they will no longer enter into the criminal's decision process of committing criminal acts. But the variable cost of crime will enter into the criminal's decision process. The example of the criminal's decision to purchase a radar detector and to speed is used to illustrate the point.   <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/waldfogel.html">Sentencing Policy, Implied Demographic Welfare Weights, and the Theory of Sentencing Reform</A> by Joel <STRONG>Waldfogel</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Different groups of people experience varying degrees of different externalties. By a government's choice of expenditures to control externalities, it affects different members of the population differently. These choices implicitly "value" the welfare of members of different groups. This paper adapts the framework developed by Ahmad and Stern (1984) to infer welfare weights underlying a system of commodity taxation, to infer the welfare weights implicitly attached to different population groups by U.S. sentencing policy. We also calculate welfare-improving directions of sentencing reform. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/chung.html">Settlement of Litigation under Rule 68: An Economic Analysis</A> by Tai-Yeong <STRONG>Chung</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Rule 68 of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure provides that a plaintiff who refuses a defendant's formal settlement offer and then obtains a judgment not more favorable than the offer must pay the defendant's post-offer costs. An economic analysis is provided (i) to argue that the standard definition of settlement range is not adequate for analyzing Rule 68, because it contains unreasonable, dominated offers, (ii) to present a new definition of the refined settlement range that is adequate for analyzing the effects of Rule 68, and (iii) to propose a revision of Rule 68 to encourage settlements of litigation. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/conferen/papers/schwartz.html">Simple Majority Rule for Criminal Jury Trials: The Verdict is Now In</A> by Edward P. Schwartz and Warren F.  <STRONG>Schwartz</STRONG><I>  .</I> The paper proposes that the current two way unanimity rule governing jury verdicts in criminal cases be replaced by a rule of simple majority.  Neither the history of the use of the unanimity rule nor the reasons advanced to justify its use provide persuasive grounds for retaining the rule rather than employing the rule of simple majority which is used in virtually all other democratic institutions.   <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/ogus1.html">Some Reflections on the Woolf Interim Report</A> by Anthony  <STRONG>Ogus</STRONG><I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1.</I> Drawing on law and economics literature, the author critically examines some of the key features of the Woolf Interim Report. The need to constrain lawyers' incentives to escalate costs is paramount and some shift away from the adversarial culture to judicial management is desirable. But care must be exercised in designing new procedures if the changes are not to be self-defeating. There is also a danger of over- optimism regarding proposals for encouraging alternative dispute resolution (ADR). More generally, legal costs will remain a problem so long as professional self-regulation is allowed to imposes fetters on competition.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506001.abs">Stigma and Self-Fulfilling Expectations of Criminality</A> by Eric  <STRONG>Rasmusen</STRONG><I>  .</I> A convicted criminal suffers not only from public penalties, but from stigma, the reluctance of others to interact with him economically and socially. Conviction can convey useful information about a person, which makes stigmatization an important and legitimate function of the criminal justice system, quite apart from moral considerations. Whether stigma will operate in this way depends on expectations and the crime rate, however, which can lead to multiple, pareto-ranked equilibria with different amounts of crime and stigma.   <I> (Postscript/PDF) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/dewees.html">Sulfur Dioxide Emissions from Smelters: The Historical Inefficiency of Tort Law</A> by Donald N. <STRONG>Dewees</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> This paper examines the success of tort law in dealing with the massive discharge of sulfur dioxide and toxic metals from non-ferrous smelters between 1890 and 1940. These large and isolated sources should have been the easiest of polluters to sue; there could be no doubt as to whose pollution caused the damage. But devastating pollution often survived litigation. To what extent were the external costs of pollution actually imposed on the polluter? Did injunctive relief or damages more closely approximate optimal pollution control? Were special commissions more or less adept at understanding and controlling the problem than the courts? The performance of the tort system is evaluated. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/wyeth.html">Takings as the Failure of the Regulatory Market</A> by George <STRONG>Wyeth</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> This paper suggests addressing the stubborn "takings" problem by using a hypothetical perfectly competitive "regulatory market" as a normative reference point. The paper contends that this approach allows us to resolve apparent tensions between past takings analyses, and reconcile apparently conflicting views about the desirability of compensation. It also examines the light that such an approach sheds on the generally discredited notion of a "harm-benefit" distinction -- arguing that the hypothetical market provides the "baseline" that allows such a distinction to be drawn.. This approach is seen to explain some hitherto difficult rulings, and to suggest changes in other areas. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/adler.html">Theory of Corporate Insolvency</A> by Barry E <STRONG>Adler</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Modern scholarship on corporate bankruptcy proceeds from the premise that investors are willing to expend resources identifying and saving insolvent firms that can continue efficiently. In this paper, I argue that this premise may be faulty, at least for publicly held firms. Viewed properly, from an ex ante perspective, investors may wish to design initial capital structures that will produce few insolvent but viable firms. Consequently, in a world of unimpeded contractual choice, investors might forgo any collective insolvency process and permit a firm's dismemberment by individual creditors. I argue, accordingly, that corporate bankruptcy law is illegitimate for large firms, not because these firms face no collective action problem among creditors, but because it may be appropriate for these firms to suffer the consequences of any such problem. In the process of making this argument, I offer new explanations for three puzzling phenomena: the apparent investor acquiescience in the expensive American bankruptcy reorganization process; common equity's residual interest in a firm that fails to pay dividends on preferred stock; and asset-based finance. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/peterson.html">Theory Versus Fact in the Choice of Organizational Form: A Study of Body and Frame Production in the Automobile Industry</A> by Laura Bennett Peterson and Thomas G. <STRONG>Marx</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Klein, Crawford and Alchian (hereinafter  "Klein") argue that relationship-specific assets raise problems of opportunism, escalate the cost of market  contracting, and explain General Motors' vertical integration into body manufacturing. We set forth in our paper the theoretical debate between Coase and Klein. Coase understates, we believe, the extent to which the cost of contracts rises with the risk of opportunism. We study the General Motors-Fisher Body relationship after GM's acquisition of its body supplier. A relationship is seen between asset specificity and internal, as well as external, transactions costs. We examine the historical relationships between other automobile companies and their body suppliers. We find a range of customer-supplier relationships -- from total integration, to tapered integration, to no integration and from long-term contracts, to short-term contracts, to no contracts. Such a range of relationships undermines any deterministic conclusion that asset specificity dictates vertical  integration. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/clay.html">Trade without Law: Private-Order Institutions in Mexican California</A> by Karen <STRONG>Clay</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> This paper examines the role played by a private-order institution in California in the growth of a complex system of trade in the absence of law. This institution, a coalition, governed agency relations among the merchants in California. A reputation mechanism supported by an information network, behavioral norms, and expectations regarding who was a member mitigated the commitment problem inherent in having individuals handle goods that they did not own by linking a merchant's past behavior and his future payoff. A game-theoretic model of the agent's commitment problem motivated by primary evidence from the merchants' correspondence on individual transactions is presented. Predictions that follow from the model explain patterns of social and economic behavior, the organization of trade, and the coalition's response to exogenous shocks. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz3a.html">When Should an Offer Stick? The Economics of Promissory Estoppel in Preliminary Negotiations (forthcoming, Yale Law Journal, 1996) </A> by Avery  <STRONG>Katz </STRONG><I>  .</I> Under the modern doctrine of promissory estoppel, a person making an offer is bound when the offeree relies, even in the absence of an acceptance or any explicit negotiation for a binding option. But courts have generally declined to construe the offeree's reliance as an acceptance or as a promise to accept. This paper considers the incentive effects of this rule for the optimal timing of contract formation and reliance. In preliminary negotiations both parties have some control over the timing of reliance, but the rule of law affects their relative incentives to exercise this control. I argue that the efficiency of promissory estoppel in preliminary negotiations depends in large part on which party holds the bulk of the bargaining power ex post.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/brinig.html">Why Can't a Woman Be More Like a Man? Or Do Gender Differences Affect Choice ?</A> by Margaret F <STRONG>Brinig</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> The question explored in this paper is whether a woman operates like a man when making choices.  In the first section, I present some empirical data consistent with theories of innate gender difference in attitudes towards risk. In each case, however, at least one other explanation for the results cannot be ruled out. The next section discusses whether women are more altruistic than men. Several empirical evaluations of altruism reveal no measurable difference based upon gender, except for findings that women do more housework and spend more time with children even when working the same number of hours as men. Finally, I conclude with some very preliminary experimental results on gender and time preference. The empirical work provided in this paper includes fairly extensive testing of risk aversion and more limited information about differential altruism and discount rates. Women do seem to behave quite distinctively when their choices involve their families. However but their decisionmaking is otherwise similar to that of men, except that women are more risk averse. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
