<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Legal Education
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Legal Education
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1d.html">Building on the Paper Case</A> by J. <STRONG>Killingley</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1f.html">CD-roms in Legal Education </A> by N.  <STRONG>Nunn-Price</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/hodgson5.html">Comparative Dimension (or What do They Know of England, that only England Know?)</A> by John  <STRONG>Hodgson</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5.</I> This article examines the provisional proposals in the ACLEC Consultation Paper on the initial stage of legal education which bear on the emphasis to be given to the study of European and Comparative law. The article attempts to analyse the practical implications of this approach. In particular the empirical evidence as to the expertise and resources available in this field is scrutinised. The thrust of the ERASMUS/SOCRATES programmes is considered, and attempts are made to indicate an academically appropriate but practical way forward.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/birks1.html">Compulsory Subjects: Will the Seven Foundations ever Crumble?</A> by Peter <STRONG>Birks</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1.</I> In this comment the consequences for legal education of the joint announcement by the Law Society and the Council of Legal Education in January 1995 of the changes to the core requirements for qualifiying law degrees are examined. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3f.html">Computer Managed Teaching and Learning in Law</A> by R. <STRONG>Jones</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>" <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/cal/1maharg/">Contracts": An Introduction to the Skills of Legal Writing and Analysis</A> by Paul  <STRONG>Maharg</STRONG><I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One .</I> <I>Contracts</I> is a computer program designed for first year undergraduates. The program addresses undergraduates' legal writing and problem-solving skills. <I>Contracts</I> calls on learning theories which support the view that such skills can be learned via computer-based learning. Despite the general opinion that legal practitioners will more and more be using computers to communicate, there have been few other attempts to date to help students learn basic legal writing skills on computer.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2b.html">Cost of Computer Assisted Learning (CAL)</A> by M. <STRONG>Young</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1ed.html">Courseware Consortium for Law</A> by A. <STRONG>Paliwala</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/reuther.pag">Dorothy's friend goes to law school</A> by Kevin  <STRONG>Reuther</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995).</I> The experiences of a gay student at Harvard Law School. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/section3.html">Editorial --  Legal Education</A> by Fiona <STRONG>Cownie</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/wheater.txt">Electronic Classroom : a Personal Account of Learning the Law by Email</A> by Murray <STRONG>Wheater</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993.</I> A student's personal account of the initial attempt to teach a law course with a computer network as a tool of teaching. This is with particular emphasis on the use of information technology.  This leads to personal reflection on the benefits of structuring the course in such a way. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1e.html">Executive Training </A> by N. <STRONG>McDonnell</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I> With all the hype about the information age, it is not surprising that lawyers and other professionals feel that they should learn about computers. But how? This article presents one successful approach at the University of Waikato, NZ.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>An <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1b.html">Experiment with Electronic Law Tutorials </A> by R. Widdison and F.  <STRONG>Pritchard </STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/webb2.html">Extending the Theory-Practice Spiral: Action Research as a Mechanism for crossing the Academic/Professional Divide</A> by Julian <STRONG>Webb</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I> Current theory and practice in legal education is increasingly emphasising the need to develop in students the capacity for 'reflective practice' or 'humane professionalism'. This paper argues that the logic of humane professionalism has yet to be carried through to the later, continuing, stages of English legal education. It suggests that the law schools should play a significant part in this development by fostering an alternative, research-based, paradigm for continuing professional development. The vehicle proposed for this is 'action research', a hermeneutic and practice-based research method, which shares many of its epistemological assumptions with the experiential methods of clinical legal education. The paper concludes by analysing the main strengths and weaknesses of action research and offers a preliminary assessment of its capacity to contribute both to practitioners' self-knowledge of their practices and to academic understanding of the 'legal world'. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/mbecker.pag">Foreword: Becoming Visible</A> by Mary  <STRONG>Becker</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995).</I> In this introduction to the Symposium, Prof. Becker describes the subsequent articles and gives her perspective on the difficult position of gays and lesbians in the legal academy. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2j.html">How can learning technologies improve learning ?</A> by D. <STRONG>Laurillard</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/abbey5.html">Information Technology and the Legal Practice Course</A> by Robert M  <STRONG>Abbey</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5.</I> This article considers four topics. First, it considers the nature of the legal practice course ("LPC") in the context of its stated aims and information technology ("IT"). Secondly, it seeks to review that context in the light of the forms of IT currently used in the legal profession. Thirdly, it reports the results of a survey of the provision of IT within existing legal practice courses. Finally the article concludes with an analysis of the use of IT within one specific LPC and makes some general recommendations.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3e.html">Interactive video in legal education and practice</A> by K.Vaughan and M. <STRONG>Hibbs</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1c.html">Justification and Criticism of Legal Computer Assisted Learning (CAL)</A> by M. <STRONG>Young</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/cownie2.html">Language of the Law: international students and the reading of statutes</A> by Fiona Cownie, with Wendy <STRONG>Addison</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I> Working in a second or third language can cause difficulties for such students, especially in a subject like law, where the nuances of language are so important. The problems which can arise are readily apparent when students begin to work with statutory materials. This article suggests an approach to the reading of statutes which could be used by law teachers and language support staff in working with international law students. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/widdis4.html">Law Courseware: Big Bang or Damp Squib?</A> by Robin  <STRONG>Widdison</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/rofes.html">Law school and the constitution</A> by Peter K.  <STRONG>Rofes</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1.</I> This essay is a satirical look at constitutional law course descriptions in law school bulletins. The author suggests alternative descriptions that would make bulletins as "fresh and original" as the typical curriculum in the classroom. This essay is part of a larger project in which the author examines different aspects of the American law school. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/torrem5.html">Legal Education in Flanders</A> by Leo F.T. Torremans and Paul L.C  <STRONG>Torremans</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5.</I> This article describes the system of legal education in Flanders. It subjects both the curriculum and methods of teaching and assessment to critical review and highlights a number of areas where there is room for improvement. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/leith4.html">Legal Education in Germany: becoming a Lawyer, Judge, and Professor</A> by Philip  <STRONG>Leith</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 .</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/boy.htm">Logic and Experience: The Origin of Modern American Legal Education" by William P. Lapiana</A> reviewed by Allen D <STRONG>Boyer</STRONG><I> Cornell LR January 1995.</I>  <I> (book review) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3i.html">Lord Chancellor's Advisory Committee on Legal Education</A>  <STRONG></STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3c.html">New Frontiers in Instructional Software</A> by B. <STRONG>Boyd</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3b.html">Place of Computers in Legal Education</A> by H. <STRONG>Collins</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mcgregor.txt">Practical Strategies for Using Computers in Legal Education</A> by Myles McGregor-Lowndes and Alan <STRONG>Davidson</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2.</I> The paper chronicles the past experience and future plans of the School of Accounting Legal Studies Computer Based Education Project at the Queensland University of Technology.  The first part of the paper describes the computer based learning products that have been produced and tested.  The second part of the paper outlines products that are currently under production. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/maughan2.html">Problem-Solving Through Reflective Practice: The Oxygen of Expertise or Just Swamp Gas?</A> by Caroline  <STRONG>Maughan</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> Donald Schn provides us with a theory of professional knowledge and its development through 'reflection'. He claims it is the ability to practise reflectively which distinguishes the expert from the merely competent professional. The central question for this paper is the value of developing reflective practice skills and processes at the 'novice' level. The author argues that novice lawyers can be enabled to develop reflective skills and habits. However, she indicates that there are still unanswered questions about the transferability of the skills and processes learned as students progress into the vocational stage of legal education and the early years of practice.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/sears.pag">Queer L</A> by Brad  <STRONG>Sears</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995).</I> The experiences of a gay student at Harvard Law School. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/bradney1.html">Raising the Drawbridge: Defending University Law Schools</A> by Anthony <STRONG>Bradney</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1.</I> This article considers the implications for legal education of the consultation paper produced by the Lord Chancellor's Advisory Committee on Legal Education. It seeks to analyse the broad themes of the paper in the light of the changing context in which legal education and university education generally takes place. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/resear1.html">Research Report One: The Association of Law Teachers Legal Education</A>  <STRONG></STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/resear2.html">Research Report Two: Legal Skills and Clinical Legal Education</A> by Richard <STRONG>Grimes</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2e.html">Setting Common Minimum Standards of Computer Competency for undergraduates</A> by P. <STRONG>Osbourne</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/lauw.txt">Specialisation, accreditation and the legal profession in Australia and Canada</A> by Inge <STRONG>Lauw</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994.</I> An analysis and comparative evaluation of formal specialisation and accreditation programmes in Australia and Canada, as a means of improving the public's access to legal services.  Also examines the implications of these programmes on marketing and advertising by the legal profession. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3h.html">Teaching Artificial Intelligence to Law Students</A> by D. <STRONG>Hunter</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2i.html">Technology, Learning and the Trans-Atlantic divide</A> by R. Susskind and A. <STRONG>Paterson</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/jarvis5.html">The Quiet Revolution - Improving Student Learning in Law" by Le Brun and Johnstone</A> reviewed by Francoise  <STRONG>Jarvis</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/valdes2.pag">Tracking and Assessing the (Non)Inclusion of Courses on Sexuality and/or Sexual Orientation in the American Law School Curriculum: Reports From the Field After a Decade of Effort </A> by Francisco  <STRONG>Valdes</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995).</I> In this article Prof. Valdes presents his survey of American law schools offering courses pertaining to sexual orientation and sexuality issues and expresses "cautious optimism" about the future inclusion of gay and lesbian issues in legal curricula.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1a.html">Using Artificial Intelligence in Legal Computer Assisted Instruction</A> by R. <STRONG>Jones</STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-1e.html">Using computers in the classroom: An electronic discussion</A>  <STRONG></STRONG><I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.1.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/hartwell.pag">What a Difference a Gay Makes:  An Empirical Study of the Impact of 'Out' Gay Law Faculty on Law School Curriculum and Policies</A> by Steven  <STRONG>Hartwell</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995).</I> In this article Prof. Hartwell presents a study of out gay faculty in American law schools and the correlation between out gay faculty and gay student activity.  <I>  </I><HR>
