<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Medical Law
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Medical Law
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/keywood3.html">B v Croydon Health Authority 1994, CA: Force-Feeding the Hunger-Striker under the Mental Health Act 1983</A> by Kirsty <STRONG>Keywood</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> Judgments declaring the legality of force-feeding under the Mental Health Act 1983 had previously been made by courts of first instance. B v Croydon Health Authority [1995] 1 All ER 683 gave the Court of Appeal the opportunity to review the legality of force-feeding under the Mental Health Act.  This casenote assesses the validity of the ruling that force-feeding under the Mental Health Act 1983, s 63 is lawful and analyses the implications of the decision for hunger-strikers in other contexts. <I> (Casenote) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/mcginley.html">Beyond health care reform: reconsidering certificate of need laws in a managed competition system</A> by Patrick  <STRONG>McGinley</STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1.</I> Today, thirty-eight states retain CON ("certificate of need")laws, requiring advance approval by state agencies for most hospital expansions and major equipment purchases. Many of these same states have passed managed competition laws. This Comment explores the role of CON laws. It summarizes the origin and implementation of a managed competition health care strategy, illustrating that managed competition can lower health care costs. Part IV shows that managed competition invalidates the presumptions underlying the alleged need for CON. Part V focuses on Florida, and urges Florida and similarly situated states either to scale back CON or accept the failure of managed competition that CON will inevitably cause. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/platt.html">Dispelling the negative myths of managed care: an analysis of anti-managed care legislation and the quality of care  provided by health maintenance organizations </A> by Lisa D. Stream and Bruce D.  <STRONG>Platt </STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2).</I> The first part of this Article discusses managed care legislation. Specifically, it provides a summary of some of the last five years of Florida's legislative health care advancements incorporating managed care concepts. It then discusses some of the proposed legislation which targets HMOs and other managed care plans. The available literature indicates that the quality of care provided by HMOs is as good as, if not better than, the quality of care provided in a traditional fee-for-service setting. Legislation which would cripple managed care in the name of preserving quality is unnecessary and counterproductive.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/swensen.txt">Drug Problems in Western Australia:  a review of non-criminal mechanisms ...</A> Greg <STRONG>Swensen</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I> Discussion of the shortcomings in the Western Australian system of notifying drug addicts. There is an examination of the practical considerations as well as the natural justice implications. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/chiles.html">Health care reform in Florida: promoting improved access, cost, and quality</A> by Lawton  <STRONG>Chiles </STRONG><I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2).</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.vifp.monash.edu.au/contents.html">Law and Ethics in Medicine"</A>  <STRONG></STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2.</I>  <I> (online book) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/rodgers4.html">Law Commission's Proposals on Mental Capacity and the Legality of Elective Ventilation for Transplantation Purposes</A> by M E  <STRONG>Rodgers</STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 .</I> This article discusses the legality of elective ventilation in the light of the recent proposals on mental capacity by the Law Commission. The author suggests that the process is not tainted with illegality. In addition, the relationship between the process of elective ventilation and the importance of the patient's best interests is explored, through consideration of the definition of 'best interests' put forward by the Law Commission. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/laing1.html">Police Surgeon and Mentally Disordered Suspects: An Adequate Safeguard?</A> by Judith M  <STRONG>Laing</STRONG><I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1.</I> This article examines the role of the police surgeon in identifying and assessing mentally disordered suspects in police custody. It suggests that police surgeons lack the relevant knowledge and expertise to deal with these people, and concludes that duty-psychiatrist schemes currently operating at magistrates' courts should be extended to police stations to ensure that mentally disordered suspects are assessed by medical professionals who possess the relevant psychiatric expertise.    <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/kee2.txt">Refusal to Consent to Treatment on Religious Grounds</A> by Pei-Teing <STRONG>Kee</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2.</I> The writer considers the legal aspects of refusal of consent to medical treatment on medical grounds, particularly focussing on refusal of blood transfusions by Jehovah's Witnesses.  The paper concludes with an examination of the ethics of overriding patients' informed decisions based on religious objections. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/parkin2.html">Where now on Mental Incapacity?</A> by Alan  <STRONG>Parkin</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> The investigation carried out by the Law Commission into mental incapacity and ways in which the law in relation to it might be regularised has been exhaustive and thorough. The decision not to proceed with the resulting draft bill in its present form leaves matters, for the moment, in limbo. The constituency affected is large but its members are easily overlooked. Is it the case that the long awaited regularisation of their legal position is to be delayed because of fears, which may be groundless, that the recommendations make euthanasia more likely? Will doubts about some aspects of the report prevent or unduly delay straightforward and non-controversial reforms which will affect the lives of many <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
