<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Taxation
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Taxation
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/bandt.txt">Against Fairness: A Brief Critical Look at Concepts Used to Analyse a Tax system</A> by Adam <STRONG>Bandt</STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994.</I> The author examines from a Marxist perspective the criteria of equity, efficiency and simplicity commonly used to critique taxation systems. Contradictions arising from the use of these ideals are discussed by reference to the Australian tax system. By contrast with capitalist ideology, the author concludes that an ideal tax system should be revolutionary, empathic and democratic <I>   </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/kaplow2.html">Fundamental Objection to Tax Equity Norms: A Call for Utilitarianism Taxation</A> by Louis <STRONG>Kaplow</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> Anti-utilitarian norms often are used in assessing tax systems. Two motivations support this practice. First, many believe utilitarianism to be insufficiently egalitarian. Second, utilitarianism does not give independent weight to other equitable principles, notably concerns that reforms may violate horizontal equity or result in rank reversals in the income distribution. This investigation suggests that a policy maker who believes in the Pareto principle -- that any reform preferred by everyone should be adopted -- cannot consistently adhere to any of these anti-utilitarian sentiments. Moreover, the affirmative case for utilitarian tax policy assessment is stronger than is generally appreciated. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/schoettle.html">Reconsidering the Supreme Court's Role in Deciding Challanges to State Taxes - Some Perspectives from the Gatt</A> by Ferdinand P. <STRONG>Schoettle</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> This paper recommends that the Supreme Court adopt free trade principles as criteria for deciding Commerce-Clause-based disputes about the Constitutionality of state taxes and abandon its current approach of balancing the states' need for revenues against other considerations. The paper summarizes the principles that guide tax design in a multijurisdicitonal free trade world. Analogies from the GATT illustrate that in deciding challenges to state taxes based on free-trade principles the Supreme Court fills a normal institutional role that other free-trade federations replicate. GATT panel reports illustrate how the basic economic principles supporting free trade can serve as guides to decision. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/11/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/watax">Review of Western Australian State Taxes - 1993</A>  <STRONG></STRONG><I> E-Law Volume 1 No 2 1994.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/11/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/94watax">Review of Western Australian State Taxes - 1994</A>  <STRONG></STRONG><I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994.</I> The review is particularly concerned with issues of equity, efficiency and simplicity.  The review also considers moral exemptions, Federal-State financial relations, the effect of technological advances on financial taxes and examines other forms of revenue raising by the government, including departmental fees and charges.  Several recommendations are made for the improvement of the method of taxation in Western Australia. <I> (WordPerfect 5.1) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/kee1.txt">Should Gambling Gains Be Taxed as Income?</A> by Pei-Teing <STRONG>Kee</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2.</I> The author considers the taxation treatment of gambling gains in Australia.  She examines the reasons for and against taxing such gains as income, how this could be done and whether losses would then have to be deductible. The paper concludes that these gains should be taxed, and proposes a way in which this could be done. <I>  </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
