<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Trusts and Estates
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Trusts and Estates
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/morris3.html">Charity Investment in the UK: Some Contemporary Issues for the 1990s</A> by Debra <STRONG>Morris</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> The investment duties of charity trustees have been highlighted recently due to the termination of the investment function of the Official Custodian for Charities (who previously held investments worth about 1.25 billion for over 40,000 charities) together with the increased awareness of trustee responsibilities generally. In April 1995, the law relating to charity investment changed so that now charity trustees are less restricted in their investment decisions.  The Charity Commissioners have also issued a number of recent policy  statements concerned with investment powers. This paper examines these recent developments and argues for an even less restricted legal regime. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/dunn2.html">Charity law - a political scandal?</A> by Alison  <STRONG>Dunn</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2.</I> The extent to which charities may pursue political activities is a contentious issue. Whilst Parliament has steadfastly refused to embrace political aims as charitable purposes, charities are nevertheless permitted to undertake a degree of political activity. The Charity Commission has updated its guidelines on the types of political activity and political campaigning that charities may pursue, and the penalties involved for breach. Whilst advice in this uncertain area is to be welcomed, the Charity Commission guidelines have limitations.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/hansmann.html">Comparative Law and Economics of Private Trusts</A> by Ugo Mattei and Henry <STRONG>Hansmann</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I>  <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/sprince1.html">Trustees' duty to defend - Look before you leap, when to leap and how high</A> by Alan <STRONG>Sprince</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1.</I> Fear of exposure to costs is a dominant influence in concentrating the minds of litigants, actual and potential.  For trustees, however, the dilemma is more complex. The precise nature of the duty to defend proceedings - was examined and refined by Lightman J in the recent case of Alsop Wilkinson (A Firm) v Neary ([1995] 1 All ER 431, Ch D). <I> (casenote) </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
