<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by subject :   Women and Law
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/GIFS/BOOK.GIF" ALIGN = MIDDLE>Essays by subject : Women and Law
  </H1>

<LI><A HREF="gopher://gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk:70/00/ltc/publications/conferences/oxford/akobay.txt">Challenging the National Dream: Gender Persecution and Canadian Imigration Law</A> by Audrey <STRONG>Kobayashi</STRONG><I> Oxford Critical Legal Conference 1993.</I>  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/morris5.html">Death throes of the sick man: Webb v EMO Air Cargo (UK) Ltd (No 2) (Casenote)</A> by Anne  <STRONG>Morris </STRONG><I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5.</I> Starting with the notion that the Sex Discrimination Act 1975 could not apply to pregnant women, the judges finally accepted that the Act could be construed to protect them from sexually discriminatory behaviour on the part of employers, but only by the clumsy mechanism of comparison with a sick man. Despite what seemed to be clear and definitive decisions from the European Court of Justice, the judges in the United Kingdom have persisted in the idea that comparison was necessary. Nowhere was the reluctance to promote equality of opportunity for pregnant workers more apparent than in the long, tortuous saga of Mrs Webb. Eight years after she announced her pregnancy and was sacked, we have a final decision, (The Times, 20 October 1995; other references in the text are from the transcript) subject only to the calculation of compensation.  <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/morris4.html">Equal Helpings: Ratcliffe and others v North Yorkshire County Council</A> by Anne <STRONG>Morris</STRONG><I> Web JCLI [1995] 4.</I> Women workers, particularly part-timers, have seen significant successes in their pursuit of sex equality, and there are signs that the English courts are matching - even outdoing - the European Court in matters connected with employment rights and wages (see R v Secretary of State for Employment ex parte EOC ([1994] 1 All ER 910 HL, and R v Secretary of State ex parte Seymour-Smith CA (unreported). The Ratcliffe decision in the House of Lords ([1995] IRLR 439) has ramifications not only for equal pay generally but also for the policy of compulsory competitive tendering.  <I> (Casenote) </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/iorns3.txt">Feminist Looks at Ronald Dworkin's Theory of Equality</A> by Catherine J. <STRONG>Iorns</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993.</I> This piece is a 'work in progress' dealing Dworkin's theory of equality and its related social vision from a feminist perspective.  A notable substantive problem is the theory's reliance on a questionable public/private distinction.  The definition of equality fails to address the reality of the oppression of women in the real world. The author criticises the central freedom/equality dichotomy. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A "<A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/clarke.txt">Near" Contract Experience</A> by Kirsty <STRONG>Clarke</STRONG><I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994.</I> The author focusses especially on the unwillingness of the court to intervene in and enforce 'domestic' agreements, in which women are often the weaker party.   It is propounded that contractual rules and terminology may be manipulated so as to perpetuate and legitimate an unequal status quo.  The concepts of the 'reasonable person' and 'freedom of contract' are criticised, and it is proposed that these concepts should be expanded to apply wider principles of fairness which will remedy  basic inequalities of bargaining power. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/valdes3.pag">Proceedings of the Panel on Gender, Sexual Orientation & HIV at the 1995 Women in the Law Conference, Monterey, California, May 5, 1995 </A> Introduced by Francisco  <STRONG>Valdes</STRONG><I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996).</I> In this transcript of the proceedings of the panel on Gender, Sexual Orientation and HIV, sponsored by the State Bar of California Women in Law Committee, the panelists focus on how AIDS affects women, including lesbians.  Four women, a legal worker living with AIDS, an AIDS health and social service provider, a policy-worker and a legal service provider, tell their stories and express their opinions about the impact of the AIDS crisis on them and women generally.   <I>  </I><HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/schenk.html">Proposal to Improve the Treatment of Women in Asylum Law :  Adding a "Gender" Category to the International Definition of "Refugee"</A> by Todd Stewart <STRONG>Schenk</STRONG><I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994.</I>  <I> (Note) </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/edge3.html">Reforming Termination of Pregnancy : Two Models within the British Islands</A> by Peter W <STRONG>Edge</STRONG><I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3.</I> This note considers current proposals for reform of the law governing termination of pregnancy in the Isle of Man and Jersey, and suggests the possible value of these developments for the English jurisdiction. <I>  </I><HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/brinig.html">Why Can't a Woman Be More Like a Man? Or Do Gender Differences Affect Choice ?</A> by Margaret F <STRONG>Brinig</STRONG><I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995.</I> The question explored in this paper is whether a woman operates like a man when making choices.  In the first section, I present some empirical data consistent with theories of innate gender difference in attitudes towards risk. In each case, however, at least one other explanation for the results cannot be ruled out. The next section discusses whether women are more altruistic than men. Several empirical evaluations of altruism reveal no measurable difference based upon gender, except for findings that women do more housework and spend more time with children even when working the same number of hours as men. Finally, I conclude with some very preliminary experimental results on gender and time preference. The empirical work provided in this paper includes fairly extensive testing of risk aversion and more limited information about differential altruism and discount rates. Women do seem to behave quite distinctively when their choices involve their families. However but their decisionmaking is otherwise similar to that of men, except that women are more risk averse. <I> (PostScript) </I><HR>
<UL>
<BR>
</UL>
