<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   A</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/A.GIF" >
Essays by author :   A</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Robert M <EM> Abbey</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/abbey5.html">Information Technology and the Legal Practice Course </A> This article considers four topics. First, it considers the nature of the legal practice course ("LPC") in the context of its stated aims and information technology ("IT"). Secondly, it seeks to review that context in the light of the forms of IT currently used in the legal profession. Thirdly, it reports the results of a survey of the provision of IT within existing legal practice courses. Finally the article concludes with an analysis of the use of IT within one specific LPC and makes some general recommendations.   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Frederick M.<EM> Abbott</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/abbott.html">Regional Integration Mechanisms in the Law of the United States: Starting Over </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by William E. <EM> Adams, Jr.</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/adams.pag">Amicus Brief in Opposition to Florida's Anti-Gay Constitutional Amendment </A> This brief was filed in response to a proposed state constitutional amendment in Florida similar to those proposed in Colorado and Oregon prohibiting protection on the basis of sexual orientation, by specifying bases on which protection <I>could</I> be provided.  This brief successfully argued to the court that the amendment violated Florida statutory requirements requiring that its language and its title be clear and unambiguous in that "the only place where it is not made abundantly clear that this initiative is about the rights or lesbians and gay men is in the amendment itself and its ballot title and summary." (Decision reported at  632 So.2d 1018 (Florida 1994)).   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Fiona Cownie, with Wendy<EM> Addison</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/cownie2.html">Language of the Law: international students and the reading of statutes </A> Working in a second or third language can cause difficulties for such students, especially in a subject like law, where the nuances of language are so important. The problems which can arise are readily apparent when students begin to work with statutory materials. This article suggests an approach to the reading of statutes which could be used by law teachers and language support staff in working with international law students.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Barry E<EM> Adler</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/adler.html">A Theory of Corporate Insolvency </A> Modern scholarship on corporate bankruptcy proceeds from the premise that investors are willing to expend resources identifying and saving insolvent firms that can continue efficiently. In this paper, I argue that this premise may be faulty, at least for publicly held firms. Viewed properly, from an ex ante perspective, investors may wish to design initial capital structures that will produce few insolvent but viable firms. Consequently, in a world of unimpeded contractual choice, investors might forgo any collective insolvency process and permit a firm's dismemberment by individual creditors. I argue, accordingly, that corporate bankruptcy law is illegitimate for large firms, not because these firms face no collective action problem among creditors, but because it may be appropriate for these firms to suffer the consequences of any such problem. In the process of making this argument, I offer new explanations for three puzzling phenomena: the apparent investor acquiescience in the expensive American bankruptcy reorganization process; common equity's residual interest in a firm that fails to pay dividends on preferred stock; and asset-based finance.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Duane Chapman, Vivek Suri and Jean <EM> Agras </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/chapman.html">International Law, Industrial Location, and Pollution </A> The dominant position of economists on trade and environment is that increasing trade raises living standards, which provide the economic basis for reduced pollution. The paper presents a very different perspective. In summary, on a global basis, the international economy is characterized by increasing trade and world economic product, stagnation in gross economic product per capita, accelerating energy use, and exponential growth in emissions of major pollutants.   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Duane Chapman, Vivek Suri and Jean <EM> Agras</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/chapman.html">International Law, Industrial Location, and Pollution </A> The dominant position of economists on trade and environment is that increasing trade raises living standards, which provide the economic basis for reduced pollution. The paper presents a very different perspective. In summary, on a global basis, the international economy is characterized by increasing trade and world economic product, stagnation in gross economic product per capita, accelerating energy use, and exponential growth in emissions of major pollutants.   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael<EM> Aikenhead</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/aiken2.html">Legal knowledge based systems: some observations on the future </A> The adoption by AI researchers specialising in law of new AI techniques, such as case based reasoning, neural networks, fuzzy logic, deontic logics and non-monotonic logics, may move closer to achieving an automation of legal reasoning.   Even if these new techniques do not achieve an automation of legal reasoning however, they will still be valuable in better automating office tasks and in providing insights about the nature of law.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>Reviewed by Michael <EM> Aikenhead</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/aiken2.html">Review of John Zeleznikow and Dan Hunter, Building Intelligent Legal Information Systems: Representation and Reasoning in Law </A> y  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Tom<EM> Allen</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/allen1.html">Children with Special Educational Needs in a Consumer-Driven Education System </A> This article looks at recent changes in the English educational provision which make it more difficult for parents to obtain a satisfactory education for children who have special needs, while at the same time expanding their legal right to the question the provision their children do receive. It examines the general trend to consumerism as the underlying philosophy of educational 'planning' and the statutory framework for protecting the position of special needs children.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by G. Giampieri and A. <EM> Alpa</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Alpa-1995/alpa.html">Law and Economics and Method Analysis: the Contractual Damages Issue </A>   <I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Alfred C<EM> Aman, Jr</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/aman.html">A Global Perspective on Current Regulatory Reform: Rejection, Relocation, or Reinvention </A> This article addresses recent U.S. administrations' attempts at regulatory reform and notes that as far as the actual reforms are concerned, there are more similarities over time than differences. The globalization of politics and markets and manufacturing, in particular, has helped create global political economic forces that militate in favor of various forms of deregulation and privatization not only in the United States, but in other western democracies as well. Firms are increasingly free to choose where to locate plants and employ labor. He considers the Reagan, Bush, and Clinton administrations' market-oriented regulatory reforms. He notes some important differences among these administrations, however, and argues that reformers who advocate market approaches as a means to collective ends, rather than as ends in themselves, are likely to be more receptive to the development of new global legal regimes.  <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Alfred C.<EM> Aman, Jr.</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/aman.html">Migration and Globalization </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> (symposium introduction)
<HR>
<LI>by Alfred C. <EM> Aman, Jr.</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/acaintro.html">Symposium: Introduction </A> There is strong evidence to suggest that increasing world trade and production has dramatically increased global pollution and that the legal regimes currently in place can be made more effective. If these treaties and organizations are but the first steps towards achieving an international approach to environmental quality, what should the next generation of international environmental laws, agencies, and approaches look like? Do we have the necessary legal framework in place to protect the global environment, or are new approaches and reforms necessary?   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Vikram David<EM> Amar</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/ama.htm">Jury participation as political participation akin to voting </A> The argument of this Article is that the link between jury service and other rights of political participation is an important part of our overall constitutional structure.  The voting-jury service linkage was recognized by the Framers in the 1780s, by those responsible for drafting the reconstruction amendments and implementing legislation, and still later.   Moreover, each of the groups the Supreme Court has already determined should be protected against discrimination in jury service is also protected by one of the voting discrimination amendments.  <I> Cornell LR January 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jeffery <EM> Atik</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/atik.html">Environmental Standards Within NAFTA: Difference by Design and the Retreat from Harmonization </A> Professor Atik argues that NAFTA, in legitimating regulatory differences among the NAFTA parties, represents a repudiation of standard harmonization. Both high- standard and low-standard parties may prefer the maintenance of differentials. While there may be efficiency gains, other interests, including environmental quality, may well be compromised. However, despite NAFTA's maintenance of divergent standards, the agreement does allow for the joint determination of environmental standards, and institutions established by NAFTA are available to both monitor and adjust standards (especially Mexico's) to appropriate levels.   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Francis<EM> Auburn</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/auburn1.html">Usenet News And The Law </A> In Rindos v Hardwick (1994) the Western Australia Supreme Court awarded damages for defamation arising out of an item in a newsgroup published on the Internet. This comment examines the decision and considers its wider implications both for users of the Internet and service providers on the Internet.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> (casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by Eric Talley and Ian<EM> Ayres</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/ayres.html">Distinguishing Between Consensual and Nonconsensual Advantages of Liability Rules </A>   <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
