<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   B</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/B.GIF" >
Essays by author :   B</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Adam<EM> Bandt</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/bandt.txt">Against Fairness: A Brief Critical Look at Concepts Used to Analyse a Tax system </A> The author examines from a Marxist perspective the criteria of equity, efficiency and simplicity commonly used to critique taxation systems. Contradictions arising from the use of these ideals are discussed by reference to the Australian tax system. By contrast with capitalist ideology, the author concludes that an ideal tax system should be revolutionary, empathic and democratic  <I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994</I>  
<HR>
<LI>by Benjamin R.<EM> Barber</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/barber.html">Global Democracy or Global Law: Which Comes First? </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by N D M Parry and F R <EM> Barker</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/parry2.html">Open Access, Rights and Legislation </A> At first sight, Part V of the National Parks and Access to the Countryside Act 1949 is a radical piece of legislation. It provides for members of the public to have open access to specified areas of "open country". This is in apparent contrast to the general position in England and Wales. This article seeks generally to examine the impact and effect of Part V of the 1949 Act, and to evaluate the public access 'rights' for which it makes provision, in particular in the light of some of the recent changes to the law of trespass introduced by the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994.   <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Craig Lind and Anne <EM> Barlow</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/lind2.html">Family Redefinition under Part III of the Family Law Bill 1996 </A> We assess the effects of Part III of the Family Law Bill 1996 on unmarried couples in domestic violence law, and on the jurisprudential scope of family law itself. We begin by noting the erosion of the dominance of the traditional married family. Then we consider the equivocal and, consequently, incohesive legal response to this social diversification. We examine the adequacy of the new remedies available to expanded categories of victims of family violence. We conclude that the Bill significantly improves current law, but that by creating three tiers of legal regulation, it inappropriately complicates the resolution of comparable disputes. The ideological importance of the married state has prevented pragmatic and coherent reform.   <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Mary <EM> Becker</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/mbecker.pag">Foreword: Becoming Visible </A> In this introduction to the Symposium, Prof. Becker describes the subsequent articles and gives her perspective on the difficult position of gays and lesbians in the legal academy.  <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Lewis <EM> Becker</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/becker.pag">Recognition of Domestic Partnerships by Governmental Entities and Private Employers </A> In this piece, Lewis Becker discusses the creation and benefits of domestic partnerships.  Prof. Becker explains and examines arguments advanced by opponents of the recognition of domestic partners concluding that these arguments are not supported by the evidence.  Finally Prof. Becker points out questions about the legal effects of domestic partner registration which remain unanswered.    <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael<EM> Begg</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/begg.txt">Justice at Last or Just More of the Past - An Evaluation of the British Columbia Treaty Commission </A> This paper discusses a new agency intended to help create new equitable treaties between the indigenous peoples of British Columbia and the governments of that Province and of Canada. It evaluates the British Columbia Treaty Commission in the hope that readers can draw ideas from the Canadian experience.  The Treaty Commission has no power to investigate, make conclusions, or submit recommendations but is a facilitative agency whose duty is to keep negotiations organised and whose power is primarily persuasive.  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by David Drehmer, Louis Raho, and Jim <EM> Belohlav</EM>, <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/belohlav.html">Ethical Issues of Expert Systems </A> This study examines ethical considerations related to one of the more recent information technologies, the expert system. Specifically, the study examines the perceptions of 499 computer professionals with respect to contribution and ownership issues arising from expert system usage within organizations. The results indicate that no uniform ethical perspective yet dominates the perceptions of the respondents in assessing expert system applications. Unless ethical differences are resolved, the eventual repercussion will be increasing individual and organizational conflict as greater numbers of expert systems are developed and become a part of organizational operations.    <I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1 * No. 2 *</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by J P <EM> Bergfeld</EM>, <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1dutch/default.htm">The Impact of the EC Data Protection Directive on Dutch Data Protection Law </A>   <I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Brett Jarad <EM> Berlin</EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/berlin.html">Revealing the constitutional infirmities of the "crime victims protection act", Florida's new privacy statute for sexual assault victims  </A> This Comment attempts to organize the relevant issues surrounding Florida's new privacy statute for sexual assault victims. It reviews Florida's original legislative answer to the identity-disclosure debate and identifies victim privacy statutes from other jurisdictions. It then summarizes the facts surrounding the publication of the name of William Kennedy Smith's alleged victim. It then analyzes the Florida court opinions in </B>Globe Communications</B> that unanimously held the original ban unconsitutional. Finally, it describes and critiques the replacement statute passed by the Florida Legislature six months after the <B>Globe</B> decision. This Comment concludes that Florida's new Crime Victims Protection Act is no more constitutional than the original statute.    <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Nicolas <EM> Bernard</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/bernard5.html">"Enforcing EC Law" by Josephine Steiner  </A>   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by J.<EM> Bing</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1b.html">Information Systems and Regulatory Management </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Edward L. <EM> Birk</EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/birk.html">Protecting truthful advertising by attorney-cpasIbanez v. Florida Department of Business & Professional Regulation, Board of Accountancy, 114 S. Ct. 2084 (1994) </A> Sylvia Ibanez advertised her qualifications as a member of the Florida Bar, a certified financial planner, and a certified public accountant. She was reprimanded by the Florida Board of Accountancy. Ibanez challenged the Board decision, and the United States Supreme Court ruled in her favour. This Note examines <i>Ibanez</I> and considers the substantial government interests states must demonstrate before they may regulate truthful commercial speech. It concludes that the <i>Ibanez</I> Court failed in its reasoning and holding to extend - under its own precedent - the maximum possible protection to consumers who may be misled, or at least left uninformed.  <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Peter<EM> Birks</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/birks1.html">Compulsory Subjects: Will the Seven Foundations ever Crumble? </A> In this comment the consequences for legal education of the joint announcement by the Law Society and the Council of Legal Education in January 1995 of the changes to the core requirements for qualifiying law degrees are examined.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael<EM> Blakeney</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/blakeney.txt">Milpurrurru & Ors v Indofurn Pty Ltd & Ors - Protecting Expressions of Aboriginal Folklore Under Copyright Law </A> The author traces the development of the law through two cases.  The author points out that the Copyright Act's requirement that the creator of a work be able to assert copyright ownership creates a problem where the design which is the subject of a claim dates back more than 50 years before the infringing act. The author concludes by emphasising the importance of comprehensive legislation to protect expressions of Aboriginal folklore.  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Mark A.<EM> Bland</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/bland.html">Analysis of the United Nations International Tribunal to Adjudicate War Crimes Committed in the Former Yugoslavia:  Parallels, Problems, Prospects </A>    <I>  Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> (Note)
<HR>
<LI>by Micheal A. <EM> Bloom</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/bloom.htm">Bankruptcy's Fresh Start vs. Enviromental Cleanup: Statutory Schizophrenia </A> This article takes a hard look at the exacerbating conflict between bankruptcy and environmental law, especially after the Third Circuit's recent decision in In re Torwico Electronics, Inc. 1 First, this Article outlines the two-step analysis required in administering environmental obligations in bankruptcy. Next, it examines the pertinent case law for each step of the analysis. Finally, this Article attempts to craft a synthesized approach to resolving environmental obligations in bankruptcy, taking into account judicial economies, public policy and the objectives of both bankruptcy and environmental laws. In so doing, the author hopes to simplify and clarify one of the most controversial and confusing areas in bankruptcy and environmental law today.   <I> Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Peter <EM> Blume</EM>, <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1danish/default.htm">Implementation of the European Data Protection Directive : The View from Denmark </A>   <I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Daniel <EM> Bodansky</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/bodansky.html">Customary (and not so Customary) International Environmental Law </A> This article reevaluates the concept of customary international environmental law. Claims that these norms have the status of customary law reflect a conception of "customary law" that focuses on what states say, rather than what they do. The purported norms of customary environmental law represent community standards - they set the general terms of the debate about what actions are appropriate. Since this functions do not depend on a norm's legal status, debates about whether a norm is part of customary international law tend to be sterile. The author concludes that international lawyers should spend less time debating the legal status of environmental norms and more time working to make them more precise and effective.    <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Faye <EM> Boland</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/boland4.html">Involuntary Intoxication Is Not A Defence </A> In R v Kingston [1994] 3 All ER 353, HL, it was held that involuntary intoxication is no defence to a criminal charge and is only relevant insofar as it disproves or proves mens rea. An intent produced by the surreptitious administration of drink or drugs is still a criminal intent.  <I> Web JCLI [1995] no. 4</I> (Casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by D. L. <EM> Booton</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/booton2.html">Novelty of Inventions under the Patents Act 1977 and the European Patent Convention </A> In Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals Inc and Another v H N Norton & Co Ltd, the House of Lords considered the circumstances under which an invention shall be taken to be new under the Patents Act 1977 s 2. Their Lordships questioned whether a patent may be granted for an old product used in an old way but for a new purpose. This aspect of the decision created problems in respect of infringement. Nevertheless, it was acknowledged that while the question of whether a person is working an invention is objective in the case of a claim for a product per se, this may be different where the claim is for the use of a product.    <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> (casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by B.<EM> Boyd</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3c.html">New Frontiers in Instructional Software </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Allen D<EM> Boyer</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/boy.htm">"Logic and Experience: The Origin of Modern American Legal Education" by William P. Lapiana </A>   <I> Cornell LR January 1995</I> (book review)
<HR>
<LI>by Sandra<EM> Boyle</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/boyle.txt">Caveatable interests - the common lore distinguished </A> This paper argues for the removal of heresy in the interpretation of caveatable interests under the Western Australian Torrens System.  Simply, the determination of a caveatable interest should be more flexible, incorporating equitable rules.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by R.<EM> Bradgate</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1f.html">Privacy and Telecommunications </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael Rosenzweig and Michael<EM> Bradley</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/bradley.html">In Defense of Abolishing Chapter 11 </A> In this paper we have responded to those who have criticized our call for repeal of Chapter 11.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Anthony<EM> Bradney</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/bradney1.html">Raising the Drawbridge: Defending University Law Schools </A> This article considers the implications for legal education of the consultation paper produced by the Lord Chancellor's Advisory Committee on Legal Education. It seeks to analyse the broad themes of the paper in the light of the changing context in which legal education and university education generally takes place.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by John <EM> Bridge</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/bridge4.html">"Decisions of the European Court of Justice and their Constitutional Implications" by Aidan O'Neill </A>   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Margaret F<EM> Brinig</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/brinig.html">Why Can't a Woman Be More Like a Man? Or Do Gender Differences Affect Choice ? </A> The question explored in this paper is whether a woman operates like a man when making choices.  In the first section, I present some empirical data consistent with theories of innate gender difference in attitudes towards risk. In each case, however, at least one other explanation for the results cannot be ruled out. The next section discusses whether women are more altruistic than men. Several empirical evaluations of altruism reveal no measurable difference based upon gender, except for findings that women do more housework and spend more time with children even when working the same number of hours as men. Finally, I conclude with some very preliminary experimental results on gender and time preference. The empirical work provided in this paper includes fairly extensive testing of risk aversion and more limited information about differential altruism and discount rates. Women do seem to behave quite distinctively when their choices involve their families. However but their decisionmaking is otherwise similar to that of men, except that women are more risk averse.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Ruth <EM> Buchanan</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/buchanan.html">Border Crossings: NAFTA, Regulatory Restructuring, and the Politics of Place  </A> Professor Buchanan begins her paper by questioning whether recent economic and political shifts towards notions of "globalization" (e.g., the NAFTA) have failed to consider the politics or economics of change in particular places. Her prime example of a "place" where integration is illogically forced against a background of differentiation is the U.S.-Mexico border region. Through the scope of a "regulatory complex" (a complex of legal, institutional, regulatory, and social orderings), she departs from the common view of the NAFTA as a productive tool of North American integration, and instead views the NAFTA as exacerbating "differences between localities, industries, and labor markets." She argues that the debate over the NAFTA underemphasized its different local, sectoral, and regional impacts.. The author focuses primarily on the social and economic aspects of the maquiladora industry, including labor migration into the United States and the potential for increased migration because of the NAFTA. She concludes by arguing for a shift in perspective from the outdated, territorial concept of "borders" to the richer, more complex concept of "borderlands."  <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Dan L. <EM> Burk </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/burk.html">Trademarks Along the Infobahn: A First Look at the Emerging Law of Cybermarks  </A>   <I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Anne M. <EM> Burton</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/burton.html">Gay Marriage - A Modern Proposal:  Applying Baehr v.  Lewin to the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights </A>   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> (Note)
<HR>
<LI>by U. Mattei and M. <EM> Bussani</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Torts/Mattei1.html">Making the Other Path Efficient :Economic Analysis and Tort Law in Less Developed Countries </A>   <I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
