<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/C.GIF" >
Essays by author :   C</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Stephanie E. Lucas and Marc L. <EM> Caden</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/caden_lucas.html">Accidents on the Information Superhighway: On-line Liability and Regulation </A>   <I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Kitty<EM> Calavita</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/calavita.html">U.S. Immigration Policy: Contradictions and Projections for the Future </A> What will become of immigration barriers in the future, particularly given the globalization of capital and the increasing free trade of goods?  And second, is democratic rule antithetical to or destructive of such barriers.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by R. <EM> Caranta</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Torts/Caranta-1996/Frank.htm">Governmental Liability after Francovich </A>   <I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by William J.<EM> Carney</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/carney.html">The Political Economy of Competition for Corporate Charters </A> This paper explains the differences between American and European corporate laws using interest group theory. Interest groups are described as seeking to extract rents through corporate laws. Their ability to do so is constrained by the mobility of corporations to seek competing corporate laws. A common market provides the optimal competitive setting, and has been present in the U.S. but not in Europe until recently. Evidence of interest group legislation appears far greater in Europe than in the U.S. Further, European nations adopted anticompetitive conflicts of law rules that U.S. states could not adopt, given their competitive setting.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by John F. <EM> Carroll, IV </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/carroll.html">Priority of Invention in United States Patents: From the Paris Convention to GATT (Note) </A>   <I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Fred<EM> Cate</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/cate.html">Global Information Policymaking and Domestic Law </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by S. Tamer<EM> Cavusgil</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/cav.html">Globalization of Markets and Its Impact on Domestic Institutions </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Susanna<EM> Chan</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/chan.html">Taiwan's Application to the GATT: A New Urgency With the Conclusion of the Uruguay Round </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> (Note)
<HR>
<LI>by Vivek Suri, Jean Agras and Duane <EM> Chapman</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/chapman.html">International Law, Industrial Location, and Pollution </A> The dominant position of economists on trade and environment is that increasing trade raises living standards, which provide the economic basis for reduced pollution. The paper presents a very different perspective. In summary, on a global basis, the international economy is characterized by increasing trade and world economic product, stagnation in gross economic product per capita, accelerating energy use, and exponential growth in emissions of major pollutants.   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by A. <EM> Charlesworth </EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1k.html">"Cyberspace and the Law: Your Rights and Duties in the On-line World" by Gavino Morin & Edward A. Cavazos  </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by A. <EM> Charlesworth </EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1j.html">"Electronic Banking and the Law" (2nd Ed.) By Anu Anora </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by A. <EM> Charlesworth</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1l.html">"Publishing and Multimedia Law" by Michael Henry </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Lawton <EM> Chiles </EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/chiles.html">Health care reform in Florida: promoting improved access, cost, and quality </A>   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Manda Mellors and Andrew L-T<EM> Choo</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/choo2.html">Undercover Police Operations and What the Suspect said (or didn't say) </A> This paper is about the legal regulation of undercover police operations. A number of recent cases, notably the celebrated cases of Keith Hall and Colin Stagg in 1994, provide instances of undercover operations which apparently have as an aim the extraction of confessions from suspects. This paper examines the adequacy of the relevant executive and judicial pronouncements on undercover police operations.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Warren <EM> Christopher</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/christop.html">U.S. Policy toward the New Independent States: A Pragmatic Strategy Grounded in America's Fundamental Interests  </A>   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Tai-Yeong<EM> Chung</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/chung.html">Settlement of Litigation under Rule 68: An Economic Analysis </A> Rule 68 of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure provides that a plaintiff who refuses a defendant's formal settlement offer and then obtains a judgment not more favorable than the offer must pay the defendant's post-offer costs. An economic analysis is provided (i) to argue that the standard definition of settlement range is not adequate for analyzing Rule 68, because it contains unreasonable, dominated offers, (ii) to present a new definition of the refined settlement range that is adequate for analyzing the effects of Rule 68, and (iii) to propose a revision of Rule 68 to encourage settlements of litigation.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Robert <EM> Clark</EM>, <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1eire/default.htm">Data Protection in the Republic of Ireland </A>   <I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Kirsty<EM> Clarke</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/clarke.txt">A "Near" Contract Experience </A> The author focusses especially on the unwillingness of the court to intervene in and enforce 'domestic' agreements, in which women are often the weaker party.   It is propounded that contractual rules and terminology may be manipulated so as to perpetuate and legitimate an unequal status quo.  The concepts of the 'reasonable person' and 'freedom of contract' are criticised, and it is proposed that these concepts should be expanded to apply wider principles of fairness which will remedy  basic inequalities of bargaining power.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Karen<EM> Clay</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/clay.html">Trade without Law: Private-Order Institutions in Mexican California </A> This paper examines the role played by a private-order institution in California in the growth of a complex system of trade in the absence of law. This institution, a coalition, governed agency relations among the merchants in California. A reputation mechanism supported by an information network, behavioral norms, and expectations regarding who was a member mitigated the commitment problem inherent in having individuals handle goods that they did not own by linking a merchant's past behavior and his future payoff. A game-theoretic model of the agent's commitment problem motivated by primary evidence from the merchants' correspondence on individual transactions is presented. Predictions that follow from the model explain patterns of social and economic behavior, the organization of trade, and the coalition's response to exogenous shocks.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by L.M.<EM> Clements</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/clements3.html">Lending on the Security of Co-Owned Homes, Suretyship and Undue Influence </A> The purpose of this Article is to examine how the law relating to lending on the security of co-owned homes, suretyship and undue influence has recently been developed, what are the real underlying policy issues and whether a balance is being struck between the competing economic interests and protection of the vulnerable.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by David F. Link and Thomas F. <EM> Coleman</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/coleman.pag">Analysis of the Opinion of the Attorney General of California on the Registration of Names of Family Associations by the Secretary of State </A> This article analyzes a recent attempt by gay and lesbian families in California to gain legal recognition by registering with the Secretary of State as unincorporated nonprofit associations as "family associations". Despite opposition, the Secretary of State of California refused to prohibit registration. The authors analyze the statutory language of the California Corporations Code relating to associational name registration and discusses the interpretations applied in light of the highly charged political atmosphere.   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Richard<EM> Collier</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/collier2.html">"Criminological Theory :  Context and Consequences", by J. Robert Lilly, Francis T. Cullen and Richard A. Ball </A>   <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> book review
<HR>
<LI>by H.<EM> Collins</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3b.html">The Place of Computers in Legal Education </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Brian St.J<EM> Collins</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/collins3.html">The Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1994 </A> This article examines the substantive provisions of the Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1994 and compares the protection which these Regulations will afford to consumers with that which is currently available under common law and statutory provisions, in particular the Unfair Contract Terms Act 1977.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by R.V. De Mulder and C.J.M. <EM> Combrink-Kuiters</EM>, <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/issue1/1demuldr/">Is a computer capable of interpreting case law? </A> In the near future the complete texts of all the verdicts of the Supreme Court and a selection of lower courts verdicts will be electronically accessible. This will give a new stimulus to jurimetrical research because some techniques can be applied only on digitised material. Particular attention is paid to the question of whether a conceptual technique is capable of deciding whether cases could be classified as 'positive' or 'negative' in the light of a specific legal item. In other words, whether a computer could interpret legal cases with respect to their outcome.    <I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael <EM> Connolly</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/connolly1.html">How an ECJ Decision on Equal Pay May Affect British Indirect Discrimation Law </A> This note will bring into focus one element of Britain's indirect discrimination legislation: the need for the alleged discriminator to have applied a requirement or condition to the claimant. The standing of the Court of Appeal's judgement in Perera v Civil Service Commission (No 2) [1983] ICR 428 on this element will be examined in light of the decision of the European Court of Justice in Enderby v Frenchay Health Authority [1994] ICR 112, a case on equal pay.   <I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Dennis<EM> Conway</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/conway.htm">Are There New Complexities in Global Migration Systems of Consequence for the United States "Nation-State"? </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Simon <EM> Cooper</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/cooper4.html">Jury Warnings: The Exercise of Judicial Discretion </A> The Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994 abrogated the need for a trial judge to warn the jury of the dangers of acting on the uncorroborated evidence of an alleged accomplice or victim of a sexual offence. This casenote evaluates R v Makanjuola [1995] 145 NLJ 959, the first Court of Appeal case to address these provisions, and considers the future of jury warnings where the evidence has been provided by a witness whose testimony is in some way suspect.  <I> Web JCLI [1995] 4</I> (Casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by C. <EM> Cope</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1g.html">CD-roms - A Law Librarian's Perspective  </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Fiona<EM> Cownie</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/section3.html">Editorial --  Legal Education </A>   <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Wendy Addison and Fiona<EM> Cownie</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/cownie2.html">Language of the Law: international students and the reading of statutes </A> Working in a second or third language can cause difficulties for such students, especially in a subject like law, where the nuances of language are so important. The problems which can arise are readily apparent when students begin to work with statutory materials. This article suggests an approach to the reading of statutes which could be used by law teachers and language support staff in working with international law students.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Barbara <EM> Cox</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/cox3.pag">Amicus brief: In re H.S.H-K, 193 Wis. 2d 649, 533 N.W.2d 419(1995) with introduction. </A> This brief, with an introduction by Prof. Barbara Cox, was written by her and filed with the Wisconsin Supreme Court on behalf of the National Center for Lesbian Rights.  That case involved a custody and visitation claim filed by a non-biological parent of H.S.H-K, who had participated in the decision to have and raise the child with the child's biological parent.  The court granted the petition and in doing so, became the first state supreme court to recognize the visitation rights of a non-biological lesbian parent.   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Barbara J. <EM> Cox</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/cox.pag">A (Personal) Essay on Same-Sex Marriage </A> In this article Barbara Cox examines the institution of marriage in the gay and lesbian community from a personal perspective.  Prof. Cox reviews recent articles in the gay and lesbian literature arguing both for and against marriage as a political goal for homosexuals.  She then relates experiences arising out of her marriage to her partner, Peg.  The author advocates same-sex unions as a way to radically restructure the institution of marriage while challenging heterosexual assumptions about gay and lesbian love.   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Yvonne<EM> Cripps</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/cripps.html">Some Effects of European Law on English Administrative Law </A> Dr. Cripps discusses how European law has affected English law in recent decades, particularly with regard to the constitutional supremacy enjoyed by the English legislative branch.  Dr. Cripps predicts that the English bench will be increasingly willing to take European law into account in their decisionmaking.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
