<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   D</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/D.GIF" >
Essays by author :   D</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Kyle W. <EM> Danish</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/danish.html">International Environmental Law and the &quot;Bottom-Up&quot; Approach:  A Review of the Desertification Convention </A> Mr. Danish analyzes the Desertification Convention of 1995, discussing both the Convention's efforts to address the environmental degradation and the Convention's impact on international notions of the state. This Convention employs a "bottom-up" approach; it focuses on local developmental issues and the marginalized peoples living in the threatened areas. It provides increased international recognition for non-governmental organizations and local land users. The article presents an overview of the Convention and analysis based on international environmental legal norms.   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Eve <EM> Darian-Smith </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/smith.html">Legal Imagery in the "Garden of England"  </A> Ms. Darian-Smith explores the relationship between law and the concept of "landscapes," which she describes as the spatial imagery through which law is conceived and from which it draws meaning. In general terms, the "garden image" is injected into issues of environmental law. Further, she notes that the garden has been a fluid, ever-changing concept. Specifically, Darian-Smith focuses on a recent development regarding the interaction between the law, the garden, and spatial imagery in England: she argues that the new Channel Tunnel between England and France undermines England's identity as an island nation, in effect physically and symbolically severing its claim as the bounded "Garden of England." Such a development, Darian-Smith argues, is a symbol of the eroding of an English identity traditionally thought to be distinct and separate from Europe and its influences, a notion analogous to the way European Community law and English law have been meshed together in environmental issues.  <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jennifer F. Reinganum and Andrew F. <EM> Daughety </EM>, <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/game/papers/9403/9403007.abs">Product Safety: Liability, R&D and Signaling  </A> This paper develops a two-stage model of product design and safety signaling incorporating a parametric liability specification in a monopoly context. In the first stage, the firm engages in research and development in order to determine the safety of its product. We model the research and development process as sequential sampling from a fixed distribution of potential safety levels. Since the outcome of research and development trials is unobservable to consumers, in the second stage of the model the firm must choose its price with the understanding that consumers may attempt to draw inferences about the product's safety.   <I>  </I> (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>by Jennifer F. Reinganum and Andrew F.<EM> Daughety</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/daughety.html">Product Safety: Liability, R&D and Signaling </A> We develop a monopoly model of product design and safety signaling incorporating a parametric liability specification. The firm first engages in R&D to affect the safety of its product. Since the outcome of R&D trials is unobservable to consumers, the firm then chooses its price, understanding that consumers may draw inferences from the price about the product's safety. Consumers acquire and use the product; injuries lead to losses which are allocated by the liability system. We vary the liability system's allocation of losses and trace out the implications for R&D investment and the price-safety relationship.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by William J.<EM> Davey</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/davey.html">European Integration: Reflections on Its Limits and Effects </A> I will first give an overview of this process and consider the factors that the European experience in "regionalization" suggests may limit economic and other forms of integration at the global level. I will then speculate on how the integration of markets in Europe will change European trade policies and on how those changes might affect the United States.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Myles McGregor-Lowndes and Alan<EM> Davidson</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mcgregor.txt">Practical Strategies for Using Computers in Legal Education </A> The paper chronicles the past experience and future plans of the School of Accounting Legal Studies Computer Based Education Project at the Queensland University of Technology.  The first part of the paper describes the computer based learning products that have been produced and tested.  The second part of the paper outlines products that are currently under production.  <I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Simon<EM> Davies</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/davies1.html">"Privacy and Human Rights" by James Michael </A>   <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> (book review)
<HR>
<LI>by Ian <EM> Dawson</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/dawson5.html">Public Policy, Security of Tenure and the Agricultural Holdings Acts  </A> Until recently, an existing existing tenant given security for his life but additionally on two occasions after he voluntarily gave up the tenancy or died, members of his family could go before the Agricultural Lands Tribunal and obtain a new tenancy in their own names. It became accepted doctrine that this security for farmers was essential. With the Agricultural Tenancies Act 1995 there is no statutory security of tenure as regards future tenancies, only that contained in the tenancy agreement itself. But that Act does not affect existing tenancies which continue to enjoy their earlier security of tenure This article seeks to explore the extent to which in fact the accepted doctrine was well founded and whether some adjustment is necessary in the new world after the 1995 Act.   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Guy<EM> De Lusignan</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/delusign.html">Global Migration and European Integration </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by C.J.M. Combrink-Kuiters and R.V. <EM> De Mulder</EM>, <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/issue1/1demuldr/">Is a computer capable of interpreting case law? </A> In the near future the complete texts of all the verdicts of the Supreme Court and a selection of lower courts verdicts will be electronically accessible. This will give a new stimulus to jurimetrical research because some techniques can be applied only on digitised material. Particular attention is paid to the question of whether a conceptual technique is capable of deciding whether cases could be classified as 'positive' or 'negative' in the light of a specific legal item. In other words, whether a computer could interpret legal cases with respect to their outcome.    <I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Fernand<EM> De Varennes</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/devarenn.txt">Indigenous Peoples and Language </A> This article explores the entitlement of indigenous peoples to preferential treatment in linguistic affairs.  This is due not to their position as a minority, but to the acknowledgement in international law, as well as in some national jurisdictions, that indigenous peoples occupy a unique political and legal niche, with corresponding privileges not necessarily available to others.  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jost<EM> Delbrck</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/delbruck.html">Global Migration -- Immigration -- Multiethnicity: Challenges to the Concept of the Nation-State </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jost<EM> Delbrck</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/delbruck.html">The Globalization of Law, Politics, and Markets Implications for Domestic Law: A European Perspective </A> Professor Delbrck argues that the modern form of the State should be based on the concept of the "Open Republic" -- a constitutional government involving the democratic participation of all citizens and a "marketplace of ideas."   He focuses on a republic geared in nature and character toward an "openness" to accepting and assimilating citizens of different ethnic, religious, or cultural backgrounds, with equal rights for those diverse citizens.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Donald N.<EM> Dewees</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/dewees.html">Sulfur Dioxide Emissions from Smelters: The Historical Inefficiency of Tort Law </A> This paper examines the success of tort law in dealing with the massive discharge of sulfur dioxide and toxic metals from non-ferrous smelters between 1890 and 1940. These large and isolated sources should have been the easiest of polluters to sue; there could be no doubt as to whose pollution caused the damage. But devastating pollution often survived litigation. To what extent were the external costs of pollution actually imposed on the polluter? Did injunctive relief or damages more closely approximate optimal pollution control? Were special commissions more or less adept at understanding and controlling the problem than the courts? The performance of the tort system is evaluated.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Brice<EM> Dickson</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.qub.ac.uk/1legal.htm">The Legal System of Nortern Ireland </A> The history and adminstration of the Legal System of Northern Ireland.  <I> Book Chapter </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Professor Janet<EM> Dine</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/dine1.html">Corporate Governance, Cadbury and Friendly Societies </A> The Cadbury Report upon corporate governance has inspired both the Friendly Societies Act 1992 and also a recently published Code of Practice by the Friendly Societies Commission.  Janet Dine sets out details of this Code and comments upon the significance of the new Cadbury-inspired regime for Friendly Societies.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Robert C. <EM> Dorf</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part4.htm">"Use" and the irresistible impulse to legislate  </A> The purpose of this article is to discuss the loss of the possession-use distinction. It is possible that both Congress and the New York legislature will amend the statutes in question to punish both "use" and "possession" of firearms at the same level. It is impossible to applaud judicial hammering of statutory "possession" into "use" which is contrary to legislative intent.    <I> Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Robbie<EM> Downing</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/downing4.html">Magill and the Software Directive: are they interoperable? </A> In Magill, the ECJ held that a refusal to license copyright protected materials could be an abuse of a dominant position under Article 86 of the EC Treaty. The ECJ's analysis could be applied to certain cases where copyright protection of computer programs is relied on to control the creation of a third party product or service, although much depends on how we interpret the ECJ's notion of abuse. Courts would be better advised sensitively to circumscribe the scope of copyright protection under the Software Directive taking into account the experience of US courts.  Article 86 is arguably not the proper instrument to strike the balance inherent in the grant of an intellectual property right. Moreover, in applying Magill, a realistic approach to market power in secondary markets is required.  <I> Web JCLI [1995] no. 4</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jim Belohlav, Louis Raho, and David <EM> Drehmer</EM>, <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/belohlav.html">Ethical Issues of Expert Systems </A> This study examines ethical considerations related to one of the more recent information technologies, the expert system. Specifically, the study examines the perceptions of 499 computer professionals with respect to contribution and ownership issues arising from expert system usage within organizations. The results indicate that no uniform ethical perspective yet dominates the perceptions of the respondents in assessing expert system applications. Unless ethical differences are resolved, the eventual repercussion will be increasing individual and organizational conflict as greater numbers of expert systems are developed and become a part of organizational operations.    <I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1 * No. 2 *</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Thomas E.<EM> Drennen</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/drennen.html">"Environmental Diplomacy: Negotiating More Effective Global Agreements" by Lawrence E. Susskind </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> (book review)
<HR>
<LI>by Alison <EM> Dunn</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/dunn2.html">Charity law - a political scandal? </A> The extent to which charities may pursue political activities is a contentious issue. Whilst Parliament has steadfastly refused to embrace political aims as charitable purposes, charities are nevertheless permitted to undertake a degree of political activity. The Charity Commission has updated its guidelines on the types of political activity and political campaigning that charities may pursue, and the penalties involved for breach. Whilst advice in this uncertain area is to be welcomed, the Charity Commission guidelines have limitations.   <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
