<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   E</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/E.GIF" >
Essays by author :   E</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Wayne<EM> Eastman</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/eastman.html">The Logic of the Two-Person Coase Theorem in Game-Theoretic Terms </A> The logic of the Coase Theorem translates into the game-theoretic point that a 2 x 1 matrix in which only one player apparently has a choice is actually a 2 x 2 matrix in which the other player can offer the first player a payoff. Given this point, it follows that there is a close connection between the Coase Theorem and the Prisoner's Dilemma. It further follows that a Coasean analysis of a payoff matrix will often show opportunities for threat bargaining that a standard analysis does not show. The game-theoretic interpretation of Coasean logic has implications for law, some of which differ from those associated with other interpretations of the Coase Theorem.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Peter W<EM> Edge</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/edge2.html">The Missionary's Position After Kokkinakis v Greece </A> The issue before the European Court of Human Rights in Kokkinakis v Greece concerned Article 9 of the European Convention on Human Rights which protects freedom of religion and required the Court to consider the relationship between those who wish to proselytise, and those who are the targets of such action.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> (Case Comment)
<HR>
<LI>by Peter W<EM> Edge</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/edge3.html">Reforming Termination of Pregnancy : Two Models within the British Islands </A> This note considers current proposals for reform of the law governing termination of pregnancy in the Isle of Man and Jersey, and suggests the possible value of these developments for the English jurisdiction.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Aaron S.<EM> Edlin</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/edlin.html">Do Guaranteed-Low-Price Policies Guarantee High Prices?  How Price Matching Challenges Antitrust </A> Price-matching policies can allow firms to break a competitive equilibrium by discriminating in price between informed and uninformed customers. The resulting high prices can persist even when there is entry to the industry, which implies that welfare losses may be much larger than under ordinary monopoly. This article suggests that price-matching policies may violate the price-discrimination laws and examines whether price matchers should be able to protect themselves with a "meeting competition" defense. The article concludes they should not have such a defense; studying price-matching policies forces one to acknowledge that meeting competition is not inherently competitive. The article also explores whether the vertical agreements between buyer and seller violate the Sherman Act.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Sandy Wong, Fred Greguras and Michael R<EM> Egger</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/greguras.txt">Multimedia Content and the Super Highway: Rapid Acceleration or Foot on the Brake? </A> This article discusses emerging legal issues concerning copyright/patent protection of material used in multimedia applications. Describes existing processes for the administration of copyright/patent material in the US and the deficencies of traditional rights agreements where material is used in multimedia products.  Cites recent reports from Japan concerning the advantages of streamlining copyright/patent administration, and proposes the establishment of a US based copyright/patent clearinghouse for multimedia materials.  <I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Stephanie J. Young and Charles W. <EM> Ehrhardt </EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/ehrhardt.html">Using leading questions during direct examination </A> Historically, limitations upon a party's impeaching its own witness and upon using leading questions during direct examination have been intertwined. Clarification of this area began in 1990, when the Florida Legislature amended section 90.608, Florida Statutes, to permit impeachment of a party's own witness. In 1995, the Florida Legislature amended section 90.612(3), Florida Statutes, to provide for the use of leading questions during direct examination. This Article traces the development of the Florida Rules of Civil Procedure and the Florida Statutes from before the adoption of the Florida Evidence Code to the present.   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Carl H.<EM> Esbeck</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.hamline.edu/~jlr/survey94.html">Survey of Trends and Developments on Religious Liberty in the Courts 1994 </A> The purpose of this survey is to note important case law developments in the state and lower federal courts concerning religious liberty. Purposely omitted are the widely reported United States Supreme Court opinions, as well as cases where the Supreme Court has granted review during the 1993-94 term. The focus here is on significant or interesting cases that may otherwise escape broad attention. Only the facts and rationale of each decision is summarized. No editorial comment on the merits of these cases is intended.  <I> 10 J Law & Relig 544-572 (1993-94)</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
