<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   G</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/G.GIF" >
Essays by author :   G</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Ralph <EM> Gaebler</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/gaebler.html">Review of Yael Tamir, "Liberal Nationalism" </A>   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Sean P. <EM> Gallagher </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/gallaghe.html">Great Lakes Water Quality Initiative: National Standards Governing a Binational Resource; A Call for International Rulemaking  </A>   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I> (note)
<HR>
<LI>by Sam<EM> Garkawe</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/garkawe.txt">Impact of the Doctrine of Cultural Relativism on the Australian Legal System, The </A> This article commences with a discussion of the doctrine of cultural relativism and its validity. In relation to immigrant practices and customs, the doctrine does not deny the incorporation of international human rights standards into Australian law, but calls for a sensitive and culturally aware approach to the question of prohibition of these practices. However, the author concludes that the doctrine does make out a case for denying the applicability of international human rights standards to aboriginal practices and customs.  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by A. Hoey and J. <EM> Garvan </EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1c.html">A Purchasing Decision Support System  </A> Public procurement law is a complex subject which is continually evolving. As a result of the formation of the single market public procurement has become high profile and all those involved in purchasing are now required to be familiar with legislation operating in the fields of public supplies, works, services and utilities. This paper reports on the development of a computerised decision support tool in public procurement by a team of staff from the University of Ulster.   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by A. Hoey and J. <EM> Garvan</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1c.html">A Purchasing Decision Support System  </A> Public procurement law is a complex subject which is continually evolving. As a result of the formation of the single market public procurement has become high profile and all those involved in purchasing are now required to be familiar with legislation operating in the fields of public supplies, works, services and utilities. This paper reports on the development of a computerised decision support tool in public procurement by a team of staff from the University of Ulster.   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jon M. Shepard, Michael G. Goldsby and Virginia W. <EM> Gerde</EM>, <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/gerde.html">Teaching Business Ethics Through Literature </A> America's economic ideology lacks a vocabulary of ethics. If, as we assume, an economic system requires a moral component for long-term survival, students in business schools must be exposed to a vocabulary of ethics that is consistent with the ideology of capitalism. We present a vocabulary of ethics and describe an approach to teaching business ethics based on business-related classic literature and moral philosophy.     <I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1  No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Alison E. <EM> Gerencser</EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/gerencse.html">Family mediation: screening for domestic abuse </A> This Article proposes that all legislatures mandating family mediation allow exemption from mediation when participant screeners determine that, because of the level of domestic abuse, mediation is inappropriate. Next, this Article argues that legislatures also must mandate that all participants screen for domestic violence. The Article concludes by discussing the multi-tiered screening process and the roles of the various participants in screening for domestic abuse.  <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by G. Alpa and A. <EM> Giampieri</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Alpa-1995/alpa.html">Law and Economics and Method Analysis: the Contractual Damages Issue </A>   <I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Geoff <EM> Gilbert</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/gilbert4.html">"Problems and Process: International Law and How We Use It", by Rosalyn Higgins </A>   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Geoff<EM> Gilbert</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/gilb2.html">Who has Jurisdiction for Cross-Frontier Financial Crimes? </A> This article has been prompted by the Nick Leeson case, where a trader in the Japanese derivatives market was working in Singapore, but whose activities had the effect of bringing down Barings, the oldest merchant bank in the City of London. It considers which State should have jurisdiction in these circumstances, particularly since the alleged criminal may now be in a third State.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Paul Todd and Nicola <EM> Glover</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/todd4.html">Inferring share of interest in home: Midland Bank v Cooke (Casenote) </A> In Midland Bank v Cooke, CA, 7 July 1995, the Court of Appeal held that Mrs Cooke was entitled to a half share in the matrimonial home, binding on a third party mortgagee, although this was not justified by her direct contribution to the purchase price, and there had been no express discussions between the parties. In Springette v Defoe (1992) 24 HLR 552, [1992] 2 FCR 561, the Court of Appeal had held that the absence of express discussions precluded any claim to apportion shares otherwise than in proportion to contributions to the purchase price, but Waite LJ in Midland Bank v Cooke took the view that the lack of discussions or express agreement did not preclude the court from inferring an agreement on general equitable principles.   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Paul Todd and Nicola <EM> Glover</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/todd5.html">Occupation for Life: Satisfying the Equity </A> Suppose that A, who has legal title to a house, represents to B that B will be allowed to occupy the house for his or her life, and B relies on that representation to his or her detriment. There is no problem, on the principles enunciated by Lord Bridge in Lloyds Bank plc v Rosset [1991] 1 AC 107, eg at p 132, in granting B an interest, by way of constructive trust or proprietary estoppel. When it comes to quantifying the interest, however, the courts are prevented from reaching an equitable solution by legislation which had its origins over a century ago, and was intended to deal with an entirely different problem. To judge from the number of recent cases, the situation must be quite a common one.    <I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Susan <EM> Goldammer</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/goldamm.html">International Reaction to Hong Kong's Countdown to 1997: Doors Open to Hong Kong's Emigrants </A>   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jon M. Shepard, Virginia W. Gerde and Michael G. <EM> Goldsby</EM>, <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/gerde.html">Teaching Business Ethics Through Literature </A> America's economic ideology lacks a vocabulary of ethics. If, as we assume, an economic system requires a moral component for long-term survival, students in business schools must be exposed to a vocabulary of ethics that is consistent with the ideology of capitalism. We present a vocabulary of ethics and describe an approach to teaching business ethics based on business-related classic literature and moral philosophy.     <I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1  No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jennifer <EM> Goodman</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/goodman.htm">Morton International v. General Accident Insurance Co.: The New Jersey Supreme Court Defines the Scope of the Qualified Pollution Exclusion Clause in Comprehensive General Liability Policies </A>   <I> Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I> (casebrief)
<HR>
<LI>by Carol J.<EM> Greenhouse</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/greenhouse.html">Democracy and Demography </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Anne<EM> Greenshields</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/netwatch/netw1.txt">Netwatch April 1995 </A> This issue of Netwatch focuses on indigenous resources.  While this listing is not a comprehensive list of indigenous peoples resources it is a list of sites which the library has been able to connect to and have determined that they are resources which would interest a researcher in this area.  New sites and new discussion lists follow the special subject section.  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Davydd J.<EM> Greenwood</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/green.html">Cultural Identities and Global Political Economy from an Anthropological Vantage Point </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Sandy Wong, Michael R Egger and Fred<EM> Greguras</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/greguras.txt">Multimedia Content and the Super Highway: Rapid Acceleration or Foot on the Brake? </A> This article discusses emerging legal issues concerning copyright/patent protection of material used in multimedia applications. Describes existing processes for the administration of copyright/patent material in the US and the deficencies of traditional rights agreements where material is used in multimedia products.  Cites recent reports from Japan concerning the advantages of streamlining copyright/patent administration, and proposes the establishment of a US based copyright/patent clearinghouse for multimedia materials.  <I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Andrew<EM> Greinke</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/greinke.txt">Legal Expert Systems: A Humanistic Critique of Mechanical Legal Inference </A> The author surveys a wide range of computerised expert systems and shows that they invariably rely on pattern-matching and rule application strategies which have been embodied in their inference mechanisms and knowledge representations.  This computational approach is argued to be unsuitable for use with law which presents a domain of intractable complexity arising out of the need to refer to social context and human purpose in resolving legal issues. The author concludes that a better use for computation in legal applications is in the form of decision- support systems that leave legal inference to human agents.  <I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Andrew<EM> Griffin</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/griffin.html">MARPOL 73/78 and Vessel Pollution: A Glass Half Full or Half Empty? </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Richard<EM> Grimes</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/resear2.html">Research Report Two: Legal Skills and Clinical Legal Education </A>   <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by D.C. Ormerod and M.J. <EM> Gunn</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/ormerod1.html">Criminal Liability for the Transmission of HIV </A> This article explores the issues arising when a person, knowing that he or she is anti-HIV positive, proceeds to engage in intimate sexual behaviour, and asks whether he or she is liable to criminal prosecution.  In the light of the Government's refusal to legislate in this area, the article considers the possible sanctions under existing criminal law, providing analysis of sections 23 and 24 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861. It reviews possible problems with the use of these sections, and concludes that they could be used successfully to prosecute this type of behaviour. Finally, consideration is given to proposed law reform.   <I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
