<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/H.GIF" >
Essays by author :   H</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Debora<EM> Halbert</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/halbert.txt">Computer technology and legal discourse : the potential for modern communication technology to challenge legal discourses of authorship and property </A>   <I> E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Richard <EM> Hansen</EM>, <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/michalos.html">Review of "A Pragmatic Approach to Business Ethics" by Alex Michalos </A>   <I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1  No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Ugo Mattei and Henry<EM> Hansmann</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/hansmann.html">The Comparative Law and Economics of Private Trusts </A>   <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by I. Trotter <EM> Hardy </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/hardy.html">Contracts, Copyright and Preemption in a Digital World  </A>   <I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Alon <EM> Harel</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/harel.pag">Overview & Commentary: Bagaz 721/94 El-Al v. Danilowitz and the Future of Sexual Minority Rights in Israel  </A> In this article Prof. Harel provides the context for and explains the Supreme Court of Israel's recent decision in El-Al v. Danilowitz, in which the Court held that same-sex partners of El-Al Airlines employees must be granted the same benefits as cross-sex partners.    <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jeffrey A.<EM> Hart</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/hart.html">Comments on "Changing Sovereignty Games and International Migration" </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Angela<EM> Hartley</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/hartley.txt">"Introduction to the Law of Contract: Computorials" </A>   <I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I> (book review)
<HR>
<LI>by Steven <EM> Hartwell</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/hartwell.pag">What a Difference a Gay Makes:  An Empirical Study of the Impact of 'Out' Gay Law Faculty on Law School Curriculum and Policies </A> In this article Prof. Hartwell presents a study of out gay faculty in American law schools and the correlation between out gay faculty and gay student activity.   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Steve<EM> Hedley</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/hedley1.html">Recovering lost legacies: White v. Jones in the Lords </A> White v Jones, [1995] 1 All ER 691, HL holds that a solicitor retained to draw up a will, but who fails to do so before the testator's sudden death, may owe a duty in tort to disappointed beneficiaries, with the result that they can claim the value of their lost legacies from the solicitor if they can establish fault.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> (casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by James T. <EM> Heeney</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/heeney.htm">">A Sizeable Sling Stone: The Staggering Impact of United States v. Colorado on the EPA Goliath </A>   <I> Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I> (Casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by Angela<EM> Hegarty</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/hegarty2.html">Examining Equality: The Fair Employment Act (NI) 1989 and Its Review </A> The Act is currently the subject of a government sponsored review, a review which is bound to focus on the many criticisms levelled at the Act in its five years of operation. This article examines the background to the legislation and the issues which relate to its operation.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No.  2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Gregor<EM> Heinrich</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/hein3.html">Harmonised Global Interchange - UNCITRAL's Draft Model Law for Electronic Data Interchange </A> Traditionally, companies have always conducted and documented a large part of their business on paper. Paper transactions went along with well-developed mechanisms and legal concepts for proving origin, preventing repudiation and maintaining confidentiality. Now, this paper-based tradition is increasingly being abandoned in favour of 'electronic data interchange' (EDI). However, it is generally accepted that electronic exchange of trade data between companies, across business branches and even across borders is ultimately inconceivable without a high degree of standardisation.  A recent initiative by the United Nations Commission on International Trade Law (UNCITRAL) is now trying to fill this gap by creating a set of rules that aim at establishing a global legal framework for EDI.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Ralph <EM> Henham</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/henham1.html">Harm, Sentence Severity and Serious Motoring Offenders </A> This note delineates the difficulties inherent in emphasising risk assessment for the purpose of determining the quality of driving in serious motoring offences. It is argued that the current substantive principles militate against subjective consideration of risk assessment which are relevant at the sentencing stage. It is submitted that penalty levels and sentencing principles for serious motoring offences would be more appropriately based upon harm assessment.   <I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by K.Vaughan and M.<EM> Hibbs</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3e.html">Interactive video in legal education and practice </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by J. William<EM> Hicks</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/hicks.html">Protection of Individual Investors Under U.S. Securities Laws :  The Impact of International Regulatory Competition </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Mason<EM> Hills</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mhills.txt">The Rule of law and democracy in Hong Kong : comparative analysis of British Liberalism and Chinese Socialism </A> This paper seeks to explore the concept of Rule of Law in Hong Kong, at the present and in its future as part of the People's Republic of China. Democracy is seen as not essential but complementary to Rule of Law providing checks on its implementation. Some of the main political, ethnic and cultural influences is explored. It concludes with the assertion that Rule of Law is one of the elements required for the maintenance of a stable Hong Kong society.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by John <EM> Hodgson</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/hodgson5.html">The Comparative Dimension (or What do They Know of England, that only England Know?) </A> This article examines the provisional proposals in the ACLEC Consultation Paper on the initial stage of legal education which bear on the emphasis to be given to the study of European and Comparative law. The article attempts to analyse the practical implications of this approach. In particular the empirical evidence as to the expertise and resources available in this field is scrutinised. The thrust of the ERASMUS/SOCRATES programmes is considered, and attempts are made to indicate an academically appropriate but practical way forward.   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Amanda <EM> Hoey </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/hoey1.html">Analysis of The Police and Criminal Evidence Act, s.69 - Computer Generated Evidence </A> At present there are special rules governing the admissibility of computer-generated evidence in criminal proceedings. In this article the issues of when computer output will be considered direct evidence or hearsay and the reliability of computer-generated evidence are discussed. In conclusion the article attempts to ascertain whether these special rules for computer output are necessary and, if so, whether the conditions established by the statutory provisions are appropriate.    <I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by J. Garvan and A. <EM> Hoey </EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1c.html">A Purchasing Decision Support System  </A> Public procurement law is a complex subject which is continually evolving. As a result of the formation of the single market public procurement has become high profile and all those involved in purchasing are now required to be familiar with legislation operating in the fields of public supplies, works, services and utilities. This paper reports on the development of a computerised decision support tool in public procurement by a team of staff from the University of Ulster.   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Marc A.<EM> Horwitz</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/horwitz.html">Swaps Ahoy! Should Regulators Voyage into Unknown Waters? </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by P. K. Jameson and Marsha <EM> Hosack </EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/jameson.html">Citizen initiative in Florida: an analysis of Florida's constitutional initiative process, issues, and statutory intitiative alternatives  </A> This Article examines Florida's constitutional initiative process and describes the constitutional and statutory initiative processes in other states. It then discusses issues about Florida's current constitutional initiative process and addresses several bills introduced during the 1995 Regular Session to revise the current process. The Article concludes that Florida should develop and adopt an indirect statutory initiative procedure. It further concludes that in tandem with insituting a statutory process, Florida should revise the current constitutional initiative process to make it more difficult toamend the constitution.   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Adrian<EM> Howe</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/howe.txt">A Poststructuralist Consideration of Property as Thin Air- Mabo, A Case Study </A> This report examines the decision in _Mabo (no 2)_ from the point of view of property as a power relation rather than a tangible resource. The actual nature of the rights recognised has resulted in uncertainty. The result of the case is to "propertise" Aboriginal interests in land, rendering them a "real", though second rate, interest.  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Alison<EM> Humphry</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/humphry.txt">Opportunity Lost for Aboriginal Self-Determination: Australia's compliance with ILO 169 </A> The paper addresses the requirements of articles 8 and 9 of ILO 169 and whether WA complies with these. It examines primarily the interplay between the customary law of Australian Aboriginal people and the criminal justice system of Western Australia. The author concludes that compliance is limited to taking into account customary law when applying non-Aboriginal law and not so much compliance with the requirements of respect for Aboriginal law and institutions.  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by D.<EM> Hunter</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3h.html">Teaching Artificial Intelligence to Law Students </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
