<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/I.GIF" >
Essays by author :   I</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Catherine J.<EM> Iorns</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns1.txt">Australian Ratification of International Labour Organisation Convention No. 169 </A> The Convention accords little status to indigenous laws and values, and it is generally paternalistic.  However, adopting it will expand upon the rights of Australian Aborigines and may foster wider recognition of the rights of Indigenous Peoples worldwide  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Catherine J.<EM> Iorns</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns2.txt">A Draft Declaration of the Rights of Indigneous Peoples </A> This article discusses the important provisions therein.  Suggestions are made for improvements that might be incorporated before it is adopted by the UN General Assembly  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Catherine J.<EM> Iorns</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/iorns3.txt">A Feminist Looks at Ronald Dworkin's Theory of Equality </A> This piece is a 'work in progress' dealing Dworkin's theory of equality and its related social vision from a feminist perspective.  A notable substantive problem is the theory's reliance on a questionable public/private distinction.  The definition of equality fails to address the reality of the oppression of women in the real world. The author criticises the central freedom/equality dichotomy.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Catherine J.<EM> Iorns</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns4.txt">Report of the 11th Session of the Working Group of Indigenous Peoples, 19-30 July 1993 </A> The major items were the debate on the draft Declaration of Rights of Indigenous Peoples and the Review of Developments, where Indigenous Peoples worldwide present statements to the session describing their current circumstances.  There were also reports on studies conducted by Working Group members and by a Maori group.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Catherine J.<EM> Iorns</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns95.txt">Report on Aboriginal Women and Bias in the Western Australian Justice System </A> This is an account of the Sub-Committee on Aboriginal Women and the Law in the Taskforce which drafted a report into gender bias in the law and administration of justice in Western Australia in 1994.  It looks into some of the recommendations for reform that could significantly reduce the many difficulties faced by Aboriginal women due to bias in the Western Australian legal system  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
