<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   K</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/K.GIF" >
Essays by author :   K</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by T.<EM> Kamien</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/kamien.txt">Implementing Self-Government- An Examination of the Aboriginal Communities Act (Western Australia) </A> This report examines the Aboriginal Communities Act in the context of the right to self-government given by article 31 of the Draft Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples.  The report criticises the Act in that although it has found some acceptance with Aboriginal people, it has an assimilationist focus, in some cases increasing powerlessness felt by Aboriginal people.  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Emilia <EM> Kandeva-Spiridonova </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/kandeva.html">"The Legal System and American Constitutional Democracy" Edited by Maria Frankowska & Albert P. Melone  </A>   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Price V Fishback and Shawn Everett<EM> Kantor</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/kantor.html">Insurance Rationing and the Origins of Workers' Compensation </A> A central question concerning the economic motivation for the adoption of workers' compensation is the extent to which workers had access to their desired levels of private accident insurance around the turn of the century. We develop a theoretical model that suggests that workers' compensation should have caused a reduction in households' precautionary saving. Our empirical test is based on a sample of over 7000 households surveyed for the 1917-1919 Bureau of Labor Statistics Cost-of-Living study. Regression analysis suggests that households tended to save less, holding all else constant, if their states had workers' compensation in force. This finding, in concert with qualitative information about the insurance industry, provide some evidence that insurance companies were unable to effectively offer workplace accident insurance to a wide range of workers.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Louis<EM> Kaplow</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/kaplow2.html">A Fundamental Objection to Tax Equity Norms: A Call for Utilitarianism Taxation </A> Anti-utilitarian norms often are used in assessing tax systems. Two motivations support this practice. First, many believe utilitarianism to be insufficiently egalitarian. Second, utilitarianism does not give independent weight to other equitable principles, notably concerns that reforms may violate horizontal equity or result in rank reversals in the income distribution. This investigation suggests that a policy maker who believes in the Pareto principle -- that any reform preferred by everyone should be adopted -- cannot consistently adhere to any of these anti-utilitarian sentiments. Moreover, the affirmative case for utilitarian tax policy assessment is stronger than is generally appreciated.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Steven Shavell and Louis<EM> Kaplow</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/shavell.html">Property Rules vs Liability Rules </A> A fundamental legal problem is whether property rights should be protected by property rules or by liability rules. In this Article, we provide a systematic economic analysis of the choice between property and liability rules. We answer a basic question: why is it that liability rules are commonly used in the context of harmful externalities (such as pollution and automobile accidents), whereas property rules are generally employed toprotect possessors of things against potential takers? In the course of our analysis, we demonstrate that many commonly held beliefs about property and liability rules are mistaken. Our analysis is also relevant to policy; for example, we show that in important contexts liability rules (and pollution taxes) are more efficient than property rules (including much regulation) even when damages must be set using only limited information about harm.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Mehmet E. <EM> Karaaslan</EM>, <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9503/9503001.abs">Identifying Participants in a Price-fixing Conspiracy: Output and Market Share Tests Reexamined  </A> If there is a cartel agreement among a subset of firms in an industry, it should be predicted that all firms in that industry will increase prices. According to the output test and its market share variant if the output or the market share of the firm that claims to be innocent in the collusive activity rises in response to the price increase, that firm's claim should be accepted as true. Using a collusive variant of the dominant firm model, this paper shows that these are not robust tests to reveal innocence or guilt. This paper also shows that a market share test can not be used to prove a dominant firm's intent for predatory pricing    <I>  </I> (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>by Lauren<EM> Kares</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/kar.htm">Unlucky Thirteenth: a constitutional amendment in search of a doctrine </A> *Steirer* is not anomalous; in fact, the Thirteenth Amendment is notable for its lack of a coherent jurisprudence.  This Note argues that a balancing test like the one used by the *Steirer* trial court is more useful and truer to the Thirteenth Amendment's vision of liberty than the criminal standard used by the appellate court.  Consistent application of a balancing test would afford the Thirteenth Amendment a degree of elasticity and relevance that it now lacks.  <I> Cornell LR January 1995</I> (note)
<HR>
<LI>by Kenneth L.<EM> Karst</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/karst.html">Out of Many, One? </A> The Governor of California has called for an amendment to the U.S. Constitution that would deny citizenship to a child born in the United States if the child's parents entered the country illegally. Although this appalling proposal seems unlikely to be taken seriously in Congress, undoubtedly it is well received by a constituency the Governor needs to reassure. Similar constituencies were vocal during the colonial era, and their successors have made nativism a recurring political theme. In sum, this experience makes clear that the ideal of the "Open Republic," so ably defended by Professor Jost Delbrck, confronts powerful opposition. In this paper I comment briefly on the problems of maintaining political community and political legitimacy in the face of ethnic difference.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by George <EM> Katrougalos</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/katart5.html">The Rights of Foreigners and Immigrants in Europe: Recent Trends </A> Immigration policies which have been traditionally conceived and implemented at the national level can not cope with the new situation of globalization and European unification. Within the European Union, the easing of "internal" frontier controls contrasts with an intensification of controls at the "external frontiers". The Schengen Treaty is the culmination of this trend. Moreover, there is a universal tightening of the policies and procedures in granting asylum, that resulted in constitutional revision in France and Germany. Most other European countries have enacted new, more restrictive legislation toward foreigners, adapted in the context of European Integration and the Schengen criteria. The article reviews the present status of national and international legislation related to foreigners' rights, in order to analyze the relationship between nationality and citizenship rights. It concludes with the proposal of a concept of rights based on residence.   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by M. Ethan <EM> Katsh </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/katsh.htm">Cybertime, Cyberspace and Cyberlaw </A> Professor Katsh pursues the relationship between time in cyberspace, or "cybertime" as he calls it, and legal doctrines. He speculates that many such doctrines are based explicitly or implicitly on time or our conception of time. He then asks whether the concept of "cybertime", with its accelerated pace, may not cause substantial disruption in these legal doctrines, a disruption not before noted or appreciated.   <I> Journal of Online Law  </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Avery <EM> Katz</EM>, <A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz1a.html">Bargaining at a Distance: the Mailbox Rule and Related Contract Formation Games </A> This essay applies economic analysis to the so-called "mailbox rule". An economic analysis reveals some broad functional implications of the rule. It turns out that the legal rule governing contracts by correspondence does make an allocative difference -- though not for the reliance reason that has been offered in the legal commentary. The difference between the rules lies in their ability to encourage the offeror to keep to the bargain when bad news arrives only after reliance has taken place. On this dimension of efficiency, the mailbox rule performs better than its alternatives.   <I>  </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by R. Susskind, M. Young, and A.<EM> Katz</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3i.html">LINK - The Legal Information Network: Users views </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Avery <EM> Katz </EM>, <A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz2a.html">Positivism and the Separation of Law and Economics  </A> The economic analysis of law has since its beginnings in the early 1960s provoked substantial opposition and antagonism in the legal academy and, to a lesser extent, in the profession at large. In this essay, I argue (1) that economists as a matter of official professional methodology subscribe to a strong form of positivism; and that law and economics is particularly influenced by this approach; (2) that this methodological position places law and economics firmly on one side of the controversy over legal positivism, and (3) that the pragmatic justifications for taking this methodological position within the field of economics do not necessarily carry over to the field of law.   <I>  </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Avery <EM> Katz </EM>, <A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz3a.html">When Should an Offer Stick? The Economics of Promissory Estoppel in Preliminary Negotiations (forthcoming, Yale Law Journal, 1996)  </A> Under the modern doctrine of promissory estoppel, a person making an offer is bound when the offeree relies, even in the absence of an acceptance or any explicit negotiation for a binding option. But courts have generally declined to construe the offeree's reliance as an acceptance or as a promise to accept. This paper considers the incentive effects of this rule for the optimal timing of contract formation and reliance. In preliminary negotiations both parties have some control over the timing of reliance, but the rule of law affects their relative incentives to exercise this control. I argue that the efficiency of promissory estoppel in preliminary negotiations depends in large part on which party holds the bulk of the bargaining power ex post.   <I>  </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Peter J.<EM> Katzenstein</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/katz.html">A World of Regions:   America, Europe, and East Asia </A> Recent events in world politics are creating a substantial break in the history of international politics comparable in this century only to the years 1917-22 and 1947-53. With specific reference to Germany and Europe as well as to Japan and East Asia, this essay argues that these changes in world politics tend to reinforce a new political regionalism that expresses different norms, which, in the foreseeable future, are unlikely to be assimilated fully into one normative global order.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Tim <EM> Kaye</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/kaye3.html">Implementing An EC Directive on Unfair Terms </A> This article considers the substantive effect of the Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1994, and argues that despite their apparent commencement date of 1st July 1995 consumers have been able to claim the benefit of the protection afforded by the Regulations on the grounds that the Minister's specification of 1st July 1995 as the effective date of implementation is ultra vires.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Pei-Teing<EM> Kee</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/kee2.txt">Refusal to Consent to Treatment on Religious Grounds </A> The writer considers the legal aspects of refusal of consent to medical treatment on medical grounds, particularly focussing on refusal of blood transfusions by Jehovah's Witnesses.  The paper concludes with an examination of the ethics of overriding patients' informed decisions based on religious objections.  <I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Pei-Teing<EM> Kee</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/kee1.txt">Should Gambling Gains Be Taxed as Income? </A> The author considers the taxation treatment of gambling gains in Australia.  She examines the reasons for and against taxing such gains as income, how this could be done and whether losses would then have to be deductible. The paper concludes that these gains should be taxed, and proposes a way in which this could be done.  <I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Pei Teing<EM> Kee</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/colaw.txt">"Understanding Company Law: Computer Tutorials" </A> Student review of a computerised tutorial package for use in teaching Australian company law.  <I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994</I> (review)
<HR>
<LI>by Leslie M. <EM> Kelleher</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part3.htm">The December 1993 amendments to the Federal rules of civil procedure  </A>   <I> Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Kirsty<EM> Keywood</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/keywood3.html">B v Croydon Health Authority 1994, CA: Force-Feeding the Hunger-Striker under the Mental Health Act 1983 </A> Judgments declaring the legality of force-feeding under the Mental Health Act 1983 had previously been made by courts of first instance. B v Croydon Health Authority [1995] 1 All ER 683 gave the Court of Appeal the opportunity to review the legality of force-feeding under the Mental Health Act.  This casenote assesses the validity of the ruling that force-feeding under the Mental Health Act 1983, s 63 is lawful and analyses the implications of the decision for hunger-strikers in other contexts.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> (Casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by J.<EM> Killingley</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1d.html">Building on the Paper Case </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael<EM> King</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk:70/00/ltc/publications/conferences/oxford/mking.txt">Religion into Law, Law into Religion :  the Construction of a Secular Identity for Islam </A> Oxford Critical Legal Conference  <I> 1993 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Matthew<EM> Klaben</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/kla.htm">Split-recovery statutes: the interplay of the takings and excessive fines clauses </A> This Note argues that a split-recovery statute giving the state a prejudgment interest in punitive damage awards does not constitute a taking if it limits the plaintiff's interest to a portion of the punitive award.   Punitive damage awards in jurisdictions having split-recovery statutes are likely to be subject to constitutional review for excessiveness.   Although a legislature could draft a split-recovery statute that is not subject to the limitations of the Takings or in Excessive Fines Clauses, such an objective poses serious practical difficulties.  <I> Cornell LR November 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Audrey<EM> Kobayashi</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk:70/00/ltc/publications/conferences/oxford/akobay.txt">Challenging the National Dream: Gender Persecution and Canadian Imigration Law </A>   <I> Oxford Critical Legal Conference 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Daryl <EM> Koehn</EM>, <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/hand.html">The Ethics of Handwriting Analysis in Pre-Employment Screening </A>   <I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1 * No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Daryl <EM> Koehn</EM>, <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/fukuyama.html">Review of "Trust: The Social Virtues and Creation of Prosperity" by Francis Fukuyama </A>   <I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1  No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Chris Pounder and Freddy <EM> Kosten</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/kosten2">The EC Data Protection Directive 1995: An Analysis </A>   <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
