<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   L</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/L.GIF" >
Essays by author :   L</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Greg <EM> Ladner </EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/ladner.pag">Baehr v. Lewin: Will Equal Protection Lead to the End of Prohibitions on Same-Sex Marriages? </A> In this casenote Greg Ladner reviews the decision by the Hawaii Supreme Court regarding same-sex marriage, </B>Baehr v. Lewin</B>.  Ladner begins with an examination of the regulation of marriage in the United States by state courts and the U.S. Supreme Court, then reviews the history of attempts of same-sex couples to gain legal recognition; he then examines the <B>Baehr</B> decision and concludes with a discussion of the national impact this casemay have as other states face the same issue.     <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Latour Rey <EM> Lafferty</EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/lafferty.html">Florida's capital sentencing jury override: whom should we trust to make the ultimate ethical judgment? </A> This article examines Florida's trifurcated capital sentencing scheme, specifically the jury override provision, from its origin to the present. It identifies and analyzes several criticisms of Florida's jury override provision, and examines the potential impact of Florida Committee Substitute for House Bill 1319, which Governor Chiles vetoed on June 14, 1995. Finally, this Article concludes that the Governor's veto was appropriate because Florida's jury override provision represents a valuable balance between the judge and the jury.    <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Judith M <EM> Laing</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/laing1.html">The Police Surgeon and Mentally Disordered Suspects: An Adequate Safeguard? </A> This article examines the role of the police surgeon in identifying and assessing mentally disordered suspects in police custody. It suggests that police surgeons lack the relevant knowledge and expertise to deal with these people, and concludes that duty-psychiatrist schemes currently operating at magistrates' courts should be extended to police stations to ensure that mentally disordered suspects are assessed by medical professionals who possess the relevant psychiatric expertise.     <I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by D.<EM> Laurillard</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2j.html">How can learning technologies improve learning ? </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Inge<EM> Lauw</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/lauw2.txt">Recognition of Same-Sex Marriage :  Time for Change ? </A> Discusses the case Baehr v Lewin, relating to legal recognition of same-sex marriages.  Also examines policy arguments for and against granting marriage licences to same-sex couples.  Briefly examines the situation in Australia  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Inge<EM> Lauw</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/lauw.txt">Specialisation, accreditation and the legal profession in Australia and Canada </A> An analysis and comparative evaluation of formal specialisation and accreditation programmes in Australia and Canada, as a means of improving the public's access to legal services.  Also examines the implications of these programmes on marketing and advertising by the legal profession.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Inge<EM> Lauw</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/lauw3.txt">Victimless Crimes :  Decriminalisation of Homosexual Sexual Activity </A> Explores the arguments for and against decriminalisation of sexual acts between consenting adult males.  Also discusses the recent statement by the United Nations Human Rights Committee declaring Tasmania's anti-sodomy laws to be unlawful.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by David J.<EM> Lazerwitz</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/lazer.html">The Flow of International Water Law: The International Law Commission's Law of the Non-Navigational Uses of International Watercourses </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> (Note)
<HR>
<LI>by Ian<EM> Leigh</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/leigh3.html">Prerogative, Legislative Power, and the Democratic Deficit: The Fire Brigades Union Case </A> The recent decision of the House of Lords in R v Secretary of State for the Home Department, ex parte Fire Brigades Union [1995] 2 WLR 464 raises important constitutional questions about the extent to which the government is required to seek Parliamentary approval for its policies or may rely instead on prerogative powers. This note considers the implications of the ruling.  It is argued that the House of Lords reached the right decision, but for the wrong reasons.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Ian<EM> Leigh</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/leigh2.html">Reforming Public Interest Immunity </A> This article makes recommendations for the reform of Public Interest Immunity (PII) against the background of the Matrix Churchill case and of evidence to the Scott Inquiry. Three issues are critically evaluated: the distinction between class and contents claims of immunity, whether ministers should continue to sign PII certificates, and the role of the judiciary in dealing with inspection and disclosure of documents in criminal proceedings.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Andrew D<EM> Leipold</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/lei.htm">Why grand juries do not (and cannot) protect the accused </A> The weakness in the system lies less with the procedures employed than with the characteristics of the decisionmakers.   Rather than being asked to find facts and apply those facts to the law, the jurors are presented with a single set of facts, instructed on the law by the prosecutor, and asked to decide whether those undisputed facts are sufficient to satisfy a specific legal test - the probable cause standard.  Even reasonable, independent-minded jurors will defer to the prosecutor's judgment that an indictment should issue.  <I> Cornell LR January 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Philip <EM> Leith</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/leith4.html">Legal Education in Germany: becoming a Lawyer, Judge, and Professor </A>   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Mark A. <EM> Lemley</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/lemley.html">Rights of Attribution and Integrity in Online Communications </A> Is there a right of attribution in cyberspace? Professor Lemley explores the interrelated rights of attribution, integrity of identity, and anonymity as they apply to electronic communications. A related issue involves net users' rights to integrity of their electronic identities, whether real or pseudonymous. For a reliable online community to develop, users must be able to trust the integrity of the electronic personalities created by themselves and others. Finally, the desire of many Internet users to remain anonymous complicates the exercise of their other rights. Lemley concludes that net users may be able to protect their rights to attribution and the integrity of their electronic personalities only at the risk of losing their right to anonymity.   <I> Journal of Online Law  </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Saul<EM> Levmore</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/levmore.html">Love It or Leave It: Property Rules, Liability Rules, and Exclusivity of Remedies in Partnership and Marriage </A> The traditional rule in partnership law, and the continuing rule in domestic relations law, is that a claim for dissolution (or divorce) is a partner's exclusive remedy. On its face this mandatory "love-it-or-leave-it" rule seems strange, anachronistic, unfair, and inefficient, because where there is going concern value there is room for exploitation. In contrast, corporate law offers a kind of reverse "exclusivity" rule, in that a shareholder can bring a suit for damages but can not force dissolution of the enterprise. These rules offer a window to general questions about remedies. The Calabresi-Melamed property-liability rules framework is expanded with the incorporation not only of rules explored by Polinsky and by Krier and Schwab but also with several seemingly novel rules that draw attention to the possibility of remedies that are only forward-looking or only backward-looking. The critical connection is that the power to "stop" a partnership or a marriage is akin to the power to stop a nuisance, so that love-it-or-leave-it rules can have the character of a "property rule" with no liability component.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Michael <EM> Liberman </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/liberman.html">Overreaching Provisions in Software License Agreements (Note) </A>   <I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Anne Barlow and Craig <EM> Lind </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/lind2.html">Family Redefinition under Part III of the Family Law Bill 1996 </A> We assess the effects of Part III of the Family Law Bill 1996 on unmarried couples in domestic violence law, and on the jurisprudential scope of family law itself. We begin by noting the erosion of the dominance of the traditional married family. Then we consider the equivocal and, consequently, incohesive legal response to this social diversification. We examine the adequacy of the new remedies available to expanded categories of victims of family violence. We conclude that the Bill significantly improves current law, but that by creating three tiers of legal regulation, it inappropriately complicates the resolution of comparable disputes. The ideological importance of the married state has prevented pragmatic and coherent reform.   <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Thomas F. Coleman and David F. <EM> Link</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/coleman.pag">Analysis of the Opinion of the Attorney General of California on the Registration of Names of Family Associations by the Secretary of State </A> This article analyzes a recent attempt by gay and lesbian families in California to gain legal recognition by registering with the Secretary of State as unincorporated nonprofit associations as "family associations". Despite opposition, the Secretary of State of California refused to prohibit registration. The authors analyze the statutory language of the California Corporations Code relating to associational name registration and discusses the interpretations applied in light of the highly charged political atmosphere.   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Margaret<EM> Llewelyn</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/llewel2.html">Proposals for the Introduction of a Community Utility Model System: A UK Perspective </A> The European Commission is currently looking at proposals to introduce a new Community intellectual property right (IPR), the Utility Model (UM) which will serve to protect those inventions which are not regarded as capable of fulfilling the strict granting requirements of the patent system. The Commission wishes to harmonise existing practices and to broadened the scope of UM protection. One of the EU member states which has been the most vocal in voicing its concerns over the proposals is the UK. The reason for the extent of concern is that UK does not at present operate a UM system. There is, therefore, considerable concern and doubt about: a) the need to introduce UM protection and b) the scope and type of protection to be granted.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Ian <EM> Lloyd</EM>, <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/intros/default.htm">An Outline of the European Data Protection Directive </A>   <I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Benjamin T.<EM> Lo</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/lo.html">Improving Corporate Governance: Lessons from the European Community </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> (note)
<HR>
<LI>Reviewed by Eva <EM> Lomnicka</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/lomnicka2.html">Review of Janet Dine, "Criminal Law in the Company Context". </A>   <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Richard L. Manning and John R.<EM> Lott</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/lott.html">Have Changing Liability Rules Compensated Workers Twice for Occupational Hazards?: Earnings Premiums and Cancer Risks </A> During the last couple of decades, courts have intervened in employment relationships by allowing employees to circumvent workers' compensation liability restrictions, and gain compensation for long term illnesses  through tort cases. Recent papers point to firms divesting themselves of  operations whose employees handled dangerous substances as firms protecting themselves from these new liabilities. Supposedly, these actions prevent their workers from being justly compensated. We show that the central legal  premise behind this argument is wrong. Firms cannot expose workers to  hazards and then eliminate this liability by divesting or shutting down the hazardous operation. This paper also shows that workers were already being well compensated for carcinogenic exposures even before the courts started allowing workers to collect large damages for occupational illnesses.  Instituting the new liability rules also coincided with a large drop in earnings premiums.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by David J<EM> Loundy</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/loundy.txt">E-Law 2.0 :  Computer Information Systems Law and System Operator Liability Revisited </A> The article examines the current regulatory structure of Cyberspace in the United States.  The article also discusses the liability of the operators/administrators of these systems  ("Sysops") in this context, and includes an examination of the relevant legislation.  The author outlines the difficulties involved in applying current regulatory standards to Cyberspace in general, and contends that the creators of the law need to have an adequate understanding of the technology relevant to computer systems if the laws are to effectively regulate such a rapidly changing area as this  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael<EM> Lower</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/lower1.html">Going Dutch? Who foots the bill in section 459 petitions </A> Whether or not the company can play, and fund out of corporate assets, an active role in section 459 proceedings was considered in Re a Company (No 001126 of 1992) and Re Milgate Developments Limited. The latter decision also considers whether a petitioner can obtain an injunction to prevent a company from playing an active part in section 459 proceedings.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> (casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by Marc L. Caden and Stephanie E. <EM> Lucas</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/caden_lucas.html">Accidents on the Information Superhighway: On-line Liability and Regulation </A>   <I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Peter<EM> Luther</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/luther1.html">"Common Law" by M Arnheim (ed.) </A>   <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> (book review)
<HR>
<LI>by Jamie H.<EM> Lyford</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/lyford.txt">Ministry of Truth Redefined: A Consideration of Privacy and Data Protection Law ... </A> This paper looks at the issue of privacy in light of the information age.  Particular emphasis is made in the Australian context.  National and international laws are also examined.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
