<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   N</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/N.GIF" >
Essays by author :   N</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by June<EM> Nash</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/nash.html">The Challenge of Trade Liberalization to Cultural Survival on the Southern Frontier of Mexico </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by <EM> National Center for Lesbian Rights, et al.</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/thomas.pag">Amicus brief: In re Ry R.-Y. </A> This amicus brief, filed by the National Center for Lesbian Rights on behalf of the defendant argues that the decision of a New York trial court, <B>Thomas S. v. Robin Y.</B>, 599 N.Y.S.2d 377 (Fam. Ct. 1993) to deny the paternity petition of Thomas S., a known sperm donor and the biological father of Ry, a child born into a household of a lesbian couple, should be affirmed.  The appellate court held that, despite an oral agreement to the contrary, Thomas S.'s paternity petition should be granted. <B>Thomas S. v. Robin Y.</B>, 618 N.Y.S.2d 356 (App. Div. 1994).  The Court of Appeals, New York's highest court, stayed the appellate court's decision and granted certiorari.  The appeal was ultimately dismissed, however, when Thomas S. withdrew his paternity petition.    <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by N. <EM> Nunn-Price</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1f.html">CD-roms in Legal Education  </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>

