<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   O</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/O.GIF" >
Essays by author :   O</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Mary Ellen <EM> O'Connell</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/oconnell.html">Enforcement and the Success of International Environmental Law </A> Professor O'Connell argues that international law is generally obeyed. Its enforcement is based primarily on compliance, not enforcement. Accordingly, the author argues against using international enforcement mechanisms to enforce international environmental law. Instead, she posits that domestic courts should be used; however, certain obstacles, such as sovereign immunity, the doctrine of standing, and the principle of forum non conveniens, must be overcome. She argues that it may be possible to overcome many of these court-made obstacles to enforcing international law through domestic courts.   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Mary Ellen<EM> O'Connell</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/oconnell.html">Using Trade to Enforce International Environmental Law :   Implications for United States Law </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Ursula A <EM> O'Hare</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/ohare2.html">Positive Action Before the European Court of Justice: CASE C-450/93 Kalanke v Freie Hansestadt Bremen </A> Express provision is made for positive action measures to promote equal opportunities between men and women under European Community law. In October 1995 the European Court of Justice ruled that a 'tie-break' positive action scheme which gives priority to a woman candidate for an employment position over an equally qualified male competitor, was contrary to the terms of the Equal Treatment Directive. This article reviews the judgment and argues that the lack of reasoning in this decision is unfortunate.   <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> (casenote)
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by Helen<EM> O'Nions</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/onions2.html">Blackstone's Guide to the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994, by Martin Wasik and Richard Taylor </A>   <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> (book review)
<HR>
<LI>by Helen<EM> O'Nions</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/onions3.html">The Marginalisation of Gypsies </A> Gypsies have persistently suffered discrimination and prejudice from the rest of society.  The Criminal Justice Act 1994 contains provisions which will reduce the number of authorised Gypsy sites available in an attempt to discourage the nomadic way of life.  The legislation is likely to have severe implications for the welfare of the Gypsy family unit.  Ultimately however, a comparison with other European jurisdictions will illustrate that this legislation will not succeed in persuading Gypsies to abandon their traditions because it is founded on a myth, namely that Gypsies are simply a social bonding of nomads with no distinctive culture or group identity.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Anthony <EM> Ogus</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/ogus1.html">Some Reflections on the Woolf Interim Report </A> Drawing on law and economics literature, the author critically examines some of the key features of the Woolf Interim Report. The need to constrain lawyers' incentives to escalate costs is paramount and some shift away from the adversarial culture to judicial management is desirable. But care must be exercised in designing new procedures if the changes are not to be self-defeating. There is also a danger of over- optimism regarding proposals for encouraging alternative dispute resolution (ADR). More generally, legal costs will remain a problem so long as professional self-regulation is allowed to imposes fetters on competition.   <I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by M.J. Gunn and D.C. <EM> Ormerod </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/ormerod1.html">Criminal Liability for the Transmission of HIV </A> This article explores the issues arising when a person, knowing that he or she is anti-HIV positive, proceeds to engage in intimate sexual behaviour, and asks whether he or she is liable to criminal prosecution.  In the light of the Government's refusal to legislate in this area, the article considers the possible sanctions under existing criminal law, providing analysis of sections 23 and 24 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861. It reviews possible problems with the use of these sections, and concludes that they could be used successfully to prosecute this type of behaviour. Finally, consideration is given to proposed law reform.   <I> Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by P.<EM> Osbourne</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2e.html">Setting Common Minimum Standards of Computer Competency for undergraduates </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
