<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   P</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/P.GIF" >
Essays by author :   P</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Bill <EM> Padgett </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/padgett.html">The African Elephant, Africa, and CITES: The Next Step  </A>   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I> (note)
<HR>
<LI>by A.<EM> Paliwala</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1ed.html">The Courseware Consortium for Law </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Adbul <EM> Paliwala</EM>, <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/issue1/1abdul/">From Academic Tombstones to Living Bazaars - The Changing Shape of Law Reviews </A> Electronic law journals are likely to be successful because they meet a need, the resolution of a crisis in academic journal publishing which cannot fulfill the needs of a fast changing legal information environment. This requires electronic law journals and reviews which promote living intellectual discourse through uptodate and interactive information. However, this requires the overcoming of a number of obstacles, and in particular it is necessary to promote changes in academic legal culture which make writing and reading electronic journals an acceptable activity.    <I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by R. <EM> Pardolesi</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Pardolesi-1995/pardo.html">Economic Analysis of Contract Law: Some Insights </A>   <I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Alan <EM> Parkin</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/parkin2.html">Where now on Mental Incapacity? </A> The investigation carried out by the Law Commission into mental incapacity and ways in which the law in relation to it might be regularised has been exhaustive and thorough. The decision not to proceed with the resulting draft bill in its present form leaves matters, for the moment, in limbo. The constituency affected is large but its members are easily overlooked. Is it the case that the long awaited regularisation of their legal position is to be delayed because of fears, which may be groundless, that the recommendations make euthanasia more likely? Will doubts about some aspects of the report prevent or unduly delay straightforward and non-controversial reforms which will affect the lives of many  <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by F R Barker and N D M <EM> Parry</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/parry2.html">Open Access, Rights and Legislation </A> At first sight, Part V of the National Parks and Access to the Countryside Act 1949 is a radical piece of legislation. It provides for members of the public to have open access to specified areas of "open country". This is in apparent contrast to the general position in England and Wales. This article seeks generally to examine the impact and effect of Part V of the 1949 Act, and to evaluate the public access 'rights' for which it makes provision, in particular in the light of some of the recent changes to the law of trespass introduced by the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994.   <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael Fix and Jeffrey S.<EM> Passel</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/passel.html">U.S. Immigration in a Global Context: Past, Present, and Future </A> Through the use of their own empirical studies, the authors address three themes: (1) immigration in the global context; (2) the scale and characteristics of immigration to the United States; and (3) the expected future impact of immigration to the United States. The authors conclude that the situation is not dire; rather, they believe that the ties created by immigrants may become increasingly important to the United States in an interrelated world economy.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by R. Susskind and A.<EM> Paterson</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2i.html">Technology, Learning and the Trans-Atlantic divide </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by R.S.<EM> Pathak</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/pathak.html">International Trade and Environmental Development: A View from India </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by P.<EM> Pearce</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2a.html">Bringing Law into the Information Age </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Steven <EM> Pepe</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part5.htm">Multimedia computing:  copyright law's &quot;last stand&quot;  </A>   <I> Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Thomas G. Marx and Laura Bennett<EM> Peterson</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/peterson.html">Theory Versus Fact in the Choice of Organizational Form: A Study of Body and Frame Production in the Automobile Industry </A> Klein, Crawford and Alchian (hereinafter  "Klein") argue that relationship-specific assets raise problems of opportunism, escalate the cost of market  contracting, and explain General Motors' vertical integration into body manufacturing. We set forth in our paper the theoretical debate between Coase and Klein. Coase understates, we believe, the extent to which the cost of contracts rises with the risk of opportunism. We study the General Motors-Fisher Body relationship after GM's acquisition of its body supplier. A relationship is seen between asset specificity and internal, as well as external, transactions costs. We examine the historical relationships between other automobile companies and their body suppliers. We find a range of customer-supplier relationships -- from total integration, to tapered integration, to no integration and from long-term contracts, to short-term contracts, to no contracts. Such a range of relationships undermines any deterministic conclusion that asset specificity dictates vertical  integration.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Lisa D. Stream and Bruce D. <EM> Platt </EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/platt.html">Dispelling the negative myths of managed care: an analysis of anti-managed care legislation and the quality of care  provided by health maintenance organizations  </A> The first part of this Article discusses managed care legislation. Specifically, it provides a summary of some of the last five years of Florida's legislative health care advancements incorporating managed care concepts. It then discusses some of the proposed legislation which targets HMOs and other managed care plans. The available literature indicates that the quality of care provided by HMOs is as good as, if not better than, the quality of care provided in a traditional fee-for-service setting. Legislation which would cripple managed care in the name of preserving quality is unnecessary and counterproductive.   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Robert B. Mison, Paul Salvatore and Bettina B. <EM> Plevan </EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/mison.pag">Sexual Orientation Discrimination in the Workplace: A Legal Reference Guide </A> This recently updated outline of law relating to sexual stereotyping, domestic partnership benefits, employment discrimination and sexual orientation harassment provides citations of key federal and state cases, law review articles and state and local laws in a concise and accessible format.   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Ileana M. <EM> Porras</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/porras.html">The Puzzling Relationship Between Trade and Environment:  NAFTA, Competitiveness, and the Pursuit of Environmental Welfare Objectives </A> Harmonization of standards to facilitate the free flow of trade is a familiar trade goal. NAFTA's provisions regarding environmental standards, however, are not a straightforward requirement to harmonize standards. Rather, NAFTA recognizes state autonomy in standard setting, on the one hand, while requiring a form of upward harmonization, on the other. The result of such an arrangement is the perpetuation of economic and political inequality among states. NAFTA fails to give equal attention to the demands of "sustainable development" in poorer countries.   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Richard A.<EM> Posner</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/posner.html">The Economic Psychology of the Old </A> Economists usually take values, preferences and attitudes as givens and  consider how a rational actor can maximize his utility by the choices he makes based on those givens. This paper takes a different tack and considers  the extent to which the psychology of the old might fruitfully be modelled as a consequence rather than foundation of rational choice. The paper does  not argue that old people always or even often make conscious choices; only  that certain choices, conscious or unconscious, appear to be rational in the  sense of utility-maximizing once the fundamental attributes of being old are  understood.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by D.G. <EM> Post</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Informatica/Post-1996/Post~1.htm">Anarchy, State, and the Internet: an Essay on Law-Making in Cyberspace </A>   <I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by David G. <EM> Post</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/post.html">Anarchy, State, and the Internet: An Essay on Law-Making in Cyberspace </A> The legal rules that will govern cyberspace are yet to be clarified. Important as those rules will be, a prior question is "who will make and enforce those rules?" Professor Post examines various "controllers," or points from which rules can issue, ranging from technical network protocols, to private organizations like universities, to Congressional statutes. These controllers vary in their ability to enforce whatever rules they choose to adopt, depending on the existence of conflicting higher-level controllers, and on the possibility that those who are subject to the rules can change jurisdictions to seek a more favorable rule set.   <I> Journal of Online Law  </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Freddy Kosten and Chris <EM> Pounder</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/kosten2">The EC Data Protection Directive 1995: An Analysis </A>   <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Dan R. Stengle, Robert M. Rhodes, and David L. <EM> Powell </EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/powell.html">A Measured step to protect private property rights </A> A 1995 measure of the Florida legislature measure includes a new cause of action providing judicial relief to landowners who suffer inordinate burdens on the use of their land. If properly implemented and applied, the measure will have none of the feared undesriable effects. The legislation grants important new rights to landowners while maintaining existing environmental protection and growth management programs. Perhaps most importantly, the measure is intended to reform the way government does business with landowners. The legislation strikes a balance between conflicting, but equally valid, public and private interests.   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Sarah<EM> Pritchard</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/pritchar.txt">Constitutional Validity of the Commonwealth's Native Title Regime Confirmed </A> Case comment on the recent Australian cases of The State of Western Australia v the Commonwealth; The Wororra Peoples v The Commonwealth; Teddy Biljabu v The Commonwealth   decided by the High Court of Australia  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> (case comment)
<HR>
<LI>by R. Widdison and F. <EM> Pritchard </EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1b.html">An Experiment with Electronic Law Tutorials  </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
