<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   R</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/R.GIF" >
Essays by author :   R</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Jim Belohlav, David Drehmer, and Louis <EM> Raho</EM>, <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/belohlav.html">Ethical Issues of Expert Systems </A> This study examines ethical considerations related to one of the more recent information technologies, the expert system. Specifically, the study examines the perceptions of 499 computer professionals with respect to contribution and ownership issues arising from expert system usage within organizations. The results indicate that no uniform ethical perspective yet dominates the perceptions of the respondents in assessing expert system applications. Unless ethical differences are resolved, the eventual repercussion will be increasing individual and organizational conflict as greater numbers of expert systems are developed and become a part of organizational operations.    <I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1 * No. 2 *</I> 
<HR>
<LI>reviewed by David L<EM> Ranson</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/ranson.txt">"Expert Evidence"  by Freckleton and Selby </A>   <I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I> (book review)
<HR>
<LI><EM> Rasmusen</EM>, <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506002.abs">The Economics of Agency Law and Contract Formation </A> This article addresses issues that arise in agency law when agents make contracts on behalf of principals. The main issue is whether the principal should be bound when the agent makes a contract with some third party on his behalf which the principal would immediately wish to disavow. The resulting tradeoffs resemble those in tort law, so the least-cost-avoider principle is useful for deciding when contracts are valid and may be the underlying logic behind a number of different legal doctrines applied to agency cases. In particular, an efficiency explanation can be found for the undisclosed principal rule.    <I>  </I> (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>by Eric <EM> Rasmusen </EM>, <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506003.abs">Predictable and Unpredictable Error in Tort Awards: The Effect of Plaintiff Self Selection and Signalling </A> If a potential tort plaintiff can predict that the court will overestimate damages he is more likely to bring suit, but if the court is aware of this, it will adjust its awards accordingly. In general, court error implies that the court should moderate extreme awards whether they are high or low, because of regression towards the mean. Predictable error, however, tends to push the optimal adjustment downwards and unpredictable error pushes it upwards, because of plaintiff selection and signalling, respectively. The expectation of either kind of error leads plaintiffs to bring meritless suits.    <I>  </I> (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>by Eric <EM> Rasmusen</EM>, <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506001.abs">Stigma and Self-Fulfilling Expectations of Criminality </A> A convicted criminal suffers not only from public penalties, but from stigma, the reluctance of others to interact with him economically and socially. Conviction can convey useful information about a person, which makes stigmatization an important and legitimate function of the criminal justice system, quite apart from moral considerations. Whether stigma will operate in this way depends on expectations and the crime rate, however, which can lead to multiple, pareto-ranked equilibria with different amounts of crime and stigma.    <I>  </I> (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>by Samuel A.<EM> Rea, Jr.</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecipa/archive/UT-ECIPA-REAS-95-01.html">Breaking Up is Hard to Do: The Economics of Spousal Support  </A> The introduction of "no-fault" divorce has eliminated the traditional basis for spousal support without providing a satisfactory alternative. In a recent case, Elliot v. Elliot, an Ontario court awarded the woman half of the difference between her earnings had she not married and her earnings after the divorce. The model developed in this paper highlights the changes in earnings that result from specialization in housework or market work, investment in children, and investment in the spouse's human capital. The incentive effects on human capital, marriage, and divorce are considered. Although no measure is perfect, the paper concludes that the approach taken in Elliot, adjusted for additional leisure enjoyed during marriage, offers a reasonable compromise between competing objectives.   <I>  </I> (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>by D. Wall and K.<EM> Reid</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2d.htm">The Electric Lawyer: From Quill to Computer </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Andrew F. Daughety and Jennifer F. <EM> Reinganum</EM>, <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/game/papers/9403/9403007.abs">Product Safety: Liability, R&D and Signaling  </A> This paper develops a two-stage model of product design and safety signaling incorporating a parametric liability specification in a monopoly context. In the first stage, the firm engages in research and development in order to determine the safety of its product. We model the research and development process as sequential sampling from a fixed distribution of potential safety levels. Since the outcome of research and development trials is unobservable to consumers, in the second stage of the model the firm must choose its price with the understanding that consumers may attempt to draw inferences about the product's safety.   <I>  </I> (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>by Andrew F. Daughety and Jennifer F.<EM> Reinganum</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/daughety.html">Product Safety: Liability, R&D and Signaling </A> We develop a monopoly model of product design and safety signaling incorporating a parametric liability specification. The firm first engages in R&D to affect the safety of its product. Since the outcome of R&D trials is unobservable to consumers, the firm then chooses its price, understanding that consumers may draw inferences from the price about the product's safety. Consumers acquire and use the product; injuries lead to losses which are allocated by the liability system. We vary the liability system's allocation of losses and trace out the implications for R&D investment and the price-safety relationship.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Kevin <EM> Reuther</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/reuther.pag">Dorothy's friend goes to law school </A> The experiences of a gay student at Harvard Law School.  <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Steven P. <EM> Reynolds</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/reynolds.htm">The German Recycling Experiment and Its Lesons for United States Policy </A>   <I> Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by David L. Powell, Dan R. Stengle, and  Robert M. <EM> Rhodes</EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/powell.html">A Measured step to protect private property rights </A> A 1995 measure of the Florida legislature measure includes a new cause of action providing judicial relief to landowners who suffer inordinate burdens on the use of their land. If properly implemented and applied, the measure will have none of the feared undesriable effects. The legislation grants important new rights to landowners while maintaining existing environmental protection and growth management programs. Perhaps most importantly, the measure is intended to reform the way government does business with landowners. The legislation strikes a balance between conflicting, but equally valid, public and private interests.   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by M. <EM> Ricolfi</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Bioethics/Ricolfi-1995/Bioethics.html">Bioethics Market and Morals: the Case of Biotechnological Patents </A>   <I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael <EM> RobertsonReal Property</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.ualberta.ca/ee/fulltext/paper.robertson_m.html">Property and Ideology </A>   <I> Electronic Easement </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by M E <EM> Rodgers</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/rodgers4.html">The Law Commission's Proposals on Mental Capacity and the Legality of Elective Ventilation for Transplantation Purposes </A> This article discusses the legality of elective ventilation in the light of the recent proposals on mental capacity by the Law Commission. The author suggests that the process is not tainted with illegality. In addition, the relationship between the process of elective ventilation and the importance of the patient's best interests is explored, through consideration of the definition of 'best interests' put forward by the Law Commission.  <I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by M E <EM> Rodgers</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/rodgers2.html">Standard of Proof in Care Order Applications under the Children Act 1989 </A> In re H and Others (Minors) [1995] 2 WLR 8, HL is the culmination of a series of appeals by the Nottingham County Council against the judgment of His Honour Judge Davidson on 23rd November 1994. The application for care orders under Children Act 1989, s 31, in respect of 3 children was refused. A subsequent appeal to the Court of Appeal was dismissed on 14th December 1994. The Local Authority appealed to the House of Lords, the matter being heard on 17 & 18th July 1995, with judgement reserved, and opinions being delivered on 14th December 1995.    <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> (casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by Peter K. <EM> Rofes</EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/rofes.html">Law school and the constitution </A> This essay is a satirical look at constitutional law course descriptions in law school bulletins. The author suggests alternative descriptions that would make bulletins as "fresh and original" as the typical curriculum in the classroom. This essay is part of a larger project in which the author examines different aspects of the American law school.  <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Jeffrey<EM> Rosales-Castaneda</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/quest.txt">QUEST Evidence Computer Tutorials - A Review </A> A student review of a computer based tutorial for use in teaching Australian evidence law  <I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Richard<EM> Rosecrance</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/rose.html">U.S.-Japan Trading Relationship and Its Effects </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael Bradley and Michael<EM> Rosenzweig</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/bradley.html">In Defense of Abolishing Chapter 11 </A> In this paper we have responded to those who have criticized our call for repeal of Chapter 11.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Susan<EM> Ross</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/ross.txt">Learning About Survival From Survivors: Mohawk Environmental Communicative Action </A> This report examines two case-studies in order to illustrate the argument that environmental justice requires that indigenous people, who may have a different world-view, be involved in environmental decision-making. The author stresses the danger of using purely "statistical and quantitative" methods and excluding human, ethical value-judgements in formulating environmental policy  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by A. <EM> Rossato</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Students/neg.html">An Economic Analysis of Liability Rules </A>   <I> Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Joel L. Schrag and Paul H.<EM> Rubin</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/rubin.html">Judicial Hierarchies and the Rule-Individual Tradeoff </A> In the United States laws are interpreted by a hierarchy of judges. In this paper we identify a conflict between the different levels of the hierarchy. When deciding how to rule in a case, a judge balances the interests of the litigants against the interests of the people who will be affected by the precedent that the ruling establishes. But higher level judges' decisions affect more people than lower level judges' decisions. Therefore, higher level judges should produce decisions that are less sensitive to the litigants' interests and more sensitive to the interests of the rest of society.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Rudolph C.<EM> Ryser</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/ryser.txt">Resuming Self-Government in Indian Country: From Imposed Government to Self-Rule Inside and Outside the United States of America </A> This paper examines the right of self-determination with particular focus upon the native Americans of the United States of America.  <I> E-Law </I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<A HREF="A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="Q.HTM">Q</A> | <A HREF="R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="Z.HTM">Z</A> 
