<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   S</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/S.GIF" >
Essays by author :   S</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Robert B. Mison, Bettina B. Plevan and Paul <EM> Salvatore</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/mison.pag">Sexual Orientation Discrimination in the Workplace: A Legal Reference Guide </A> This recently updated outline of law relating to sexual stereotyping, domestic partnership benefits, employment discrimination and sexual orientation harassment provides citations of key federal and state cases, law review articles and state and local laws in a concise and accessible format.   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Philippe<EM> Sands</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/sands.html">The "Greening" of International Law Emerging Principles and Rules </A> The article is outlines some of the more controversial (from a U.S. perspective) international legal issues which have arisen in recent years, including in particular the global instruments adopted at the United Nations Conference on Environment and Development  (UNCED), held at Rio de Janeiro in June 1992, as well as the regional developments reflecting the efforts of the EC Member States in their attempt to "green" the EEC Treaty.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by John A.<EM> Scanlan</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/scanlan.html">A View from the United States -- Social, Economic, and Legal Change, the Persistence of the State, and Immigration Policy in the Coming Century </A> In this article, Professor Scanlan argues that in spite of recent trends toward globalism, traditionally composed nation-states, especially the United States, will continue to exercise localized control over immigration and receiving nations may pursue increasingly restrictive policies.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Stephen E. <EM> Scheele</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/scheetr1.html">The Politics of Western Immigration </A>   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Todd Stewart<EM> Schenk</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/schenk.html">A Proposal to Improve the Treatment of Women in Asylum Law :  Adding a "Gender" Category to the International Definition of "Refugee" </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> (Note)
<HR>
<LI>by Ferdinand P.<EM> Schoettle</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/schoettle.html">Reconsidering the Supreme Court's Role in Deciding Challanges to State Taxes - Some Perspectives from the Gatt </A> This paper recommends that the Supreme Court adopt free trade principles as criteria for deciding Commerce-Clause-based disputes about the Constitutionality of state taxes and abandon its current approach of balancing the states' need for revenues against other considerations. The paper summarizes the principles that guide tax design in a multijurisdicitonal free trade world. Analogies from the GATT illustrate that in deciding challenges to state taxes based on free-trade principles the Supreme Court fills a normal institutional role that other free-trade federations replicate. GATT panel reports illustrate how the basic economic principles supporting free trade can serve as guides to decision.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Paul H. Rubin and Joel L.<EM> Schrag</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/rubin.html">Judicial Hierarchies and the Rule-Individual Tradeoff </A> In the United States laws are interpreted by a hierarchy of judges. In this paper we identify a conflict between the different levels of the hierarchy. When deciding how to rule in a case, a judge balances the interests of the litigants against the interests of the people who will be affected by the precedent that the ruling establishes. But higher level judges' decisions affect more people than lower level judges' decisions. Therefore, higher level judges should produce decisions that are less sensitive to the litigants' interests and more sensitive to the interests of the rest of society.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Warren F and Edward P<EM> Schwartz</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/schwartz.html">The Challenge of Peremptory Challenges </A>   <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Edward P. Schwartz and Warren F. <EM> Schwartz</EM>, <A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/conferen/papers/schwartz.html">Simple Majority Rule for Criminal Jury Trials: The Verdict is Now In </A> The paper proposes that the current two way unanimity rule governing jury verdicts in criminal cases be replaced by a rule of simple majority.  Neither the history of the use of the unanimity rule nor the reasons advanced to justify its use provide persuasive grounds for retaining the rule rather than employing the rule of simple majority which is used in virtually all other democratic institutions.    <I>  </I> (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>by Shelley Day <EM> Sclater</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/sclater4.html">A Critical Approach to the White Paper on Divorce Reform </A> This paper discusses some of the issues raised by recent Government proposals for reform of the divorce law. It begins by considering the responses of professional bodies (the Law Society, the Solicitors' Family Law Association, and National Family Mediation) to the green consultation paper of December 1993. It is argued that the concerns voiced by lawyers have, in the main, not been addressed. It is suggested that a broader range of issues, including questions of justice and fairness, should be introduced into the debate, and that social scientific commentary has a valuable contribution to make in this regard.   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>Reviewed by Colin <EM> Scott</EM>, <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/bookrev/1scott/default.htm">Colin D Long (Ed), "Telecommunications Law and Practise"  2nd Edition  </A>   <I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by The Right Hon. Sir Richard <EM> Scott</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/scott2.html">The Use of Public Interest Immunity Claims in Criminal Cases </A> Sir Richard Scott suggests that the application to criminal trials of Public Interest Immunity principles derived from civil cases and designed for application in civil cases has been a mistake and has acted as an impediment to the evolution of satisfactory principles for dealing with PII claims in criminal trials. Sir Richard goes on to suggest what should be the correct approach to PII claims in criminal trials.    <I> Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Paul<EM> Seaman QC</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/seaman.txt">Providing a Sustainable Economic Land Base for Aboriginal Populations </A> Provides general background to the substance and implications of the High Court's Mabo decision, the workings of the _Native Title Act_, the Native Title Tribunal and an outline of statutary requirements and current policy for processing native title applications  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Brad <EM> Sears</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/sears.pag">Queer L </A> The experiences of a gay student at Harvard Law School.  <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Peter <EM> Seipel</EM>, <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1sweden/default.htm">Comments on the EC Data Protection Directive : The View from Sweden </A>   <I> Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Christopher<EM> Seline</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://sulaw.law.su.OZ.AU:70/00/Law%20Documents/Collection%20of%20various%20Laws%20%28mainly%20from%20U.S.%29/tempest.law">Eavesdropping On the Electromagnetic Emanations of Digital Equipment:  The Laws of Canada, England and the United States </A> This note explores the legal status of a surveillance technology ruefully known as TEMPEST. Using TEMPEST technology the information in any digital device may be intercepted and reconstructed into useful intelligence without the operative ever having to come near his target. The technology is especially useful in the interception of information stored in digital computers or displayed on computer terminals.  <I>  </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Greg S. <EM> Sergienko</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/sergienko.html">Incrimination and Cryptographic Keys </A>   <I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Silvia<EM> Serpe</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/ser.htm">Reviewability of environmental impact statements on legislative proposals after Franklin v. Massachusetts </A> This Note explores the need for clarification of the finality doctrine with respect to NEPA's Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) requirement. It argues that courts should be able to review an agency's failure to prepare an EIS on a legislative proposal, even if the President has the ultimate constitutional authority over the action.   Contrary holdings, which extend a strict *Franklin* articulation of "finality" to NEPA cases, the D.C. Circuit did in Public Citizen, renders NEPA's EIS requirement for legislative proposals unenforceable and moot.  <I> Cornell LR January 1995</I> (note)
<HR>
<LI>by Christopher<EM> Shanahan</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/shanahan.txt">Legislative Responses to *Mabo*- Rendering the Law Unconscious? </A> The common law precedents cited in *Mabo* reveal the common law's long established capacity to recognise pluralism.  This is contrasted with the effects of the *Native Title Act 1993* (Cth) and the *Land (Titles and Traditional Usage) Act 1993* (WA), which seek to overcome the plurality implicit in the legal recognition of indigenous interests in land, thereby denying this tradition of plurality within Anglo-Australian legal culture.  <I> E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Martin<EM> Shapiro</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/shapiro.html">The Globalization of Law </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Louis Kaplow and Steven<EM> Shavell</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/shavell.html">Property Rules vs Liability Rules </A> A fundamental legal problem is whether property rights should be protected by property rules or by liability rules. In this Article, we provide a systematic economic analysis of the choice between property and liability rules. We answer a basic question: why is it that liability rules are commonly used in the context of harmful externalities (such as pollution and automobile accidents), whereas property rules are generally employed toprotect possessors of things against potential takers? In the course of our analysis, we demonstrate that many commonly held beliefs about property and liability rules are mistaken. Our analysis is also relevant to policy; for example, we show that in important contexts liability rules (and pollution taxes) are more efficient than property rules (including much regulation) even when damages must be set using only limited information about harm.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Gregory L. <EM> Shelton</EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/shelton.html">In search of the lost amendment: challenging federal firearms regulation through the state's right interpretation of the second amendment </A> This Comment embraces the individual rights interpretation of the Second Amendment which holds that the Second Amendment grants to the citizen the right to keep and bear arms, a right that now flounders between the Scylla of state police and militia powers and the Charybdis of federal regulation. This Comment argues, however, that federal firearms regulation is unconstitutional whether Second Amendment rights are interpreted as belonging to the individual or to the states. The heart of this Comment, thus, proposes and explores constitutional challenges to federal firearms regulation.  <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Michael G. Goldsby, Virginia W. Gerde and Jon M. <EM> Shepard</EM>, <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/gerde.html">Teaching Business Ethics Through Literature </A> America's economic ideology lacks a vocabulary of ethics. If, as we assume, an economic system requires a moral component for long-term survival, students in business schools must be exposed to a vocabulary of ethics that is consistent with the ideology of capitalism. We present a vocabulary of ethics and describe an approach to teaching business ethics based on business-related classic literature and moral philosophy.     <I> The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1  No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Steven<EM> Shiffrin</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/shi.htm">Racist speech, outsider jurisprudence, and the meaning of America </A> The argument that first amendment values (such as truth, autonomy, self-expression, and liberty) dictate that racist speech cannot be regulated is ultimately indefensible.  The victims of racist speech should have the primary voice in determining whether sanctions should be imposed in this area.  My argument, therefore, seeks to close a discussion about the first amendment (of course, it will not) and open a discussion about the effectiveness of hate speech regulations in a racist society.  <I> Cornell LR November 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Steven<EM> Shortgen</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/t.htm">Dressing up software interface protection: the application of *Two Pesos* to look-and-feel </A> This note presents the Supreme Court's *Two Pesos* decision and discusses that decision's implications for intellectual property lawyers. Finally, it provides closing comments on asserting trade dress protection for GUIs, and includes a model application based loosely upon the litigation between Apple, Inc. and Microsoft, Inc. Ultimately, this Note argues that GUIs as well as future creative interfaces deserve protection under trade dress doctrine in certain cases.  <I> Cornell LR November 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Ralph<EM> Simmonds</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/simmonds.txt">Curbing Self-Dealing in Corporations: Australia's New Approach </A> The traditional approach in countries like Australia has been to rely on the common law fiduciary duties, augmented by specific statutory requirements for particular sorts of transactions perceived to carry a high risk of abuse.  The latest in the line of these requirements is contained in _Corporations Law_, Part 3.2A.  It is distinguished by the breadth of its application, particularly in relation to transactions in corporate groups.   Its greatest novelty lies in its basic rule prohibiting the giving of financial benefits to related parties unless approval by a majority of disinterested shareholders is secured.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I> Legislation Note
<HR>
<LI>by Brian I. <EM> Sopinsky</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/sopinsky.htm">Kaiser Aluminum and Ahemical Corp. v. Catellus Development Corp.: Broad Remedial Powers of CERCLA Take No Prisoners </A>   <I> Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I> (Casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by Alan<EM> Sprince</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/sprince1.html">The Trustees' duty to defend - Look before you leap, when to leap and how high </A> Fear of exposure to costs is a dominant influence in concentrating the minds of litigants, actual and potential.  For trustees, however, the dilemma is more complex. The precise nature of the duty to defend proceedings - was examined and refined by Lightman J in the recent case of Alsop Wilkinson (A Firm) v Neary ([1995] 1 All ER 431, Ch D).  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I> (casenote)
<HR>
<LI>by Timothy James <EM> Stanley </EM>, <A HREF="http://www-leland.stanford.edu/~tstanley/tjspaper/tstanley.paper.html">An Analysis of the Rules of Contribution and No Contribution for Joint and Several Liability in Conspiracy Cases  </A> This paper examines deterrence and settlement effects of three rules that have been applied in joint and several liability conspiracy cases. These rules are the no contribution rule, the contribution with claim reduction rule and the contribution with settlement reduction rule.  It is shown that where conspirators have asymmetric information that the no contribution rule could lead to less deterrence than the contribution rules for all conspirators. The paper concludes that the contribution with claim reduction rule with liability allocated per capita or the no contribution rule should be applied to joint and several liability in conspiracy situations. The one rule that is disfavored is the contribution with settlement reduction rule. More importantly this paper encourages greater focus on whether the joint harm is caused by defendants acting in concert or independently.    <I>  </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Tim <EM> Stanley</EM>, <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9507/9507002.abs">Radar Detectors, Fixed and Variable Costs of Crime  </A> Raising the sanction will not always lead to less crime, and may lead to more crime. If a criminal has the opportunity to commit multiple criminal acts and has fixed and variable costs of committing these acts, then an increase in the criminal sanction, over a certain range of sanctions, may actually lead the criminal to commit more crime. Once the criminal pays his fixed costs, they will be sunk costs, and thus they will no longer enter into the criminal's decision process of committing criminal acts. But the variable cost of crime will enter into the criminal's decision process. The example of the criminal's decision to purchase a radar detector and to speed is used to illustrate the point.    <I>  </I> (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>by Jenny<EM> Steele</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/steele2.html">Private Rights and Planning Consent </A> Despite the scope for conflict between the private law of nuisance and the public law of the planning system, there has not been much litigation. The cases of Wheeler v JJ Saunders Ltd and Hunter and Others v Canary Wharf Ltd demonstrate that no clear principles have yet emerged.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> (Case Comment)
<HR>
<LI>by Jocelyn Mason and Andrew <EM> Steer </EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/steer.html">The Role of Multilateral Finance and the Environment: A View from the World Bank </A> Since funding for the Rio Earth Summit agreements has not been forthcoming, multilateral financial institutions (MFIs) have taken responsibility for advancing the environmental agenda set forth at the Summit. MFIs furnish three crucial functions in implementing the global environmental agenda. First, MFIs are able to target investments in developing countries that involve important environmental issues. Second, MFIs are able to support policy reforms within developing countries to ensure environmental standards and issues are properly addressed. Finally, MFIs can multiply a small amount of funding into a significant amount.   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Helen Xanthaki and Constantin<EM> Stefanou</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/stefan3.html">Article 224 of the Treaty of Rome and the Repercussions of Case C-120/94 </A> This article examines an almost forgotten, original Article of the Treaty of Rome, Article 224, in the light of the recent case of Commission v Greece (C-120/94). The article consists of two parts.  The first part looks at the ECJ's precedents, attempts an interpretation of Article 224 and then proceeds to apply the analysis on case C-120/94. The second part concentrates on the 'political' repercussions of the case which, because of its subject matter, have particular significance for the EU.  Depending on the ECJ's pending final decision it may herald a return to the Court's 'activism' or confirm the 'minimalist' trend of recent years.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by David L. Powell, Robert M. Rhodes, and Dan R. <EM> Stengle </EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/powell.html">A Measured step to protect private property rights </A> A 1995 measure of the Florida legislature measure includes a new cause of action providing judicial relief to landowners who suffer inordinate burdens on the use of their land. If properly implemented and applied, the measure will have none of the feared undesriable effects. The legislation grants important new rights to landowners while maintaining existing environmental protection and growth management programs. Perhaps most importantly, the measure is intended to reform the way government does business with landowners. The legislation strikes a balance between conflicting, but equally valid, public and private interests.   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by C. Maureen <EM> Stinger</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/stinger.html">Arizona v. Evans: Adapting the Exclusionary Rule to Advancing Computer Technology </A>   <I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Richard<EM> Stone</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/stone3.html">Exclusion of Evidence under Section 78 of the Police and Criminal Evidence Act: Practice and Principles </A> Section 78 of PACE gives the courts a discretion to exclude from a criminal trial evidence which has been obtained unfairly.   This article is an attempt to analyse the principles which the courts use.  It trying to identify the factors which the judges regard as relevant to this discretion.  Secondly, it examines the possible policies which might underlie a discretion to exclude.  It then attempts to match the practice to the policies, and concludes that fairness as fair play is the dominant policy. The conclusion considers how the changes in the rights of the suspect (in particular the right to remain silent) introduced by the Criminal Justice Act 1994 are likely to impact on the operation of s 78.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Lynn A.<EM> Stout</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/stout.html">The Heterogeneous Expectations Model of Speculation and Speculative Bubbles </A> Economists disagree over the proper definition of the word "speculation" as well as over its effects on the welfare of speculators and society as a whole. Although conventional theories of risk-hedging, information arbitrage, and liquidity dealing certainly explain some apparently speculative transactions, this paper examines a fourth, and relatively neglected, approach that focuses on heterogeneous expectations and uncertainty as a cause of speculative trading. The paper explores the value of the HE approach by examining the implications of the HE model for three issues that have troubled economic theory: the proper definition of "speculation", the causes and nature of asset price bubbles, and the normative significance of speculative trading. In each case, the HE model proves of value in understanding speculative phenomena.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Bruce D. Platt and Lisa D. <EM> Stream</EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/platt.html">Dispelling the negative myths of managed care: an analysis of anti-managed care legislation and the quality of care  provided by health maintenance organizations  </A> The first part of this Article discusses managed care legislation. Specifically, it provides a summary of some of the last five years of Florida's legislative health care advancements incorporating managed care concepts. It then discusses some of the proposed legislation which targets HMOs and other managed care plans. The available literature indicates that the quality of care provided by HMOs is as good as, if not better than, the quality of care provided in a traditional fee-for-service setting. Legislation which would cripple managed care in the name of preserving quality is unnecessary and counterproductive.   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Victor <EM> Streib</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/streib.pag">Death Penalty for Lesbians </A> In this piece Victor Streib looks at compilations of data on the effect of gender on the likelihood a person accused of a capital crime will be sentenced to death, and asks if a woman's lesbianism impacts the incidence of her being sentenced to death and finally executed.  Using 4 case studies of women who were sentenced to death in cases where their lesbianism played a role, Prof. Streib finds that a number of factors impact the equation. While lesbianism is not seen as a mitigating factor, it is often overshadowed by the extreme violence of the crime, and thus does not stand out as an aggravating factor.    <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Duane Chapman, Jean Agras and Vivek <EM> Suri</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/chapman.html">International Law, Industrial Location, and Pollution </A> The dominant position of economists on trade and environment is that increasing trade raises living standards, which provide the economic basis for reduced pollution. The paper presents a very different perspective. In summary, on a global basis, the international economy is characterized by increasing trade and world economic product, stagnation in gross economic product per capita, accelerating energy use, and exponential growth in emissions of major pollutants.   <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by A. Katz, M. Young, and R.<EM> Susskind</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3i.html">LINK - The Legal Information Network: Users views </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by A. Paterson and R.<EM> Susskind</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2i.html">Technology, Learning and the Trans-Atlantic divide </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Greg<EM> Swensen</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/swensen.txt">Drug Problems in Western Australia:  a review of non-criminal mechanisms ... </A> Discussion of the shortcomings in the Western Australian system of notifying drug addicts. There is an examination of the practical considerations as well as the natural justice implications.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
