<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   V</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/V.GIF" >
Essays by author :   V</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Francisco <EM> Valdes</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/valdes.pag">Coming Out and Stepping Up: Queer Legal Theory and Connectivity </A> In this article Francisco Valdes calls for the creation of Queer Legal theory based on the coalescence of a "sexual minority" over the past twenty-five years.  Prof. Valdes discusses the relationship of Queer Legal theory to Feminist Legal Theory and Critical Race Theory detailing the common "psycho-social isolation" of gays and lesbians, women and racial minorities. He encourages recognition of the common interests and goals of the three groups and urges each to be sensitive to the interrelationship, or "connectivity," among them.   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>Introduced by Francisco <EM> Valdes</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/valdes3.pag">Proceedings of the Panel on Gender, Sexual Orientation & HIV at the 1995 Women in the Law Conference, Monterey, California, May 5, 1995  </A> In this transcript of the proceedings of the panel on Gender, Sexual Orientation and HIV, sponsored by the State Bar of California Women in Law Committee, the panelists focus on how AIDS affects women, including lesbians.  Four women, a legal worker living with AIDS, an AIDS health and social service provider, a policy-worker and a legal service provider, tell their stories and express their opinions about the impact of the AIDS crisis on them and women generally.    <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Francisco <EM> Valdes</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/valdes2.pag">Tracking and Assessing the (Non)Inclusion of Courses on Sexuality and/or Sexual Orientation in the American Law School Curriculum: Reports From the Field After a Decade of Effort  </A> In this article Prof. Valdes presents his survey of American law schools offering courses pertaining to sexual orientation and sexuality issues and expresses "cautious optimism" about the future inclusion of gay and lesbian issues in legal curricula.   <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Sylvia R. Lazos <EM> Vargas </EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/lazos.html">Florida's property rights act: a political quick fix results in a mixed bag of tricks </A> This Article reviews the political climate that made passage of the 1995 Florida Property Rights Act possible. It articulates an interpretive framework for the Act, briefly describes the law, and applies that framework to key issues posed by the Act. It explains how the settlement order mechanism is a type of decentralized decisionmaking and explores why decentralized decisionmaking is becoming a trend in regulatory reform. It also examines how information asymmetry, transaction costs, perceived risks, and other factors could affect the strategic behavior of property owners and agencies, thereby skewing incentives in the settlement order process. Finally, it suggests reforms that need to be considered in order to avoid results not intended by the Act.   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by M. Hibbs and K.<EM> Vaughan</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3e.html">Interactive video in legal education and practice </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by George A. <EM> Voegele, Jr.</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/voegele.htm">EPA's Problematic Enforcement policy for the RCRA Section3004(j) Storage Prohibition as Applied to Mixed Wastes: Edison Electric Institute v. EPA </A>   <I> Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I> (Casenote)
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
