</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   W</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/W.GIF" >
Essays by author :   W</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by John <EM> W. Larson </EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/larson.html">Florida's new partnership law: the revised uniform partnership act and limited liability partnerships </A> After eighty years of nearly uniform and virtually unchanged partnership law, the recent passage of these two laws has ushered in a truly new era of partnership jurisprudence, both in the United States and in Florida. This Article will explain the major changes in partnership law wrought by the Revised Florida Act, identify the Florida nonuniform provisions, and consider the meaning and significance of Florida's limited liability partnership legislation.    <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Joel<EM> Waldfogel</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/waldfogel.html">Sentencing Policy, Implied Demographic Welfare Weights, and the Theory of Sentencing Reform </A> Different groups of people experience varying degrees of different externalties. By a government's choice of expenditures to control externalities, it affects different members of the population differently. These choices implicitly "value" the welfare of members of different groups. This paper adapts the framework developed by Ahmad and Stern (1984) to infer welfare weights underlying a system of commodity taxation, to infer the welfare weights implicitly attached to different population groups by U.S. sentencing policy. We also calculate welfare-improving directions of sentencing reform.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by K. Reid and D.<EM> Wall</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2d.htm">The Electric Lawyer: From Quill to Computer </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by S. van<EM> Walsum</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk:70/00/ltc/publications/conferences/oxford/walsum.txt">Mixed Metaphors: The Nation and the Family </A> The concept of nationality is a contingent one, and must be placed in its historical and geographical context. Equally important for the meaning of this concept is the legal field in which it is employed: immigration law, law of conflicts or social policies directed at migrants. The equally contingent concept of family is intimately linked to that of nationality, and this relationship too varies according to time, place and specific legal context. This paper attempts to analyse the relationship between the nation and the family in the specific context of present-day Dutch immigration law. Inspired by writings of the geographer David Harvey, the author considers the consequences for control over mobility, identity and family loyalty.  <I> Oxford Critical Legal Conference 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by David<EM> Waterman</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/waterman.html">Local Monopsony, Free Riding, and Antitrust Policy </A> This paper models the development of market structure in industries which are characterized by upstream economies of scale in the distribution of differentiated products to retail firms having local monopoly power within separate geographic areas. Examples are cable television and other mass media. Antitrust applications to the cable television, motion picture, and newspaper industries are discussed.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>by Julian<EM> Webb</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/webb2.html">Extending the Theory-Practice Spiral: Action Research as a Mechanism for crossing the Academic/Professional Divide </A> Current theory and practice in legal education is increasingly emphasising the need to develop in students the capacity for 'reflective practice' or 'humane professionalism'. This paper argues that the logic of humane professionalism has yet to be carried through to the later, continuing, stages of English legal education. It suggests that the law schools should play a significant part in this development by fostering an alternative, research-based, paradigm for continuing professional development. The vehicle proposed for this is 'action research', a hermeneutic and practice-based research method, which shares many of its epistemological assumptions with the experiential methods of clinical legal education. The paper concludes by analysing the main strengths and weaknesses of action research and offers a preliminary assessment of its capacity to contribute both to practitioners' self-knowledge of their practices and to academic understanding of the 'legal world'.  <I> Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Peter D. <EM> Webster</EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/webster.html">Selection and retention of judges: is there one "best" method? </A> This Article first discusses the relationship between judicial theory and choice of a method of judicial selection and retention. It then addresses what each of the principal alternative methods of judicial selection and retention now in use does, and does not, accomplish. Finally, it proposes a compromise method which might prove more likely to satisfy all participants in the debate than does any of the current alternatives.  <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Kay <EM> Wheat</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/wheat2.html">The Law Commission Consultation Paper No 137 - Liability for Psychiatric Illness </A> This paper examines negligently inflicted psychiatric illness when the plaintiff is a secondary victim, i.e. someone who has suffered the illness as a result of injury to another, the primary victim. The law imposes a number of restrictions.  The Law Commission look at these restrictions and make a number of provisional recommendations. The paper outlines these recommendations in their legal context.  <I>  </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Murray<EM> Wheater</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/wheater.txt">The Electronic Classroom : a Personal Account of Learning the Law by Email </A> A student's personal account of the initial attempt to teach a law course with a computer network as a tool of teaching. This is with particular emphasis on the use of information technology.  This leads to personal reflection on the benefits of structuring the course in such a way.  <I> E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by F. Pritchard and R. <EM> Widdison </EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1b.html">An Experiment with Electronic Law Tutorials  </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Robin <EM> Widdison</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/widdis4.html">Law Courseware: Big Bang or Damp Squib? </A>   <I> [1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Robin<EM> Widdison</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1 /widdis1.html">Lawyering on the Internet </A> This article attempts to show why the Internet is not just a passing fad but also a major step forward in information technology that will have enduring significance both in the workplace and the place of study. Secondly, it seeks to explain the Internet by reference to what it enables users to do rather than in terms of its underlying technologies. Finally, the article examines how the development of the Internet is likely to impact on legal practice and on legal education.  <I> [1995] No. 1 Web JCLI</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by David<EM> Williams</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/profwms.html">European and U.S. Perspectives on Civic Republicanism </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Sir David<EM> Williams Q.C.</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/sirwms.html">Law and Administrative Discretion </A> Williams proceeds to analyze administrative law development in England. Williams also stresses the relationship between democratic ideals and judicial deference to the decisions of local authorities. He concludes by describing the ever-evolving nature of administrative law in England today, arguing that just as in the 1920s, the underlying approach of the courts to questions in administrative law can only be interpreted by taking into account the multitude of circumstances from which such questions arise.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by E.<EM> Wilson</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2f.html">Automating Design Packages for Law </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Evan <EM> Wolfson</EM>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/wolfson.pag">Fighting to Win and Keep the Freedom to Marry: The Legal, Political, and Cultural Challenges Ahead  </A> In this series of documents Mr. Wolfson describes Lambda's work in the area of marriage rights and provides information necessary for anyone to help promote equal marriage rights for gays and lesbians including a briefing on the legal status of the case and the tasks ahead, a series of questions and answers about marrage and gay people and finally a series of documents designed to help gays and lesbians in all states gain legal recognition of Hawaii marriages, assuming a victorious conclusion of the litigation there.    <I> The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I> 
<HR>
<LI>Reviewed by Jeffrey A. <EM> Wolfson</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/wolfson.html">Review of <i>Federal Broadband Law</i> by John Thorne, Peter W. Huber, and Michael K. Kellog </A>   <I> Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Fred Greguras, Michael R Egger and Sandy<EM> Wong</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/greguras.txt">Multimedia Content and the Super Highway: Rapid Acceleration or Foot on the Brake? </A> This article discusses emerging legal issues concerning copyright/patent protection of material used in multimedia applications. Describes existing processes for the administration of copyright/patent material in the US and the deficencies of traditional rights agreements where material is used in multimedia products.  Cites recent reports from Japan concerning the advantages of streamlining copyright/patent administration, and proposes the establishment of a US based copyright/patent clearinghouse for multimedia materials.  <I> E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Diane P.<EM> Wood</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/wood.html">United States Antitrust Law in the Global Market </A>   <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Marsha<EM> Woodbury</EM>, <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/woodbury.txt">Freedom of Information Laws Affect the Autonomy of American Universities </A> The author recognises the tension between the need to maintain public trust through accountabiity and the desire to foster academic freedom, efficiency and to preserve privacy. She argues that universities should become more open with operations such as presidential/chancellor searches, crime statistics and peer review.  Disclosure and openness should be achieved voluntarily, thus avoiding the need for legal intervention or enforcement of change. Guidelines recently announced by President Clinton and Attorney-General Janet Remo which emphasize a presumption of disclosure are recommended.  <I> E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by George<EM> Wyeth</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/wyeth.html">Takings as the Failure of the Regulatory Market </A> This paper suggests addressing the stubborn "takings" problem by using a hypothetical perfectly competitive "regulatory market" as a normative reference point. The paper contends that this approach allows us to resolve apparent tensions between past takings analyses, and reconcile apparently conflicting views about the desirability of compensation. It also examines the light that such an approach sheds on the generally discredited notion of a "harm-benefit" distinction -- arguing that the hypothetical market provides the "baseline" that allows such a distinction to be drawn.. This approach is seen to explain some hitherto difficult rulings, and to suggest changes in other areas.  <I> American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I> (PostScript)
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
