<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   Y</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/Y.GIF" >
Essays by author :   Y</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by M.<EM> Young</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2b.html">Cost of Computer Assisted Learning (CAL) </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by M.<EM> Young</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1c.html">Justification and Criticism of Legal Computer Assisted Learning (CAL) </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by R. Susskind, A. Katz, and M.<EM> Young</EM>, <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3i.html">LINK - The Legal Information Network: Users views </A>   <I> Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Charles W. Ehrhardt and Stephanie J. <EM> Young </EM>, <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/ehrhardt.html">Using leading questions during direct examination </A> Historically, limitations upon a party's impeaching its own witness and upon using leading questions during direct examination have been intertwined. Clarification of this area began in 1990, when the Florida Legislature amended section 90.608, Florida Statutes, to permit impeachment of a party's own witness. In 1995, the Florida Legislature amended section 90.612(3), Florida Statutes, to provide for the use of leading questions during direct examination. This Article traces the development of the Florida Rules of Civil Procedure and the Florida Statutes from before the adoption of the Florida Evidence Code to the present.   <I> Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<A HREF="A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="Q.HTM">Q</A> | <A HREF="R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="Z.HTM">Z</A> 
