<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by author :   Z</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/Z.GIF" >
Essays by author :   Z</H1>
<UL>

<LI>by Aristide R.<EM> Zolberg</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/zolberg.html">Changing Sovereignty Games and International Migration </A> In this article, Professor Zolberg argues that today's immigration issues should be analyzed within their historical bases.  The author concludes that despite the recent development of borderless markets and communication infrastructures, much remains to be done to build a truly global community.  <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I> 
<HR>
<LI>by Elisabeth <EM> Zoller</EM>, <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/zoller.html">Institutional Aspects of International Governance </A> Professor Zoller argues that the international community is not really a community at all, but several "intertangled communities" with common interests. Common interests among nation states and priority setting are the two prerequisites necessary for international governance. Although power is decentralized in international governance, it can still be exercised collectively. She concludes by suggesting that the shortcomings of global regulation, especially with respect to environmental issues, can be addressed most effectively by the institutional aspects of international governance. To that end, the success of international governance, in terms of international environmental protection, depends upon the leadership exerted by the "great powers," specifically the United States.    <I> Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I> 
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<A HREF="A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="Q.HTM">Q</A> | <A HREF="R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="Z.HTM">Z</A> 
