<DOCNO>WT18-B20-120</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA030-000643-B022-6</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.law.cam.ac.uk:80/TITLES/A.HTM 131.111.173.8 19970122114520 text/html 14059
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Microsoft-IIS/2.0
Date: Wed, 22 Jan 1997 11:42:47 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Accept-Ranges: bytes
Last-Modified: Thu, 11 Apr 1996 17:50:10 GMT
Content-Length: 13860
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   A</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/A.GIF" >
Essays by title :   A</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/caden_lucas.html">Accidents on the Information Superhighway: On-line Liability and Regulation</A>   by Stephanie E. Lucas and Marc L. <EM> Caden</EM>.       <I>Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/padgett.html">African Elephant, Africa, and CITES: The Next Step </A>   by Bill <EM> Padgett </EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I>   (note)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/bandt.txt">Against Fairness: A Brief Critical Look at Concepts Used to Analyse a Tax system</A>   by Adam<EM> Bandt</EM>.    The author examines from a Marxist perspective the criteria of equity, efficiency and simplicity commonly used to critique taxation systems. Contradictions arising from the use of these ideals are discussed by reference to the Australian tax system. By contrast with capitalist ideology, the author concludes that an ideal tax system should be revolutionary, empathic and democratic   <I>E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994</I>    
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/thomas1.html">Aldermen, Reasons and Judicial Review</A>   by Robert <EM> Thomas</EM>.    At present there is no general duty upon public authorities to provide reasons for their decisions. The courts have recently increased the situations in which reasons must be given. R v The Mayor and Commonalty and Citizens of the City of London ex parte Matson (transcript, 18th August 1995) is the latest in a line of cases where fairness has been employed to require reasons to be given. However, there is an inherent contradiction within the reasoning employed in such cases, which, if explicated, demonstrates the need for a general duty to give reasons.    <I>Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I>   (casenote)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/adams.pag">Amicus Brief in Opposition to Florida's Anti-Gay Constitutional Amendment</A>   by William E. <EM> Adams, Jr.</EM>.    This brief was filed in response to a proposed state constitutional amendment in Florida similar to those proposed in Colorado and Oregon prohibiting protection on the basis of sexual orientation, by specifying bases on which protection <I>could</I> be provided.  This brief successfully argued to the court that the amendment violated Florida statutory requirements requiring that its language and its title be clear and unambiguous in that "the only place where it is not made abundantly clear that this initiative is about the rights or lesbians and gay men is in the amendment itself and its ballot title and summary." (Decision reported at  632 So.2d 1018 (Florida 1994)).    <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/cox3.pag">Amicus brief: In re H.S.H-K, 193 Wis. 2d 649, 533 N.W.2d 419(1995) with introduction.</A>   by Barbara <EM> Cox</EM>.    This brief, with an introduction by Prof. Barbara Cox, was written by her and filed with the Wisconsin Supreme Court on behalf of the National Center for Lesbian Rights.  That case involved a custody and visitation claim filed by a non-biological parent of H.S.H-K, who had participated in the decision to have and raise the child with the child's biological parent.  The court granted the petition and in doing so, became the first state supreme court to recognize the visitation rights of a non-biological lesbian parent.    <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/thomas.pag">Amicus brief: In re Ry R.-Y.</A>   by <EM> National Center for Lesbian Rights, et al.</EM>.    This amicus brief, filed by the National Center for Lesbian Rights on behalf of the defendant argues that the decision of a New York trial court, <B>Thomas S. v. Robin Y.</B>, 599 N.Y.S.2d 377 (Fam. Ct. 1993) to deny the paternity petition of Thomas S., a known sperm donor and the biological father of Ry, a child born into a household of a lesbian couple, should be affirmed.  The appellate court held that, despite an oral agreement to the contrary, Thomas S.'s paternity petition should be granted. <B>Thomas S. v. Robin Y.</B>, 618 N.Y.S.2d 356 (App. Div. 1994).  The Court of Appeals, New York's highest court, stayed the appellate court's decision and granted certiorari.  The appeal was ultimately dismissed, however, when Thomas S. withdrew his paternity petition.     <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/coleman.pag">Analysis of the Opinion of the Attorney General of California on the Registration of Names of Family Associations by the Secretary of State</A>   by David F. Link and Thomas F. <EM> Coleman</EM>.    This article analyzes a recent attempt by gay and lesbian families in California to gain legal recognition by registering with the Secretary of State as unincorporated nonprofit associations as "family associations". Despite opposition, the Secretary of State of California refused to prohibit registration. The authors analyze the statutory language of the California Corporations Code relating to associational name registration and discusses the interpretations applied in light of the highly charged political atmosphere.    <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/hoey1.html">Analysis of The Police and Criminal Evidence Act, s.69 - Computer Generated Evidence</A>   by Amanda <EM> Hoey </EM>.    At present there are special rules governing the admissibility of computer-generated evidence in criminal proceedings. In this article the issues of when computer output will be considered direct evidence or hearsay and the reliability of computer-generated evidence are discussed. In conclusion the article attempts to ascertain whether these special rules for computer output are necessary and, if so, whether the conditions established by the statutory provisions are appropriate.     <I>Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI>An <A HREF="http://www-leland.stanford.edu/~tstanley/tjspaper/tstanley.paper.html">Analysis of the Rules of Contribution and No Contribution for Joint and Several Liability in Conspiracy Cases </A>   by Timothy James <EM> Stanley </EM>.    This paper examines deterrence and settlement effects of three rules that have been applied in joint and several liability conspiracy cases. These rules are the no contribution rule, the contribution with claim reduction rule and the contribution with settlement reduction rule.  It is shown that where conspirators have asymmetric information that the no contribution rule could lead to less deterrence than the contribution rules for all conspirators. The paper concludes that the contribution with claim reduction rule with liability allocated per capita or the no contribution rule should be applied to joint and several liability in conspiracy situations. The one rule that is disfavored is the contribution with settlement reduction rule. More importantly this paper encourages greater focus on whether the joint harm is caused by defendants acting in concert or independently.     <I> </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/bland.html">Analysis of the United Nations International Tribunal to Adjudicate War Crimes Committed in the Former Yugoslavia:  Parallels, Problems, Prospects</A>   by Mark A.<EM> Bland</EM>.        <I> Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   (Note)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Informatica/Post-1996/Post~1.htm">Anarchy, State, and the Internet: an Essay on Law-Making in Cyberspace</A>   by D.G. <EM> Post</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/post.html">Anarchy, State, and the Internet: An Essay on Law-Making in Cyberspace</A>   by David G. <EM> Post</EM>.    The legal rules that will govern cyberspace are yet to be clarified. Important as those rules will be, a prior question is "who will make and enforce those rules?" Professor Post examines various "controllers," or points from which rules can issue, ranging from technical network protocols, to private organizations like universities, to Congressional statutes. These controllers vary in their ability to enforce whatever rules they choose to adopt, depending on the existence of conflicting higher-level controllers, and on the possibility that those who are subject to the rules can change jurisdictions to seek a more favorable rule set.    <I>Journal of Online Law  </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/froomkin.htm">Anonymity and Its Enmities</A>   by A. Michael <EM> Froomkin</EM>.    Professor Froomkin analyzes the legal status of attempts to ban anonymity. Through a combination of public-key encryption and special "anonymous remailer" computers, messages can be sent over the net with a high degree of certainty that they cannot be traced to their originator. These techniques also make possible the creation of "pseudonymous" personalities. The Supreme Court in the McIntyre case recently struck down state prohibitions on the use of anonymity in the context of political leaflets. But such state laws have generally been very broadly drawn, and have been applied to political speech. The possibility remains that a narrowly drawn statute banning anonymous political speech, or one directed to non-political speech, might nevertheless be upheld.     <I>Journal of Online Law </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/myers.html">Apple v. Microsoft: Virtual Identity in the GUI Wars (Note)</A>   by Joseph <EM> Myers </EM>.       <I>Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/french.txt">Applying the Native Title Act 1993</A>   by Justice Robert<EM> French</EM>.    Outlines the common law of concepts of native title contained within the High Courts Mabo decision, the scope of the _Native Title Act_ and provides details of the operations and directions of the Native Title Tribunal.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/conway.htm">Are There New Complexities in Global Migration Systems of Consequence for the United States "Nation-State"?</A>   by Dennis<EM> Conway</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/stinger.html">Arizona v. Evans: Adapting the Exclusionary Rule to Advancing Computer Technology</A>   by C. Maureen <EM> Stinger</EM>.       <I>Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/stefan3.html">Article 224 of the Treaty of Rome and the Repercussions of Case C-120/94</A>   by Helen Xanthaki and Constantin<EM> Stefanou</EM>.    This article examines an almost forgotten, original Article of the Treaty of Rome, Article 224, in the light of the recent case of Commission v Greece (C-120/94). The article consists of two parts.  The first part looks at the ECJ's precedents, attempts an interpretation of Article 224 and then proceeds to apply the analysis on case C-120/94. The second part concentrates on the 'political' repercussions of the case which, because of its subject matter, have particular significance for the EU.  Depending on the ECJ's pending final decision it may herald a return to the Court's 'activism' or confirm the 'minimalist' trend of recent years.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns1.txt">Australian Ratification of International Labour Organisation Convention No. 169</A>   by Catherine J.<EM> Iorns</EM>.    The Convention accords little status to indigenous laws and values, and it is generally paternalistic.  However, adopting it will expand upon the rights of Australian Aborigines and may foster wider recognition of the rights of Indigenous Peoples worldwide   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2f.html">Automating Design Packages for Law</A>   by E.<EM> Wilson</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
