<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/C.GIF" >
Essays by title :   C</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/boyle.txt">Caveatable interests - the common lore distinguished</A>   by Sandra<EM> Boyle</EM>.    This paper argues for the removal of heresy in the interpretation of caveatable interests under the Western Australian Torrens System.  Simply, the determination of a caveatable interest should be more flexible, incorporating equitable rules.   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1g.html">CD-roms - A Law Librarian's Perspective </A>   by C. <EM> Cope</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1f.html">CD-roms in Legal Education </A>   by N. <EM> Nunn-Price</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/tessrtr2.html">Challenge of Immigration Policy in the New South Africa</A>   by Kevin <EM> Tessier</EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/schwartz.html">Challenge of Peremptory Challenges</A>   by Warren F and Edward P<EM> Schwartz</EM>.       <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/nash.html">Challenge of Trade Liberalization to Cultural Survival on the Southern Frontier of Mexico</A>   by June<EM> Nash</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk:70/00/ltc/publications/conferences/oxford/akobay.txt">Challenging the National Dream: Gender Persecution and Canadian Imigration Law</A>   by Audrey<EM> Kobayashi</EM>.       <I>Oxford Critical Legal Conference 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/zolberg.html">Changing Sovereignty Games and International Migration</A>   by Aristide R.<EM> Zolberg</EM>.    In this article, Professor Zolberg argues that today's immigration issues should be analyzed within their historical bases.  The author concludes that despite the recent development of borderless markets and communication infrastructures, much remains to be done to build a truly global community.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/morris3.html">Charity Investment in the UK: Some Contemporary Issues for the 1990s</A>   by Debra<EM> Morris</EM>.    The investment duties of charity trustees have been highlighted recently due to the termination of the investment function of the Official Custodian for Charities (who previously held investments worth about 1.25 billion for over 40,000 charities) together with the increased awareness of trustee responsibilities generally. In April 1995, the law relating to charity investment changed so that now charity trustees are less restricted in their investment decisions.  The Charity Commissioners have also issued a number of recent policy  statements concerned with investment powers. This paper examines these recent developments and argues for an even less restricted legal regime.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/dunn2.html">Charity law - a political scandal?</A>   by Alison <EM> Dunn</EM>.    The extent to which charities may pursue political activities is a contentious issue. Whilst Parliament has steadfastly refused to embrace political aims as charitable purposes, charities are nevertheless permitted to undertake a degree of political activity. The Charity Commission has updated its guidelines on the types of political activity and political campaigning that charities may pursue, and the penalties involved for breach. Whilst advice in this uncertain area is to be welcomed, the Charity Commission guidelines have limitations.    <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/maslen3.html">Child Soldiers, The Role of Children in Armed Conflicts", by G S Goodwin-Gill and I Cohn</A>   by Stuart<EM> Maslen</EM>.       <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   (book review)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/allen1.html">Children with Special Educational Needs in a Consumer-Driven Education System</A>   by Tom<EM> Allen</EM>.    This article looks at recent changes in the English educational provision which make it more difficult for parents to obtain a satisfactory education for children who have special needs, while at the same time expanding their legal right to the question the provision their children do receive. It examines the general trend to consumerism as the underlying philosophy of educational 'planning' and the statutory framework for protecting the position of special needs children.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/jameson.html">Citizen initiative in Florida: an analysis of Florida's constitutional initiative process, issues, and statutory intitiative alternatives </A>   by P. K. Jameson and Marsha <EM> Hosack </EM>.    This Article examines Florida's constitutional initiative process and describes the constitutional and statutory initiative processes in other states. It then discusses issues about Florida's current constitutional initiative process and addresses several bills introduced during the 1995 Regular Session to revise the current process. The Article concludes that Florida should develop and adopt an indirect statutory initiative procedure. It further concludes that in tandem with insituting a statutory process, Florida should revise the current constitutional initiative process to make it more difficult toamend the constitution.    <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/bookrev/1scott/default.htm">Colin D Long (Ed), "Telecommunications Law and Practise"  2nd Edition </A>   Reviewed by Colin <EM> Scott</EM>.       <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/valdes.pag">Coming Out and Stepping Up: Queer Legal Theory and Connectivity</A>   by Francisco <EM> Valdes</EM>.    In this article Francisco Valdes calls for the creation of Queer Legal theory based on the coalescence of a "sexual minority" over the past twenty-five years.  Prof. Valdes discusses the relationship of Queer Legal theory to Feminist Legal Theory and Critical Race Theory detailing the common "psycho-social isolation" of gays and lesbians, women and racial minorities. He encourages recognition of the common interests and goals of the three groups and urges each to be sensitive to the interrelationship, or "connectivity," among them.    <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/hart.html">Comments on "Changing Sovereignty Games and International Migration"</A>   by Jeffrey A.<EM> Hart</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1sweden/default.htm">Comments on the EC Data Protection Directive : The View from Sweden</A>   by Peter <EM> Seipel</EM>.       <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/luther1.html">Common Law" by M Arnheim (ed.)</A>   reviewed by Peter<EM> Luther</EM>.       <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   (book review)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/hodgson5.html">Comparative Dimension (or What do They Know of England, that only England Know?)</A>   by John <EM> Hodgson</EM>.    This article examines the provisional proposals in the ACLEC Consultation Paper on the initial stage of legal education which bear on the emphasis to be given to the study of European and Comparative law. The article attempts to analyse the practical implications of this approach. In particular the empirical evidence as to the expertise and resources available in this field is scrutinised. The thrust of the ERASMUS/SOCRATES programmes is considered, and attempts are made to indicate an academically appropriate but practical way forward.    <I>[1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/hansmann.html">Comparative Law and Economics of Private Trusts</A>   by Ugo Mattei and Henry<EM> Hansmann</EM>.       <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/birks1.html">Compulsory Subjects: Will the Seven Foundations ever Crumble?</A>   by Peter<EM> Birks</EM>.    In this comment the consequences for legal education of the joint announcement by the Law Society and the Council of Legal Education in January 1995 of the changes to the core requirements for qualifiying law degrees are examined.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3f.html">Computer Managed Teaching and Learning in Law</A>   by R.<EM> Jones</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/halbert.txt">Computer technology and legal discourse : the potential for modern communication technology to challenge legal discourses of authorship and property</A>   by Debora<EM> Halbert</EM>.       <I>E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/pritchar.txt">Constitutional Validity of the Commonwealth's Native Title Regime Confirmed</A>   by Sarah<EM> Pritchard</EM>.    Case comment on the recent Australian cases of The State of Western Australia v the Commonwealth; The Wororra Peoples v The Commonwealth; Teddy Biljabu v The Commonwealth   decided by the High Court of Australia   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   (case comment)
<HR>
<LI>" <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/cal/1maharg/">Contracts": An Introduction to the Skills of Legal Writing and Analysis</A>   by Paul <EM> Maharg</EM>.     <I>Contracts</I> is a computer program designed for first year undergraduates. The program addresses undergraduates' legal writing and problem-solving skills. <I>Contracts</I> calls on learning theories which support the view that such skills can be learned via computer-based learning. Despite the general opinion that legal practitioners will more and more be using computers to communicate, there have been few other attempts to date to help students learn basic legal writing skills on computer.     <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/hardy.html">Contracts, Copyright and Preemption in a Digital World </A>   by I. Trotter <EM> Hardy </EM>.       <I>Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/dine1.html">Corporate Governance, Cadbury and Friendly Societies</A>   by Professor Janet<EM> Dine</EM>.    The Cadbury Report upon corporate governance has inspired both the Friendly Societies Act 1992 and also a recently published Code of Practice by the Friendly Societies Commission.  Janet Dine sets out details of this Code and comments upon the significance of the new Cadbury-inspired regime for Friendly Societies.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2b.html">Cost of Computer Assisted Learning (CAL)</A>   by M.<EM> Young</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1ed.html">Courseware Consortium for Law</A>   by A.<EM> Paliwala</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/ormerod1.html">Criminal Liability for the Transmission of HIV</A>   by D.C. Ormerod and M.J. <EM> Gunn</EM>.    This article explores the issues arising when a person, knowing that he or she is anti-HIV positive, proceeds to engage in intimate sexual behaviour, and asks whether he or she is liable to criminal prosecution.  In the light of the Government's refusal to legislate in this area, the article considers the possible sanctions under existing criminal law, providing analysis of sections 23 and 24 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861. It reviews possible problems with the use of these sections, and concludes that they could be used successfully to prosecute this type of behaviour. Finally, consideration is given to proposed law reform.    <I>Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/collier2.html">Criminological Theory :  Context and Consequences", by J. Robert Lilly, Francis T. Cullen and Richard A. Ball</A>   reviewed by Richard<EM> Collier</EM>.       <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   book review
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/sclater4.html">Critical Approach to the White Paper on Divorce Reform</A>   by Shelley Day <EM> Sclater</EM>.    This paper discusses some of the issues raised by recent Government proposals for reform of the divorce law. It begins by considering the responses of professional bodies (the Law Society, the Solicitors' Family Law Association, and National Family Mediation) to the green consultation paper of December 1993. It is argued that the concerns voiced by lawyers have, in the main, not been addressed. It is suggested that a broader range of issues, including questions of justice and fairness, should be introduced into the debate, and that social scientific commentary has a valuable contribution to make in this regard.    <I>[1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/green.html">Cultural Identities and Global Political Economy from an Anthropological Vantage Point</A>   by Davydd J.<EM> Greenwood</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/simmonds.txt">Curbing Self-Dealing in Corporations: Australia's New Approach</A>   by Ralph<EM> Simmonds</EM>.    The traditional approach in countries like Australia has been to rely on the common law fiduciary duties, augmented by specific statutory requirements for particular sorts of transactions perceived to carry a high risk of abuse.  The latest in the line of these requirements is contained in _Corporations Law_, Part 3.2A.  It is distinguished by the breadth of its application, particularly in relation to transactions in corporate groups.   Its greatest novelty lies in its basic rule prohibiting the giving of financial benefits to related parties unless approval by a majority of disinterested shareholders is secured.   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I>   Legislation Note
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/bodansky.html">Customary (and not so Customary) International Environmental Law</A>   by Daniel <EM> Bodansky</EM>.    This article reevaluates the concept of customary international environmental law. Claims that these norms have the status of customary law reflect a conception of "customary law" that focuses on what states say, rather than what they do. The purported norms of customary environmental law represent community standards - they set the general terms of the debate about what actions are appropriate. Since this functions do not depend on a norm's legal status, debates about whether a norm is part of customary international law tend to be sterile. The author concludes that international lawyers should spend less time debating the legal status of environmental norms and more time working to make them more precise and effective.     <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1k.html">Cyberspace and the Law: Your Rights and Duties in the On-line World" by Gavino Morin & Edward A. Cavazos </A>   reviewed by A. <EM> Charlesworth </EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/jol/katsh.htm">Cybertime, Cyberspace and Cyberlaw</A>   by M. Ethan <EM> Katsh </EM>.    Professor Katsh pursues the relationship between time in cyberspace, or "cybertime" as he calls it, and legal doctrines. He speculates that many such doctrines are based explicitly or implicitly on time or our conception of time. He then asks whether the concept of "cybertime", with its accelerated pace, may not cause substantial disruption in these legal doctrines, a disruption not before noted or appreciated.    <I>Journal of Online Law  </I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
