<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   D</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/D.GIF" >
Essays by title :   D</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1eire/default.htm">Data Protection in the Republic of Ireland</A>   by Robert <EM> Clark</EM>.       <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Students/Marino1.html">Database Protection in the European Union</A>   by F. <EM> Marino</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/streib.pag">Death Penalty for Lesbians</A>   by Victor <EM> Streib</EM>.    In this piece Victor Streib looks at compilations of data on the effect of gender on the likelihood a person accused of a capital crime will be sentenced to death, and asks if a woman's lesbianism impacts the incidence of her being sentenced to death and finally executed.  Using 4 case studies of women who were sentenced to death in cases where their lesbianism played a role, Prof. Streib finds that a number of factors impact the equation. While lesbianism is not seen as a mitigating factor, it is often overshadowed by the extreme violence of the crime, and thus does not stand out as an aggravating factor.     <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/morris5.html">Death throes of the sick man: Webb v EMO Air Cargo (UK) Ltd (No 2) (Casenote)</A>   by Anne <EM> Morris </EM>.    Starting with the notion that the Sex Discrimination Act 1975 could not apply to pregnant women, the judges finally accepted that the Act could be construed to protect them from sexually discriminatory behaviour on the part of employers, but only by the clumsy mechanism of comparison with a sick man. Despite what seemed to be clear and definitive decisions from the European Court of Justice, the judges in the United Kingdom have persisted in the idea that comparison was necessary. Nowhere was the reluctance to promote equality of opportunity for pregnant workers more apparent than in the long, tortuous saga of Mrs Webb. Eight years after she announced her pregnancy and was sacked, we have a final decision, (The Times, 20 October 1995; other references in the text are from the transcript) subject only to the calculation of compensation.    <I>[1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part3.htm">December 1993 amendments to the Federal rules of civil procedure </A>   by Leslie M. <EM> Kelleher</EM>.       <I>Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/bridge4.html">Decisions of the European Court of Justice and their Constitutional Implications" by Aidan O'Neill</A>   reviewed by John <EM> Bridge</EM>.       <I>[1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/greenhouse.html">Democracy and Demography</A>   by Carol J.<EM> Greenhouse</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/thompson.html">Determining Appropriate Surface Water Quality Policies through a Law and Economics Theory of a Sanctionable Act</A>   by Dale B.<EM> Thompson</EM>.    In this paper, I examine surface water quality policies using a new pragmatic policy-analysis framework. This framework emphasizes institutional-transaction-costs which are normally forgotten or misanalyzed in typical cost-benefit analyses. These costs include the costs of initially enacting a policy,implementing it, and enforcing it. A performance-based policy instrument, nontradeable effluent limit permits, has much lower institutional- transaction-costs associated with it than does an incentive based instrument, effluent taxes. My framework allows these transaction costs to be properly considered in relation with other costs and benefits. I conclude that we should address policies to reduce nonpoint pollution at regional bodies like irrigation districts.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/marasi.txt">Development ideology perspective</A>   by Lakshman<EM> Marasinghe</EM>.    The article traces the legal history of Sri Lanka -- highlighting the assumptions relating to individual rights to property made in colonial law. The author then discusses the move away from adjudication by means of an adversarial system towards the establishment of conciliation boards for dispute resolution.   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Musy-1995/musy1.htm">Disclosure of Information in the Pre-contractual Bargaining</A>   by A.M. <EM> Musy</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/maxwell1.html">Discrimination against part-time workers</A>   by Patricia<EM> Maxwell</EM>.    This is set within the context of developments in Europe, including approaches taken in other European countries, and Britain's recent veto of the latest EU proposal for a Directive on atypical workers.  The use of the concept of indirect discrimination as a vehicle to secure rights for part-time workers is also discussed, but at the same time highlighting its limitations.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/platt.html">Dispelling the negative myths of managed care: an analysis of anti-managed care legislation and the quality of care  provided by health maintenance organizations </A>   by Lisa D. Stream and Bruce D. <EM> Platt </EM>.    The first part of this Article discusses managed care legislation. Specifically, it provides a summary of some of the last five years of Florida's legislative health care advancements incorporating managed care concepts. It then discusses some of the proposed legislation which targets HMOs and other managed care plans. The available literature indicates that the quality of care provided by HMOs is as good as, if not better than, the quality of care provided in a traditional fee-for-service setting. Legislation which would cripple managed care in the name of preserving quality is unnecessary and counterproductive.    <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mccallum.txt">Dispute Resolution Mechanisms in the Resolution of Comprehensive Aboriginal Claims:  Power Imbalance Between Aboriginal Claimants and Governments -- Negotiation</A>   by Andrea Gaye<EM> McCallum</EM>.    This article focuses on the manner in which negotiation has been, or may be, employed to resolve Aboriginal claims.  The process of negotiation is analysed and assessed in terms of the extent to which it facilitates cultural domination, and reinforces power imbalance between the parties. The author concludes by suggesting various means by which the negotiation process may be improved to redress elements of the power imbalance between the parties.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/ayres.html">Distinguishing Between Consensual and Nonconsensual Advantages of Liability Rules</A>   by Eric Talley and Ian<EM> Ayres</EM>.       <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/edlin.html">Do Guaranteed-Low-Price Policies Guarantee High Prices?  How Price Matching Challenges Antitrust</A>   by Aaron S.<EM> Edlin</EM>.    Price-matching policies can allow firms to break a competitive equilibrium by discriminating in price between informed and uninformed customers. The resulting high prices can persist even when there is entry to the industry, which implies that welfare losses may be much larger than under ordinary monopoly. This article suggests that price-matching policies may violate the price-discrimination laws and examines whether price matchers should be able to protect themselves with a "meeting competition" defense. The article concludes they should not have such a defense; studying price-matching policies forces one to acknowledge that meeting competition is not inherently competitive. The article also explores whether the vertical agreements between buyer and seller violate the Sherman Act.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/reuther.pag">Dorothy's friend goes to law school</A>   by Kevin <EM> Reuther</EM>.    The experiences of a gay student at Harvard Law School.   <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/iorns2.txt">Draft Declaration of the Rights of Indigneous Peoples</A>   by Catherine J.<EM> Iorns</EM>.    This article discusses the important provisions therein.  Suggestions are made for improvements that might be incorporated before it is adopted by the UN General Assembly   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/t.htm">Dressing up software interface protection: the application of *Two Pesos* to look-and-feel</A>   by Steven<EM> Shortgen</EM>.    This note presents the Supreme Court's *Two Pesos* decision and discusses that decision's implications for intellectual property lawyers. Finally, it provides closing comments on asserting trade dress protection for GUIs, and includes a model application based loosely upon the litigation between Apple, Inc. and Microsoft, Inc. Ultimately, this Note argues that GUIs as well as future creative interfaces deserve protection under trade dress doctrine in certain cases.   <I>Cornell LR November 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/swensen.txt">Drug Problems in Western Australia:  a review of non-criminal mechanisms ...</A>   by Greg<EM> Swensen</EM>.    Discussion of the shortcomings in the Western Australian system of notifying drug addicts. There is an examination of the practical considerations as well as the natural justice implications.   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
