<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   E</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/E.GIF" >
Essays by title :   E</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/loundy.txt">E-Law 2.0 :  Computer Information Systems Law and System Operator Liability Revisited</A>   by David J<EM> Loundy</EM>.    The article examines the current regulatory structure of Cyberspace in the United States.  The article also discusses the liability of the operators/administrators of these systems  ("Sysops") in this context, and includes an examination of the relevant legislation.  The author outlines the difficulties involved in applying current regulatory standards to Cyberspace in general, and contends that the creators of the law need to have an adequate understanding of the technology relevant to computer systems if the laws are to effectively regulate such a rapidly changing area as this   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://sulaw.law.su.OZ.AU:70/00/Law%20Documents/Collection%20of%20various%20Laws%20%28mainly%20from%20U.S.%29/tempest.law">Eavesdropping On the Electromagnetic Emanations of Digital Equipment:  The Laws of Canada, England and the United States</A>   by Christopher<EM> Seline</EM>.    This note explores the legal status of a surveillance technology ruefully known as TEMPEST. Using TEMPEST technology the information in any digital device may be intercepted and reconstructed into useful intelligence without the operative ever having to come near his target. The technology is especially useful in the interception of information stored in digital computers or displayed on computer terminals.   <I> </I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/kosten2">EC Data Protection Directive 1995: An Analysis</A>   by Chris Pounder and Freddy <EM> Kosten</EM>.       <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Pardolesi-1995/pardo.html">Economic Analysis of Contract Law: Some Insights</A>   by R. <EM> Pardolesi</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI>An <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Students/neg.html">Economic Analysis of Liability Rules</A>   by A. <EM> Rossato</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Torts/Monateri-1995/ecolos.html">Economic Losses in Italy</A>   by P.G. <EM> Monateri</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/posner.html">Economic Psychology of the Old</A>   by Richard A.<EM> Posner</EM>.    Economists usually take values, preferences and attitudes as givens and  consider how a rational actor can maximize his utility by the choices he makes based on those givens. This paper takes a different tack and considers  the extent to which the psychology of the old might fruitfully be modelled as a consequence rather than foundation of rational choice. The paper does  not argue that old people always or even often make conscious choices; only  that certain choices, conscious or unconscious, appear to be rational in the  sense of utility-maximizing once the fundamental attributes of being old are  understood.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506002.abs">Economics of Agency Law and Contract Formation</A>   <EM> Rasmusen</EM>.    This article addresses issues that arise in agency law when agents make contracts on behalf of principals. The main issue is whether the principal should be bound when the agent makes a contract with some third party on his behalf which the principal would immediately wish to disavow. The resulting tradeoffs resemble those in tort law, so the least-cost-avoider principle is useful for deciding when contracts are valid and may be the underlying logic behind a number of different legal doctrines applied to agency cases. In particular, an efficiency explanation can be found for the undisclosed principal rule.     <I> </I>   (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecipa/archive/UT-ECIPA-MTURNER-95-02.html">Economics without Free-disposal: Quota-induced Discarding in Heterogenous Fisheries </A>   by Matthew A. <EM> Turner </EM>.    Individual quota (IQ) programs are a promising and increasingly common means of regulating fisheries. The responses of profit maximizing fishers to different IQ programs are analysed. This analysis shows first that the most common types of individual quota program can induce discarding, and second that of all possible individual quota programs, only those that regulate the value of harvest never induce discarding. Since discarded fish have a high mortality rate, "value-based" individual quota programs are superior to their more conventional counterparts in that they waste fewer fish. These results are driven by the fact that the fishing technology examined here does not satisfy a "free-disposal" assumption. Since this free disposal assumption is ubiquitous in production theory, and not obviously true, the framework developed herein is useful for analyzing a broad class of problems involving joint production.     <I> </I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/section3.html">Editorial --  Legal Education</A>   by Fiona<EM> Cownie</EM>.       <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-2d.htm">Electric Lawyer: From Quill to Computer</A>   by D. Wall and K.<EM> Reid</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.2</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1j.html">Electronic Banking and the Law" (2nd Ed.) By Anu Anora</A>   reviewed by A. <EM> Charlesworth </EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/wheater.txt">Electronic Classroom : a Personal Account of Learning the Law by Email</A>   by Murray<EM> Wheater</EM>.    A student's personal account of the initial attempt to teach a law course with a computer network as a tool of teaching. This is with particular emphasis on the use of information technology.  This leads to personal reflection on the benefits of structuring the course in such a way.   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/oconnell.html">Enforcement and the Success of International Environmental Law</A>   by Mary Ellen <EM> O'Connell</EM>.    Professor O'Connell argues that international law is generally obeyed. Its enforcement is based primarily on compliance, not enforcement. Accordingly, the author argues against using international enforcement mechanisms to enforce international environmental law. Instead, she posits that domestic courts should be used; however, certain obstacles, such as sovereign immunity, the doctrine of standing, and the principle of forum non conveniens, must be overcome. She argues that it may be possible to overcome many of these court-made obstacles to enforcing international law through domestic courts.    <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/bernard5.html">Enforcing EC Law" by Josephine Steiner </A>   reviewed by Nicolas <EM> Bernard</EM>.       <I>[1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/drennen.html">Environmental Diplomacy: Negotiating More Effective Global Agreements" by Lawrence E. Susskind</A>   reviewed by Thomas E.<EM> Drennen</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   (book review)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/atik.html">Environmental Standards Within NAFTA: Difference by Design and the Retreat from Harmonization</A>   by Jeffery <EM> Atik</EM>.    Professor Atik argues that NAFTA, in legitimating regulatory differences among the NAFTA parties, represents a repudiation of standard harmonization. Both high- standard and low-standard parties may prefer the maintenance of differentials. While there may be efficiency gains, other interests, including environmental quality, may well be compromised. However, despite NAFTA's maintenance of divergent standards, the agreement does allow for the joint determination of environmental standards, and institutions established by NAFTA are available to both monitor and adjust standards (especially Mexico's) to appropriate levels.    <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/voegele.htm">EPA's Problematic Enforcement policy for the RCRA Section3004(j) Storage Prohibition as Applied to Mixed Wastes: Edison Electric Institute v. EPA</A>   by George A. <EM> Voegele, Jr.</EM>.       <I>Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I>   (Casenote)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/morris4.html">Equal Helpings: Ratcliffe and others v North Yorkshire County Council</A>   by Anne<EM> Morris</EM>.    Women workers, particularly part-timers, have seen significant successes in their pursuit of sex equality, and there are signs that the English courts are matching - even outdoing - the European Court in matters connected with employment rights and wages (see R v Secretary of State for Employment ex parte EOC ([1994] 1 All ER 910 HL, and R v Secretary of State ex parte Seymour-Smith CA (unreported). The Ratcliffe decision in the House of Lords ([1995] IRLR 439) has ramifications not only for equal pay generally but also for the policy of compulsory competitive tendering.    <I>Web JCLI [1995] 4</I>   (Casenote)
<HR>
<LI>A (Personal) <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/cox.pag">Essay on Same-Sex Marriage</A>   by Barbara J. <EM> Cox</EM>.    In this article Barbara Cox examines the institution of marriage in the gay and lesbian community from a personal perspective.  Prof. Cox reviews recent articles in the gay and lesbian literature arguing both for and against marriage as a political goal for homosexuals.  She then relates experiences arising out of her marriage to her partner, Peg.  The author advocates same-sex unions as a way to radically restructure the institution of marriage while challenging heterosexual assumptions about gay and lesbian love.    <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 1 (1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/belohlav.html">Ethical Issues of Expert Systems</A>   by David Drehmer, Louis Raho, and Jim <EM> Belohlav</EM>.    This study examines ethical considerations related to one of the more recent information technologies, the expert system. Specifically, the study examines the perceptions of 499 computer professionals with respect to contribution and ownership issues arising from expert system usage within organizations. The results indicate that no uniform ethical perspective yet dominates the perceptions of the respondents in assessing expert system applications. Unless ethical differences are resolved, the eventual repercussion will be increasing individual and organizational conflict as greater numbers of expert systems are developed and become a part of organizational operations.     <I>The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1 * No. 2 *</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/hand.html">Ethics of Handwriting Analysis in Pre-Employment Screening</A>   by Daryl <EM> Koehn</EM>.       <I>The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1 * No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/profwms.html">European and U.S. Perspectives on Civic Republicanism</A>   by David<EM> Williams</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/davey.html">European Integration: Reflections on Its Limits and Effects</A>   by William J.<EM> Davey</EM>.    I will first give an overview of this process and consider the factors that the European experience in "regionalization" suggests may limit economic and other forms of integration at the global level. I will then speculate on how the integration of markets in Europe will change European trade policies and on how those changes might affect the United States.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/hegarty2.html">Examining Equality: The Fair Employment Act (NI) 1989 and Its Review</A>   by Angela<EM> Hegarty</EM>.    The Act is currently the subject of a government sponsored review, a review which is bound to focus on the many criticisms levelled at the Act in its five years of operation. This article examines the background to the legislation and the issues which relate to its operation.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No.  2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/stone3.html">Exclusion of Evidence under Section 78 of the Police and Criminal Evidence Act: Practice and Principles</A>   by Richard<EM> Stone</EM>.    Section 78 of PACE gives the courts a discretion to exclude from a criminal trial evidence which has been obtained unfairly.   This article is an attempt to analyse the principles which the courts use.  It trying to identify the factors which the judges regard as relevant to this discretion.  Secondly, it examines the possible policies which might underlie a discretion to exclude.  It then attempts to match the practice to the policies, and concludes that fairness as fair play is the dominant policy. The conclusion considers how the changes in the rights of the suspect (in particular the right to remain silent) introduced by the Criminal Justice Act 1994 are likely to impact on the operation of s 78.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1e.html">Executive Training </A>   by N.<EM> McDonnell</EM>.    With all the hype about the information age, it is not surprising that lawyers and other professionals feel that they should learn about computers. But how? This article presents one successful approach at the University of Waikato, NZ.    <I>Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>An <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1b.html">Experiment with Electronic Law Tutorials </A>   by R. Widdison and F. <EM> Pritchard </EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/ranson.txt">Expert Evidence"  by Freckleton and Selby</A>   reviewed by David L<EM> Ranson</EM>.       <I>E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I>   (book review)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/webb2.html">Extending the Theory-Practice Spiral: Action Research as a Mechanism for crossing the Academic/Professional Divide</A>   by Julian<EM> Webb</EM>.    Current theory and practice in legal education is increasingly emphasising the need to develop in students the capacity for 'reflective practice' or 'humane professionalism'. This paper argues that the logic of humane professionalism has yet to be carried through to the later, continuing, stages of English legal education. It suggests that the law schools should play a significant part in this development by fostering an alternative, research-based, paradigm for continuing professional development. The vehicle proposed for this is 'action research', a hermeneutic and practice-based research method, which shares many of its epistemological assumptions with the experiential methods of clinical legal education. The paper concludes by analysing the main strengths and weaknesses of action research and offers a preliminary assessment of its capacity to contribute both to practitioners' self-knowledge of their practices and to academic understanding of the 'legal world'.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="/TITLES/A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Q.HTM">Q</A> |  <A HREF="/TITLES/R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Z.HTM">Z</A> 
