<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   F</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/F.GIF" >
Essays by title :   F</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/gerencse.html">Family mediation: screening for domestic abuse</A>   by Alison E. <EM> Gerencser</EM>.    This Article proposes that all legislatures mandating family mediation allow exemption from mediation when participant screeners determine that, because of the level of domestic abuse, mediation is inappropriate. Next, this Article argues that legislatures also must mandate that all participants screen for domestic violence. The Article concludes by discussing the multi-tiered screening process and the roles of the various participants in screening for domestic abuse.   <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/lind2.html">Family Redefinition under Part III of the Family Law Bill 1996</A>   by Craig Lind and Anne <EM> Barlow</EM>.    We assess the effects of Part III of the Family Law Bill 1996 on unmarried couples in domestic violence law, and on the jurisprudential scope of family law itself. We begin by noting the erosion of the dominance of the traditional married family. Then we consider the equivocal and, consequently, incohesive legal response to this social diversification. We examine the adequacy of the new remedies available to expanded categories of victims of family violence. We conclude that the Bill significantly improves current law, but that by creating three tiers of legal regulation, it inappropriately complicates the resolution of comparable disputes. The ideological importance of the married state has prevented pragmatic and coherent reform.    <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/iorns3.txt">Feminist Looks at Ronald Dworkin's Theory of Equality</A>   by Catherine J.<EM> Iorns</EM>.    This piece is a 'work in progress' dealing Dworkin's theory of equality and its related social vision from a feminist perspective.  A notable substantive problem is the theory's reliance on a questionable public/private distinction.  The definition of equality fails to address the reality of the oppression of women in the real world. The author criticises the central freedom/equality dichotomy.   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 1 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/wolfson.pag">Fighting to Win and Keep the Freedom to Marry: The Legal, Political, and Cultural Challenges Ahead </A>   by Evan <EM> Wolfson</EM>.    In this series of documents Mr. Wolfson describes Lambda's work in the area of marriage rights and provides information necessary for anyone to help promote equal marriage rights for gays and lesbians including a briefing on the legal status of the case and the tasks ahead, a series of questions and answers about marrage and gay people and finally a series of documents designed to help gays and lesbians in all states gain legal recognition of Hawaii marriages, assuming a victorious conclusion of the litigation there.     <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/lafferty.html">Florida's capital sentencing jury override: whom should we trust to make the ultimate ethical judgment?</A>   by Latour Rey <EM> Lafferty</EM>.    This article examines Florida's trifurcated capital sentencing scheme, specifically the jury override provision, from its origin to the present. It identifies and analyzes several criticisms of Florida's jury override provision, and examines the potential impact of Florida Committee Substitute for House Bill 1319, which Governor Chiles vetoed on June 14, 1995. Finally, this Article concludes that the Governor's veto was appropriate because Florida's jury override provision represents a valuable balance between the judge and the jury.     <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/larson.html">Florida's new partnership law: the revised uniform partnership act and limited liability partnerships</A>   by John <EM> W. Larson </EM>.    After eighty years of nearly uniform and virtually unchanged partnership law, the recent passage of these two laws has ushered in a truly new era of partnership jurisprudence, both in the United States and in Florida. This Article will explain the major changes in partnership law wrought by the Revised Florida Act, identify the Florida nonuniform provisions, and consider the meaning and significance of Florida's limited liability partnership legislation.     <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/lazos.html">Florida's property rights act: a political quick fix results in a mixed bag of tricks</A>   by Sylvia R. Lazos <EM> Vargas </EM>.    This Article reviews the political climate that made passage of the 1995 Florida Property Rights Act possible. It articulates an interpretive framework for the Act, briefly describes the law, and applies that framework to key issues posed by the Act. It explains how the settlement order mechanism is a type of decentralized decisionmaking and explores why decentralized decisionmaking is becoming a trend in regulatory reform. It also examines how information asymmetry, transaction costs, perceived risks, and other factors could affect the strategic behavior of property owners and agencies, thereby skewing incentives in the settlement order process. Finally, it suggests reforms that need to be considered in order to avoid results not intended by the Act.    <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/lazer.html">Flow of International Water Law: The International Law Commission's Law of the Non-Navigational Uses of International Watercourses</A>   by David J.<EM> Lazerwitz</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   (Note)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/mbecker.pag">Foreword: Becoming Visible</A>   by Mary <EM> Becker</EM>.    In this introduction to the Symposium, Prof. Becker describes the subsequent articles and gives her perspective on the difficult position of gays and lesbians in the legal academy.   <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/woodbury.txt">Freedom of Information Laws Affect the Autonomy of American Universities</A>   by Marsha<EM> Woodbury</EM>.    The author recognises the tension between the need to maintain public trust through accountabiity and the desire to foster academic freedom, efficiency and to preserve privacy. She argues that universities should become more open with operations such as presidential/chancellor searches, crime statistics and peer review.  Disclosure and openness should be achieved voluntarily, thus avoiding the need for legal intervention or enforcement of change. Guidelines recently announced by President Clinton and Attorney-General Janet Remo which emphasize a presumption of disclosure are recommended.   <I>E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/issue1/1abdul/">From Academic Tombstones to Living Bazaars - The Changing Shape of Law Reviews</A>   by Adbul <EM> Paliwala</EM>.    Electronic law journals are likely to be successful because they meet a need, the resolution of a crisis in academic journal publishing which cannot fulfill the needs of a fast changing legal information environment. This requires electronic law journals and reviews which promote living intellectual discourse through uptodate and interactive information. However, this requires the overcoming of a number of obstacles, and in particular it is necessary to promote changes in academic legal culture which make writing and reading electronic journals an acceptable activity.     <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/kaplow2.html">Fundamental Objection to Tax Equity Norms: A Call for Utilitarianism Taxation</A>   by Louis<EM> Kaplow</EM>.    Anti-utilitarian norms often are used in assessing tax systems. Two motivations support this practice. First, many believe utilitarianism to be insufficiently egalitarian. Second, utilitarianism does not give independent weight to other equitable principles, notably concerns that reforms may violate horizontal equity or result in rank reversals in the income distribution. This investigation suggests that a policy maker who believes in the Pareto principle -- that any reform preferred by everyone should be adopted -- cannot consistently adhere to any of these anti-utilitarian sentiments. Moreover, the affirmative case for utilitarian tax policy assessment is stronger than is generally appreciated.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="/TITLES/A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Q.HTM">Q</A> |  <A HREF="/TITLES/R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Z.HTM">Z</A> 
