<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   G</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/G.GIF" >
Essays by title :   G</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/burton.html">Gay Marriage - A Modern Proposal:  Applying Baehr v.  Lewin to the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights</A>   by Anne M. <EM> Burton</EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   (Note)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/reynolds.htm">German Recycling Experiment and Its Lesons for United States Policy</A>   by Steven P. <EM> Reynolds</EM>.       <I>Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/barber.html">Global Democracy or Global Law: Which Comes First?</A>   by Benjamin R.<EM> Barber</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/cate.html">Global Information Policymaking and Domestic Law</A>   by Fred<EM> Cate</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/delbruck.html">Global Migration -- Immigration -- Multiethnicity: Challenges to the Concept of the Nation-State</A>   by Jost<EM> Delbrck</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/delusign.html">Global Migration and European Integration</A>   by Guy<EM> De Lusignan</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/aman.html">Global Perspective on Current Regulatory Reform: Rejection, Relocation, or Reinvention</A>   by Alfred C<EM> Aman, Jr</EM>.    This article addresses recent U.S. administrations' attempts at regulatory reform and notes that as far as the actual reforms are concerned, there are more similarities over time than differences. The globalization of politics and markets and manufacturing, in particular, has helped create global political economic forces that militate in favor of various forms of deregulation and privatization not only in the United States, but in other western democracies as well. Firms are increasingly free to choose where to locate plants and employ labor. He considers the Reagan, Bush, and Clinton administrations' market-oriented regulatory reforms. He notes some important differences among these administrations, however, and argues that reformers who advocate market approaches as a means to collective ends, rather than as ends in themselves, are likely to be more receptive to the development of new global legal regimes.   <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/shapiro.html">Globalization of Law</A>   by Martin<EM> Shapiro</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/delbruck.html">Globalization of Law, Politics, and Markets Implications for Domestic Law: A European Perspective</A>   by Jost<EM> Delbrck</EM>.    Professor Delbrck argues that the modern form of the State should be based on the concept of the "Open Republic" -- a constitutional government involving the democratic participation of all citizens and a "marketplace of ideas."   He focuses on a republic geared in nature and character toward an "openness" to accepting and assimilating citizens of different ethnic, religious, or cultural backgrounds, with equal rights for those diverse citizens.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/cav.html">Globalization of Markets and Its Impact on Domestic Institutions</A>   by S. Tamer<EM> Cavusgil</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/lower1.html">Going Dutch? Who foots the bill in section 459 petitions</A>   by Michael<EM> Lower</EM>.    Whether or not the company can play, and fund out of corporate assets, an active role in section 459 proceedings was considered in Re a Company (No 001126 of 1992) and Re Milgate Developments Limited. The latter decision also considers whether a petitioner can obtain an injunction to prevent a company from playing an active part in section 459 proceedings.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   (casenote)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/james2.html">Good Character Directions and Blemished Defendants</A>   by Jennifer <EM> James</EM>.    Since thedecision which clarified the direction to be given to a jury in respect of an accused with a good character, the issue of who possesses such a character has become highly relevant. This article provides a brief introduction to good character evidence before concentrating on the blemished defendant whose record is not above reproach. Three categories of blemished defendants are considered and the cases analyzed with some suggestions for rationalization of the principles applicable.     <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Torts/Caranta-1996/Frank.htm">Governmental Liability after Francovich</A>   by R. <EM> Caranta</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/gallaghe.html">Great Lakes Water Quality Initiative: National Standards Governing a Binational Resource; A Call for International Rulemaking </A>   by Sean P. <EM> Gallagher </EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I>   (note)
<HR>
<LI>The "<A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/sands.html">Greening" of International Law Emerging Principles and Rules</A>   by Philippe<EM> Sands</EM>.    The article is outlines some of the more controversial (from a U.S. perspective) international legal issues which have arisen in recent years, including in particular the global instruments adopted at the United Nations Conference on Environment and Development  (UNCED), held at Rio de Janeiro in June 1992, as well as the regional developments reflecting the efforts of the EC Member States in their attempt to "green" the EEC Treaty.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="/TITLES/A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Q.HTM">Q</A> |  <A HREF="/TITLES/R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Z.HTM">Z</A> 
