<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   H</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/H.GIF" >
Essays by title :   H</H1>
<UL>

<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/todd.html">Hague Convention on the Civil Aspects of International Child Abduction: Are the Convention's Goals Being Achieved? </A>   by Julia A. <EM> Todd </EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I>   (note)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/henham1.html">Harm, Sentence Severity and Serious Motoring Offenders</A>   by Ralph <EM> Henham</EM>.    This note delineates the difficulties inherent in emphasising risk assessment for the purpose of determining the quality of driving in serious motoring offences. It is argued that the current substantive principles militate against subjective consideration of risk assessment which are relevant at the sentencing stage. It is submitted that penalty levels and sentencing principles for serious motoring offences would be more appropriately based upon harm assessment.    <I>Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/hein3.html">Harmonised Global Interchange - UNCITRAL's Draft Model Law for Electronic Data Interchange</A>   by Gregor<EM> Heinrich</EM>.    Traditionally, companies have always conducted and documented a large part of their business on paper. Paper transactions went along with well-developed mechanisms and legal concepts for proving origin, preventing repudiation and maintaining confidentiality. Now, this paper-based tradition is increasingly being abandoned in favour of 'electronic data interchange' (EDI). However, it is generally accepted that electronic exchange of trade data between companies, across business branches and even across borders is ultimately inconceivable without a high degree of standardisation.  A recent initiative by the United Nations Commission on International Trade Law (UNCITRAL) is now trying to fill this gap by creating a set of rules that aim at establishing a global legal framework for EDI.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/lott.html">Have Changing Liability Rules Compensated Workers Twice for Occupational Hazards?: Earnings Premiums and Cancer Risks</A>   by Richard L. Manning and John R.<EM> Lott</EM>.    During the last couple of decades, courts have intervened in employment relationships by allowing employees to circumvent workers' compensation liability restrictions, and gain compensation for long term illnesses  through tort cases. Recent papers point to firms divesting themselves of  operations whose employees handled dangerous substances as firms protecting themselves from these new liabilities. Supposedly, these actions prevent their workers from being justly compensated. We show that the central legal  premise behind this argument is wrong. Firms cannot expose workers to  hazards and then eliminate this liability by divesting or shutting down the hazardous operation. This paper also shows that workers were already being well compensated for carcinogenic exposures even before the courts started allowing workers to collect large damages for occupational illnesses.  Instituting the new liability rules also coincided with a large drop in earnings premiums.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/chiles.html">Health care reform in Florida: promoting improved access, cost, and quality</A>   by Lawton <EM> Chiles </EM>.       <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/stout.html">Heterogeneous Expectations Model of Speculation and Speculative Bubbles</A>   by Lynn A.<EM> Stout</EM>.    Economists disagree over the proper definition of the word "speculation" as well as over its effects on the welfare of speculators and society as a whole. Although conventional theories of risk-hedging, information arbitrage, and liquidity dealing certainly explain some apparently speculative transactions, this paper examines a fourth, and relatively neglected, approach that focuses on heterogeneous expectations and uncertainty as a cause of speculative trading. The paper explores the value of the HE approach by examining the implications of the HE model for three issues that have troubled economic theory: the proper definition of "speculation", the causes and nature of asset price bubbles, and the normative significance of speculative trading. In each case, the HE model proves of value in understanding speculative phenomena.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/connolly1.html">How an ECJ Decision on Equal Pay May Affect British Indirect Discrimation Law</A>   by Michael <EM> Connolly</EM>.    This note will bring into focus one element of Britain's indirect discrimination legislation: the need for the alleged discriminator to have applied a requirement or condition to the claimant. The standing of the Court of Appeal's judgement in Perera v Civil Service Commission (No 2) [1983] ICR 428 on this element will be examined in light of the decision of the European Court of Justice in Enderby v Frenchay Health Authority [1994] ICR 112, a case on equal pay.    <I>Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2j.html">How can learning technologies improve learning ?</A>   by D.<EM> Laurillard</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
