<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   I</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/I.GIF" >
Essays by title :   I</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9503/9503001.abs">Identifying Participants in a Price-fixing Conspiracy: Output and Market Share Tests Reexamined </A>   by Mehmet E. <EM> Karaaslan</EM>.    If there is a cartel agreement among a subset of firms in an industry, it should be predicted that all firms in that industry will increase prices. According to the output test and its market share variant if the output or the market share of the firm that claims to be innocent in the collusive activity rises in response to the price increase, that firm's claim should be accepted as true. Using a collusive variant of the dominant firm model, this paper shows that these are not robust tests to reveal innocence or guilt. This paper also shows that a market share test can not be used to prove a dominant firm's intent for predatory pricing     <I> </I>   (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/tessrnot.html">Immigration Crisis in Federalism: A Comparison of the United States and Canada</A>   by Kevin <EM> Tessier</EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/tessrtr1.html">Immigration Law in the Russian Federation</A>   by Kevin <EM> Tessier</EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/garkawe.txt">Impact of the Doctrine of Cultural Relativism on the Australian Legal System, The</A>   by Sam<EM> Garkawe</EM>.    This article commences with a discussion of the doctrine of cultural relativism and its validity. In relation to immigrant practices and customs, the doctrine does not deny the incorporation of international human rights standards into Australian law, but calls for a sensitive and culturally aware approach to the question of prohibition of these practices. However, the author concludes that the doctrine does make out a case for denying the applicability of international human rights standards to aboriginal practices and customs.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1dutch/default.htm">Impact of the EC Data Protection Directive on Dutch Data Protection Law</A>   by J P <EM> Bergfeld</EM>.       <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/1danish/default.htm">Implementation of the European Data Protection Directive : The View from Denmark</A>   by Peter <EM> Blume</EM>.       <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/kaye3.html">Implementing An EC Directive on Unfair Terms</A>   by Tim <EM> Kaye</EM>.    This article considers the substantive effect of the Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1994, and argues that despite their apparent commencement date of 1st July 1995 consumers have been able to claim the benefit of the protection afforded by the Regulations on the grounds that the Minister's specification of 1st July 1995 as the effective date of implementation is ultra vires.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/kamien.txt">Implementing Self-Government- An Examination of the Aboriginal Communities Act (Western Australia)</A>   by T.<EM> Kamien</EM>.    This report examines the Aboriginal Communities Act in the context of the right to self-government given by article 31 of the Draft Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples.  The report criticises the Act in that although it has found some acceptance with Aboriginal people, it has an assimilationist focus, in some cases increasing powerlessness felt by Aboriginal people.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/lo.html">Improving Corporate Governance: Lessons from the European Community</A>   by Benjamin T.<EM> Lo</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   (note)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/bradley.html">In Defense of Abolishing Chapter 11</A>   by Michael Rosenzweig and Michael<EM> Bradley</EM>.    In this paper we have responded to those who have criticized our call for repeal of Chapter 11.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/shelton.html">In search of the lost amendment: challenging federal firearms regulation through the state's right interpretation of the second amendment</A>   by Gregory L. <EM> Shelton</EM>.    This Comment embraces the individual rights interpretation of the Second Amendment which holds that the Second Amendment grants to the citizen the right to keep and bear arms, a right that now flounders between the Scylla of state police and militia powers and the Charybdis of federal regulation. This Comment argues, however, that federal firearms regulation is unconstitutional whether Second Amendment rights are interpreted as belonging to the individual or to the states. The heart of this Comment, thus, proposes and explores constitutional challenges to federal firearms regulation.   <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu:80/~jolt/v2i1/sergienko.html">Incrimination and Cryptographic Keys</A>   by Greg S. <EM> Sergienko</EM>.       <I>Richmond Journal of Law and Technology Volume II / Winter 1996 / Issue 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/devarenn.txt">Indigenous Peoples and Language</A>   by Fernand<EM> De Varennes</EM>.    This article explores the entitlement of indigenous peoples to preferential treatment in linguistic affairs.  This is due not to their position as a minority, but to the acknowledgement in international law, as well as in some national jurisdictions, that indigenous peoples occupy a unique political and legal niche, with corresponding privileges not necessarily available to others.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/todd4.html">Inferring share of interest in home: Midland Bank v Cooke (Casenote)</A>   by Paul Todd and Nicola <EM> Glover</EM>.    In Midland Bank v Cooke, CA, 7 July 1995, the Court of Appeal held that Mrs Cooke was entitled to a half share in the matrimonial home, binding on a third party mortgagee, although this was not justified by her direct contribution to the purchase price, and there had been no express discussions between the parties. In Springette v Defoe (1992) 24 HLR 552, [1992] 2 FCR 561, the Court of Appeal had held that the absence of express discussions precluded any claim to apportion shares otherwise than in proportion to contributions to the purchase price, but Waite LJ in Midland Bank v Cooke took the view that the lack of discussions or express agreement did not preclude the court from inferring an agreement on general equitable principles.    <I>[1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1b.html">Information Systems and Regulatory Management</A>   by J.<EM> Bing</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/abbey5.html">Information Technology and the Legal Practice Course</A>   by Robert M <EM> Abbey</EM>.    This article considers four topics. First, it considers the nature of the legal practice course ("LPC") in the context of its stated aims and information technology ("IT"). Secondly, it seeks to review that context in the light of the forms of IT currently used in the legal profession. Thirdly, it reports the results of a survey of the provision of IT within existing legal practice courses. Finally the article concludes with an analysis of the use of IT within one specific LPC and makes some general recommendations.    <I>[1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/zoller.html">Institutional Aspects of International Governance</A>   by Elisabeth <EM> Zoller</EM>.    Professor Zoller argues that the international community is not really a community at all, but several "intertangled communities" with common interests. Common interests among nation states and priority setting are the two prerequisites necessary for international governance. Although power is decentralized in international governance, it can still be exercised collectively. She concludes by suggesting that the shortcomings of global regulation, especially with respect to environmental issues, can be addressed most effectively by the institutional aspects of international governance. To that end, the success of international governance, in terms of international environmental protection, depends upon the leadership exerted by the "great powers," specifically the United States.     <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/kantor.html">Insurance Rationing and the Origins of Workers' Compensation</A>   by Shawn Everett Kantor and Price V<EM> Fishback</EM>.    A central question concerning the economic motivation for the adoption of workers' compensation is the extent to which workers had access to their desired levels of private accident insurance around the turn of the century. We develop a theoretical model that suggests that workers' compensation should have caused a reduction in households' precautionary saving. Our empirical test is based on a sample of over 7000 households surveyed for the 1917-1919 Bureau of Labor Statistics Cost-of-Living study. Regression analysis suggests that households tended to save less, holding all else constant, if their states had workers' compensation in force. This finding, in concert with qualitative information about the insurance industry, provide some evidence that insurance companies were unable to effectively offer workplace accident insurance to a wide range of workers.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3e.html">Interactive video in legal education and practice</A>   by K.Vaughan and M.<EM> Hibbs</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/danish.html">International Environmental Law and the &quot;Bottom-Up&quot; Approach:  A Review of the Desertification Convention</A>   by Kyle W. <EM> Danish</EM>.    Mr. Danish analyzes the Desertification Convention of 1995, discussing both the Convention's efforts to address the environmental degradation and the Convention's impact on international notions of the state. This Convention employs a "bottom-up" approach; it focuses on local developmental issues and the marginalized peoples living in the threatened areas. It provides increased international recognition for non-governmental organizations and local land users. The article presents an overview of the Convention and analysis based on international environmental legal norms.    <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/chapman.html">International Law, Industrial Location, and Pollution</A>   by Duane Chapman, Vivek Suri and Jean <EM> Agras </EM>.    The dominant position of economists on trade and environment is that increasing trade raises living standards, which provide the economic basis for reduced pollution. The paper presents a very different perspective. In summary, on a global basis, the international economy is characterized by increasing trade and world economic product, stagnation in gross economic product per capita, accelerating energy use, and exponential growth in emissions of major pollutants.    <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/goldamm.html">International Reaction to Hong Kong's Countdown to 1997: Doors Open to Hong Kong's Emigrants</A>   by Susan <EM> Goldammer</EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/pathak.html">International Trade and Environmental Development: A View from India</A>   by R.S.<EM> Pathak</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/hartley.txt">Introduction to the Law of Contract: Computorials"</A>   by Angela<EM> Hartley</EM>.       <I>E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I>   (book review)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/boland4.html">Involuntary Intoxication Is Not A Defence</A>   by Faye <EM> Boland</EM>.    In R v Kingston [1994] 3 All ER 353, HL, it was held that involuntary intoxication is no defence to a criminal charge and is only relevant insofar as it disproves or proves mens rea. An intent produced by the surreptitious administration of drink or drugs is still a criminal intent.   <I>Web JCLI [1995] no. 4</I>   (Casenote)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/issue1/1demuldr/">Is a computer capable of interpreting case law?</A>   by R.V. De Mulder and C.J.M. <EM> Combrink-Kuiters</EM>.    In the near future the complete texts of all the verdicts of the Supreme Court and a selection of lower courts verdicts will be electronically accessible. This will give a new stimulus to jurimetrical research because some techniques can be applied only on digitised material. Particular attention is paid to the question of whether a conceptual technique is capable of deciding whether cases could be classified as 'positive' or 'negative' in the light of a specific legal item. In other words, whether a computer could interpret legal cases with respect to their outcome.     <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/thiel.html">Is There A Demand for Pain and Suffering Coverage ?</A>   by Stuart E.<EM> Thiel</EM>.    There is a large literature on this question, almost all of which avers that economic theory rules out the possibility of demand for insurance coverage of nonpecuniary losses on a priori grounds. This paper argues that the existence or nonexistence of demand for pain and suffering coverage is a purely empirical issue and policy recommendations should view it as such. The underlying economic theory is too weak to support such a recommendation without, at least, some supporting evidence.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Business/Insol.html">Italian Insolvency Law</A>   by P.G. <EM> Monateri</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
