<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/L.GIF" >
Essays by title :   L</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/macsporr.txt">Land Ownership and Control in Nauru</A>   by Peter F<EM> MacSporran</EM>.    The article traces land ownership in Nauru (a small island in the Western Pacific) prior to, during and post colonial administration by Germany and Australia.  Customary land dealing practices are contrasted with the arrangements implemented by colonial administrators, and more recently the Naruan Lands Committee.  The impact of non traditional influences such as judicial decisions on customary practices are discussed.   <I>E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/cownie2.html">Language of the Law: international students and the reading of statutes</A>   by Fiona Cownie, with Wendy<EM> Addison</EM>.    Working in a second or third language can cause difficulties for such students, especially in a subject like law, where the nuances of language are so important. The problems which can arise are readily apparent when students begin to work with statutory materials. This article suggests an approach to the reading of statutes which could be used by law teachers and language support staff in working with international law students.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/sirwms.html">Law and Administrative Discretion</A>   by Sir David<EM> Williams Q.C.</EM>.    Williams proceeds to analyze administrative law development in England. Williams also stresses the relationship between democratic ideals and judicial deference to the decisions of local authorities. He concludes by describing the ever-evolving nature of administrative law in England today, arguing that just as in the 1920s, the underlying approach of the courts to questions in administrative law can only be interpreted by taking into account the multitude of circumstances from which such questions arise.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Contract/Alpa-1995/alpa.html">Law and Economics and Method Analysis: the Contractual Damages Issue</A>   by G. Giampieri and A. <EM> Alpa</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.vifp.monash.edu.au/contents.html">Law and Ethics in Medicine"</A>   <EM> </EM>.       <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   (online book)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/wheat2.html">Law Commission Consultation Paper No 137 - Liability for Psychiatric Illness</A>   by Kay <EM> Wheat</EM>.    This paper examines negligently inflicted psychiatric illness when the plaintiff is a secondary victim, i.e. someone who has suffered the illness as a result of injury to another, the primary victim. The law imposes a number of restrictions.  The Law Commission look at these restrictions and make a number of provisional recommendations. The paper outlines these recommendations in their legal context.   <I> </I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/rodgers4.html">Law Commission's Proposals on Mental Capacity and the Legality of Elective Ventilation for Transplantation Purposes</A>   by M E <EM> Rodgers</EM>.    This article discusses the legality of elective ventilation in the light of the recent proposals on mental capacity by the Law Commission. The author suggests that the process is not tainted with illegality. In addition, the relationship between the process of elective ventilation and the importance of the patient's best interests is explored, through consideration of the definition of 'best interests' put forward by the Law Commission.   <I>[1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/widdis4.html">Law Courseware: Big Bang or Damp Squib?</A>   by Robin <EM> Widdison</EM>.       <I>[1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/rofes.html">Law school and the constitution</A>   by Peter K. <EM> Rofes</EM>.    This essay is a satirical look at constitutional law course descriptions in law school bulletins. The author suggests alternative descriptions that would make bulletins as "fresh and original" as the typical curriculum in the classroom. This essay is part of a larger project in which the author examines different aspects of the American law school.   <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/maurer.html">Law Writing, Immigration, and Globalization in the British Virgin Islands </A>   by Bill <EM> Maurer </EM>.    While British Virgin Islanders (BVIslanders) proudly term themselves a "law and order" people and seek to distinguish themselves from other Caribbean peoples, the territory remains as wedded as ever to its British rulers and the West. BVIslanders consider their ties to Britain a critical element of their uniqueness and thus self-rule is never seriously discussed.The author illustrates this paradox by describing the passage and effects of the BVI's International Business Companies Ordinance, a law that established the BVI as a tax haven. He argues that while BVIslanders are proud to call the law their first truly local one, in fact the local legislature was forced as a result of this law to submit to increased foreign regulatory scrutiny and to enact recommendations set out in a Coopers and Lybrand study commissioned by the British. Mr. Maurer concludes that as long as Britain remains the reference point for the BVI's claims to autonomy, BVI self-rule will remain out of reach.   <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/moran.html">Law, Politics, and Economics of Amazonian Deforestation</A>   by Emilio F.<EM> Moran</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/maher.html">Lawfutures, or Will You Still Need Me, Will You Still Feed Me, When I'm Sixty-Four? (Note)</A>   by Stephen T. <EM> Maher</EM>.       <I>Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1d.html">Lawyering on the Infobahn </A>   by V. <EM> Mayer-Schoenberger</EM>.    This paper presents three models of information processing, three models of legal practice in Europe and four very practical conclusions for lawyering in a digital age.    <I>Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1 /widdis1.html">Lawyering on the Internet</A>   by Robin<EM> Widdison</EM>.    This article attempts to show why the Internet is not just a passing fad but also a major step forward in information technology that will have enduring significance both in the workplace and the place of study. Secondly, it seeks to explain the Internet by reference to what it enables users to do rather than in terms of its underlying technologies. Finally, the article examines how the development of the Internet is likely to impact on legal practice and on legal education.   <I>[1995] No. 1 Web JCLI</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/ross.txt">Learning About Survival From Survivors: Mohawk Environmental Communicative Action</A>   by Susan<EM> Ross</EM>.    This report examines two case-studies in order to illustrate the argument that environmental justice requires that indigenous people, who may have a different world-view, be involved in environmental decision-making. The author stresses the danger of using purely "statistical and quantitative" methods and excluding human, ethical value-judgements in formulating environmental policy   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/torrem5.html">Legal Education in Flanders</A>   by Leo F.T. Torremans and Paul L.C <EM> Torremans</EM>.    This article describes the system of legal education in Flanders. It subjects both the curriculum and methods of teaching and assessment to critical review and highlights a number of areas where there is room for improvement.   <I>[1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/leith4.html">Legal Education in Germany: becoming a Lawyer, Judge, and Professor</A>   by Philip <EM> Leith</EM>.       <I>[1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/greinke.txt">Legal Expert Systems: A Humanistic Critique of Mechanical Legal Inference</A>   by Andrew<EM> Greinke</EM>.    The author surveys a wide range of computerised expert systems and shows that they invariably rely on pattern-matching and rule application strategies which have been embodied in their inference mechanisms and knowledge representations.  This computational approach is argued to be unsuitable for use with law which presents a domain of intractable complexity arising out of the need to refer to social context and human purpose in resolving legal issues. The author concludes that a better use for computation in legal applications is in the form of decision- support systems that leave legal inference to human agents.   <I>E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/smith.html">Legal Imagery in the "Garden of England" </A>   by Eve <EM> Darian-Smith </EM>.    Ms. Darian-Smith explores the relationship between law and the concept of "landscapes," which she describes as the spatial imagery through which law is conceived and from which it draws meaning. In general terms, the "garden image" is injected into issues of environmental law. Further, she notes that the garden has been a fluid, ever-changing concept. Specifically, Darian-Smith focuses on a recent development regarding the interaction between the law, the garden, and spatial imagery in England: she argues that the new Channel Tunnel between England and France undermines England's identity as an island nation, in effect physically and symbolically severing its claim as the bounded "Garden of England." Such a development, Darian-Smith argues, is a symbol of the eroding of an English identity traditionally thought to be distinct and separate from Europe and its influences, a notion analogous to the way European Community law and English law have been meshed together in environmental issues.   <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/aiken2.html">Legal knowledge based systems: some observations on the future</A>   by Michael<EM> Aikenhead</EM>.    The adoption by AI researchers specialising in law of new AI techniques, such as case based reasoning, neural networks, fuzzy logic, deontic logics and non-monotonic logics, may move closer to achieving an automation of legal reasoning.   Even if these new techniques do not achieve an automation of legal reasoning however, they will still be valuable in better automating office tasks and in providing insights about the nature of law.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/kandeva.html">Legal System and American Constitutional Democracy" Edited by Maria Frankowska & Albert P. Melone </A>   by Emilia <EM> Kandeva-Spiridonova </EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.qub.ac.uk/1legal.htm">Legal System of Nortern Ireland</A>   by Brice<EM> Dickson</EM>.    The history and adminstration of the Legal System of Northern Ireland.   <I>Book Chapter </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/shanahan.txt">Legislative Responses to *Mabo*- Rendering the Law Unconscious?</A>   by Christopher<EM> Shanahan</EM>.    The common law precedents cited in *Mabo* reveal the common law's long established capacity to recognise pluralism.  This is contrasted with the effects of the *Native Title Act 1993* (Cth) and the *Land (Titles and Traditional Usage) Act 1993* (WA), which seek to overcome the plurality implicit in the legal recognition of indigenous interests in land, thereby denying this tradition of plurality within Anglo-Australian legal culture.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/clements3.html">Lending on the Security of Co-Owned Homes, Suretyship and Undue Influence</A>   by L.M.<EM> Clements</EM>.    The purpose of this Article is to examine how the law relating to lending on the security of co-owned homes, suretyship and undue influence has recently been developed, what are the real underlying policy issues and whether a balance is being struck between the competing economic interests and protection of the vulnerable.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/jones4.html">Liability for Psychiatric Illness - More Principle, Less Subtlety ?</A>   by Michael A.<EM> Jones</EM>.    This article considers the future direction of the law in the light of the English Law Commission's Consultation Paper No. 137, Liability for Psychiatric Illness. It argues that the present state of the law is unsatisfactory in view of the wholly artificial and arbitrary restrictions on recovery; that the policy factors relied upon to justify these restrictions do not stand up to analysis; and that the provisional views of the Law Commission on reform of the law, though widening the potential ambit of recovery, do not go far enough. There is no longer any sensible basis for adopting liability rules which distinguish between plaintiffs who sustain physical injury and those who suffer psychiatric illness as a result of a defendant's carelessness.    <I>Web JCLI [1995] no. 4</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3i.html">LINK - The Legal Information Network: Users views</A>   by R. Susskind, M. Young, and A.<EM> Katz</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/waterman.html">Local Monopsony, Free Riding, and Antitrust Policy</A>   by David<EM> Waterman</EM>.    This paper models the development of market structure in industries which are characterized by upstream economies of scale in the distribution of differentiated products to retail firms having local monopoly power within separate geographic areas. Examples are cable television and other mass media. Antitrust applications to the cable television, motion picture, and newspaper industries are discussed.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/boy.htm">Logic and Experience: The Origin of Modern American Legal Education" by William P. Lapiana</A>   reviewed by Allen D<EM> Boyer</EM>.       <I>Cornell LR January 1995</I>   (book review)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/eastman.html">Logic of the Two-Person Coase Theorem in Game-Theoretic Terms</A>   by Wayne<EM> Eastman</EM>.    The logic of the Coase Theorem translates into the game-theoretic point that a 2 x 1 matrix in which only one player apparently has a choice is actually a 2 x 2 matrix in which the other player can offer the first player a payoff. Given this point, it follows that there is a close connection between the Coase Theorem and the Prisoner's Dilemma. It further follows that a Coasean analysis of a payoff matrix will often show opportunities for threat bargaining that a standard analysis does not show. The game-theoretic interpretation of Coasean logic has implications for law, some of which differ from those associated with other interpretations of the Coase Theorem.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3i.html">Lord Chancellor's Advisory Committee on Legal Education</A>   <EM> </EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/levmore.html">Love It or Leave It: Property Rules, Liability Rules, and Exclusivity of Remedies in Partnership and Marriage</A>   by Saul<EM> Levmore</EM>.    The traditional rule in partnership law, and the continuing rule in domestic relations law, is that a claim for dissolution (or divorce) is a partner's exclusive remedy. On its face this mandatory "love-it-or-leave-it" rule seems strange, anachronistic, unfair, and inefficient, because where there is going concern value there is room for exploitation. In contrast, corporate law offers a kind of reverse "exclusivity" rule, in that a shareholder can bring a suit for damages but can not force dissolution of the enterprise. These rules offer a window to general questions about remedies. The Calabresi-Melamed property-liability rules framework is expanded with the incorporation not only of rules explored by Polinsky and by Krier and Schwab but also with several seemingly novel rules that draw attention to the possibility of remedies that are only forward-looking or only backward-looking. The critical connection is that the power to "stop" a partnership or a marriage is akin to the power to stop a nuisance, so that love-it-or-leave-it rules can have the character of a "property rule" with no liability component.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/munsey.pag">Love That Need Not Name its Speaker </A>   by David M. <EM> Munsey</EM>.    In this piece, presented at the University of Oregon in April 1995, Prof. David Munsey discusses the essentialism/ constructivism debate in gay and lesbian scholarship.  After describing various positions within the debate he advocates an anti-essentialist position, that homosexuality is "more akin to an appetite than a property."  As a consequence of his view Munsey advocates a process of education demonstrating the lack of differences between people of different sexual orientations.    <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
