<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   M</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/M.GIF" >
Essays by title :   M</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/bookrev/1terrett/default.htm">M Ethan Katsch, "Law In A Digital World"</A>   Reviewed by Andrew <EM> Terrett</EM>.       <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/downing4.html">Magill and the Software Directive: are they interoperable?</A>   by Robbie<EM> Downing</EM>.    In Magill, the ECJ held that a refusal to license copyright protected materials could be an abuse of a dominant position under Article 86 of the EC Treaty. The ECJ's analysis could be applied to certain cases where copyright protection of computer programs is relied on to control the creation of a third party product or service, although much depends on how we interpret the ECJ's notion of abuse. Courts would be better advised sensitively to circumscribe the scope of copyright protection under the Software Directive taking into account the experience of US courts.  Article 86 is arguably not the proper instrument to strike the balance inherent in the grant of an intellectual property right. Moreover, in applying Magill, a realistic approach to market power in secondary markets is required.   <I>Web JCLI [1995] no. 4</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Torts/Mattei1.html">Making the Other Path Efficient :Economic Analysis and Tort Law in Less Developed Countries</A>   by U. Mattei and M. <EM> Bussani</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/onions3.html">Marginalisation of Gypsies</A>   by Helen<EM> O'Nions</EM>.    Gypsies have persistently suffered discrimination and prejudice from the rest of society.  The Criminal Justice Act 1994 contains provisions which will reduce the number of authorised Gypsy sites available in an attempt to discourage the nomadic way of life.  The legislation is likely to have severe implications for the welfare of the Gypsy family unit.  Ultimately however, a comparison with other European jurisdictions will illustrate that this legislation will not succeed in persuading Gypsies to abandon their traditions because it is founded on a myth, namely that Gypsies are simply a social bonding of nomads with no distinctive culture or group identity.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/griffin.html">MARPOL 73/78 and Vessel Pollution: A Glass Half Full or Half Empty?</A>   by Andrew<EM> Griffin</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/powell.html">Measured step to protect private property rights</A>   by Dan R. Stengle, Robert M. Rhodes, and David L. <EM> Powell </EM>.    A 1995 measure of the Florida legislature measure includes a new cause of action providing judicial relief to landowners who suffer inordinate burdens on the use of their land. If properly implemented and applied, the measure will have none of the feared undesriable effects. The legislation grants important new rights to landowners while maintaining existing environmental protection and growth management programs. Perhaps most importantly, the measure is intended to reform the way government does business with landowners. The legislation strikes a balance between conflicting, but equally valid, public and private interests.    <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/aman.html">Migration and Globalization</A>   by Alfred C.<EM> Aman, Jr.</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   (symposium introduction)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/blakeney.txt">Milpurrurru & Ors v Indofurn Pty Ltd & Ors - Protecting Expressions of Aboriginal Folklore Under Copyright Law</A>   by Michael<EM> Blakeney</EM>.    The author traces the development of the law through two cases.  The author points out that the Copyright Act's requirement that the creator of a work be able to assert copyright ownership creates a problem where the design which is the subject of a claim dates back more than 50 years before the infringing act. The author concludes by emphasising the importance of comprehensive legislation to protect expressions of Aboriginal folklore.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/lyford.txt">Ministry of Truth Redefined: A Consideration of Privacy and Data Protection Law ...</A>   by Jamie H.<EM> Lyford</EM>.    This paper looks at the issue of privacy in light of the information age.  Particular emphasis is made in the Australian context.  National and international laws are also examined.   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/edge2.html">Missionary's Position After Kokkinakis v Greece</A>   by Peter W<EM> Edge</EM>.    The issue before the European Court of Human Rights in Kokkinakis v Greece concerned Article 9 of the European Convention on Human Rights which protects freedom of religion and required the Court to consider the relationship between those who wish to proselytise, and those who are the targets of such action.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   (Case Comment)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/mcc.htm">Mistakes, precedent, and the rise of the administrative state:  toward a constitutional theory of the second best</A>   by Peter<EM> McCutchen</EM>.    This Article proposes a form of constitutional damage control.   Under this theory, the Court should adhere to constitutional structures whenever possible.  Nonetheless, the Court should tolerate structures or practices that are conceded to be unconstitutional when such structures or practices have become institutionalized.. Where unconstitutional institutions are allowed to stand based on a theory of precedent, the Court should allow (or even require) the creation of compensating institutions that seek to move governmental structures closer to the constitutional equilibrium.   <I>Cornell LR November 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://gopher.law.warwick.ac.uk:70/00/ltc/publications/conferences/oxford/walsum.txt">Mixed Metaphors: The Nation and the Family</A>   by S. van<EM> Walsum</EM>.    The concept of nationality is a contingent one, and must be placed in its historical and geographical context. Equally important for the meaning of this concept is the legal field in which it is employed: immigration law, law of conflicts or social policies directed at migrants. The equally contingent concept of family is intimately linked to that of nationality, and this relationship too varies according to time, place and specific legal context. This paper attempts to analyse the relationship between the nation and the family in the specific context of present-day Dutch immigration law. Inspired by writings of the geographer David Harvey, the author considers the consequences for control over mobility, identity and family loyalty.   <I>Oxford Critical Legal Conference 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/dfriedman.html">More Justice for Less Money: A Step Beyond Cimino</A>   by David<EM> Friedman</EM>.    In Cimino v. Raymark, a federal court resolved 2298 asbestos cases with 160 trials by grouping the cases, trying a random sample of each group, and awarding to all members of each group the average verdict. I propose an improved procedure designed to allocate damages correctly among plaintiffs. Plaintiffs' attorney submits a list of claims; defense selects cases for trial. Plaintiffs in untried cases receive their claim times the average ratio of award to claim for tried cases. Some potential problems are examined through a formal model. Modifications are suggested to adapt the procedure to situations involving a very large number of very small cases.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/goodman.htm">Morton International v. General Accident Insurance Co.: The New Jersey Supreme Court Defines the Scope of the Qualified Pollution Exclusion Clause in Comprehensive General Liability Policies</A>   by Jennifer <EM> Goodman</EM>.       <I>Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I>   (casebrief)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part5.htm">Multimedia computing:  copyright law's &quot;last stand&quot; </A>   by Steven <EM> Pepe</EM>.       <I>Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/greguras.txt">Multimedia Content and the Super Highway: Rapid Acceleration or Foot on the Brake?</A>   by Sandy Wong, Fred Greguras and Michael R<EM> Egger</EM>.    This article discusses emerging legal issues concerning copyright/patent protection of material used in multimedia applications. Describes existing processes for the administration of copyright/patent material in the US and the deficencies of traditional rights agreements where material is used in multimedia products.  Cites recent reports from Japan concerning the advantages of streamlining copyright/patent administration, and proposes the establishment of a US based copyright/patent clearinghouse for multimedia materials.   <I>E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="/TITLES/A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Q.HTM">Q</A> |  <A HREF="/TITLES/R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Z.HTM">Z</A> 
