<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   N</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/N.GIF" >
Essays by title :   N</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/meyer.html">National and International Copyright Liability for Electronic System Operators </A>   by Charles J. <EM> Meyer </EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I>   (note)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mah.txt">National Native Title Tribunal - Compensation Issues -  A Discussion Paper</A>   by Daniel C. H.<EM> Mah</EM>.    Although the Tribunal was largely set up as a mediating body, with the reaching of compensation agreements to be a consensual process between parties, certain boundaries have been set within that process. This paper considers those processes and boundaries, with emphasis on determining liability for compensation, measurement and forms that compensation may take, and the application procedure   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>A "<A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/clarke.txt">Near" Contract Experience</A>   by Kirsty<EM> Clarke</EM>.    The author focusses especially on the unwillingness of the court to intervene in and enforce 'domestic' agreements, in which women are often the weaker party.   It is propounded that contractual rules and terminology may be manipulated so as to perpetuate and legitimate an unequal status quo.  The concepts of the 'reasonable person' and 'freedom of contract' are criticised, and it is proposed that these concepts should be expanded to apply wider principles of fairness which will remedy  basic inequalities of bargaining power.   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 3 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/netwatch/netw1.txt">Netwatch April 1995</A>   by Anne<EM> Greenshields</EM>.    This issue of Netwatch focuses on indigenous resources.  While this listing is not a comprehensive list of indigenous peoples resources it is a list of sites which the library has been able to connect to and have determined that they are resources which would interest a researcher in this area.  New sites and new discussion lists follow the special subject section.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.gelso.unitn.it/card-adm/Review/Constitutional/Mattei2.html">New Ethiopian Constitution: First Thoughts on Ethnical Federalism and the Reception of Western Institutions</A>   by U. <EM> Mattei</EM>.       <I>Cardozo Electronic Law Bulletin </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3c.html">New Frontiers in Instructional Software</A>   by B.<EM> Boyd</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/tessrtr3.html">New Slave Trade:  The International crisis of Immigrant Smuggling</A>   by Kevin <EM> Tessier</EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/booton2.html">Novelty of Inventions under the Patents Act 1977 and the European Patent Convention</A>   by D. L. <EM> Booton</EM>.    In Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals Inc and Another v H N Norton & Co Ltd, the House of Lords considered the circumstances under which an invention shall be taken to be new under the Patents Act 1977 s 2. Their Lordships questioned whether a patent may be granted for an old product used in an old way but for a new purpose. This aspect of the decision created problems in respect of infringement. Nevertheless, it was acknowledged that while the question of whether a person is working an invention is objective in the case of a claim for a product per se, this may be different where the claim is for the use of a product.     <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   (casenote)
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="/TITLES/A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Q.HTM">Q</A> |  <A HREF="/TITLES/R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Z.HTM">Z</A> 
