<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   O</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/O.GIF" >
Essays by title :   O</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/todd5.html">Occupation for Life: Satisfying the Equity</A>   by Paul Todd and Nicola <EM> Glover</EM>.    Suppose that A, who has legal title to a house, represents to B that B will be allowed to occupy the house for his or her life, and B relies on that representation to his or her detriment. There is no problem, on the principles enunciated by Lord Bridge in Lloyds Bank plc v Rosset [1991] 1 AC 107, eg at p 132, in granting B an interest, by way of constructive trust or proprietary estoppel. When it comes to quantifying the interest, however, the courts are prevented from reaching an equitable solution by legislation which had its origins over a century ago, and was intended to deal with an entirely different problem. To judge from the number of recent cases, the situation must be quite a common one.     <I>[1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/parry2.html">Open Access, Rights and Legislation</A>   by N D M Parry and F R <EM> Barker</EM>.    At first sight, Part V of the National Parks and Access to the Countryside Act 1949 is a radical piece of legislation. It provides for members of the public to have open access to specified areas of "open country". This is in apparent contrast to the general position in England and Wales. This article seeks generally to examine the impact and effect of Part V of the 1949 Act, and to evaluate the public access 'rights' for which it makes provision, in particular in the light of some of the recent changes to the law of trespass introduced by the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994.    <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/humphry.txt">Opportunity Lost for Aboriginal Self-Determination: Australia's compliance with ILO 169</A>   by Alison<EM> Humphry</EM>.    The paper addresses the requirements of articles 8 and 9 of ILO 169 and whether WA complies with these. It examines primarily the interplay between the customary law of Australian Aboriginal people and the criminal justice system of Western Australia. The author concludes that compliance is limited to taking into account customary law when applying non-Aboriginal law and not so much compliance with the requirements of respect for Aboriginal law and institutions.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/karst.html">Out of Many, One?</A>   by Kenneth L.<EM> Karst</EM>.    The Governor of California has called for an amendment to the U.S. Constitution that would deny citizenship to a child born in the United States if the child's parents entered the country illegally. Although this appalling proposal seems unlikely to be taken seriously in Congress, undoubtedly it is well received by a constituency the Governor needs to reassure. Similar constituencies were vocal during the colonial era, and their successors have made nativism a recurring political theme. In sum, this experience makes clear that the ideal of the "Open Republic," so ably defended by Professor Jost Delbrck, confronts powerful opposition. In this paper I comment briefly on the problems of maintaining political community and political legitimacy in the face of ethnic difference.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI>An <A HREF="http://elj.warwick.ac.uk/elj/jilt/dp/intros/default.htm">Outline of the European Data Protection Directive</A>   by Ian <EM> Lloyd</EM>.       <I>Journal of Information, Law and Technology Issue One </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/liberman.html">Overreaching Provisions in Software License Agreements (Note)</A>   by Michael <EM> Liberman </EM>.       <I>Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/harel.pag">Overview & Commentary: Bagaz 721/94 El-Al v. Danilowitz and the Future of Sexual Minority Rights in Israel </A>   by Alon <EM> Harel</EM>.    In this article Prof. Harel provides the context for and explains the Supreme Court of Israel's recent decision in El-Al v. Danilowitz, in which the Court held that same-sex partners of El-Al Airlines employees must be granted the same benefits as cross-sex partners.     <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="/TITLES/A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Q.HTM">Q</A> |  <A HREF="/TITLES/R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Z.HTM">Z</A> 
