<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   P</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/P.GIF" >
Essays by title :   P</H1>
<UL>

<LI>The <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3b.html">Place of Computers in Legal Education</A>   by H.<EM> Collins</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/laing1.html">Police Surgeon and Mentally Disordered Suspects: An Adequate Safeguard?</A>   by Judith M <EM> Laing</EM>.    This article examines the role of the police surgeon in identifying and assessing mentally disordered suspects in police custody. It suggests that police surgeons lack the relevant knowledge and expertise to deal with these people, and concludes that duty-psychiatrist schemes currently operating at magistrates' courts should be extended to police stations to ensure that mentally disordered suspects are assessed by medical professionals who possess the relevant psychiatric expertise.      <I>Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/carney.html">Political Economy of Competition for Corporate Charters</A>   by William J.<EM> Carney</EM>.    This paper explains the differences between American and European corporate laws using interest group theory. Interest groups are described as seeking to extract rents through corporate laws. Their ability to do so is constrained by the mobility of corporations to seek competing corporate laws. A common market provides the optimal competitive setting, and has been present in the U.S. but not in Europe until recently. Evidence of interest group legislation appears far greater in Europe than in the U.S. Further, European nations adopted anticompetitive conflicts of law rules that U.S. states could not adopt, given their competitive setting.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/scheetr1.html">Politics of Western Immigration</A>   by Stephen E. <EM> Scheele</EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/ohare2.html">Positive Action Before the European Court of Justice: CASE C-450/93 Kalanke v Freie Hansestadt Bremen</A>   by Ursula A <EM> O'Hare</EM>.    Express provision is made for positive action measures to promote equal opportunities between men and women under European Community law. In October 1995 the European Court of Justice ruled that a 'tie-break' positive action scheme which gives priority to a woman candidate for an employment position over an equally qualified male competitor, was contrary to the terms of the Equal Treatment Directive. This article reviews the judgment and argues that the lack of reasoning in this decision is unfortunate.    <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   (casenote)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz2a.html">Positivism and the Separation of Law and Economics </A>   by Avery <EM> Katz </EM>.    The economic analysis of law has since its beginnings in the early 1960s provoked substantial opposition and antagonism in the legal academy and, to a lesser extent, in the profession at large. In this essay, I argue (1) that economists as a matter of official professional methodology subscribe to a strong form of positivism; and that law and economics is particularly influenced by this approach; (2) that this methodological position places law and economics firmly on one side of the controversy over legal positivism, and (3) that the pragmatic justifications for taking this methodological position within the field of economics do not necessarily carry over to the field of law.    <I> </I>   
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/howe.txt">Poststructuralist Consideration of Property as Thin Air- Mabo, A Case Study</A>   by Adrian<EM> Howe</EM>.    This report examines the decision in _Mabo (no 2)_ from the point of view of property as a power relation rather than a tangible resource. The actual nature of the rights recognised has resulted in uncertainty. The result of the case is to "propertise" Aboriginal interests in land, rendering them a "real", though second rate, interest.   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/mcgregor.txt">Practical Strategies for Using Computers in Legal Education</A>   by Myles McGregor-Lowndes and Alan<EM> Davidson</EM>.    The paper chronicles the past experience and future plans of the School of Accounting Legal Studies Computer Based Education Project at the Queensland University of Technology.  The first part of the paper describes the computer based learning products that have been produced and tested.  The second part of the paper outlines products that are currently under production.   <I>E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506003.abs">Predictable and Unpredictable Error in Tort Awards: The Effect of Plaintiff Self Selection and Signalling</A>   by Eric <EM> Rasmusen </EM>.    If a potential tort plaintiff can predict that the court will overestimate damages he is more likely to bring suit, but if the court is aware of this, it will adjust its awards accordingly. In general, court error implies that the court should moderate extreme awards whether they are high or low, because of regression towards the mean. Predictable error, however, tends to push the optimal adjustment downwards and unpredictable error pushes it upwards, because of plaintiff selection and signalling, respectively. The expectation of either kind of error leads plaintiffs to bring meritless suits.     <I> </I>   (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/leigh3.html">Prerogative, Legislative Power, and the Democratic Deficit: The Fire Brigades Union Case</A>   by Ian<EM> Leigh</EM>.    The recent decision of the House of Lords in R v Secretary of State for the Home Department, ex parte Fire Brigades Union [1995] 2 WLR 464 raises important constitutional questions about the extent to which the government is required to seek Parliamentary approval for its policies or may rely instead on prerogative powers. This note considers the implications of the ruling.  It is argued that the House of Lords reached the right decision, but for the wrong reasons.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/carroll.html">Priority of Invention in United States Patents: From the Paris Convention to GATT (Note)</A>   by John F. <EM> Carroll, IV </EM>.       <I>Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/davies1.html">Privacy and Human Rights" by James Michael</A>   reviewed by Simon<EM> Davies</EM>.       <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   (book review)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1f.html">Privacy and Telecommunications</A>   by R.<EM> Bradgate</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/steele2.html">Private Rights and Planning Consent</A>   by Jenny<EM> Steele</EM>.    Despite the scope for conflict between the private law of nuisance and the public law of the planning system, there has not been much litigation. The cases of Wheeler v JJ Saunders Ltd and Hunter and Others v Canary Wharf Ltd demonstrate that no clear principles have yet emerged.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   (Case Comment)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/maughan2.html">Problem-Solving Through Reflective Practice: The Oxygen of Expertise or Just Swamp Gas?</A>   by Caroline <EM> Maughan</EM>.    Donald Schn provides us with a theory of professional knowledge and its development through 'reflection'. He claims it is the ability to practise reflectively which distinguishes the expert from the merely competent professional. The central question for this paper is the value of developing reflective practice skills and processes at the 'novice' level. The author argues that novice lawyers can be enabled to develop reflective skills and habits. However, she indicates that there are still unanswered questions about the transferability of the skills and processes learned as students progress into the vocational stage of legal education and the early years of practice.     <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles4/gilbert4.html">Problems and Process: International Law and How We Use It", by Rosalyn Higgins</A>   reviewed by Geoff <EM> Gilbert</EM>.       <I>[1995] Web JCLI No.4 </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/valdes3.pag">Proceedings of the Panel on Gender, Sexual Orientation & HIV at the 1995 Women in the Law Conference, Monterey, California, May 5, 1995 </A>   Introduced by Francisco <EM> Valdes</EM>.    In this transcript of the proceedings of the panel on Gender, Sexual Orientation and HIV, sponsored by the State Bar of California Women in Law Committee, the panelists focus on how AIDS affects women, including lesbians.  Four women, a legal worker living with AIDS, an AIDS health and social service provider, a policy-worker and a legal service provider, tell their stories and express their opinions about the impact of the AIDS crisis on them and women generally.     <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/game/papers/9403/9403007.abs">Product Safety: Liability, R&D and Signaling </A>   by Jennifer F. Reinganum and Andrew F. <EM> Daughety </EM>.    This paper develops a two-stage model of product design and safety signaling incorporating a parametric liability specification in a monopoly context. In the first stage, the firm engages in research and development in order to determine the safety of its product. We model the research and development process as sequential sampling from a fixed distribution of potential safety levels. Since the outcome of research and development trials is unobservable to consumers, in the second stage of the model the firm must choose its price with the understanding that consumers may attempt to draw inferences about the product's safety.    <I> </I>   (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/daughety.html">Product Safety: Liability, R&D and Signaling</A>   by Jennifer F. Reinganum and Andrew F.<EM> Daughety</EM>.    We develop a monopoly model of product design and safety signaling incorporating a parametric liability specification. The firm first engages in R&D to affect the safety of its product. Since the outcome of R&D trials is unobservable to consumers, the firm then chooses its price, understanding that consumers may draw inferences from the price about the product's safety. Consumers acquire and use the product; injuries lead to losses which are allocated by the liability system. We vary the liability system's allocation of losses and trace out the implications for R&D investment and the price-safety relationship.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/game/papers/9403/9403007.abs">Product Safety: Liability, R&D and Signaling </A>   by Andrew F. Daughety and Jennifer F. <EM> Reinganum</EM>.    This paper develops a two-stage model of product design and safety signaling incorporating a parametric liability specification in a monopoly context. In the first stage, the firm engages in research and development in order to determine the safety of its product. We model the research and development process as sequential sampling from a fixed distribution of potential safety levels. Since the outcome of research and development trials is unobservable to consumers, in the second stage of the model the firm must choose its price with the understanding that consumers may attempt to draw inferences about the product's safety.    <I> </I>   (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/daughety.html">Product Safety: Liability, R&D and Signaling</A>   by Andrew F. Daughety and Jennifer F.<EM> Reinganum</EM>.    We develop a monopoly model of product design and safety signaling incorporating a parametric liability specification. The firm first engages in R&D to affect the safety of its product. Since the outcome of R&D trials is unobservable to consumers, the firm then chooses its price, understanding that consumers may draw inferences from the price about the product's safety. Consumers acquire and use the product; injuries lead to losses which are allocated by the liability system. We vary the liability system's allocation of losses and trace out the implications for R&D investment and the price-safety relationship.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.ualberta.ca/ee/fulltext/paper.robertson_m.html">Property and Ideology</A>   by Michael <EM> RobertsonReal Property</EM>.       <I>Electronic Easement </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/shavell.html">Property Rules vs Liability Rules</A>   by Steven Shavell and Louis<EM> Kaplow</EM>.    A fundamental legal problem is whether property rights should be protected by property rules or by liability rules. In this Article, we provide a systematic economic analysis of the choice between property and liability rules. We answer a basic question: why is it that liability rules are commonly used in the context of harmful externalities (such as pollution and automobile accidents), whereas property rules are generally employed toprotect possessors of things against potential takers? In the course of our analysis, we demonstrate that many commonly held beliefs about property and liability rules are mistaken. Our analysis is also relevant to policy; for example, we show that in important contexts liability rules (and pollution taxes) are more efficient than property rules (including much regulation) even when damages must be set using only limited information about harm.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/schenk.html">Proposal to Improve the Treatment of Women in Asylum Law :  Adding a "Gender" Category to the International Definition of "Refugee"</A>   by Todd Stewart<EM> Schenk</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   (Note)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/llewel2.html">Proposals for the Introduction of a Community Utility Model System: A UK Perspective</A>   by Margaret<EM> Llewelyn</EM>.    The European Commission is currently looking at proposals to introduce a new Community intellectual property right (IPR), the Utility Model (UM) which will serve to protect those inventions which are not regarded as capable of fulfilling the strict granting requirements of the patent system. The Commission wishes to harmonise existing practices and to broadened the scope of UM protection. One of the EU member states which has been the most vocal in voicing its concerns over the proposals is the UK. The reason for the extent of concern is that UK does not at present operate a UM system. There is, therefore, considerable concern and doubt about: a) the need to introduce UM protection and b) the scope and type of protection to be granted.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/birk.html">Protecting truthful advertising by attorney-cpasIbanez v. Florida Department of Business & Professional Regulation, Board of Accountancy, 114 S. Ct. 2084 (1994)</A>   by Edward L. <EM> Birk</EM>.    Sylvia Ibanez advertised her qualifications as a member of the Florida Bar, a certified financial planner, and a certified public accountant. She was reprimanded by the Florida Board of Accountancy. Ibanez challenged the Board decision, and the United States Supreme Court ruled in her favour. This Note examines <i>Ibanez</I> and considers the substantial government interests states must demonstrate before they may regulate truthful commercial speech. It concludes that the <i>Ibanez</I> Court failed in its reasoning and holding to extend - under its own precedent - the maximum possible protection to consumers who may be misled, or at least left uninformed.   <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/hicks.html">Protection of Individual Investors Under U.S. Securities Laws :  The Impact of International Regulatory Competition</A>   by J. William<EM> Hicks</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/seaman.txt">Providing a Sustainable Economic Land Base for Aboriginal Populations</A>   by Paul<EM> Seaman QC</EM>.    Provides general background to the substance and implications of the High Court's Mabo decision, the workings of the _Native Title Act_, the Native Title Tribunal and an outline of statutary requirements and current policy for processing native title applications   <I>E-Law Vol.2 No.1 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/dawson5.html">Public Policy, Security of Tenure and the Agricultural Holdings Acts </A>   by Ian <EM> Dawson</EM>.    Until recently, an existing existing tenant given security for his life but additionally on two occasions after he voluntarily gave up the tenancy or died, members of his family could go before the Agricultural Lands Tribunal and obtain a new tenancy in their own names. It became accepted doctrine that this security for farmers was essential. With the Agricultural Tenancies Act 1995 there is no statutory security of tenure as regards future tenancies, only that contained in the tenancy agreement itself. But that Act does not affect existing tenancies which continue to enjoy their earlier security of tenure This article seeks to explore the extent to which in fact the accepted doctrine was well founded and whether some adjustment is necessary in the new world after the 1995 Act.    <I>[1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1l.html">Publishing and Multimedia Law" by Michael Henry</A>   reviewed by A. <EM> Charlesworth</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/publications/ltj/v4n1/ltj4-1c.html">Purchasing Decision Support System </A>   by A. Hoey and J. <EM> Garvan </EM>.    Public procurement law is a complex subject which is continually evolving. As a result of the formation of the single market public procurement has become high profile and all those involved in purchasing are now required to be familiar with legislation operating in the fields of public supplies, works, services and utilities. This paper reports on the development of a computerised decision support tool in public procurement by a team of staff from the University of Ulster.    <I>Law Technology Journal  Vol.4, No.1, 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/porras.html">Puzzling Relationship Between Trade and Environment:  NAFTA, Competitiveness, and the Pursuit of Environmental Welfare Objectives</A>   by Ileana M. <EM> Porras</EM>.    Harmonization of standards to facilitate the free flow of trade is a familiar trade goal. NAFTA's provisions regarding environmental standards, however, are not a straightforward requirement to harmonize standards. Rather, NAFTA recognizes state autonomy in standard setting, on the one hand, while requiring a form of upward harmonization, on the other. The result of such an arrangement is the perpetuation of economic and political inequality among states. NAFTA fails to give equal attention to the demands of "sustainable development" in poorer countries.    <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
