<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   S</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/S.GIF" >
Essays by title :   S</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/231/webster.html">Selection and retention of judges: is there one "best" method?</A>   by Peter D. <EM> Webster</EM>.    This Article first discusses the relationship between judicial theory and choice of a method of judicial selection and retention. It then addresses what each of the principal alternative methods of judicial selection and retention now in use does, and does not, accomplish. Finally, it proposes a compromise method which might prove more likely to satisfy all participants in the debate than does any of the current alternatives.   <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol. 23 - Summer 1995 - No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/waldfogel.html">Sentencing Policy, Implied Demographic Welfare Weights, and the Theory of Sentencing Reform</A>   by Joel<EM> Waldfogel</EM>.    Different groups of people experience varying degrees of different externalties. By a government's choice of expenditures to control externalities, it affects different members of the population differently. These choices implicitly "value" the welfare of members of different groups. This paper adapts the framework developed by Ahmad and Stern (1984) to infer welfare weights underlying a system of commodity taxation, to infer the welfare weights implicitly attached to different population groups by U.S. sentencing policy. We also calculate welfare-improving directions of sentencing reform.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2e.html">Setting Common Minimum Standards of Computer Competency for undergraduates</A>   by P.<EM> Osbourne</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/chung.html">Settlement of Litigation under Rule 68: An Economic Analysis</A>   by Tai-Yeong<EM> Chung</EM>.    Rule 68 of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure provides that a plaintiff who refuses a defendant's formal settlement offer and then obtains a judgment not more favorable than the offer must pay the defendant's post-offer costs. An economic analysis is provided (i) to argue that the standard definition of settlement range is not adequate for analyzing Rule 68, because it contains unreasonable, dominated offers, (ii) to present a new definition of the refined settlement range that is adequate for analyzing the effects of Rule 68, and (iii) to propose a revision of Rule 68 to encourage settlements of litigation.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/mison.pag">Sexual Orientation Discrimination in the Workplace: A Legal Reference Guide</A>   by Bettina B. Plevan, Paul Salvatore, and Robert B. <EM> Mison </EM>.    This recently updated outline of law relating to sexual stereotyping, domestic partnership benefits, employment discrimination and sexual orientation harassment provides citations of key federal and state cases, law review articles and state and local laws in a concise and accessible format.    <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 2, Issue 1 (1996)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://infolib.murdoch.edu.au:70/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/comment/kee1.txt">Should Gambling Gains Be Taxed as Income?</A>   by Pei-Teing<EM> Kee</EM>.    The author considers the taxation treatment of gambling gains in Australia.  She examines the reasons for and against taxing such gains as income, how this could be done and whether losses would then have to be deductible. The paper concludes that these gains should be taxed, and proposes a way in which this could be done.   <I>E Law Volume 2 Number 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/conferen/papers/schwartz.html">Simple Majority Rule for Criminal Jury Trials: The Verdict is Now In</A>   by Edward P. Schwartz and Warren F. <EM> Schwartz</EM>.    The paper proposes that the current two way unanimity rule governing jury verdicts in criminal cases be replaced by a rule of simple majority.  Neither the history of the use of the unanimity rule nor the reasons advanced to justify its use provide persuasive grounds for retaining the rule rather than employing the rule of simple majority which is used in virtually all other democratic institutions.     <I> </I>   (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.law.vill.edu/vls/journals/elj/volume6_1/heeney.htm">">Sizeable Sling Stone: The Staggering Impact of United States v. Colorado on the EPA Goliath</A>   by James T. <EM> Heeney</EM>.       <I>Villanova Environmental Law Journal Volume VI Issue 1</I>   (Casenote)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/cripps.html">Some Effects of European Law on English Administrative Law</A>   by Yvonne<EM> Cripps</EM>.    Dr. Cripps discusses how European law has affected English law in recent decades, particularly with regard to the constitutional supremacy enjoyed by the English legislative branch.  Dr. Cripps predicts that the English bench will be increasingly willing to take European law into account in their decisionmaking.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue1/ogus1.html">Some Reflections on the Woolf Interim Report</A>   by Anthony <EM> Ogus</EM>.    Drawing on law and economics literature, the author critically examines some of the key features of the Woolf Interim Report. The need to constrain lawyers' incentives to escalate costs is paramount and some shift away from the adversarial culture to judicial management is desirable. But care must be exercised in designing new procedures if the changes are not to be self-defeating. There is also a danger of over- optimism regarding proposals for encouraging alternative dispute resolution (ADR). More generally, legal costs will remain a problem so long as professional self-regulation is allowed to imposes fetters on competition.    <I>Web JCLI  [1996] part 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/refereed/lauw.txt">Specialisation, accreditation and the legal profession in Australia and Canada</A>   by Inge<EM> Lauw</EM>.    An analysis and comparative evaluation of formal specialisation and accreditation programmes in Australia and Canada, as a means of improving the public's access to legal services.  Also examines the implications of these programmes on marketing and advertising by the legal profession.   <I>E Law Volume 1 No 2 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/kla.htm">Split-recovery statutes: the interplay of the takings and excessive fines clauses</A>   by Matthew<EM> Klaben</EM>.    This Note argues that a split-recovery statute giving the state a prejudgment interest in punitive damage awards does not constitute a taking if it limits the plaintiff's interest to a portion of the punitive award.   Punitive damage awards in jurisdictions having split-recovery statutes are likely to be subject to constitutional review for excessiveness.   Although a legislature could draft a split-recovery statute that is not subject to the limitations of the Takings or in Excessive Fines Clauses, such an objective poses serious practical difficulties.   <I>Cornell LR November 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/rodgers2.html">Standard of Proof in Care Order Applications under the Children Act 1989</A>   by M E <EM> Rodgers</EM>.    In re H and Others (Minors) [1995] 2 WLR 8, HL is the culmination of a series of appeals by the Nottingham County Council against the judgment of His Honour Judge Davidson on 23rd November 1994. The application for care orders under Children Act 1989, s 31, in respect of 3 children was refused. A subsequent appeal to the Court of Appeal was dismissed on 14th December 1994. The Local Authority appealed to the House of Lords, the matter being heard on 17 & 18th July 1995, with judgement reserved, and opinions being delivered on 14th December 1995.     <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   (casenote)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/mayss2.html">Statutory Reform of Choice of Law in Tort and Delict: A Bitter Pill or a Cure for the Ill?</A>   by Abla <EM> Mayss</EM>.    The common law rules on choice of law in tort in the field of Private International Law have long been criticised. The double-actionability rule in Phillips v Eyre (1868) tended to operate in favour of defendants. The exception, established in Boys v Chaplin (1971) and expanded in the Red Sea Case (1994), had created much uncertainty. This article examines the new provisions in Part III of the Private International Law (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1995 , and asks whether it is likely to be a cure   <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/eprints/le/papers/9506/9506001.abs">Stigma and Self-Fulfilling Expectations of Criminality</A>   by Eric <EM> Rasmusen</EM>.    A convicted criminal suffers not only from public penalties, but from stigma, the reluctance of others to interact with him economically and socially. Conviction can convey useful information about a person, which makes stigmatization an important and legitimate function of the criminal justice system, quite apart from moral considerations. Whether stigma will operate in this way depends on expectations and the crime rate, however, which can lead to multiple, pareto-ranked equilibria with different amounts of crime and stigma.     <I> </I>   (Postscript/PDF)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/dewees.html">Sulfur Dioxide Emissions from Smelters: The Historical Inefficiency of Tort Law</A>   by Donald N.<EM> Dewees</EM>.    This paper examines the success of tort law in dealing with the massive discharge of sulfur dioxide and toxic metals from non-ferrous smelters between 1890 and 1940. These large and isolated sources should have been the easiest of polluters to sue; there could be no doubt as to whose pollution caused the damage. But devastating pollution often survived litigation. To what extent were the external costs of pollution actually imposed on the polluter? Did injunctive relief or damages more closely approximate optimal pollution control? Were special commissions more or less adept at understanding and controlling the problem than the courts? The performance of the tort system is evaluated.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.hamline.edu/~jlr/survey94.html">Survey of Trends and Developments on Religious Liberty in the Courts 1994</A>   by Carl H.<EM> Esbeck</EM>.    The purpose of this survey is to note important case law developments in the state and lower federal courts concerning religious liberty. Purposely omitted are the widely reported United States Supreme Court opinions, as well as cases where the Supreme Court has granted review during the 1993-94 term. The focus here is on significant or interesting cases that may otherwise escape broad attention. Only the facts and rationale of each decision is summarized. No editorial comment on the merits of these cases is intended.   <I>10 J Law & Relig 544-572 (1993-94)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/horwitz.html">Swaps Ahoy! Should Regulators Voyage into Unknown Waters?</A>   by Marc A.<EM> Horwitz</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol3/no1/acaintro.html">Symposium: Introduction</A>   by Alfred C. <EM> Aman, Jr.</EM>.    There is strong evidence to suggest that increasing world trade and production has dramatically increased global pollution and that the legal regimes currently in place can be made more effective. If these treaties and organizations are but the first steps towards achieving an international approach to environmental quality, what should the next generation of international environmental laws, agencies, and approaches look like? Do we have the necessary legal framework in place to protect the global environment, or are new approaches and reforms necessary?    <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 3 Issue 1 Fall 1995</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
