<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   T</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/T.GIF" >
Essays by title :   T</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/chan.html">Taiwan's Application to the GATT: A New Urgency With the Conclusion of the Uruguay Round</A>   by Susanna<EM> Chan</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   (Note)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/wyeth.html">Takings as the Failure of the Regulatory Market</A>   by George<EM> Wyeth</EM>.    This paper suggests addressing the stubborn "takings" problem by using a hypothetical perfectly competitive "regulatory market" as a normative reference point. The paper contends that this approach allows us to resolve apparent tensions between past takings analyses, and reconcile apparently conflicting views about the desirability of compensation. It also examines the light that such an approach sheds on the generally discredited notion of a "harm-benefit" distinction -- arguing that the hypothetical market provides the "baseline" that allows such a distinction to be drawn.. This approach is seen to explain some hitherto difficult rulings, and to suggest changes in other areas.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-3h.html">Teaching Artificial Intelligence to Law Students</A>   by D.<EM> Hunter</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://condor.depaul.edu/ethics/gerde.html">Teaching Business Ethics Through Literature</A>   by Jon M. Shepard, Michael G. Goldsby and Virginia W. <EM> Gerde</EM>.    America's economic ideology lacks a vocabulary of ethics. If, as we assume, an economic system requires a moral component for long-term survival, students in business schools must be exposed to a vocabulary of ethics that is consistent with the ideology of capitalism. We present a vocabulary of ethics and describe an approach to teaching business ethics based on business-related classic literature and moral philosophy.      <I>The Online Journal of Ethics Vol. 1  No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-2i.html">Technology, Learning and the Trans-Atlantic divide</A>   by R. Susskind and A.<EM> Paterson</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.2</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles5/jarvis5.html">The Quiet Revolution - Improving Student Learning in Law" by Le Brun and Johnstone</A>   reviewed by Francoise <EM> Jarvis</EM>.       <I>[1995] Web JCLI No. 5</I>   
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/adler.html">Theory of Corporate Insolvency</A>   by Barry E<EM> Adler</EM>.    Modern scholarship on corporate bankruptcy proceeds from the premise that investors are willing to expend resources identifying and saving insolvent firms that can continue efficiently. In this paper, I argue that this premise may be faulty, at least for publicly held firms. Viewed properly, from an ex ante perspective, investors may wish to design initial capital structures that will produce few insolvent but viable firms. Consequently, in a world of unimpeded contractual choice, investors might forgo any collective insolvency process and permit a firm's dismemberment by individual creditors. I argue, accordingly, that corporate bankruptcy law is illegitimate for large firms, not because these firms face no collective action problem among creditors, but because it may be appropriate for these firms to suffer the consequences of any such problem. In the process of making this argument, I offer new explanations for three puzzling phenomena: the apparent investor acquiescience in the expensive American bankruptcy reorganization process; common equity's residual interest in a firm that fails to pay dividends on preferred stock; and asset-based finance.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/peterson.html">Theory Versus Fact in the Choice of Organizational Form: A Study of Body and Frame Production in the Automobile Industry</A>   by Laura Bennett Peterson and Thomas G.<EM> Marx</EM>.    Klein, Crawford and Alchian (hereinafter  "Klein") argue that relationship-specific assets raise problems of opportunism, escalate the cost of market  contracting, and explain General Motors' vertical integration into body manufacturing. We set forth in our paper the theoretical debate between Coase and Klein. Coase understates, we believe, the extent to which the cost of contracts rises with the risk of opportunism. We study the General Motors-Fisher Body relationship after GM's acquisition of its body supplier. A relationship is seen between asset specificity and internal, as well as external, transactions costs. We examine the historical relationships between other automobile companies and their body suppliers. We find a range of customer-supplier relationships -- from total integration, to tapered integration, to no integration and from long-term contracts, to short-term contracts, to no contracts. Such a range of relationships undermines any deterministic conclusion that asset specificity dictates vertical  integration.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/valdes2.pag">Tracking and Assessing the (Non)Inclusion of Courses on Sexuality and/or Sexual Orientation in the American Law School Curriculum: Reports From the Field After a Decade of Effort </A>   by Francisco <EM> Valdes</EM>.    In this article Prof. Valdes presents his survey of American law schools offering courses pertaining to sexual orientation and sexuality issues and expresses "cautious optimism" about the future inclusion of gay and lesbian issues in legal curricula.    <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/clay.html">Trade without Law: Private-Order Institutions in Mexican California</A>   by Karen<EM> Clay</EM>.    This paper examines the role played by a private-order institution in California in the growth of a complex system of trade in the absence of law. This institution, a coalition, governed agency relations among the merchants in California. A reputation mechanism supported by an information network, behavioral norms, and expectations regarding who was a member mitigated the commitment problem inherent in having individuals handle goods that they did not own by linking a merchant's past behavior and his future payoff. A game-theoretic model of the agent's commitment problem motivated by primary evidence from the merchants' correspondence on individual transactions is presented. Predictions that follow from the model explain patterns of social and economic behavior, the organization of trade, and the coalition's response to exogenous shocks.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.urich.edu/~jolt/v1i1/burk.html">Trademarks Along the Infobahn: A First Look at the Emerging Law of Cybermarks </A>   by Dan L. <EM> Burk </EM>.       <I>Richmond Journal of Law and Technology   vol.1 no.1 (Spring 1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/sprince1.html">Trustees' duty to defend - Look before you leap, when to leap and how high</A>   by Alan<EM> Sprince</EM>.    Fear of exposure to costs is a dominant influence in concentrating the minds of litigants, actual and potential.  For trustees, however, the dilemma is more complex. The precise nature of the duty to defend proceedings - was examined and refined by Lightman J in the recent case of Alsop Wilkinson (A Firm) v Neary ([1995] 1 All ER 431, Ch D).   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   (casenote)
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="/TITLES/A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Q.HTM">Q</A> |  <A HREF="/TITLES/R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Z.HTM">Z</A> 
