<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   U</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/U.GIF" >
Essays by title :   U</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/passel.html">U.S. Immigration in a Global Context: Past, Present, and Future</A>   by Jeffrey S. Passel and Michael<EM> Fix</EM>.    Through the use of their own empirical studies, the authors address three themes: (1) immigration in the global context; (2) the scale and characteristics of immigration to the United States; and (3) the expected future impact of immigration to the United States. The authors conclude that the situation is not dire; rather, they believe that the ties created by immigrants may become increasingly important to the United States in an interrelated world economy.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/calavita.html">U.S. Immigration Policy: Contradictions and Projections for the Future</A>   by Kitty<EM> Calavita</EM>.    What will become of immigration barriers in the future, particularly given the globalization of capital and the increasing free trade of goods?  And second, is democratic rule antithetical to or destructive of such barriers.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 2 Issue 1 Fall 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol2/no2/christop.html">U.S. Policy toward the New Independent States: A Pragmatic Strategy Grounded in America's Fundamental Interests </A>   by Warren <EM> Christopher</EM>.       <I>Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies Volume 2 Issue 2 Spring 1995 </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/rose.html">U.S.-Japan Trading Relationship and Its Effects</A>   by Richard<EM> Rosecrance</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/choo2.html">Undercover Police Operations and What the Suspect said (or didn't say)</A>   by Manda Mellors and Andrew L-T<EM> Choo</EM>.    This paper is about the legal regulation of undercover police operations. A number of recent cases, notably the celebrated cases of Keith Hall and Colin Stagg in 1994, provide instances of undercover operations which apparently have as an aim the extraction of confessions from suspects. This paper examines the adequacy of the relevant executive and judicial pronouncements on undercover police operations.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="gopher://portia.murdoch.edu.au/00/.ftp/pub/subj/law/jnl/elaw/current/colaw.txt">Understanding Company Law: Computer Tutorials"</A>   reviewed by Pei Teing<EM> Kee</EM>.    Student review of a computerised tutorial package for use in teaching Australian company law.   <I>E-Law Vol.1 No.4 1994</I>   (review)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles3/collins3.html">Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1994</A>   by Brian St.J<EM> Collins</EM>.    This article examines the substantive provisions of the Unfair Terms in Consumer Contracts Regulations 1994 and compares the protection which these Regulations will afford to consumers with that which is currently available under common law and statutory provisions, in particular the Unfair Contract Terms Act 1977.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 3</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/wood.html">United States Antitrust Law in the Global Market</A>   by Diane P.<EM> Wood</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/kar.htm">Unlucky Thirteenth: a constitutional amendment in search of a doctrine</A>   by Lauren<EM> Kares</EM>.    *Steirer* is not anomalous; in fact, the Thirteenth Amendment is notable for its lack of a coherent jurisprudence.  This Note argues that a balancing test like the one used by the *Steirer* trial court is more useful and truer to the Thirteenth Amendment's vision of liberty than the criminal standard used by the appellate court.  Consistent application of a balancing test would afford the Thirteenth Amendment a degree of elasticity and relevance that it now lacks.   <I>Cornell LR January 1995</I>   (note)
<HR>
<LI>The <A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/scott2.html">Use of Public Interest Immunity Claims in Criminal Cases</A>   by The Right Hon. Sir Richard <EM> Scott</EM>.    Sir Richard Scott suggests that the application to criminal trials of Public Interest Immunity principles derived from civil cases and designed for application in civil cases has been a mistake and has acted as an impediment to the evolution of satisfactory principles for dealing with PII claims in criminal trials. Sir Richard goes on to suggest what should be the correct approach to PII claims in criminal trials.     <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI>"<A HREF="http://www.tourolaw.edu/AboutTLC/journals/lawreview/vol12n1/part4.htm">Use" and the irresistible impulse to legislate </A>   by Robert C. <EM> Dorf</EM>.    The purpose of this article is to discuss the loss of the possession-use distinction. It is possible that both Congress and the New York legislature will amend the statutes in question to punish both "use" and "possession" of firearms at the same level. It is impossible to applaud judicial hammering of statutory "possession" into "use" which is contrary to legislative intent.     <I>Touro Law Review (Volume 12, No.1 1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/auburn1.html">Usenet News And The Law</A>   by Francis<EM> Auburn</EM>.    In Rindos v Hardwick (1994) the Western Australia Supreme Court awarded damages for defamation arising out of an item in a newsgroup published on the Internet. This comment examines the decision and considers its wider implications both for users of the Internet and service providers on the Internet.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   (casenote)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj2-1a.html">Using Artificial Intelligence in Legal Computer Assisted Instruction</A>   by R.<EM> Jones</EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.2, No.1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://ltc.law.warwick.ac.uk/ltj3-1e.html">Using computers in the classroom: An electronic discussion</A>   <EM> </EM>.       <I>Law Technology Journal Vol.3, No.1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://law.fsu.edu/lawreview/issues/232/ehrhardt.html">Using leading questions during direct examination</A>   by Stephanie J. Young and Charles W. <EM> Ehrhardt </EM>.    Historically, limitations upon a party's impeaching its own witness and upon using leading questions during direct examination have been intertwined. Clarification of this area began in 1990, when the Florida Legislature amended section 90.608, Florida Statutes, to permit impeachment of a party's own witness. In 1995, the Florida Legislature amended section 90.612(3), Florida Statutes, to provide for the use of leading questions during direct examination. This Article traces the development of the Florida Rules of Civil Procedure and the Florida Statutes from before the adoption of the Florida Evidence Code to the present.    <I>Florida State University Law Review Vol 23 (Fall 1995, No.2)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/oconnell.html">Using Trade to Enforce International Environmental Law :   Implications for United States Law</A>   by Mary Ellen<EM> O'Connell</EM>.       <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 2 Spring 1994</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="/TITLES/A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Q.HTM">Q</A> |  <A HREF="/TITLES/R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Z.HTM">Z</A> 
