<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Essays by title :   W</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE  SRC="/GIFS/W.GIF" >
Essays by title :   W</H1>
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/files/hartwell.pag">What a Difference a Gay Makes:  An Empirical Study of the Impact of 'Out' Gay Law Faculty on Law School Curriculum and Policies</A>   by Steven <EM> Hartwell</EM>.    In this article Prof. Hartwell presents a study of out gay faculty in American law schools and the correlation between out gay faculty and gay student activity.    <I>The National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law Volume 1, Issue 2 (1995)</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mercury.ll.georgetown.edu/olin/papers/katz3a.html">When Should an Offer Stick? The Economics of Promissory Estoppel in Preliminary Negotiations (forthcoming, Yale Law Journal, 1996) </A>   by Avery <EM> Katz </EM>.    Under the modern doctrine of promissory estoppel, a person making an offer is bound when the offeree relies, even in the absence of an acceptance or any explicit negotiation for a binding option. But courts have generally declined to construe the offeree's reliance as an acceptance or as a promise to accept. This paper considers the incentive effects of this rule for the optimal timing of contract formation and reliance. In preliminary negotiations both parties have some control over the timing of reliance, but the rule of law affects their relative incentives to exercise this control. I argue that the efficiency of promissory estoppel in preliminary negotiations depends in large part on which party holds the bulk of the bargaining power ex post.    <I> </I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/1996/issue2/parkin2.html">Where now on Mental Incapacity?</A>   by Alan <EM> Parkin</EM>.    The investigation carried out by the Law Commission into mental incapacity and ways in which the law in relation to it might be regularised has been exhaustive and thorough. The decision not to proceed with the resulting draft bill in its present form leaves matters, for the moment, in limbo. The constituency affected is large but its members are easily overlooked. Is it the case that the long awaited regularisation of their legal position is to be delayed because of fears, which may be groundless, that the recommendations make euthanasia more likely? Will doubts about some aspects of the report prevent or unduly delay straightforward and non-controversial reforms which will affect the lives of many   <I>Web Journal of Currrent Legal Issues [1996] part 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles1/thomps1.html">Whitehall's Cultural Revolution</A>   by Brian<EM> Thompson</EM>.    The Government has issued a White Paper on the Civil Service which is, in part, a response to a report of the Sub-Committee of the House of Commons Treasury and Civil Service Select Committee. The White Paper is significant in that the Government has abandoned its opposition to some of the Sub-Committee's recommendations, in particular a new Code of Conduct for the Civil Service which includes an independent appeal procedure.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 1</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/~nlawwww/articles2/gilb2.html">Who has Jurisdiction for Cross-Frontier Financial Crimes?</A>   by Geoff<EM> Gilbert</EM>.    This article has been prompted by the Nick Leeson case, where a trader in the Japanese derivatives market was working in Singapore, but whose activities had the effect of bringing down Barings, the oldest merchant bank in the City of London. It considers which State should have jurisdiction in these circumstances, particularly since the alleged criminal may now be in a third State.   <I>Web Journal of Current Legal Issues [1995] No. 2</I>   
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.epas.utoronto.ca:8080/ecolaw/alea/archive/brinig.html">Why Can't a Woman Be More Like a Man? Or Do Gender Differences Affect Choice ?</A>   by Margaret F<EM> Brinig</EM>.    The question explored in this paper is whether a woman operates like a man when making choices.  In the first section, I present some empirical data consistent with theories of innate gender difference in attitudes towards risk. In each case, however, at least one other explanation for the results cannot be ruled out. The next section discusses whether women are more altruistic than men. Several empirical evaluations of altruism reveal no measurable difference based upon gender, except for findings that women do more housework and spend more time with children even when working the same number of hours as men. Finally, I conclude with some very preliminary experimental results on gender and time preference. The empirical work provided in this paper includes fairly extensive testing of risk aversion and more limited information about differential altruism and discount rates. Women do seem to behave quite distinctively when their choices involve their families. However but their decisionmaking is otherwise similar to that of men, except that women are more risk averse.   <I>American Law and Economics Association Conference Paper Berkeley May 1995</I>   (PostScript)
<HR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/clr/lei.htm">Why grand juries do not (and cannot) protect the accused</A>   by Andrew D<EM> Leipold</EM>.    The weakness in the system lies less with the procedures employed than with the characteristics of the decisionmakers.   Rather than being asked to find facts and apply those facts to the law, the jurors are presented with a single set of facts, instructed on the law by the prosecutor, and asked to decide whether those undisputed facts are sufficient to satisfy a specific legal test - the probable cause standard.  Even reasonable, independent-minded jurors will defer to the prosecutor's judgment that an indictment should issue.   <I>Cornell LR January 1995</I>   
<HR>
<LI>A <A HREF="http://www.law.indiana.edu/glsj/vol1/katz.html">World of Regions:   America, Europe, and East Asia</A>   by Peter J.<EM> Katzenstein</EM>.    Recent events in world politics are creating a substantial break in the history of international politics comparable in this century only to the years 1917-22 and 1947-53. With specific reference to Germany and Europe as well as to Japan and East Asia, this essay argues that these changes in world politics tend to reinforce a new political regionalism that expresses different norms, which, in the foreseeable future, are unlikely to be assimilated fully into one normative global order.   <I>Indiana Global Legal Studies Journal Volume 1 Issue 1 Fall 1993</I>   
<HR>

<BR>
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="/TITLES/A.HTM">A</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/B.HTM">B</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/C.HTM">C</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/D.HTM">D</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/E.HTM">E</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/F.HTM">F</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/G.HTM">G</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/H.HTM">H</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/I.HTM">I</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/J.HTM">J</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/K.HTM">K</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/L.HTM">L</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/M.HTM">M</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/N.HTM">N</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/O.HTM">O</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/P.HTM">P</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Q.HTM">Q</A> |  <A HREF="/TITLES/R.HTM">R</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/S.HTM">S</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/T.HTM">T</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/U.HTM">U</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/V.HTM">V</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/W.HTM">W</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/X.HTM">X</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Y.HTM">Y</A> | <A HREF="/TITLES/Z.HTM">Z</A> 
