<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>What is CELS ?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="cels.gif" ALT="Centre for European Legal Studies"></A>
</CENTER>
<BR>
Since 1991 the Centre for European Legal Studies (CELS) has provided a new focus in the Cambridge Law Faculty for activities in the field of European Community Law and European Comparative Law.  Consistently with the traditions of the Faculty, the interests of the Centre embrace not only the new legal order which, since the 1950s, has been evolving on the basis of the European Community Treaties but also the national jurisdictions of the different European countries, including those of the former Eastern Bloc, and their relationship with the common law. 
<P>
The main concerns of CELS are to encourage individual and collaborative research of the highest international quality on matters falling within its remit and, through a programme of lectures and seminars, to disseminate knowledge and understanding of those matters among the academic and the wider community.  Participation in its work by distinguished specialists from outside Cambridge has been facilitated through the establishment of Visiting Fellowships.  CELS is also playing a leading part in developing the study of the common law and European Community Law in Poland and other countries of Central and Eastern Europe, by helping to organise teaching on the spot, as well as a distance-learning programme.  It is active in arranging exchange schemes for staff and students between Cambridge and the other leading Law Schools of Europe.
<P>
Director: Professor A. A. Dashwood<BR>
Assistant Director:  Dr S&iacuteofra O'Leary<BR>
Chairman of the Committee of Management: Professor DEJ Johnston<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="home.htm">Back to CELS home page</A>


</BODY>
