<HTML><BODY   BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><HEAD><TITLE>DOCTORAL RESEARCH</TITLE></HEAD><H1><IMG ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE  ALT="crest" SRC="CAM2.GIF" ><A NAME="CDR"><B> Doctoral Research</B></H1><BODY><CENTER><IMG SRC="BLUEBAR.GIF"></CENTER><center><IMG  ALT="new" SRC="NEW.GIF"><A HREF="STUDENTS/STUDENT.HTM">New Students' Page!</A> - <A HREF="PHDLIST.HTM">Current Doctoral Research</A></p></center><H3>Ph.D. in Criminology</H3><P>Studying for the Ph.D. in the Institute of Criminology involves writing a dissertation of up to 80,000 words in length. The dissertation must represent a significant contribution to learning, for example, through the discovery of new knowledge, the connection of previously unrelated facts, the development of new theory, or the revision of old views.  In exceptional cases candidates may apply for an extension to the word limit, though extensions are not easily obtained and full reasons must be set out in a letter of application to the Board of Graduate Studies.  (Such applications have to be supported by Supervisors.) </P><P> Each Ph.D. student is allocated to a supervisor who is responsible for the general direction of that student's work over the course of the three-year period during which the Ph.D. is undertaken.  The supervisor usually plays a central role in assisting the student's research work, helping devise the framework within which the study is pursued, and advising on all aspects of the writing of the dissertation itself.  Frequency of meetings between students and their supervisors is a matter of mutual agreement, and varies according to the stage of the dissertation work and an individual's particular needs.  Most supervisors see their students once every two weeks during their first term of study, and may then move to less frequent meetings when the work is well under way.</P>  <P>The supervisor reports on a student's work annually to the Board of Graduate Studies; supervisors are also required to support a student's request for special arrangements which may be needed, such as leave to work away, or permission to intermit.</P><hr><P><h3>Admission</h3>Please see the page on <A HREF="ADDMI.HTM">Graduate Admission</A> elsewhere on this server.  Interested persons are encouraged to contact Dr Loraine Gelsthorpe or Dr David Thomas directly.<p><hr><h3>Training and Development Programme: (Director,<BR> Dr Loraine Gelsthorpe)</h3>The Institute of Criminology runs a comprehensive Training and Development Programme for its Ph.D. Students.</P>Weekly Research Group Sessions develop research skills, technique and thinking. There are regular Reading Groups, and students are able to attend various Inter-departmental Ph.D. Research Workshops. Experts on statistics and computing are available for consultation by prior arrangement, and general Computing Courses are run by the University's Computing Centre.</p><BR><center><IMG  ALT="new" SRC="NEW.GIF"><A HREF="STUDENTS/STUDENT.HTM">Go to the new Students' Page! </A><IMG  ALT="new" SRC="NEW.GIF"></center><A HREF="COURSES1.HTM"><IMG SRC="BACK.GIF" border="0">Back to the Courses Page</A></P><hr><CENTER><A HREF="iochpg.htm">|Institute|</A> <A HREF="staff.htm">|Staff|</A><A HREF="courses1.htm">|Courses|</A> <A HREF="research.htm">|Research|</A><A HREF="libhpg.htm">|Library|</A> <A HREF="pubs.htm">|Publications|</A><A HREF="crimlink.htm">|Links|</A> <A HREF="http://www.cam.ac.uk/">|University|</A></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
