<HTML><BODY  BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><HEAD><TITLE>The Admissions Procedure</TITLE></HEAD><H1><IMG ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE  ALT="crest" SRC="CAM2.GIF" ><B> The Admissions Procedure</B></H1><CENTER><IMG SRC="BLUEBAR.GIF"></CENTER><H4>The Application Procedure</H4><P>Prospective candidates for the M.Phil., M.Sc.., M.Litt. or Ph.D. Degrees should request a copy of the Institute Prospectus, the <A HREF="http://www.cam.ac.uk/CambUniv/GSProspectus/index.html">Graduate Prospectus</A> and an application form (C.I.G.A.S. form A.) from<B> Kate Curry, Graduate Studies Secretary,  Institute of Criminology, 7 West Road, Cambridge, CB3 9DT</B> or from the Secretary of the Board of Graduate Studies, 4, Mill Lane, Cambridge, CB2 1RZ.  The Institute of Criminology welcomes applications from students of all nationalities. Applications should be submitted no later than the end of March in the year in which candidates wish to come to Cambridge. Later applications may be considered, but such candidates may find that a decision is delayed or that it takes longer to be accepted by a college.</P><P>Prospective candidates may find it helpful to telephone or write to Dr David Thomas (the Admissions Officer), Dr Trevor Bennett (the Director of the M.Phil. course), or Dr Loraine Gelsthorpe (the Director of the Ph.D. Programme) at the Institute of Criminology before submitting their formal application.</P><P>Candidates for the M.Phil. degree should submit a short statement (of about 300 words) with their formal applications, on their reasons for wishing to take the course, and a sample of written work.</P><P>Candidates who wish to take the M.Phil. degree by thesis only, or who wish to be admitted directly to carry out research for the M.Litt. or Ph.D. degree without taking the M.Phil., should include a detailed research proposal and samples of their written work with their formal applications. </P><H4>The Academic Year</H4><P>The Cambridge teaching terms for the 1996-1997 academic year are as follows:<BR><UL><LI>Michaelmas Term	8 October	- 6 December 1996<LI>Lent Term	              4 January	- 14 March 1997<LI>Easter Term	                 22 April   - 13 June 1997</UL></P><H4>Choosing a College</H4><P>All graduate students of the University must be members of a college. Colleges differ in many ways and prospective students should try to identify the colleges which are likely to be most suitable for them. Some students prefer the informal atmosphere of all-graduate colleges, while others prefer the more traditional arrangements of the older Colleges. </P><H4>Residence Requirement</H4><P>All graduate courses involve full-time residence in the University of Cambridge for at least a minimum period. Although undergraduates are usually in residence only during term-time, graduate students, in particular those who are candidates for research degrees, are generally in residence continuously throughout the year, apart perhaps from short breaks taken in the periods between terms. Residing in the University means, for research students and those taking most other graduate courses, living within a distance of 10 miles from the centre of Cambridge.</P><H4>Expenses</H4><P>The University Fee for graduate students for the year 1995-96 was 2,430 for those from the UK or EC and 5,886 for those from overseas (non-UK or EC). All students at Cambridge University must belong to a College and will be charged a College Fee which varies from College to College (the estimated average cost for 1996-97 is 1,615 for the year). In addition to the cost of University and College fees, graduate students will need to show evidence that they have financial support to cover their maintenance and living expenses. It is estimated that United Kingdom students admitted in October 1995 will require at least 4,150 to cover subsistence costs (excluding travelling expenses) for a 9 month period of stay, and EC or Overseas students at least 4,610. </P><H4>Competence in the English Language</H4><P>Applicants who are not native speakers of English must possess a fluent command of the language, at a level approaching native-user standard, before admission to the University. The Board of Graduate Studies requires such applicants to submit with their application for admission a formal certificate or similar document showing their present level of proficiency in English, preferably an assessment made through the English Language Testing Service (ELTS) test or International English Testing System (IELTS) test of the Cambridge Local Examinations Syndicate jointly with the British Council and, in the case of IELTS, the International Development Program of Australian Universities and Colleges. Failure to submit this evidence will delay consideration of the application. The University's normal minimum  requirement is an Overall Band score of 7.0 with no  individual element of the Test  scoring below  6.0.  Applicants whose score in the ELTS or IELTS test is less than that required will  normally be required to achieve at least that score before an offer of admission can be confirmed. The minimum overall score normally accepted as satisfying the requirement for evidence of competence in English from those offering TOEFL is 600 with, in addition, a minimum score of 5.0 in the TOEFL Test of Written English.</P><HR><CENTER><A HREF="iochpg.htm">|Institute|</A> <A HREF="staff.htm">|Staff|</A><A HREF="courses1.htm">|Courses|</A> <A HREF="research.htm">|Research|</A><A HREF="libhpg.htm">|Library|</A> <A HREF="pubs.htm">|Publications|</A><A HREF="crimlink.htm">|Links|</A> <A HREF="http://www.cam.ac.uk/">|University|</A><A HREF="phd.htm#cdr">|Students|</A></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
