asis.</P><BR>The seminar-course options offered in the year 1995-1996 were:<BR> <I>Michaelmas Term Options</I><UL><LI>Crime and Criminals in Modern Societies<LI>The Criminal Justice Process<LI>Supplementary Qualitative Methods (not assessed)<LI>Feminist Perspectives<LI>Criminological and Legal Psychology<LI>Issues in Criminal Law<LI>Sentencing<LI>Sociology of Crime and Deviance<LI>Psychiatry and Crime</UL><BR><I>Lent Term Options</I><UL><LI>Issues in Penal Theory<LI>Supplementary Quantitative Methods (not assessed)<LI>Sexual Science and the Law<LI>Victims<LI>Police Powers<LI>Crime Prevention<LI>Criminalising Minorities<LI>Fraud Prevention and Control<LI>Prisons<LI>The Mentally Disordered in the Criminal Justice System</UL><BR><H3>Visits</H3><P>A number of optional visits to criminal justice agencies are arranged for M.Phil. students for the Michaelmas and Lent Terms. These include visits to Holloway Prison in London and to at least two prisons outside London. Visits are also arranged to police stations and headquarters when there is suitable demand. It is also possible to arrange short placements for individual students at these or other criminal justice agencies in order to conduct research or for general experience.</P><H3>Career prospects</H3><P>Postgraduate study or research in Criminology in Cambridge provides a useful preparation for a wide variety of careers, as the experience of past students illustrates. A substantial number of M.Phil. graduates are now engaged in University teaching or criminological research all over the world. Many of the remainder have embarked on careers in the legal profession or in the probation, prison, police, or social services. A number of students began a career in one of these fields before coming to Cambridge and have returned to it subsequently. Other former students of the Institute now hold positions in government and voluntary service organisations.</P><H3>M.Phil. in Criminology by long thesis</H3><P>In exceptional circumstances, it is possible for suitably qualified students to take the M.Phil. entirely by thesis. This method of taking the M.Phil. is permitted only to exceptional students and with the special permission of the Degree Committee of the Faculty of Law. A suitable candidate for the M.Phil. by long thesis would normally be one who had substantial prior qualifications in Criminology and/or substantial experience in the criminal justice system. The student must submit a thesis no longer than 35,000 words (including footnotes and appendices) on a topic approved by the Degree Committee. All students taking the M.Phil. by long thesis will also have an oral examination at the end of June. </P><P>Candidature of the M.Phil. by long thesis is normally only allowed if this has been agreed as part of the admissions procedure. Potential candidates interested in this possibility are encouraged to raise the matter at an early date.</P><HR><CENTER><A HREF="iochpg.htm">|Institute|</A> <A HREF="staff.htm">|Staff|</A><A HREF="courses1.htm">|Courses|</A> <A HREF="research.htm">|Research|</A><A HREF="libhpg.htm">|Library|</A> <A HREF="pubs.htm">|Publications|</A><A HREF="crimlink.htm">|Links|</A> <A HREF="http://www.cam.ac.uk/">|University|</A><A HREF="phd.htm#cdr">|Students|</A></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
