<HEAD><TITLE>The Cambridge Diploma and Masters' Degree in Applied Criminology</TITLE></HEAD>

<CENTER>

<H1> 

<I>The Cambridge Diploma and Masters' Degree in Applied Criminology</H1></I>

</CENTER>

<CENTER>

<IMG SRC="bluebar.gif">

</CENTER>

<BR><P>

The new Diploma and Master's Degree in Applied Criminology has been developed as part of the partnership between National Police Training and the University of Cambridge to provide training for potential chief police officers in the study of crime and crime-related issues.  The training is conducted in part at Bramshill as an integral part of the Strategic Command Course (SCC) and in part in Cambridge for those officers who want to proceed to one of the academic qualifications.</P>

<STRONG>Aims</STRONG><BR>

<P>The programme has the twin aims of: (1) introducing senior police officers to the findings of research with the view of developing a critical ability to use this material for strategic planning; and (2) providing high-quality instruction which will enable officers attending the course to work towards one or both of the academic qualifications listed above.</P>

<P>The main purpose of the programme is to enable senior police officers to make use of the research knowledge base as part of their day-to-day thinking and decision making.  In order to enable this, the course aims: (1) to increase awareness of the existence of research and the range of information available, (2) to enable senior police officers to evaluate critically research methods and findings, and (3) to provide a framework for them to use research in strategic policy and planning.</P>

<STRONG>Course Design</STRONG>

<P>The Diploma and Master's Degree in Applied Criminology are an integrated part of the SCC.</P>

<P>The Diploma is a one-year, part-time course comprising three formal teaching blocks, each of two-weeks duration.  The first block (Block A) is taught at Bramshill Police Staff College as a compulsory part of the SCC.  The second block (Block B) is taught at Bramshill as an optional part of the SCC.  The third block (Block C) is taught at Cambridge for those students wishing to study for the Diploma. Students will be given assessment work to be completed in their own time.</P><P>

The Master of Studies Degree in Applied Criminology is designed for students who have successfully completed (to a required standard) the Diploma. The Master's Degree requires further part-time study which will involve some time in Cambridge (the exact period of time required is yet to be decided, but will not exceed 6 weeks).</P>

<P>Interested persons should contact Dr Trevor Bennett for further information.</P>

