 <HTML><BODY   BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><HEAD> <TITLE>THE CROPWOOD FELLOWSHIP              PROGRAMME</TITLE></HEAD><H2><IMG  ALIGN=CENTER SRC="CAM2.GIF" ALT="crest"> Cropwood Fellowship Programme</H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="BLUEBAR.GIF"></CENTER><H3>The Programme</H3><P>The Cropwood Programme of Fellowship awards was set up in 1968 as a means of enablingpractitioners in the criminal justice field to make a contribution to knowledge in their areaof interest by undertaking a small piece of research or intensive study of a particular topic. There are no restrictions on the topics for study which may be proposed; applications arejudged entirely on their merits.  However, the Selection Committee will welcome especiallystudies which address, directly or indirectly, the issues of race relations policy and equalopportunities, within the criminal justice system.</P><H3>Eligibility</H3><P>Cropwood Fellowships are open to practitioners, managers, and policy makers of all gradesin the field of criminal justice (eg. judges, magistrates, police and probation officers, prisonstaff, psychologists, community agency workers, youth workers, victim support workers,etc.).  The annual award of Fellowships is made strictly on the basis of open competition.</P><P>Candidates for a Fellowship are not required to hold any formal educational or professionalqualifications.  It is usual, however, for candidates to have had several years' experience intheir particular field, and to be eligible for secondment on full salary by their employers forthe period of the Fellowship.  Cropwood Fellows can spend up to twelve weeks in theInstitute, either in one block or spaced out over the year to fit in with their projects andcircumstances.  The awards are not given for work on degrees, nor are they available tothose in full-time academic work.</P><H3>Allowances</H3><P>Fellows are given an allowance towards living expenses in Cambridge (rate available onrequest), and the reimbursement of travel expenses (if any) in connection with their researchor study is considered.  Payment for travel between a Fellow's home and Cambridge is notmade.</P><H3>Resources available to Fellows</H3><P>Upon appointment, Cropwood Fellows are allocated an advisor, either a member of staff ofthe Institute or an experienced researcher within the field being studied.  Fellows areencouraged to look to their advisor for advice, help and guidance with their project or studyprogramme.</P><P>Fellows are provided with study accommodation within the Institute and they have full useof the Radzinowicz Library, one of the most extensive criminological and penologicalcollections in the country.  They may also use the main University Library.  Both micro andmainframe computing facilities are available, including word processing.  Fellows are grantedmembership of the University Centre; are welcome to join in the seminar programme of theInstitute, and they are encouraged to feel a part of the academic life of the Institutegenerally.</P><H3>Applications</H3><P>The Programme runs on an annual basis.  Fellowships are advertised in the summer andformal applications must arrive by the end of September.  Short-listed candidates are theninterviewed and successful Fellows are appointed for the following year.  The Director ofStudies warmly welcomes informal discussion of possible proposals and can advise on whatis expected by the Selection Committee.  The Director of Studies also welcomes discussionswith employing bodies interested in the Programme.</P><P>Formal applications should be made to the Director of Studies at the address shown below. They should contain a detailed proposal and programme for research or study.  Applicationsmust be accompanied by a curriculum vitae, the names of two referees, and (whereapplicable) confirmation of the agreement of the applicant's employer.</P><H3>Staff of the Programme</H3><UL><LI>Director of Studies:   <A HREF="staff/KRARUP.HTM"> Helen Krarup</A><LI>Cropwood Secretary:  Helen Ruddy</UL><H3>Address for enquiries and applications</H3><I><P>The Cropwood Fellowship Programme<BR>The Institute of Criminology<BR>University of Cambridge<BR>7 West Road<BR>Cambridge<BR>CB3 9DT<BR><BR>Tel:   (Director of Studies) +44 1223 335375<BR>           (Secretary) +44 1223 335364<BR>         (Switchboard) +44 1223 335360 <BR>Fax:  +44 1223 335356<BR>email: hek</I>10<I>@cus.cam.ac.uk</P></I><HR><CENTER><A HREF="iochpg.htm">|Institute|</A> <A HREF="staff.htm">|Staff|</A><A HREF="courses1.htm">|Courses|</A> <A HREF="research.htm">|Research|</A><A HREF="libhpg.htm">|Library|</A> <A HREF="pubs.htm">|Publications|</A><A HREF="crimlink.htm">|Links|</A> <A HREF="http://www.cam.ac.uk/">|University|</A><A HREF="phd.htm#cdr">|Students|</A></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
