<HTML><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><HEAD><TITLE>The Institute of Criminology</TITLE></HEAD><IMG ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE  ALT="crest" SRC="CAM2.GIF"> <IMG  ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="IOC2.GIF"><BODY><CENTER><IMG SRC="BLUEBAR.GIF"></CENTER><br><Center><strong>Institute of Criminology,<br>7 West Road, Cambridge, CB3 9DT, England<BR>Tel. +44 1223 335360<BR>Fax  +44 1223 335356<br>http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/crim/iochpg.htm<br></strong></center><br><a href="http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/crim/iochpg.htm"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT border=0 hspace=10 vspace=5 ALT="Red door" SRC="IOCDOOR.GIF"></a>The Institute of Criminology was founded by the University of Cambridge in 1959 with a generous donation from the Wolfson Foundation. It has a strong international reputation for academic excellence for both its teaching and research. The Institute is part of the <a href="http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/">Faculty of Law</a>, but has a multi-disciplinary teaching and research staff recruited from sociology, psychiatry and psychology as well as law. Around 35 people work at the Institute, including 18 senior staff, and there are about 50 M.Phil. and 30 Ph.D. students. Lecturers and Visiting Fellows from Britain, North America, Europe and the Commonwealth contribute to its teaching programme. The Institute has been awarded the highest grades for its teaching and research programmes in the most recent ESRC, UFC and HEFCE evaluations.<P><a href="http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/crim/LIBHPG.HTM"><IMG ALIGN=right border=0 ALT="Sir Leon" SRC="SIRLEON.GIF"></a>The Institute's <a href="http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/crim/LIBHPG.HTM">Radzinowicz Library of Criminology</a> is named after Sir Leon Radzinowicz (right), the first Director of the Institute and Wolfson Professor of Criminology (1959-73). The library has one of the world's largest collections on crime, deviance and related topics, including a wide selection of periodicals, pamphlets and publications of historical, as well as contemporary, interest. It holds over 36,000 books and 15,000 pamphlets, and receives 250 periodicals annually. The library's catalogue can be accessed anywhere in the world via 'Telnet' - further details are given on the Library page.<P>The Institute provides various <a href="http://www.law.cam.ac.uk/crim/COURSES1.htm">courses</a>, including a nine-month course of study in Criminology for the M.Phil. Degree (the largest full-time post-graduate Criminology course in the UK), a Ph.D. programme, various courses for undergraduate degrees, the Cropwood Fellowship Programme (for practitioners in the criminal justice system), and a new M.St. Degree/Diploma  in Applied Criminology.<P>In addition to the above courses, the Institute runs a regular series of Seminars given by Guest Speakers, which are open to all staff and students.<p><a href="LAW.JPG"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT hspace=10 border=0 ALT="Law Faculty" SRC="SLAW.GIF"></a>Students and staff at the Institute of Criminology are also able to use various facilities in the University of Cambridge. The Institute is situated next to the new Law Faculty, designed by Sir Norman Foster, who is also the architect of the proposed new Institute of Criminology building. The Law Faculty provides excellent study and research facilities (pictured - click image to view full size). The Institute is also just one minute's walk from the <a href="http://www.cam.ac.uk/Libraries/">University Library</a>, which holds one of the largest collections of books and periodicals in Britain.  Lastly, there are various College and Departmental Libraries, across the University, many of which allow book access to members of the Institute.<p>All students, and most academic staff, are also members of one of the Cambridge Colleges. The Colleges vary in size, age and style, but share the same central task: to bring people together from a wide range of intellectual disciplines. Most Colleges offer accommodation, dining facilities, and a bar (all at reasonable cost), as well as common rooms, various social events, and sporting facilities. Many Colleges now have their own web site, with <a href="http://www.cam.ac.uk/UnivInfoRes.html#colleges">further details and photographs</a>.<p><H2>How to reach us:</H2><a href="IOCMAP.GIF"><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT hspace=5  ALT="Cambridge Map" border=0 SRC="SIOCMAP.GIF"></a><strong>By Car: </strong>South/West - M25, M11 (exit junction 12) or A1 to A10.  North - A1 to A14 (A604).  East - A14 (A45).  (<strong>Click</strong> the map to view at full size.)<p><strong>By Train: </strong>There are frequent trains to Cambridge from London (King's Cross & Liverpool Street stations). There is a <A HREF="http://www.cam.ac.uk/CambArea/Trains/index.html">timetable</A> on the University's server.<p><strong><P>By Air: </strong><a href="http://www.theaa.co.uk/AAGuide/reg25txt.html">Stansted Airport</a> is the nearest to Cambridge, Luton Airport is fairly close, and Heathrow only 1 hr 30 mins away.</P><STRONG>By Coach</STRONG> Cambridge Coach Services run a regular coach service between Cambridge and Gatwick, Heathrow, Luton and Stansted Airports. Tickets can be purchased onboard the coach.</p><HR><CENTER><A HREF="iochpg.htm"><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="IoC Home Page" IMG SRC="f1.GIF" border=0></A><img src="fb.gif" border=0 align=middle><A HREF="staff.htm"><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Staff" IMG SRC="f2.GIF" border=0></A><img src="fb.gif" border=0 align=middle><A HREF="courses1.htm"><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Courses" IMG SRC="f3.GIF" border=0></A><img src="fb.gif" border=0 align=middle><A HREF="students/student.htm"><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Student" IMG SRC="f4.GIF" border=0></A><img src="fb.gif" border=0 align=middle><A HREF="research.htm"><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Research" IMG SRC="f5.GIF" border=0></A><img src="fb.gif" border=0 align=middle><A HREF="pubs.htm"><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Publications" IMG SRC="f6.GIF" border=0></A><img src="fb.gif" border=0 align=middle><A HREF="libhpg.htm"><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Library" IMG SR