<head><BODY  BGCOLOR="#ffffff"   >
<title>
New Publications
</title>
</head>
<IMG  ALT="[shield]"  ALIGN=middle SRC="cam2.gif"><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="latest.GIF"><CENTER><IMG SRC="bluebar.gif" align=absleft></CENTER>
<BR>
<H4><CITE>Preventing Crime and Disorder:  Targeting Strategies and Responsibilites</CITE> - Edited by Trevor Bennett, Cambridge, University of Cambridge, Institute of Criminology, 1996.  ISBN:  0901382167</H4>
<IMG  ALIGN=LEFT border=0 hspace=15 vspace=5 SRC="TREV2.GIF" ALT="Book">
<P>The 22nd <A HREF="CROPINFO.HTM">Cambridge Cropwood Conference</A> (on which this book is based) aimed to explore the relationship between the recipients and the providers of crime prevention.  One task of the conference was to consider the feasibility of targeting preventative strategies at specific individuals, victims, or locations in order to provide a better match between crime problems and crime prevention solutions.  Another task was to explore the nature of responsibilities for crime prevention at the national, community and local level and to consider who should do what to whom.</P>
<P>The book comprises 17 specially commissioned papers which were drafted before the conference and then revised and edited for publication.  The authors of these papers include some of the key writers in the field of crime and crime prevention.  Together they deal with some of the most important current issues in the development of crime prevention theory and practice.  The book would be of interest to academics, students, researchers, policy makers, the police, voluntary organisations, and private citizens who are concerned about developments in crime and crime prevention.</P>

Full  <A HREF="TBCON.HTM">contents</A> page. <BR>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH80=%>

<h4><CITE>Witnessing Insanity - Madness and Mad-Doctors in the English Court</CITE> - by Joel Peter Eigen, New Haven, Yale University Press, 1995, ISBN: 0300062893</H4>
<BR>
<IMG  ALIGN=RIGHT  border=0 hspace=15 vspace=5 SRC="JOELBLK2.GIF" ALT="Book">
<P>This intriguing book by Joel Eigen is the first systematic investigation of the evolution of medical testimony in British insanity trials from its beginnings in 1760 to 1843, when the Insanity Rules were formulated during the trial of Daniel McNaughton.  Based on verbatim testimony of court-room participants - the ordinary as well as the notorious - the book shows how the conception  of madness changed over time, how ambitious defense attorneys began to make use of medical opinion on madness, how the self-proclaimed specialists distanced themselves from lay witnesses, and how defendants offered the court a glimpse of madness "from the inside."</P>

<P>Eigen goes beyond existing accounts of famous trials to analyze the elements and development of the insanity defense in hundreds of ordinary prosecutions ranging from burglary and forgery to sheep stealing.  Drawing on recent scholarship on eighteenth century crime and punishment, he sheds new light on how the legal system adapted to a novel definition of insanity that blurred traditional conceptions of human will, self-control, and criminal responsibility.</P>

<P>Joel Peter Eigen is professor of sociology at Franklin and Marshall College, Life Member of Clare Hall  and Visiting Scholar at the Institute of Criminology, University of Cambridge 1996-1997.
</P>

</MENU>
