<HTML><BODY  BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><HEAD><TITLE>Dr Loraine Gelsthorpe</TITLE><H1><IMG ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE  ALT="crest" SRC="CAM2.GIF" > Dr Loraine Gelsthorpe</H1></HEAD><BR><CENTER><IMG SRC="BLUEBAR.GIF"></CENTER><P> University Lecturer in Criminology and Fellow of Pembroke College; currently Director of the Ph.D. programme.</P><P> Dr Gelsthorpe has carried out a number of empirical research studies since the early 1980s, including work on police decision-making with regard to juvenile offenders; the operation of multi-agency juvenile panels; the role of the Crown Prosecution Service in juvenile justice; gender issues in juvenile justice; the theory, policy and practice of attendance centres; the treatment of fine defaulters in magistrates courts; and race and gender issues in social inquiry reports. She has recently conducted work on  Home Office-funded projects on inter-agency aspects of crime prevention strategies and on pre-sentence reports. Current research interests revolve around notions of justice in sentencing, and the development of criminological and social theories in their social and political context since 1945.</P> <P> Dr Gelsthorpe's books include<I> Women and Crime</I> (1981), <I>Gender Issues in Juvenile Justice</I> (1985),<I> Sexism and the Female Offender</I> (1989) and <I>Feminist Perspectives in Criminology</I> (1990). She is Secretary of the Professional and Ethical Committee of the British Society of Criminology and Editor of the Society's Newsletter.  Dr Gelsthorpe maintains an active interest in local community safety issues and regularly works with a large range of national voluntary organisations on juvenile justice matters.<BR></P><HR><P>Institute of Criminology<BR>University of Cambridge<BR>7 West Road<BR>Cambridge<BR>England<BR>CB3  9DT<BR><BR>Tel:  +44 1223 335360<BR>Fax: +44 1223 335356<BR>email:  lrg10@cam.ac.uk</P></BODY></HTML>
