<HTML><BODY  BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><HEAD><TITLE>Professor Andrew von Hirsch</TITLE><H1><IMG ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE  ALT="crest" SRC="CAM2.GIF" > Professor Andrew von Hirsch</H1><CENTER><IMG SRC="BLUEBAR.GIF"></CENTER></HEAD><BR><P>Honorary Professor of Penal Theory and Penal Law and Fellow of Fitzwilliam College 1996-1999.</P><P>Professor von Hirsch's special interests are criminal sanctioning theory and philosophy of criminal law.  Three of his books deal with the rationale of criminal sentencing; <I>Doing Justice</I> (1976), <I>Past or Future Crimes</I> (1986) and <I>Censure and Sanctions</I> (1993).  Two books deal, respectively, with parole and sentencing guidelines: <I>The Question of Parole</I> (1979) and <I>The Sentencing Commission and its Guidelines</I> (1987).  He is co-editor, with Andrew Ashworth, of a reader on sentencing theory and policy, <I>Principled Sentencing</I> (1992).  He has also written on jurisprudential questions concerning substantive criminal law.  He is currently completing a book on gauging the seriousness of crimes and on questions of the scope of the criminal law.  He was, until recently, Professor at the School of Criminal Justice, Rutgers University.  He is now also Adjunct Professor of Penology Law Faculty, Uppsala University, and holds an honorary doctorate of laws from that institution.</P><HR><P>Institute of Criminology<BR>University of Cambridge<BR>7 West Road<BR>Cambridge<BR>England<BR>CB3  9DT<BR><BR>Tel:  +44 1223 335360<BR>Direct Line: +44 1223 335365<BR>Fax: +44 1223 335356<BR></P></BODY></HTML>
