<HEAD>
    <TITLE>News and Developments - Current Developments</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="image51.gif" WIDTH="392" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="image45.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><IMG SRC="image78.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></CENTER>
<P><BR>
Date: <B><I>6/18/96</I></B><I> _____________________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
</I><STRONG>New officer will be President in the year 2000</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Dean Gilstrap will ring in the next millenia as the President of TASSP.
But until that time, he has three years to learn how to be a figurehead
and role model for over 4,000 Texas secondary principals. Starting out as
the 1996-97 TASSP Second Vice President.<BR>
<BR>
Gilstrap, who has been in education for 16 of the past twenty-three years,
also spent time as a safety & personnel director for a drilling company,
a sales representative for a sporting goods store and as an insurance agent.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I got out of education for financial reasons: we had two small children,
and I was made an offer I 'couldn't refuse.' Within three months, I had
doubled what I was making as a teacher, and within a year, had tripled it.
But I always felt torn because I loved what I was able to do with teaching
and coaching and I missed my colleagues.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
When the opportunity came around in 1988 for him to return to education
as a teacher and coach in Petrolia ISD, he jumped at the chance. &quot;I
was relieved and glad to get back into education,&quot;&nbsp;said Gilstrap.<BR>
<BR>
Gilstrap is currently the principal of Henrietta High School and has been
a member of TASSP for the past six years.<BR>
<BR>
What areas does he plan to focus on during his 1999-2000 term?<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I want to continue work in the area of accountability,&quot; said
Gilstrap. &quot;I think principals should have the opportunity to have more
input into the whole system of how they get evaluated, and I think that
just as teachers are held accountable for their work, principals should
be, too. But they should have a chance to develop the means by which they
are accountable. I think this will be a key issue in the next few years.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Gilstrap continues to reside in Henrietta with his wife, Freida. They have
two children: Jason, a senior at Midwestern State University in Wichita
Falls and Kristen, a sophomore at Lee College in Cleveland, Tennessee.<BR>
<P><CENTER><I> _____________________________________________________________<BR>
<BR>
</I></CENTER>
<P><STRONG>Old face in new position</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Alan Veach, principal, Conroe High School, was named the TASSP State Coodinator
at the 1996 TASSP Summer Workshop. Veach had been the Assistant State Coordinator
from 1990-1996. Veach's new duties include being Texas's representative
at NASSP Region Meetings and the state's voting representative at the NASSP
National Convention. Additionally, Veach will network with NASSP representatives
from other states on various issues and will make recommendations to the
TASSP President, the Executive Committee and the Board of Directors based
on his NASSP experiences.<BR>
<BR>
Veach succeeds Larry Bradley, principal, Pflugerville High School, who had
been the State Coordinator since 1990.<BR>
<P><CENTER><I> _____________________________________________________________</I></CENTER>
<P><BR>
<STRONG>TASSP gets new Assistant State Coodinator</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Archie McAfee, principal, Plano East Senior High School, was named the TASSP
Assistant State Coordinator at the 1996 Summer Workshop. McAfee says he
is &quot;excited and elated to have been elected to this position.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I am excited about bringing my ideas on increasing membership to this
position, and for the opportunity to work with the excellent Regional Coodinators
and with Alan Veach (the new State Coordinator).&quot;<BR>
<BR>
McAfee is especially interested in increasing membership in Region 10 (his
own school's region), which currently has a 48 percent TASSP membership
among principals and assistant principals. (Average regional membership
is estimated at 65-70 percent.)<BR>
<BR>
Some of McAfee's duties now include being responsible for TASSP and NASSP
membership promotion, orientation of Assistant District Coordinators on
their duties in membership promotion, making recommendations to improve
membership procedures and working with the Assistant District Coordinators
to formulate recommendations for membership services. McAfee's new position
was previously held by Alan Veach (see article, below).<BR>
<BR>
McAfee has been the principal of Plano East Senior High School since 1981.
He is currently working on his Doctorate in Education at the University
of North Texas. McAfee lives in Plano with his wife of 27 years, Sharon,
and their two daughters, Kelli (15) and Lindsay (11).<BR>
<P><CENTER><I> _____________________________________________________________</I></CENTER>
