<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Related Sites</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="image51.gif" WIDTH="392" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
<H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="image130.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
</H2>
<H2>Education Related Sites</H2>
Here are some of our favorite sites around the web. Let us know about other
sites you feel would be helpful to educators. 
<H3>Primarily for Principals</H3>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.tenet.edu/">TENET Web</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>This site contains the Tenet Network, Tenet Central Station, Tenet
Vault and the State Networking Project. Included are subjects such as the
UIL realignment and important legislative items. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.tea.texas.gov/">Texas Education Agency</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Download the latest edition of the Texas Essential Knowledge and Skills,
read the latest on the accountability system, TEA Clearinghouse, a searchable
edition of Senate Bill 1, etc. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.tea.state.tx.us:70/1/juris">Legislation, Court Rulings,
Waivers and Rules</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Possibly the most practical site for principals in that it contains
a &quot;principal friendly&quot; searchable edition of the Texas Education
Code (Senate Bill 1). Simply type in a word or phrase and the search engine
does the work. This site also contains other important legislation, court
rulings and TEA waivers. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.state.tx.us/TIF/">Texas Telecommunications Infrastructure
Fund Homepage</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Everything you need to know about the $150,000,000 fund appropriated
for education technology and how to get your school's share. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.sedl.org/">New SEDL Shape</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Home page of the Southwest Education Development Laboratory. This
site includes publications, technical assistance, educational activities,
internet resources, server information. It is especially good for small
and rural schools. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://dewey.esc1.tenet.edu/html/other.html">Region One E S
C -- Edinburg, Texas</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>This service center has identified several informative sites for educators.
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.nassp.org/">NASSP Home Page</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Instant connection and communication with our national affiliate.
This site provides principals another source of quality information, service
and assistance. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.ascd.org/">The ASCD Web</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>The Association for Supervision and Curriculum Development. Opportunities
for professional development, outstanding publications, other resources
for principals, supervisors and teachers. Many excellent links to other
important education sites. 
  </UL>
</DL>
<H3>Primarily for Counselors</H3>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://cbweb1.collegeboard.org/index.html">College Board Online
Home Page</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>An exceptional site for students, parents, counselors, teachers and
administrators. A world of information on colleges and universities, financial
aid, admission requirements, test dates and online registration. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.tgslc.org/tgslc/">Texas Guaranteed Student Loan
Corporation</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>This organization administers the Federal Family Education Loan Program.
Information on eligibility requirements and availability. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.tgslc.org/">Adventures in Education</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>A subsite of the TGSLC with unlimited information on planning a career,
selecting a school, and paying for higher education. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.testprep.com/">TESTPREP.COM(tm) Home Page</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Sponsored by Stanford University this site provides free online test
preparation programs for SAT, ACT, GRE, etc. A great deal of other information
and assistance in preparing for these important tests. 
  </UL>
</DL>
<H3>For All Educators</H3>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://ericir.syr.edu/">AskERIC Home Page</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>One of the most valuable resources of information and research on
almost any topic related to education. An unusual opportunity to ask and
get answers to questions from the field of education. A Virtual Library
connects you to many other resources. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://web66.coled.umn.edu/schools.html">Web66: International
WWW School Registry</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Locate almost any campus web site around the world. Easy access which
includes categories on a variety of special schools. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.ccsi.com/yeeha/">yeeHa ! Texas Website & Resource
Directory - HOME PAGE</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>A directory of informative web sites on almost any topic including
education 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.csu.edu.au/education/general_lev.html">Education
Virtual Library - All Levels (General)</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>A comprehensive listing of &quot;virtually&quot; every kind of K-12
education related resources available around the world. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.utexas.edu/texas/edu/">Web Texas - Education</A>
  <UL>
  <LI>UT Austin is the official WWW registration site for Texas Web servers.
Web Texas is divided in Commercial, Education, Government, and Non-Profit
Organization lists. The education list includes Texas colleges with subservers
at larger schools, some ISD's and public/private K-12 campuses. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://longwood.cs.ucf.edu/~MidLink/index.html">MidLink Magazine</A>
  <UL>
  <LI>A colorful electronic magazine for Middle level students, generally
ages 10 - 15. Sponsored by Florida and North Carolina universities, the
e-zine is published four times each year 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.lib.umich.edu/chouse/tree/edu.html">Education</A>
  <UL>
  <LI>University of Michigan's Clearinghouse for Internet Resource Guides
attempts to facilitate intellectural access to information resources on
the Internet. Each guide is evaluated for quality. This link goes to the
education Clearinghouse. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.tenet.edu/tenet-info/school/teacher.html">Teacher's
Bookmarks</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Part of the TENET site, this area is developed by Teachers and includes
their favorite sites, from curricular (all levels) to genealogy to web design.
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://riceinfo.rice.edu/armadillo/">Armadillo's WWW Server</A>
  <UL>
  <LI>Home Page of the Houston ISD. In addition to an indepth look at the
Houston ISD, this site also contains a searchable file for a wide variety
of education related resources. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.si.edu/">The Smithsonian Institution Home Page</A>
  <UL>
  <LI>&quot;America's Treasure House For Learning&quot;. This site is unbelievable
both in appearance and in its information and in its links to other resources.
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://altavista.digital.com/">Alta Vista: Main Page</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>This will provide a quick connection to a &quot;search&quot; engine
that appears to be one of the best 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://miso.wwa.com/~boba/kidsi.html">(Bob Allison's Home Page)
Uncle Bob's Kids' Page</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>One of the very best pages for teachers and younger kids. Lots of
games and activities for children. 
  </UL>
</DL>
<H3>Not Necessarily Education Related</H3>
<UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www2.switchboard.com/">Switchboard</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Looking for a former roommate, a colleague from days of yore? Switchboard
helps locate the &quot;missing.&quot; Try it! You'll like it! 
  </UL>
</UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.elibrary.com/">Electronic Library</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Super research tool. Use the free trial to experience it and decide
if it would be worthwhile for you, your family, or your school. 
  </UL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.eb.com/">Enclyclopedia Britannica OnLine</A> 
  <UL>
  <LI>Like the elibrary above, this site offers (for a fee) some outstanding
reference materials. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
  </UL>
  <UL><CENTER><A HREF="mainmenu.htm"><IMG SRC="image230.gif" WIDTH="54"
HEIGHT="42" ALIGN=middle NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" BORDER="0"></A>Click icon or
<A HREF="mainmenu.htm">here</A> to return to Main Menu</CENTER>
  </UL>
