<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Assistant Principal Leadership Development Conference</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<STRONG>ASSISTANT PRINCIPAL LEADERSHIP DEVELOPMENT CONFERENCE <BR>
February 9-11, 1997 <BR>
Austin Renaissance (Stouffer) Hotel<BR>
<BR>
Full Day Legal Seminar Planned</STRONG><BR>
At the request of TASSP's assistant principals, a full day Legal Seminar
is again featured at this year's conference. Focusing solely on an AP's
needs, this conference activity is especially important in light of the
revised Texas Education Code and its impact on almost every facet of campus
life. Conference participants will spend Monday with some of the finest
education attorneys in our state. &quot;Law Dawg&quot; Jim Walsh will return
to moderate with a full slate of hot topics including discipline, parent
rights, special education/504, tips on interpreting and implementing policy
and others.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Sunday Agenda</STRONG><BR>
Back again by popular demand are Sunday afternoon &quot;share shops&quot;
designed to assist in learning from each other how to successfully tackle
the tough student management issues. Joe Hairston, longtime Texas school
law attorney, brings his unique perspective of life on the frontline to
conference participants in the opening general session. <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Tuesday Professional Development Opportunities</STRONG><BR>
An added activity at this year's conference includes five special professional
development opportunities offered at no extra charge on Tuesday, February
11th from 8:00 a.m. until noon. If you are able to stay over, check your
choice of the following on the conference registration form (please note
that all sessions except #2 are limited to 60 participants):<BR>
<BR>
1) <I>Mastering Effective Documentation</I> with Frank Kemerer, UNT Regents
Professor and author of The Documentation Handbook. This session provides
a &quot;hands-on&quot; introduction to the basics of effective documentation,
with a review of the legal framework within which documentation takes place
and the principles of effective documentation. The Documentation Handbook
will be available for purchase at the workshop.<BR>
<BR>
2) <I>Sexual Harrassment at School</I> with Shelley Hoffman, Director of
Legal Services for the Texas Association of School Boards. Participants
will learn to determine improper behavior and the steps they can take to
prevent sexual harrassment.<BR>
<BR>
3) <I>Win-Win Resolutions: What an AP Must Know to Manage Conflict</I> with
Betty Jo Monk, Associate Dean, Baylor School of Education. Learn &quot;nuts
& bolts&quot; strategies for dealing with conflict that facilitate creation
of &quot;win-win&quot; resolutions. THIS SESSION IS FULL.<BR>
<BR>
4) <I>Use TAAS, Don't Let TAAS Use You!</I> with David Molina, UT Mathematics
Professor. This interactive session, primarily focused on the math portion
of TAAS, will include activities to better understand the test and use the
data generated for redefining the curriculum and instruction.<BR>
<BR>
5) <I>The Answer is &quot;I Want to Be a Principal.&quot; So What Are the
Questions?</I> with Millie Klein, Director of Field Services, ESC Region
XX. Participate in an interactive session designed to answer career development
questions concerning professional growth, marketing yourself and effective
interviewing techniques.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Registration Information</STRONG><BR>
Preregistration is encouraged for those who can make an early commitment
to attend the conference. The preregistration fee is $75 for TASSP members
and $115 for non-members. Those who preregister will have a conference packet
waiting for them on arrival. On-site registration will be available for
those participants who cannot register before January 27th. Fees on-site
will be $85 for members and $125 for non-members.<BR>
<BR>
Call the TASSP office for the forms -- if you don't already have them (512-443-2100).
The preregistration form should be sent to TASSP. Send the Housing Request
form directly to the Renaissance Hotel. As in the past, the Renaissance
Hotel airport shuttle is operated for the convenience of conference participants.
The shuttle leaves the hotel on the hour and the airport on the half hour
beginning at 7 a.m. at a cost of $8.00 one way.<BR>
<BR>
Conference activities will begin at 1:30 p.m. on Sunday, February 9th with
a Legislative Forum. Check the conference schedule provided for specific
activity times and make your plans now to join us in Austin. See you in
February!<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>SCHEDULE<BR>
<BR>
Sunday, February 9</STRONG><BR>
12:30 p.m. - 1:30 p.m. -- Registration<BR>
1:30 p.m. - 2:15 p.m. -- Legislative Forum -- (Julian Shaddix, TASSP Executive
Director)<BR>
2:30 p.m. - 3:30 p.m. -- UIL Update -- (Bill Farney/Bonnie Northcutt, UIL,
Austin)<BR>
3:45 p.m. - 4:55 p.m. -- Share Shops<BR>
5:00 p.m. - 5:45 p.m. -- Keynote Session -- (Joe Hairston, Attorney, Walsh/Anderson)<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Monday, February 10 <BR>
(Legal Seminar -- Jim Walsh, Austin Attorney, Moderator)</STRONG><BR>
8:15 a.m. - 8:30 a.m. -- Introduction of Assistant Principal Committee & Assistant
Principal of the Year<BR>
8:30 a.m. - 9:00 a.m. -- Advice from the Law Dawg -- (Jim Walsh)<BR>
9:00 a.m. - 10:00 a.m. -- IEP, ARD, LRE & the AP: What You Need to Know
About Special Education -- (Elena Gallegos)<BR>
10:20 a.m. - 11:00 a.m. -- How to Make the E.B.B. (Enormous Blue Book) Work
for You -- (Chris Elizalde)<BR>
11:00 a.m. - 11:45 a.m. -- Parents as Partners: Issues for the A.P. -- (John
Aldridge)<BR>
1:00 p.m. - 2:00 p.m. -- Personnel Issues & the A.P. -- (Judy Underwood)<BR>
2:20 p.m. - 4:30 p.m. -- Legal Issues in Student Discipline -- (Jim Walsh)<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Tuesday, February 11</STRONG><BR>
8:00 a.m. - Noon -- Special Professional Development Opportunities (choose
one):<BR>
1) Mastering Effective Documentation: A &quot;How-to&quot; Workshop -- (Frank
Kemerer, UNT/Legal Digest, Denton)<BR>
2) Sexual Harrassment at School -- (Shelley Hoffman, TASB, Austin)<BR>
3) Win-Win Resolutions -- (Betty Jo Monk, Baylor University, Waco)<BR>
4) Use TAAS, Don't Let TAAS Use You -- (David Molina, UT/SSI, Austin)<BR>
5) The Answer is &quot;I Want to Be A Principal&quot; -- (Millie Klein,
ESC Region XX, San Antonio)
</BODY>
</HTML>
