<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Summer Conference Program </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="image51.gif" WIDTH="392" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="image167.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><BR>
<BR>
1996 TASSP Summer Workshop Concurrent Sessions</CENTER>
<P>Topics: Technology, Leadership or Student Support<BR>
<BR>
from <STRONG>1996 TASSP Summer Workshop Program</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
WEDNESDAY, JUNE 12TH, 1:15 P.M. - 2:30 P.M.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>1 Assessment and Development: A Productive Mix for Professional
Growth<BR>
Colorado Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Ray Lemley, Executive Director, Texas Principal Leadership Initiative,
Austin [512-473-8754]</I><BR>
Assessment activities can provide participants an opportunity to receive
specific feedback about skills designated for success in the principalship.
Sound developmental assessment can point participants toward insights not
gotten in other ways. During this workshop, participants will get hands-on
experience in responding to a brief in-basket, a focused school related
problem and a brief sample interview. In addition, the participants will
learn about the strategies used in applying assessment activities to their
developmental planning. Ray will conclude this presentation with an overview
of the activities of the Texas Principals Leadership Initiative. Additionally,
he will respond to questions and concerns focused upon developmental assessment.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> robert mears, principal, denison hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>2 Leading Learning Organizations<BR>
Live Oak Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Diana Miller, Principal Consultant, Experiential Learning Systems,
Lewisville [214-436-7710] </I><BR>
Is your school a true learning organization? How your organization learns
- or fails to learn - will determine its success, now more than ever. Why?
Because people in learning organizations are better prepared to adapt quickly
to internal or external change. Such people are able to create innovative,
high-performance teams that continuously build on each other's knowledge
and skills. The results are sustained high levels of performance and outstanding
achievements.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> shana nix, vice principal, nichols jhs, arlington <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>3 Information on the Telecommunications Infrastructure Fund<BR>
Lone Star Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Representative, TIF, Austin [512-475-3156]</I><BR>
Now in its initial planning phase, the TIF is a $150 million grant program
to be administered over ten years. It will facilitate the deployment and
use of advanced telecommunications technologies in Texas public schools,
hospitals, libraries and other public institutions. Join the TIF representative
for an overview of the Fund and general information about grants, which
will be awarded beginning late this year.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> doyle dean, principal, plano sr. hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>4 Integrating WWW Resources Into the Curriculum<BR>
Lavaca Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Gayle Gaston, Web Master, TENET, Austin [512-414-2090]</I><BR>
The World Wide Web offers an incredibly rich library of resources for education.
However, finding just the right information can be an overwhelming task.
This session will attempt to answer the following questions: When is it
feasible to use web resources as opposed to traditional print and audio
visual materials? What techniques can be used to find information on specific
topics? How can teachers minimize students' access to inappropriate or irrelevant
materials on the web? How can a school that wishes to publish its own web
site effectively contribute to this rapidly expanding body of knowledge?<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> ray alvarez, vice principal, shepard ms, san antonio<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>5 SHIFT - A Student-Led Approach to Technology Integration<BR>
Water Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Ted Moore, Principal [214-727-0340]; Steve Payne, Teacher & Courtney
Glazer, Teacher, Curtis Middle School, Allen</I><BR>
In two years, CMS has gone from the information back roads to the Superinformation
Highway. A dynamic business partnership has given birth to Cyberfair, student
corporation and a new way of doing business.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> dave lyons, principal, ingleside hs<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>6 Long-Term Planning for Technology Imple-mentation in Rural Schools<BR>
Cedar Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Bruce Barker, Chairman, Department of Instructional Technology,
College of Education & Human Services, Western Illinois University, Macomb,
Illinois [309-298-1952]</I><BR>
This session focuses on the key elements and procedures needed in setting-up
and implementing a schoolwide and/or districtwide long-term technology plan.
Topics discussed include: putting together a committee, getting the &quot;right&quot;
information, looking at a &quot;mix&quot; of advanced technologies, integrating
technology into the curriculum, questions to consider in guiding long-term
planning, issues related to staff development, anticipated costs, making
progress in increments, etc.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> tim turner, principal, eastland hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>7 Increasing the Graduation Expectations for All Students and Getting
There<BR>
Ballroom B<BR>
</STRONG><I>George Thompson, Principal, Bell County High School, Pineville,
Kentucky [606-337-7061]</I><BR>
This session discusses the role of the principal in setting minimum high
standards for all students and providing the means to achieve them. Redesigning
the secondary school is required. Integration across the curriculum with
a career focus provides a powerful learning environment for all students.
Applied learning strategies and culminating events enable students to demonstrate
proficiency in knowledge and the application of such knowledge.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> peter rayome, principal, little elm ms <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>8 Non-Violent Schools in a Violent Society<BR>
Cypress Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Gary Weart, Chairman & Founder, Students Against Violence Everywhere
(SAVE), Charlotte, North Carolina [704-532-5503]</I><BR>
Students Against Violence Everywhere is a proactive, long-term violence
prevention program that is student-initiated, owned and driven. There are
currently over 200 chapters and 15,000 student members across the country.
Chapters provide opportunities for student leadership, community service
and interaction among all students K-12, resulting in self-esteem and positive
peer pressure. All materials necessary to establish a chapter will be provided.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> chris hines, principal, hays hs, buda <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>9 Gangs! How Do Schools Cope?<BR>
Brazos Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Bob Fawcett, Assistant Principal [713-477-1501]; Wayne Adams,
Principal, Pasadena High School </I><BR>
Learn how to organize and maintain an effective program of control involving
intelligence, suppression and discipline. How to educate parents and patrons
will also be discussed. Cooperative arrangements with law enforcement will
be covered.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> paul abundez, principal, presidio hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>10 U CAN 'ACE' IT<BR>
Pecan Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Dottie Chiles, Director of Secondary Instruction [512-643-6566]
& Joe Thedford, Superintendent, Gregory-Portland ISD </I><BR>
The &quot;ACE&quot; (Alternative Center for Education) has been a very successful
new program. Using uniforms and unusual daily progress reports to parents,
most students are successful in changing attitudes and behavior. The academic
and counseling components are interdisciplinary in design.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> esther barrientos, principal, pearsall jhs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>11 COOL Week: Career Opportunities On Location<BR>
Hickory Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Charles Rouse, Principal [512-435-8000]; Mark Kincaid, Transition
Coordinator & students from Leander High School</I><BR>
High school juniors... a week, during the school year, in the work place...
solving problems. Sound futuristic? At Leander High School it is quickly
becoming a reality. Last March, 200 juniors went to work at 64 businesses
for five days instead of going to school. While at work, the students were
interviewed, were given a job-related problem to solve and were expected
to work as a team to solve the problem and present their solution to company
representatives by the end of the week. During this session, students will
share their experiences. Goals for the 1997 COOL Week will be discussed.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> gary crowell, associate superintendent, pasadena isd<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>12 Project GRAD: Graduation Really Achieves the Dreams of Kindergarteners
(K-12 Project)<BR>
Ash Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Emily Cole, Principal, Jefferson Davis High School [713-226-4900];
Wanda Watson, Principal, Ryan Elementary; Silvia McClure, Principal, Lamar
Elementary; Armandina Farias, Principal, Jefferson Elementary; Victor Cardenas,
Principal, Lee Elementary; Barbara Moseley, Principal, Looscan Elementary;
Roberto Gonzalez, Principal, Marshall Middle School; Patricia Sosa-Gonzales,
Principal, Martinez Elementary and Georgia Hinds McGlasson, Principal, Sherman
Elementary, Houston</I><BR>
Principals from the elementary feeder schools of the Jefferson Davis High
School Vertical Team will describe their successes in working together as
a Pre-K through grade 12 team. Project GRAD, funded with the help of corporate
and nonprofit sponsors, will be described as a dropout prevention project.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> mary alice deike, principal, fredericksburg hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>13 Taming the Block: A Survival Guide for Teachers and Administrators<BR>
Mulberry Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>David O'Neill, Director of Secondary Education [512-863-6595];
Linda Holstrom, Director of Career & Technology; Becky Washington, Principal,
Williams Elementary; Debra Crais, Theresa Cavender, Melinda Ellerbee, Donna
Hart, Teachers; Georgetown ISD</I><BR>
Georgetown ISD has been working with K-12 educators by providing a flexible,
student-centered approach to instruction, curriculum and assessment that
allows for the instructional shift to ninety minutes. Additionally, all
students develop the thinking and learning skills necessary for success
in our service-based economy.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> linda combs, liaison, region vii esc, kilgore <BR>
<BR>
THURSDAY, JUNE 13, 8:30 A.M. - 9:45 A.M.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>14 Breaking Ranks: Changing an American Institution<BR>
Ballroom C<BR>
</STRONG><I>Tim Westerberg, Principal, Littleton HS, Littleton, CO [303-347-7717]</I><BR>
This session will highlight some of the major recommendations from the recently
released NASSP/Carnegie Foundation Commission report, Breaking Ranks: Changing
an American Institution. The report, which is expected to have far-reaching
effects on the way we think of, design, and carry out high school educatiion
is a rich reservoir of seminal ideas for educational leaders and anyone
interested in the future of the American High School.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> ann froelich, principal, huntsville hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>15 A Successful Induction/Mentoring Model<BR>
San Jacinto Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Robert Presley, Administrative Director, Human Resource Development
[512-268-2141]; Sherri White, Teacher and Coordinator of the Induction/Mentoring
Program, Hays CISD, Kyle</I><BR>
Hays CISD, in an effort to promote student success by improving teaching
performance and to ensure a rewarding and successful first year teaching
experience for teachers new to the district, has implemented a comprehensive,
team-based Induction and Mentoring Program. This presentation will enable
you to analyze the four key components of the Hays program and receive information
and insights which will be useful in the development of a formal Induction
and Mentoring Program in your school.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> eloy chapa, principal, patti welder ms, victoria<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>16 Planning and Living a Better Retirement<BR>
Brazos Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Joan Pember Adams, CFP [800-865-2095] & Cecile Russell, MetLife
Resources, Austin</I><BR>
Can I afford to retire? Will my income keep pace with inflation? This seminar
will give you 11 basic ideas on retirement planning. It is designed to help
you get started or to refine your retirement plans so your retirement years
are your &quot;golden years.&quot;<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> jackie tuggle, asst. principal, nichols jhs, arlington<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>17 Good Intentions Get You Nowhere<BR>
Live Oak Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Stephen Russell, President, New Focus Leadership Training Company,
Winnsboro [903-342-5002]</I><BR>
The session will provide an understanding of the differences between Externally
Controlled and Internally Managed people. Participants will gain an understanding
of the &quot;why&quot; of behaviors, of how to break the cycle of behaviors
and how the IM process works in moving people toward taking responsibility
and accountability for their behavior.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> mike terry, principal, evadale hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>18 Time, Stress and Wellness Strategies for Educational Leaders<BR>
Pine Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Doug Beers, Consultant, Premier School Agendas, Bellingham,
Washington [604-855-0620]</I><BR>
As an educational leader, is your day &quot;stressful&quot; because you
are reacting to a constant flow of &quot;crises and interruptions?&quot;
Are you going home late, exhausted, having completed only a portion of what
you had set out to do? This situation is not only counter-productive, but
it also affects your personal wellness. Using lecture style and audience
participation, this special session offers practical time and stress management
strategies to help educational leaders enhance their effectiveness in our
changing, reactionary school environment.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> joe roach, principal, kennard hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>19 So You Want to Be a Principal...<BR>
Pecan Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Nita Ellis, Principal, Hall Middle School [817-921-2664] & Linda
Starnes, Principal, Travis Elementary School, Weatherford</I><BR>
This is a session for people headed for a principalship. The focus will
be on some of the things you might be dealing with that no one prepared
you for...&quot;This wasn't mentioned in my mid-management courses.&quot;<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> dianne pritchett, assistant principal, channelview hs<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>20 Architecture and the Educational Model<BR>
Red River Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Claude Cunningham, Executive Director Student Services/Secondary
Instruction, Mansfield ISD [817-473-5600] & Diana Macon Bernshausen, Instructor/Secondary
Coordinator, Houston Baptist University, Houston</I><BR>
This presentation addresses the relationship between the physical school
structure and the educational model that the structure supports and the
need for change in order to support new models of technology. Models are
discussed. Roundtable discussion and brainstorming of changes needed in
order to support future models and technology advancements are included.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> tony swafford, principal, brownwood hs<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>21 Information on the Telecommunications Infrastructure Fund<BR>
Lone Star Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Representative, TIF, Austin [512-475-3156]</I><BR>
Now in its initial planning phase, the TIF is a $150 million grant program
to be administered over ten years. It will facilitate the deployment and
use of advanced telecommunications technologies in Texas public schools,
hospitals, libraries and other public institutions. Join the TIF representative
for an overview of the Fund and general information about grants, which
will be awarded beginning late this year.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> harold kellogg, principal, richardson west jhs<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>22 Integrating WWW Resources Into the Curriculum<BR>
Lavaca Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Gayle Gaston, Web Master, TENET, Austin [512-414-2090]</I><BR>
The World Wide Web offers an incredibly rich library of resources for education.
However, finding just the right information can be an overwhelming task.
This session will attempt to answer the following questions: When is it
feasible to use web resources as opposed to traditional print and audio
visual materials? What techniques can be used to find information on specific
topics? How can teachers minimize students' access to inappropriate or irrelevant
materials on the web? How can a school that wishes to publish its own web
site effectively contribute to this rapidly expanding body of knowledge?<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> archie mc afee, principal, plano east sr. hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>23 Technology Between and for Rural Schools<BR>
Water Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Pennie Sumrall, Technology Coordinator [817-623-4255]; Amy Feller,
Principal; Polly Boyd, Superintendent, Bynum ISD; Janice Trompler, Technical
Coordinator, Hubbard ISD, Dekalb & Bob Odell, Technical Coordinator, Dawson
ISD, Welch</I><BR>
Six central Texas rural school districts teamed together to establish a
two-way interactive video and data communication link via a fiber optic
network. You will be able to find out how it was implemented as well as
current and future uses.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> judy blair, assistant principal, fort stockton hs<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>24 Large Urban High School, Suburban School District: How Do You
Make It Work?<BR>
Ballroom B<BR>
</STRONG><I>Phil Gainous, Principal, Montgomery Blair High School, Silver
Springs, Maryland [301-650-6636]</I><BR>
This presentation will discuss programs, strategies and suggestions for
administering a successful large high school located in an urban setting
within a suburban school district. Topics will include: maintaining a safe
school environment, achieving high academic performance for all students
with a focus on the needs of minority students, curriculum development,
innovation and implementation, support programs for students, community
involvement in all aspects of the school and how to develop and maintain
community support and suggestions for raising needed supplementary funds
to support school programs and needs. The presentation will be followed
by a question and answer period.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> rose mediano, principal, lubbock hs<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>25 Creating Win-Win Situations for Students with Extremely Disruptive
Behavior<BR>
Sabine Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Jackie Townsend, ESC Region IV, Houston [713-462-7708]</I><BR>
Through the ESCs the Crisis Prevention Institute offers you and your staff
the keys to being successful with highly disruptive and disturbed students.
Come to this session and find out what CPI training is all about and how
you can access it.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> susie fegraeus, asst. principal, naaman forest hs, garland<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>26 Parent Education and Involvement: Reconnecting Families, Schools
and Communities<BR>
Neches Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Judy Farmer, Consultant, TX Assn. of School Boards, Austin [512-467-0222]</I><BR>
Educators, school boards, and community members throughout the state and
nation have identified parental involvement as a key issue in education.
This session explores opportunities for parents, schools and community organizations
to work to develop effective strategies for parental involvement and to
encourage effective communication with the school community. <BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> gail krohn, principal, central ms, nederland<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>27 Interagency Collaboration Through Community Resource Coordination
Groups of Texas<BR>
Trinity Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Debbie Bentley, Assistant Principal/Coordinator for Special
Education Services, Pflugerville High School [512-251-2238]; Mary Margaret
Sauls & Rachel Howell, ESC Region XIII, Austin</I><BR>
Community Resource Coordination Groups (CRCGs) of Texas is a successful
interagency initiative that was piloted five years ago and now is available
to 97% of all school age children. CRCGs are locally driven groups of educators,
health and human service, juvenile justice, and private sector providers
who come together to meet the service needs of children and youth (ages
0 to 22) who may potentially fall through the system's service delivery
cracks. CRCGs meet to develop service plans for individual children and
youth who require interagency coordination.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> donella green, asst. principal, schimelpfenig ms, plano<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>28 TAAS Road Map to Dynamite &quot;Hands-On&quot; Activities = Success
on TAAS Math<BR>
Colorado Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Cheryl Cox, Director of Special Programs, Garland ISD [214-494-8955]
& Janice Overstreet, Curriculum Director, Glen Rose ISD</I><BR>
Have you developed a road map that will help ensure success? Information
that is critical to student success on TAAS Math will be shared in this
session. Exciting &quot;hands-on&quot; activities and strategies for teaching
the critical TAAS math skills will also be shared.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> susanne warren, asst. principal, texas hs, texarkana<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>29 Non-Violent Schools in a Violent Society<BR>
Cypress Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Gary Weart, Chairman & Founder, Students Against Violence Everywhere
(SAVE), Charlotte, North Carolina [704-532-5503]</I><BR>
Students Against Violence Everywhere is a proactive, long-term violence
prevention program that is student-initiated, owned and driven. There are
currently over 200 chapters and 15,000 student members across the country.
Chapters provide opportunities for student leadership, community service
and interaction among all students K-12, resulting in self-esteem and positive
peer pressure. All materials necessary to establish a chapter will be provided.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> gwen poteet, principal, westlawn ms, texarkana<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>30 Flex Into the Future<BR>
Cedar Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Kenn Franklin, Principal [903-963-8623]; Rick Palmer, Assistant
Principal; Shelby Davidson; Trecia Bass; Donna Wallace & Donna Rainwater,
Teachers, Van High School</I><BR>
Hear about an exciting method of meeting the needs of your high school community
through a variety of courses that relate to career planning and a flexible
high school schedule. Increase student interest by modifying the block schedule
and school calendar to meet the needs of your students. The schedule and
calendar allow students to expand rather than limit the flexibility of the
high school program.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> mauro vasquez, principal, mercedes jhs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>31 Breaking the Mold of Mathematics Education<BR>
mulberry Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Richard Myers, Math/Science/Computer Science Teacher, Brownwood
High School [915-646-0703]</I><BR>
Join a discussion in restructuring the teaching of Algebra I & II in order
that it becomes a usable tool for solving &quot;real world&quot; problems
rather than its current design as mostly an abstract preparatory class for
advanced mathematics, which most students never take. Integration is a key
factor in restructuring.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> bobby wheeley, assistant principal, kilgore hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>32 A Creative Way to Blend 'Choice' with 'Placed' in an Alternative
School Setting<BR>
Ash Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Kathy Gaines, LEAP Alternative School, Brenham [409-277-6537]</I><BR>
An overview of a rural school district's handling of an alternative school
with three distinct programs: mastery-based high school diploma; in-school
GED preparation; and AEP pre-expulsion, discipline.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> greg whitman, principal, holloway ms, whitehouse<BR>
<BR>
THURSDAY, JUNE 13, 3:15 P.M. - 4:30 P.M.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>33 Five Power Tools for Creating Dynamic Teamwork & Progressive
Leadership Skills!<BR>
Sabine Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Link Fuller, Nat'l Educational Trainer/Consultant, Lone Oak
[903-447-4776]</I><BR>
This workshop will focus on how to develop and apply the vital tools and
skills necessary for Effective Teamwork, Collaborative Problem-Solving and
Positive Leadership. The tempo of this seminar will be fast-paced, participatory,
humorous, practical and motivational.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> chester lott, assistant principal, leander hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>34 A Collaborative Approach to Teacher Appraisal: The Danbury Model<BR>
Neches Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Steve Gaskin, Principal, Danbury High School [713-393-1779]</I><BR>
This session will provide you with an alternative teacher/mentor appraisal
model that works. All participants will be provided with a detailed handout
of the appraisal instrument.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> raymond davis, principal, tom browne ms, corpus christi<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>35 Building Your Financial House<BR>
Brazos Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Cecile Russell [800-865-2095] & Joan Pember Adams, CFP, MetLife
Resources, Austin</I><BR>
Do you want to build a basic house or the house of your dreams? This seminar
will help you target your savings and investment needs to reach your ultimate
financial goals with an emphasis on mutual funds.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> ed lyman, principal, elkhart hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>36 From Battleground to Common Ground: Applying Religious Liberty
Principles in Public Schools<BR>
Colorado Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Charles Haynes, Scholar in Residence, The Freedom Forum First
Amendment Center, Vanderbilt University, Nashville, Tennessee [615-321-9588]</I><BR>
Public schools have become a storm center of controversy on a wide range
of issues involving deeply held world views. How should schools address
religion and values? Can we find new ways to avoid shouting matches and
lawsuits by finding common ground as American citizens? This session explores
the First Amendment principles within which we are able to debate our differences,
to understand one another and to forge public policies that serve the common
good in public education.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> tom leyden, principal, schimelpfenig ms, plano <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>37 Organizing Adults to Serve Children: The Comprehensive Management
System<BR>
Live Oak Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Mike Occhipinti, Consultant, North Carolina Department of Public
Instruction, Raleigh [919-851-1693] & Jeff Nash, Assistant Principal, Wake
County Public Schools, Raleigh, North Carolina</I><BR>
This presentation will explain a system used by over 400 schools in North
Carolina. It examines new and exciting ways of utilizing humor, time, financial
and material resources.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> mike brown, principal, anson hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>38 In the Trenches: Survival Tactics for APs<BR>
Cedar Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Linda Snook, Principal [713-354-4137] & Theresa Beauchamp, Assistant
Principal, New Caney Middle School, Porter</I><BR>
Bring your shovels and let's dig in! A group-oriented session designed to
assist new assistant principals with information, how-to's, time-savers,
and stress busters.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> carolyn kitchens, asst. principal, haltom sr. hs, ft.
worth<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>39 Time, Stress and Wellness Strategies for Educational Leaders<BR>
Pine Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Doug Beers, Consultant, Premier School Agendas, Bellingham,
WA [604-855-0620]</I><BR>
As an educational leader, is your day &quot;stressful&quot; because you
are reacting to a constant flow of &quot;crises and interruptions?&quot;
Are you going home late, exhausted, having completed only a portion of what
you had set out to do? This situation is not only counter-productive, but
it also affects your personal wellness. Using lecture style and audience
participation, this special session offers practical time and stress management
strategies to help educational leaders enhance their effectiveness in our
changing, reactionary school environment.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> james brewer, principal, de kalb hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>40 Campus Administration by the (Big Blue) Book<BR>
San Jacinto Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Carita Simons, Policy Consultant/Analyst, Texas Association
of School Boards, Austin [512-467-0222]</I><BR>
This session will introduce participants to the TASB Localized Policy Manual,
adopted by nearly 1,000 districts. Participants will be taught how to find
information within the manual, identify and discuss policy codes essential
to school administration and offer suggestions on how to approach the numbered
Localized Updates produced by TASB Policy Service.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> jim gwaltney, principal, hamilton hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>41 Leadership Academy: The ABC's Fostering In-House Leadership<BR>
Red River Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Claude Cunningham, Executive Director Student Services/Secondary
Instruction [817-473-5600] & Pamela Rudnicki, Instructional/Programs Coordinator,
Mansfield ISD</I><BR>
A rapidly growing school district has acted pro-actively to address their
near future need for campus and districtwide leadership through a three-pronged
approach. We discuss one of the three prongs in depth and touch on the other
two. We will address our Leadership Academy for potential campus leaders.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> shirley nichols, principal, wood ms, san antonio<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>42 Primer on Computer Networking<BR>
Lone Star Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Kyle Blanscet, Systems Analyst, TENET, Austin [512-475-9471]</I><BR>
This presentation is designed for the person who knows little or nothing
about the fundamentals of networking. Discussion topics will include the
basic network building blocks, Ethernet wiring and components and network
design. The attendees will come away from the presentation with a basic
understanding of the components and guidelines necessary to design and install
a local area network.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> bill shatford, trinity hs, euless <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>43 What Educators Establishing Policies Should Know Concerning Information
Technology<BR>
Lavaca Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Connie Stout, Director, TENET, Austin [512-475-9420]</I><BR>
Creating an on-line environment for schools presents many challenges. Districts
will need to develop policies, administrative guidelines and an understanding
of the issues surrounding information laws. The presentation will help provide
guidance for administrators.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> ronny beard, principal, bangs hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>44 You Gotta Question, We Gotta Answer!!<BR>
Ballroom A<BR>
</STRONG><I>Laura Van Zandt, Professor, Trinity University, San Antonio
[210-736-7501]; Becky Nugent, Director of Communications, Bryan ISD; Vern
Edin, Principal, Coppell Middle School, West; Janet Patton, Principal, Sonora
Junior High School & a cast of hundreds</I><BR>
Middle level, what does it really mean? Can we really change the image?
Will inclusion really work? How do you keep the momentum going? What's really
working? These questions and many more will be addressed as participants
have the opportunity to participate in large and small group activities.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> cecil floyd, middle level director, tassp, austin<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>45 Large Urban High School, Suburban School District: How Do You
Make It Work?<BR>
Ballroom B<BR>
</STRONG><I>Phil Gainous, Principal, Montgomery Blair High School, Silver
Springs, Maryland [301-650-6636]</I><BR>
This presentation will discuss programs, strategies and suggestions for
administering a successful large high school located in an urban setting
within a suburban school district. Topics will include: maintaining a safe
school environment, achieving high academic performance for all students
with a focus on the needs of minority students, curriculum development,
innovation and implementation, support programs for students, community
involvement in all aspects of the school and how to develop and maintain
community support and suggestions for raising needed supplementary funds
to support school programs and needs. The presentation will be followed
by a question and answer period.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> anita delafield, assistant principal, pasadena hs<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>46 Developing and Implementing Standards-Based Education<BR>
Ballroom C<BR>
</STRONG><I>Tim Westerberg, Principal, Littleton HS, Littleton, CO [303-347-7717]</I><BR>
In this session Dr. Westerberg will outline the system used to implement
standards-based education at Littleton High School and how that system has
evolved in a changing political environment. A process for developing a
school vision around student achievement through standards-based education
will be discussed, along with options for implementation. This session will
also be of interest to educators looking for ways to implement the curriculum
and the assessment sections of Breaking Ranks.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> george banda, principal, galena park hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>47 Reaching the Hard to Teach: Creatively Solving Your Problem<BR>
Trinity Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Randy Soffer, Education Director, Inclusion Works, Austin [512-454-6694];
David Leigh, Tech-Prep Project Director, Temple Community College & Mike
Cargill, Principal, Georgetown High School </I><BR>
Tired of the same old solutions for the same old problems? If so, come to
this session and learn how one high school used an IBM-developed problem
solving model to better meet the needs of its 'at risk' students.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> judy grantham, principal, san marcos hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>48 Dynamite Strategies for Motivating Low Level Students to Read
and Improve Their Reading Comprehension<BR>
Mulberry Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Janice Overstreet, Curriculum Director, Glen Rose ISD [817-897-3331]
& Cheryl Cox, Director of Special Programs, Garland ISD</I><BR>
Do you have students who are reading below grade level or that lack motivation
to pick up a book? In this session, exciting &quot;hands-on&quot; strategies
and activities that are correlated with TAAS will be shared that will help
ensure even the most reluctant reader to become actively involved in the
reading process.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> blanca hernandez, principal, rivera hs, brownsville<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>49 Changing Instruction to Make Block Scheduling (Trimester) a Success<BR>
Water Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>E. Don Brown, Principal [817-282-2551]; Sherilynn Cotten, Math
Chair & Judy Chapman, Language Arts Chair, Bell High School, Hurst</I><BR>
Take advantage of the extended period to make instruction come alive. We
&quot;TRI&quot;ed the trimester and found it a perfect fit for our students
and our school.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> larry bradley, principal, pflugerville hs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>50 Success Through Community Service Learning<BR>
Cypress Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Mona Weatherly, Community Service Learning Coordinator [817-825-3264];
Robert Ulibarri, Principal; Kristen Ogle & Holly Bishop, students, Nocona
High School</I><BR>
An effective community service learning program expands the classroom into
the real world through the partnership among students, teachers and community
members. In addition to benefiting the community, service learning employs
the best dropout prevention practices and provides educators with an innovative
way to reach students at risk. Nocona High School representatives will share
their experiences in starting, integrating and maintaining a successful
program of service learning. Students will share how their experiences with
the program have impacted their lives.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> wendell dunlap, principal, estacado jhs, plainview<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>51 Making it Work: Different Block Schedules in a Small ISD<BR>
Pecan Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Michael Nesbit, Principal, Huntington High School [409-876-4150]
& Glenn Frank, Principal, Huntington Middle School</I><BR>
High schools and middle schools in small ISDs are often faced with multitudes
of scheduling problems. Dynamic Leadership can bring about the diligent
planning and cooperation needed to allow differing block schedules to be
utilized by high schools and middle schools that share facilities and personnel.
This session will explain how problems were identified and resolved.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> alfredo acevedo, principal, memorial ms, alice<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>52 Hidden Rules in Generational Poverty<BR>
Hickory Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Ruby Payne, RFT Publishing Company, Baytown [713-424-9151]</I><BR>
In order to work with students from generational poverty, it is important
to understand the hidden rules they bring to school which guide their behavior
and thinking.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> linda robinson, principal, alvin jhs <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>53 A Little Fish in a Big Pond<BR>
Ash Room<BR>
</STRONG><I>Malcolm Dennis, Principal [713-453-7183]; James Johnson & Joe
Zuniga, Teachers, North Shore High School, Houston</I><BR>
The transition from middle school to high school is a difficult undertaking
for many freshmen. In order to create a positive first-year experience for
students, an orientation class may be the key to shaping and developing
the positive mental attitudes needed to deal with the rigors of high school.
Participants will learn how to help students improve study skills, research
career choices, set goals and explore other important aspects of their lives
to help make the high school experience a positive one.<BR>
<I>facilitator:</I> robin adkins, principal, west texas ms, stinnett <BR>
<BR>
