<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>News - Archive</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="image51.gif" WIDTH="392" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<IMG SRC="image45.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><IMG SRC="image79.gif" WIDTH="197" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></CENTER>
<P>Date: <B><I>6/12/96</I></B><I> _____________________________________________________________<BR>
<P><CENTER></I><B>OFFICERS &amp; OTHER ASSOCIATION LEADERS &amp; COMMITTEES
TO BE<BR>
WORKING THROUGHOUT THE SUMMER</B></CENTER>
<P>During the summer months, the TASSP Officers, Board of Directors and
Committee members<BR>
will be attending various meetings to prepare for the 1996-97 school year.
The following meetings<BR>
have been scheduled:<BR>
<BR>
June 12-14, 1996: At the 1996 TASSP Summer Workshop, the Board of Directors
will meet, as<BR>
will several TASSP committees (Small Schools Roundtable Committee, Executive
Committee,<BR>
Nominating Committee, Constitution Committee, Joint Steering Committee,
Membership<BR>
Committee, Technology Committee, Legislative Committee). Additionally, a
training session will<BR>
be held for the 1996-97 Board of Directors.<BR>
<BR>
June 23-27, 1996: The annual Officer Planning Meeting will be held on South
Padre Island for the<BR>
1996-97 TASSP Officers.<BR>
<BR>
July 19-21, 1996: The annual TASSP Leadership Retreat will be held at the
Radisson Hotel in<BR>
Austin for the following groups: the 1996-97 TASSP Officers &amp; Board
of Directors, all members<BR>
of the High School Steering Committee, Middle Level Steering Committee,
Secondary Curriculum<BR>
&amp; Instruction Steering Committee, the 1996-97 TASC Board of Directors
and the 1996-97 TAFE<BR>
Board of Directors. <BR>
<P><CENTER><I>_____________________________________________________________<BR>
</I><B>VOTE ON TASSP CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT</B></CENTER>
<P>A proposed TASSP Constitutional Amendment will be voted on Thursday,
June 13, during the<BR>
Business Meeting at the Second General Session of the 1996 TASSP Summer
Workshop.<BR>
<BR>
The proposed amendment would authorize the elected Board of Directors to
annually determine the<BR>
membership fees. Any change in membership fees would require a two-thirds
vote of the Board of<BR>
Directors at a regularly scheduled meeting. Currently, the annual fee is
determined in the<BR>
Constitution as: the average salary of Texas principals for the second preceding
year, multiplied by<BR>
.0017.<BR>
<BR>
If adopted by a two-thirds vote of the members present and voting at the
Second General Session<BR>
of the Summer Workshop, the amendment would be in effect for the 1997-98
membership year. <BR>
<P><CENTER><I>_____________________________________________________________<BR>
<B>ODEM PRINCIPAL NAMED AS 1996-97 TASSP PRESIDENT</B></I></CENTER>
<P>At the 1996 TASSP Summer Workshop, Manuel Lunoff III, principal of Odem
High School in<BR>
Odem, Texas, will assume the reigns as the new President of the Texas Association
of Secondary<BR>
School Principals. <BR>
<BR>
A native Texan, Lunoff was born in Falfurrias, Texas and graduated from
Falfurrias High School,<BR>
where he was President of his Senior Class. He graduated twice from Texas
A&amp;I University - first<BR>
with a B.S. in Elementary Education and later with a Master's in School
Administration. <BR>
<BR>
Lunoff has been involved in the Texas education system for twenty-eight
years. He spent the first<BR>
twelve years as a teacher and part-time principal at Sam Houston Elementary
and at Windsor Park<BR>
Elementary. From 1980-1984, he was a principal at Mathis Junior High School.
Since 1984, he has<BR>
been the principal at Odem High. <BR>
<BR>
Lunoff has been an active TASSP member since 1983. One of his goals while
serving as President<BR>
is to find ways to make TASSP stronger and more active with members at the
local levels. Lunoff<BR>
will replace 1995-96 President Jan Aragon, principal of Cypress Creek High
School in Houston.<BR>
Aragon was only the second woman - in a two-year span - to serve as the
74-year-old Association's<BR>
president.<BR>
<BR>
Lunoff currently resides in Odem with his wife, Anita, an elementary school
principal. They are<BR>
both active members of Sacred Heart Catholic Church. The Lunoffs have three
children: Manuel<BR>
IV, Melissa and Andrew. <BR>
<P><CENTER><I>_____________________________________________________________<BR>
</I><B>THE AMERICAN COMMUNITY RENEWAL ACT OF 1996 (HR3467)</B></CENTER>
<P>On May 16, 1996, a bill was introduced in the House of Representatives
that will create a 7 year, $5<BR>
billion federal school choice program. The House leadership has promised
that this bill would be<BR>
acted upon by mid-July.<BR>
<BR>
The bill requires establishment of &quot;low-income educational opportunity
scholarships&quot; that would<BR>
help low-income students to pay for their attendance at either religious
or non-religious private<BR>
schools. Except for covering the transportation costs of a parent to send
their child to an alternative<BR>
public school, non of these funds could be used to support the cost of sending
a child to a public<BR>
school.<BR>
<BR>
After failing last year to significantly reduce the federal government's
investment in education, the<BR>
House leadership has now proposed adopting investment in education, the
House leadership has<BR>
now proposed adopting a federally funded school choice program by mid-July.
It is important for<BR>
you and other principals, teachers, parents and students to promote public
education. We need to<BR>
express our concerns about how this bill will affect our public education
system and the children<BR>
and communities it serves.<BR>
<BR>
Information obtained from NASSP <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Date: <I>4/10/96 _____________________________________________________________</I>
<H2><CENTER>TASSP Announces World Wide Web Site</CENTER>
</H2>
TASSP introduced a web site today designed to help its communicate with
its members on a more timely basis. The site includes updates on important
news and projects as well as bulletin boards for members to communicate
with each other. The address of the site is http://www.tassp.org.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
